<html><title>CHILD DAY CARE IN DEVELOPING
COUNTRIES
</title><head></head><body>
<h3>
CHILD DAY CARE IN DEVELOPING COUNTRIES
</h3>
<center>
                            Judith L. Evans<br>
      Consultative Group on Early Childhood Care and Development<br>
</center>
<p>
<center>

                        Paper presented at the<br>
          Section on Community and International Child Health<br>
                    American Academy of Pediatrics<br>
                          1995 Spring Session<br>
                      Philadelphia, Pennsylvania<br>
                            April 11, 1995<br>
</center>
<p>

<h3>CHILD DAY CARE IN DEVELOPING COUNTRIES</h3><br><p>

<b>1.  Introduction</b><br><p>

     One and a half billion children will be born in the decade of the 1990s, and an increasing
percentage will survive their first year of life.  However, given economic conditions worldwide,
these children will increasingly live in poverty and be raised in situations which threaten their
chances for optimal human growth and development.<br><p>

     Survival rates, as measured by infant mortality rates (IMR, deaths per 1000 births),
indicate that more and more children are surviving and living beyond the first year.  Because of
this, today there is an increasing focus on the quality of life for those children who survive. 
Feeling that the IMR does not adequately portray children's potential to thrive,  UNICEF
developed the Under 5 Mortality Rate (U5MR) to measure children's well-being.  The U5MR is
an indicator of the overall resources directed toward children.  It takes into account the nutritional
health and health knowledge of mothers, the level of immunization and use of Oral Rehydration
Therapy (ORT), the availability of maternal and child health services (including pre-natal care),
income and food availability within the household, the availability of clean water and sanitation,
and the overall safety of the child's environment. (UNICEF 1989, pg. 82)  In essence the U5MR
attempts to take into account the context within which the child lives.<br><p>

     A focus on the context is appropriate given that the latest research on the relationship
between health, nutrition and stimulation argues convincingly that an adequate food supply is
necessary but not sufficient to assure a child's optimal development.  This is also true for access to
micro-nutrients, education, and  absence of disease. Children's growth and development is
fostered when all these variables are present, within a caring environment. (Engle, 1992, Levinger,
1992, Myers, 1992, Zeitlin, 1993).    For some children this environment exists within the family. 
Increasingly, for large numbers of children a caring environment needs to be created within a child
care setting.  <br><p>

     For the purpose of this paper <i> child care is being defined as any care provided to the
child outside his/her home that involves non-familial caregivers.</i>  In this paper I will not
address the issue of whether or not child care is a good thing for children.  While that debate
continues to take place in several arenas, in many ways it is academic.  There are millions of
children worldwide who, for a variety of reasons, need to be cared for by other than their parents
and extended family members  for a good portion of the day.  The focus of this paper is on how to
promote children's optimal development in these alternative settings.<br><p>

     I will begin with a brief overview of children's needs from birth until the age of six, the
years when the quality of child care is critical.   Second, I will turn to a discussion of what
constitutes CARE for young children and what that means in relation to designing child care
settings.  Third we will focus on alternative models of child care -- what they look like, who is
involved in creating them and what that means in terms of programming and funding.  To help
illustrate the different ways child care programs have come into being, and who is involved in the
process, there will be a presentation of three case studies -- one from Colombia, one from
Malaysia and the third from India.  I will conclude with a brief description of the role of the health
sector in promoting quality child care and some remarks about the importance and value of
bringing lessons learned in developing countries to apply in the USA.<br><p>

<b>2.   A Child's Key Needs from Conception through the Early Years</b><br><p>

     Survival and healthy development cannot be achieved without significant attention to
young children, from their conception through age six. As physicians you know that the basis for
good physical health must be established during the early years.  This is also true for cognitive,
social and emotional health.  The dependence and rapid growth typical of infancy and early
childhood make young children particularly vulnerable to a variety of health, nutritional, psycho-
social and other environmental conditions.  Those living in poverty are particularly at risk of poor
physical and psycho-social development.  Thus, in terms of physical, intellectual, emotional and
social well-being, the period from conception to age six is an essential key to subsequent growth,
development and ultimate productivity. <br><p>

     Pre-natally through the sixth year there are several distinct stages. They include: intra-
uterine, intrapartum (the birth itself), postpartum (birth to one month), early infancy (the first six
months), late infancy (6-12 months), toddler (one to three years), and the pre-school child (3-6
years of age).  <br><p>

     Children have different needs, depending on where they are within these stages.  The
younger the child, the more difficult it is to disentangle the physiological and psychological factors
within the environment that govern health.  The youngest children are completely dependent on
adults.  As they become toddlers, environmental cleanliness, encouragement of eating, and
vigilance in terms of the child's safety are of utmost importance.  The pre-school child is more
self-reliant and in many cultures children at this age become caregivers themselves.  These
developmental differences become important in designing appropriate child care environments.  A
delineation of developmental differences is provided by Donohue-Colletta (1992) for three age
groups that are frequently included in child care programs.  She defines the needs as
follows:<br><p>
<pre>
     Infants (birth to 1) need:
           protection from physical danger
           adequate nutrition
           adequate health care
           adults with whom to form attachments
           adults who can understand and respond to their signals
           things to look at, touch, hear, smell, and taste
           opportunities to explore the world
           appropriate language stimulation

     Toddlers (1-3 years of age) need all the above and also require:
           support in acquiring new motor, language and  thinking skills
           a chance to develop some independence
           help in learning how to control their own behavior
           opportunities to begin to learn to care for themselves
           daily opportunities to play with a variety of objects

     Children ages 3-6 (and above), in addition to the above, also need:
           opportunities to develop fine motor skills
           encouragement of language through talking, reading, singing
           activities which will develop a positive sense of mastery
           opportunities to learn cooperation, helping, sharing
           experimentation with pre-writing and pre-reading skills  (pg. 65)
</pre><br><p>
     What is clear from this listing is that a variety of inputs are required to support children's
growth and development.  An important thing to note is that <b>all the inputs require someone
to interact with the child. </b> Very young children are not capable of obtaining what they need
on their own.,  But more important, children need to interact with caring adults in order to thrive. 
The importance of adult-child interaction is underscored by the latest research which addresses
specifically the relationship between health, nutrition and development, all of which are parts of
the care provided to children.<br><p>
 
<b>3.  Children's Requirements for Care</b><br><p>

     The quality of <b>Care</b> the young child receives determines his/her development. 
Engle (1992), defines care as <i>the provision in the household and community of time,
attention, and support to meet the physical, mental and social needs of the growing child.</i> 
<b>Care</b> includes much more than keeping the child safe and free from harm.  Caregiving
behaviors include: breastfeeding; providing emotional security and reducing the child's stress;
providing shelter, clothing, feeding, bathing, supervision of the child's toilet; preventing and
attending to illness; nurturing and showing affection, interaction and stimulation; playing and
socializing; protecting from exposure to pathogens; and providing a relatively safe environment
for exploration.  (Zeitlin, 1991, Myers, 1992)  A second set of caregiving behaviors includes the
use of resources outside the family, including curative and preventative health clinics, prenatal
care, the use of traditional healers, and members of the extended family network. (Engle, 1992)
All these behaviors are a part of supporting the development of young children.<br><p>
  
     The type of caregiving behavior required depends to a large extent on the child's
developmental age and the health and nutritional risks the child is facing.  For example, during the
first year of life the child is at the greatest risk of mortality.  During late infancy (or when
complementary foods are introduced) and during the toddler period the child is at greatest risk of
growth faltering.  <br><p>

     While growth faltering may be the result of inadequate nutrition, there is clear evidence to
suggest that it is also linked to the way young children are fed.  <b>Feeding is more than giving
children food; it includes the interactive process that accompanies the intake of food.</b> 
The interactive caregiving provided during the feeding process can have a profound effect on the
child's later development. <br><p>

     Studies comparing children who are well- and poorly-nourished suggest that there are
positive <b>Caring</b> practices associated with children with better nutritional status, even
though the children come from the same type of environment as their malnourished peers. (Zeitlin,
1993)   <br><p>

     In the context of feeding, <b>Caring</b> practices include frequent physical contact,
being consistently responsive to the child's needs and showing affection to the child. <b>
Care</b> also includes <i>active feeding</i> that means being aware of how much the child is
eating, offering the child a second helping, assisting the child in the use of a utensil instead of
expecting complete self-feeding, and offering praise for eating. (Engle, 1992)<br><p>

     The studies of feeding are but one example of current research that shows the powerful
effect of the interaction between the child and the environment on growth and development. 
Another example comes from longitudinal studies of children growing up in poverty.  In Hawaii,
Werner (1982) was able to identify children who were able to thrive even though the conditions
under which they were raised suggested they would be malnourished and not develop well.  She
termed those children that did well <i>resilient. </i> Those characterized as resilient evidence
greater autonomy and competence (pg. 158) and clearly did better developmentally and over time
than their non-resilient peers.  They did better because they were able to "elicit predominantly
positive responses from their environment."  These children were also found to be "stress-
resistant" compared to children who elicited negative responses from their
environment.<br><p>

     In her research, Werner sought to identify what makes some children more resilient.  She
concluded, as have others, that <b>the differences between children who thrive and those
who falter are determined by the type of interaction that occurs between the child and the
environment. </b> Critical in that environment are the people with whom the child interacts. 
The child's ability to thrive is greatly enhanced by the kind of care the child receives from those
around him/her.  Children who are nurtured, responded to positively, talked to and loved do much
better than children who are neglected or receive only cursory attention.<br><p>

     Given the importance of the people in the child's environment, it is critical that any model
of child care pay particular attention to the quality of interaction between the caregivers and the
children.  <br><p>
     
<b>4.  Models of Child Care</b><br><p>

     First and foremost, it must be emphasized that mono-dimensional programs (e.g. those
that provide only a nutrition supplement or focus only on immunization, or even provide only pre-
natal care for the mother without adequate follow-up once the child is born), are much less likely
to be successful than multi-dimensional programs. Mono-dimensional programs, which may meet
short term goals, are not likely to be sustainable over time.  It is rarely helpful to impose a single
solution that ignores the need for individuals and communities to control their own destinies.
<br><p>

     Multi-dimensional programs, on the other hand, are built on an awareness of the
importance of meeting the multiple needs of children and their families.  They are generally
created from a culturally-sensitive understanding of people's beliefs, perceptions, needs and
concerns, and the services they provide meet the intersecting needs of children and families.  An
example would be a program that provides children with a nutritional supplement in a child care
setting which also provides children with stimulation and emotional support.  Another component
of such a program would be work with parents to improve family nutrition.  Thus a given in all
the models being presented is that they take a multi-dimensional approach in providing services
for the child and family.<br><p>

     Given that a successful child care program needs to take into account the multiple needs
of children and of the families, the question is, what alternatives are available?   There are several
dimensions that help define alternatives.  These include: the reasons for creating the child care--
the <i>purpose;</i> who is responsible for establishing the child care--the <i>sponsor;</i> 
what the child care consists of--the <i>structure;</i> and how it is financed--the
<i>funding.</i><br><p>

<i>A.     Purpose</i><br><p>

     Child care programs are established for a number of reasons.  In some instances they are
set up explicitly to support women's increased participation in the work force. An example of this
are the child care centers created in Eastern European countries. Child care was provided for all
working women.  There was a clear expectation that women would take advantage of these
centers and return to work as soon as feasible after the birth of a child.  In general the child care
provided in these centers addressed a full range of children's needs, even though the motivation
for creating the child care was to get women into the labor force.<br><p>

     Another motive for creating child care is to provide a healthy and stimulating environment
for children who are at risk of delayed or debilitated development, regardless of whether or not
the mother is working outside the home.  An example of this comes from India where the
Integrated Child Development Services (ICDS) program provides support to pregnant and
lactating women.  It also provides health surveillance and a nutritional supplement for young
children 0-3,  and health, nutrition and education for children 3-6 years of age.  In this instance the
child care program was created primarily to support the healthy development of
children.<br><p>

     Whatever the motivation for the creation of a child care program, in order for it to be
successful it must take into account the needs of both the family and the child.  While this may
seem obvious, it has not always been the practice.  In the early 70s there were a number of mono-
dimensional nutrition programs that focused almost exclusively on one aspect of a child's need. 
While some of these programs produced short-term gains for the child, they were largely
unsuccessful in enhancing the quality of life for the child and did nothing to help parents create an
environment within which children could thrive.  A notable example comes from Chile where a
nutrition recuperation program was established that institutionalized malnourished infants until
they had gained appropriate weight for age. Many children successfully 'graduated out' of the
recuperation centers, allowing the program to achieve some important short-term political goals
focused on decreasing infant mortality during the first year of life. Once the children were
returned to their homes, however, the gains were not maintained.  The program had done little to
help change the environment within which children originally became malnourished.  Thus the
great majority of the children became malnourished once again, and many of them died.  (Evans,
1978)  Therefore, even when the primary focus may be the mother or the child, program planners
need to also consider how the program will affect on the other group.<br><p>

     The purpose of the program is related in large part to who sponsors the creation of the
child care program.<br><p>

<i>B.     Sponsors</i><br><p>

     There are several different kinds of organizations that can be responsible for sponsoring
child care.  These include government, non-governmental organizations, employers and private
individuals or groups.  Within each of these, there is yet another breakdown according to sector. 
For example, child care can be developed by the Ministry of Health, a Ministry of Social Welfare,
a Ministry of Labor, a Ministry of Women and Youth Affairs, or the Ministry of Education.  In
turn, the sector sponsoring the child care will play a strong role in determining the definition of
quality within the program, the curriculum to be implemented, expectations in terms of staff
qualifications and training, the types of materials available to the children, and the relationship
between the sponsors of the programs and the families they serve.<br><p>

     As a result of differences in sponsorship, a program provided by private business in
response to government policy, which mandates that business with a given number of women
employees must provide child care, might well look quite different from a child care program
developed by the Ministry of Health to address health and nutrition issues in an urban squatter
settlement.  While the former may be concerned only with providing custodial care and meeting
the 'letter of the law' with little regard to what happens for children on a day-to-day basis, the
latter would put considerably more emphasis on assuring the children were receiving adequate
nutrition through the program.  A private individual, on the other hand, might be more attuned to
the needs and expectations of parents than to the needs of the child.  The program she develops
would reflect her understanding of her potential market.  <br><p>

     Thus an understanding of who is sponsoring the child care is closely related to motivation. 
It is also important in determining the structure of the program. <br><p>

<i>C.     Structure:</i><br><p>

     Structure refers to such things as the physical location of the program, the age groups
being served,  the hours of operation, staffing and the flow of the day.  <br><p>

     Child care programs can either be located in centers--which may or may not be purpose-
built--and in homes.  Increasingly people are rejecting the high costs of constructing centers that
house large numbers of children.  They are turning to the creation of family day care homes within
a neighborhood or community.  While these cater to a fewer number of children in each setting,
there are more opportunities for cross-age groupings, fewer transportation problems, the
likelihood of a more 'familial' environment for the children, employment opportunities for the
women who operate the family day care, and much lower overhead costs.   Frequently family day
care also builds on traditional systems of informal care that already exist within a
community.<br><p>

     In terms of age groups, when center-care is created children are frequently segregated by
age, with the youngest children (birth through two years of age) being cared for in 'creches', and
the pre-school aged child (3-6 or school-entry age) provided for in a more educationally-oriented
'pre-school' or 'kindergarten'.<br><p>

     The hours that a program operates differ primarily according to the purpose of the
program.  If the child care has been created to support women's work, then the programs are
likely to be available on a full-day basis.  Within some Eastern European countries, for example in
Romania, there are full-week child care programs where parents drop the children off Monday
morning and collect them Friday evening.  If the program has been developed to provide children
with school-readiness skills, then it is more likely to be a half-day program that may or may not
adequately meet the needs of parents. <br><p>

     Staffing is of critical importance.  In general staff for child care programs are drawn from
the least well-educated strata within a community, primarily because of the low status and low
pay associated with being a child care provider.  It is assumed that any woman can be a child care
provider.  This is a faulty assumption.  Given the importance of the early years in terms of
children's later growth and development we should be giving priority to recruiting well-educated
and competent individuals to work with young children.  And they should receive appropriate pre-
and in-service training.  What happens is that women recruited to serve as child care providers
take on the task because they are not qualified to do anything else.  Then, if they receive training
they quickly seek out other opportunities to put that training to use in a higher paying job.  This
leads to very high turnover rates.  In a recently instituted family day care program in Bolivia the
turnover rate in the first two years was 35%.  This provides little continuity for the children in the
program.<br><p>

     The flow-of-the-day, commonly known as the daily schedule or daily routine, is generally
structured to meet the goals of the program and also to respond to children's developmental
needs.  Thus nutrition programs will have regularly scheduled snacks and meals and a
considerable amount of the caregiver's time will be devoted to preparing these meals and cleaning
up afterwards.  In many of these programs children spend a great deal of time waiting.  On the
other hand, in an educational program the caregiver devotes a greater proportion of her time to
creating an environment that supports educational goals, but the children's health may not be
monitored effectively.<br><p>
     
<i>D.     Funding: </i><br><p>

     The issue of funding is closely related to sponsorship.  Sponsors are frequently funders,
but not always.  Funders include government, international donor agencies (such as UNICEF,
USAID, World Bank),  foundations (the Bernard van Leer Foundation) non-governmental
agencies (international and national ones), employers, and private entrepreneurs.  An additional
group in this category is parents.<br><p> 

     Funding for child care programs shifts over time.  While many international donor
agencies are willing to provide funds to get a program started, they are unwilling to pay the costs
of the program over time.  For programs that are successful there is a shift from donor agency
funding to some mix of government, NGO and community funding when the program becomes
established. This is particularly true for those programs designed to serve the poorest
families.<br><p>

     Now that we have talked about the general dimensions of program models, I will shift to a
description of three very different kinds of programs, illustrating some child care possibilities
developed internationally.<br><p>

<b>5.  Case Studies</b><br><p>

 <b>Colombian Community Child Care and Nutrition Project.</b>  One of the largest
systems of family day care is currently operating in Colombia.  It is the Colombian Community
Child Care and Nutrition Project that began in 1990.  The program supports <i>Homes for well-
being,</i> a community-based, non-formal programme providing services for children from birth
to seven years of age.  The program relies heavily on community involvement.  People from the
community participate in an initial assessment of needs that helps determine the number of homes
required.  They also participate in selecting the women who will be the care providers.  Local
associations are responsible for managing the overall effort.<br><p>

     Community mothers, with assistance from volunteers on a rotating basis (mothers whose
children are in the home), provide care for up to 15 children in their home.  The community
mother receives training in child development, family and community relations, nutrition and
health.  Financial supports for the program include food to assure proper nutrition for the
children, and the mother is given a loan to upgrade her home to accommodate the children in the
program.  <br><p>

     The program is supported nationally by the <i>Instituto Colombiano de Bienstar
Familiar</i> (ICBF), working in collaboration with the Ministry of Public Health, the National
Apprentice Service, the Institute of Territorial Credit and other governmental and private
organizations.  The project was begun with World Bank and other donor monies.<br><p>

     The program has been evaluated. While children in the program had significant cognitive
and social gains, there were no significant nutritional benefits. (Myers 1993)   The nutrition
supplement provided to children accounts for half the costs of the program.   Yet despite this high
investment,  the program did not have a positive nutritional impact on the children.  As has been
found in other nutrition supplementation projects, the lack of improvement in nutritional status is
likely to be the result of parents believing that their children receive their full daily nutritional
requirements through the program and therefore they do not feed the child at home. In reality only
50-70% of the child's nutritional needs are provided by the program. Parents need to be educated
about the importance of continuing to feed the child at home.  Thus, while the effects on psycho-
social development are positive as a result of the program, these are moderated by low nutrition.
As a result of the findings of the evaluation the program is being redesigned.<br><p>

<b>Malaysian</b><i> Sang Kancil,</i><b> Community-based Services Project. </b> The
<i>Sang Kancil</i> Project was developed within the squatter settlements of Kuala Lumpur,
Malaysia.  It was begun in 1978 by the health sector in an attempt to meet the health needs of
those living in urban squatter settlements.  The rationale for working in squatter communities was
based on the fact that they are a growing phenomenon in the developing world, constituting
nearly 50% of the total urban population.  It is widely recognized that the environment within
squatter settlements is threatening to people's health--physically, mentally and in terms of psycho-
social development. <br><p>

     In Malaysia there was difficulty in providing services for squatters because they occupy
the land illegally and thus are not entitled to city services (water, sewage, medical care, education,
etc.).  Nevertheless many squatter settlements are stable communities, including people from a
variety of income levels.  The stability comes from affordable housing within the settlement that
may not be available outside, well-developed support systems, and/or leadership positions within
the settlement.  <br><p>
     
     Developers of the <i>Sang Kancil</i> project, University faculty in collaboration with
Ministry of Health personnel, used a strategy that recognized, valued, and built upon the complex
social systems that exist in the settlements. While the health sector personnel who began the
project were interested in establishing primary health care centers within kampungs (districts) in
the settlements, they began their efforts by conducting meetings with community members to
determine their needs and priorities.  The community wanted a child care programme and income-
generating activities for women.  Health care was not seen as a priority.  Program planners
listened to the community.  Rather than building a health center, they established a pre-school and
an income-generating project.  When these were well established, then it was possible to
introduce primary health care, which is now widely accepted. <br><p>

<b>India,</b><i>  Mobile Creches</i>.   India is a country that has had legislation in support of
employer-sponsored child care since 1964.  For many years it was not enforced.  However, there
is continuing pressure for industries to comply.  Within the construction industry there was
particular concern about the welfare of the numerous women workers and their children. 
Construction sites are dangerous places for young children.  Women are not able to rely on
extended family members to care for their children. Further, with the frequent moves required as
buildings are completed and new ones begun, women and children are forced to relocate
frequently.  Thus a program of early childhood care and development was begun for these
workers and their families on site.  A variety of private voluntary organizations, working with the
construction industry, created the <i>Mobile Creches</i> system, which began in 1969.   The
child care programme is established where the women are working, and moves from site to site as
buiildings are completed and new ones begun.  <i>Mobile Creches</i> have also been
established to serve the children of street cleaners, rag pickers, and other families representing the
lowest social status groups in India.<br><p>

     There are three levels to the programme, all of which exist under one roof, based on the
age of the child.  The first is a creche for infants and young children (from 3-4 weeks to age
three).  Here the focus is on health and nutrition since most of the children are malnourished when
they enter the programme.  There is an emphasis on providing them with proper foods and
educating the parents about nutrition. <br><p>

     The second level is the nursery programme for 3-6 year old children. Within the nursery
programme the health and nutritional status of the child remains an important part of the
programme.  The children are monitored weekly by a physician, and growth charts are kept on the
children. In addition, however, there is an emphasis on cognitive and psycho-social development. 
One of the goals is to help prepare the children for the formal school system. <br><p>

     The third level is an elementary programme for children from 6-12 years of age.  The
elementary programme was developed for children who traditionally would have been taking care
of their younger siblings.  Because the siblings are now in a child care programme, the older
children could be going to school.  However, there is considerable prejudice against these children
who come from the poorest families.  Because their home environments have not prepared them
for school, they do poorly.  Teachers do not want them in their classrooms.  The<i> Mobile
Creches </i> elementary programme was developed to prepare these children to enter school and
be placed within an age equivalent grade.  <br><p>

     Staff within the <i>Mobile Creches</i> system is drawn from the lower middle class. 
(Because of the longevity of the effort, there are now women teaching in<i> Mobile Creches</i>
who were once children in the <i>Creches</i>.)  Very soon after the programme began it
became evident that traditional teacher training institutes did not prepare people adequately for
work in the programme because of the unique needs of the families and children served by
<i>Mobile Creches.</i>  Thus, over time,<i> Mobile Creches</i> developed their own staff
training programme.  The training they have developed is also offered to NGOs and government
child care programs serving young children on other settings.  As the program has evolved,
classes in adult education have been added. There are literacy programs, nutrition classes, and
political discussion groups. Thus what began as a child care program has evolved into a much
larger development effort.<br><p>

<b>6.     The Health Sector and Child Care</b><br><p>

     Why should the health sector be concerned about child care?  There are  two basic
reasons.  The first is that the health sector has a significant role to play in quality assurance.  The
second is that child care can be used as a vehicle for meeting  maternal and child health goals.
<br><p>

     <i>The health sector has a role to play in the assurance of quality programs.</i> 
Programs for young children are expanding rapidly throughout the world. To be of quality, they
require a health input.  This is recognized in most countries and stringent health standards have
been developed.  In most of cases the 'ideal' is established as the 'bottom line'.  And while it would
be wonderful if developing countries could  meet these standards, in reality they cannot. What this
means is that the great majority of child care centers are never accredited.  Because they do not
meet government standards, they are not eligible to receive government support.  This means that
they continue to operate at a substandard level, never gaining access to the resources that would
help them improve the quality of their services.<br><p>

     To be supportive of child care,  the health sector needs to adopt a more flexible approach
in the development of health standards. Health standards should be based on the realities of the
context within which child care is going to be provided. In South Africa, for example, an attempt
is being made to set health standards in line with the resources of the community. Standards for
child care are being established in a step or stage process.  People from the Ministry of Health
meet with community members and together they decide what the minimal standards should be. 
When the community has met those standards, the government provides some funds to support
the child care system.  Upon receipt of those funds the community is able to upgrade its services,
thus meeting the standards at a higher level, giving them higher accreditation and access to
additional resources.  Communities with greater resources to begin with are expected to meet
higher standards.   This step system allows communities to gain access to necessary resources to
continue to upgrade their program.<br><p>

     <i>Child care programs can serve as an entry point to communities not currently
receiving health services.</i>  In some areas of the world Western medical practices and services
are not easily accepted.  Services may be underutilized because people lack an understanding of
the benefits.  Because they are socially attractive and acceptable, child care programs can serve as
an entry point into the community.  Once the child care program is firmly established, it is then
possible to introduce other development efforts, some of which promote health.  Thus initially the
health sector might begin working in the community by supporting projects that are not
necessarily health-focused.  Overtime, however, the project could add health components for the
families and broader community.   The Sang Kancil project in Malaysia is a good example of this
approach.<br><p>

     <i>A cost-effective way of delivering health care is to become collaborators in the
provision of child care.</i>  Child care programs present an excellent opportunity for the
delivery of  health care and health monitoring that would otherwise be provided through maternal
and child health (MCH) services.  The introduction of such activities can constitute a considerable
extension of existing health care services and provide the possibility for the development of
community-based primary health care that includes not only children but mothers and families as
well.<br><p>

     By working through child care programs, health professionals can assess the role that
community members can play in health promotion.  By working with and training child care
providers it would be possible to assess the extent to which people from the community, with
basic training in screening, disease management and nutrition, can complement the health and
welfare sectors and provide a meaningful extension to primary health care programs.<br><p>

     What needs to happen within the health sector for it to work more effectively with child
care programs? <br><p>

     <i>Health care professionals need to incorporate a broader definition of health into the
way they view and work with people. </i> A broad definition of health and child development can
make health workers at all levels more effective in their work with young children and their
families.  The more that health personnel at the local level can be involved in prevention and the
promotion of health, the more likely that child care providers will be responsive to what the health
sector has to offer.  All too often health professionals come in and tell others what to do without
being sensitive to either the realities of the environment or the traditions of the people.  If people
feel their way of life is valued, then they are more open to making changes.  Further, the
involvement of  local families in the planning, provision of and evaluation of child care programs,
including health, education and development activities, strengthens local understanding of the
health needs of children and improves the manner in which child care is organized and
used.<br><p>

     <i>Health professionals need to expand their own understanding of and promote all
aspects of child development. </i> Many training courses for doctors and other health
professionals focus almost exclusively on physical growth and development.  Few provide an
understanding of the processes involved in children's cognitive, social and emotional development. 
A broader understanding of all aspects of children's development would allow health professionals
to provide a much broader view of the child in their work with parents.<br><p>

     <i>Health professionals need to take a more pro-active role in the development of
appropriate health training for child care providers. </i>There is a set of basic health messages
and practices that can be carried out by people with relatively low levels of training.  Supervision
and support, however, from the formal health sector are imperative, as is support from the
educational sector and from social welfare.  This support could be in the form of training
programs, training guides, operational manuals, many of which are available through UNICEF,
WHO and other public and private organizations.  Support can also be provided through regular
contact between child care programs and workers in these specialized areas.<br><p>


<b>7.     Bringing the Lessons Home</b><br><p>

     Attention is increasingly being paid to a movement known as Lessons without Borders. 
This movement is based on a realization that the problems faced in the Majority World are similar
to those being faced by populations within the USA.  There is also a recognition that the lessons
learned from the successful programs in developing countries might well be applicable in the
USA.  Currently groups like Save the Children, which has both an international and a national
office, are seeing the parallels between what they have supported elsewhere and what can be
applied here.  They are in the process of bringing the lessons home, as are others. <br><p>

     While communication systems make the sharing of experiences across borders a
possibility, the key to making them work is an openness of mind and spirit.  Our own professional
training provides us with an artificial division of the child.  We are trained as physicians,
psychologists, educators, and social workers to view the child from the perspective of a given
discipline.  This has created suspicions, jealousies, and a lack of understanding that have gotten in
the way of us working together to promote the healthy development of all children. When we are
able to break these barriers, it will be to the benefit of all.  Margaret Alva expressed it well when
she said, <br><p>
     <pre>
     ...a child is born without barriers.  Its needs are integrated and it is
     we who choose to compartmentalize them into health, nutrition,
     hunger or education.  Yet the child itself  cannot isolate its hunger 
     for food from its hunger for affection or its hunger for knowledge. 
     The same unity extends to the child's perception of the world.  The child's
     mind is free of class, religion, colour or nationality barriers, unless we 
     wish it otherwise.  It  is this intrinsic strength in the unity of the child 
     that we need to exploit, for building a better world.       
                                             Alva, 1986
</pre>
<center>                        REFERENCES
</center><br><p>
