<html><head></head>
<TITLE> THE UTILIZATION OF EARLY CHILDHOOD CARE AND EDUCATION
PROGRAMMES </TITLE><body><p>
<p>
<CENTER>
<b>THE UTILIZATION OF EARLY CHILDHOOD CARE AND EDUCATION
PROGRAMMES FOR DELIVERY OF MATERNAL AND CHILD HEALTH COMPONENTS
OF PRIMARY HEALTH
CARE:</b><p>
<b>A FRAMEWORK FOR DECISION-MAKING</b><p>
</CENTER>
<p>

<CENTER>
Judith L. Evans<p>
with the collaboration of Robert G. Myers<p>
</CENTER><p>
<p>
High/Scope Educational Research Foundation<BR>
July, 1985<p>
<p>
This paper has been commissioned by the World Health Organization.  It is
intended to stimulate discussion and does not represent an official position of
the World Health Organization.<p>
<p>
<p>
TABLE OF CONTENTS<p>
<p>
<p>
        Summary <p>
<p>
     I. Introduction.<p>
<p>
    II. Factors Affecting the Use of Early Childhood 
         Care and Education Programmes for the Delivery
         of MCH Components in PHC <p>
<p>
   III. In What Ways are Early Childhood Care and Education
         Programmes Currently Linked to the Health Care
         Community?<p>
<p>
    IV. Developing Typologies for Early Childhood Care and
         Education Programmes<p>
<p>
     V. Case Studies of Selected Early Childhood Care and
         Education Programmes<p>
<p>
    VI. The Potential for Delivery of MCH Components of PHC
         through Early Childhood Care and Education
         Programmes:  Recommendations for Action<p>
<p>
        Bibliography<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
                                 <b>SUMMARY</b><p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
     In most parts of the developing world children under the age of 15 and
women of reproductive age constitute more than 50% of the population.  The
rapid growth and early acquisition of motor and cognitive skills typical of
infancy and early childhood and the unique biosocial characteristics of
reproduction, make children and women vulnerable to a variety of health,
nutritional, psycho- social and other environmental conditions.  Those living
in poverty are particularly at risk of poor physical and psycho- social
development.<p>
<p>
          Poverty and its correlates form the complex of factors 
      most commonly identified as threatening children's well-
      being. Such correlates include lack of adequate 
      nutrition; lack of health, educational, and other social 
      services; poor sanitary conditions and lack of environ-      mental
hygiene; overcrowding within the home and/or       community; lack of adequate
attention from caretakers;       intra-familial stress due to lack of resources
and the
          effects of the physical environment.<BR>
                                               Halpern, 1982, p.20<p>
<p>
     In recognition of these threats to all people's well-being, the World
Health Organization has made a commitment to bring health care to all parts of
the world by the year 2000. There are two levels at which this must take
place--at the level of basic <u>survival</u>, and in order to promote long-term
<u>development</u>.  At the survival level WHO has developed "high profile"
programmes aimed at capturing people's attention, interest, and commitment. At
the development level WHO has been promoting primary health care, described
as:<p>
<p>
          essential health care made universally accessible to
          individuals and families in the community by means 
          acceptable to them, through their full participation
          and at a cost that the community and country can afford.
          It forms an integral part of the country's health system
          of which it is the nucleus, and of the overall social
          and economic development of the community.<BR>
                                             WHO/MCH, 1981, p.8<p>
<p>
     Because of the immediacy and graphic nature of survival, it is possible to
mobilize national and international support for programmes which promote
survival. Development, on the other hand, requires a long-term commitment to
meeting the multiple needs of a population through multi-sectoral programmes
which promote well- being, particularly among those most at risk.  As noted:<p>
<p>
<p>
          The most effective approach to achieving a satisfactory
          status of health is multi-sectoral, preventive and
          requiring the coordinated efforts of all the sectors 
          that can contribute directly and indirectly to the
          promotion of well-being, and this approach should
          include day care.<BR>
                                            WHO/MCH, 1981, p.8<p>
<p>
<p>
     WHO has recognized that day care and pre-school, more broadly referred to
as early childhood care and education (ECCE), programmes have the potential to
reach many of the world's children and their families.  The question is how to
use ECCE systems to achieve primary health care goals.  A strategy is suggested
in this paper, a strategy which focuses on systematically examining early
childhood care and education programmes, and assessing their potential for
delivering primary and maternal and child health care components. Further, an
argument is made for the increased involvement of the World Health Organization
in the development of integrated services for young children and their families
through early childhood care and education programmes. <p>
<p>
     The Introduction, Section I, provides information on the needs of young
children and their families, and presents an argument in support of an
integrated service delivery approach. Section II contains a description of some
of the factors which would facilitate the integration of PHC/MCHcomponents into
ECCE programmes, and some of the constraints to such an effort. Before
developing a strategy, however, it should be recognized thatthere are a variety
of ways in which PHC/MCH services are already a part of ECCE efforts. The
continuum of current linkages is described in Section III. To date, the
approach has not been systematic.  There is a need to make the integration more
explicit and to develop a range of interventions to further promote the
maternal and child health components of primary health care in ECCE settings.
To start the process, a typology of ECCE programmes is needed. In Section IV
there is an overview of three typologies, or ways of categorizing, early
childhood care and education programmes, that provide a framework for
decision-making in relation to the introduction of appropriate health care
methodologies and materials into the range of ECCE programmes that exist.
Within Section V a variety of ECCE programmes are described in detail which
demonstrate the interaction of the variables within the three typologies. In
the concluding section, Section VI, an attempt is made to define the primary
health care components that could be introduced into the systems of early
childhood care and education suggested by the typologies.  Using the
hypothesized possibilities, it is then possible to develop strategies for WHO's
involvement in promoting the maternal and child health care components of
primary health care within ECCE systems. This paper is designed to serve as a
point of departure for an ongoing discussion.<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>INTRODUCTION</b><p>
<p>
<p>
<b>A. The Need</b><p>
<p>
     Young children, from birth to six years of age, are developing rapidly--
biologically, cognitively, and psycho-socially.  Basic physical, mental, and
social structures are being set into place during the early years.  There are a
variety of environmental conditions that promote the healthy development of
these structures.  They include:<p>
<UL>
<LI> adequate provision for health, safety, nutrition and shelter;<BR>
<LI> consistent caregivers;<BR>
<LI> adult and peer models of appropriate cognitive and social behavior, and
     opportunities to interact with these models;<BR>
<LI>appropriately communicated and consistent expectations and limits;<BR>
<LI> a recognition of and allowance for children's individual interests and
    developmental pattern;<BR>
<LI>a physical and social envrionment that encourages active exploration
       and provides opportunities for learning;<BR>
 <LI> feedback, both positive and negative, that provides the child with a
  positive sense of self and a trust of others.<BR>
</UL>
<p>
<p>
     The quality of the environment in which millions of children are growing
up in developing countries is inadequate by any number of criteria.
Overcrowding, lack of potable water and sewage facilities, lack of adequate
food, and inadequate caretaking characterize the environments of many young
children.  Frequent infection (most commonly diarrhea), and malnutriton account
for over 50% of all infant mortality in developing countries. To be able to
effectively manage incidents of diarrhea would be to significantly decrease
infant mortality.  As noted in the World Banks <u>World Development Report
1984</u>,<p>
<p>
<p>
          Mortality from diarrhea in the developing world is two
          to three times higher than it was in today's developed
          countries when overall mortality levels were similar.
          Diarrhea is a disease of the poor, primarily of poor

children.  It accompanies malnutrition and is exacerbated
          by poor sanitation, lack of elementary health services,
          and lack of the basic education that might allow parents
          to take the necessary precautions to prevent it.<BR>
                               World Development Report, 1984, p.73<p>
<p>
      While food availability is one of the critical factors in any situation
where malnutrition is endemic, sanitation and food preparation are also
important variables. Where improvements in the quantity of food available to
mothers for use in feeding infants and young children may not be feasible, much
can be done to improve the well being of infants and young children by assuring
that available food is appropriately prepared, provided and preserved. <p>
<p>
     It is becoming increasingly apparent that improper nutrition, poordisease
management and inadequate affective stimulation and care of the child are all
conditions which interact to influence patterns of morbidity and mortality.
Severe malnutrition, disease, and infection suffered during early years have a
permanent effect on later development, not only because of the consequences to
the child's physical well being, but because these variables interact with and
have an impact on the child's social environment.  The behavioral effects of
malnutrition, disease and infection in young children include such things as
apathy, reduced responsiveness to people and the environment, and the inability
to attend to tasks. As a result, the child is less "engaging"; caretakers find
the child less appealing and fail to provide the child with the stimulation
that is needed to promote development. A vicious cycle is created, which
results in poor developmental outcomes. To have an impact on the child's growth
and development an integrated system of care must be provided-- one which
addresses the physical, cognitive and psycho-social needs of the child and
family.<p>
<p>
     The goal of health and social programmes is to bring basic services to all
people. To do this a range of strategies is needed. The creation of primary
and/or maternal and child health care centres constitutes one strategy. Yet, in
many developing countries these may not as yet reach the high risk groups;
families living in rural and urban slum settlements have typically been
underserved.  There are several reasons for this:<p>
<p>
      1. The resources available to health and social planners concerned with
      long-range development issues have traditionally been scarce and have
    not permitted the extension of services to hard to reach groups. <p>
<p>
      2. This has been exacerbated by the tendency to try and establish health
       care services based on Western models without any differentiation of
    varying needs among social groups. <p>
<p>
      3. The fact that preventive health care is not often seen as a priority
      by traditional and low-education groups has, in turn, served to limit
    their service-seeking bahaviour.  Where maternal and child health
services are available they are often seen as sources of therapeutic
or remedial rather than preventive care.  <p>
<p>
      4. Moreover, planning by the health and social sectors, has typically
    failed to incorporate many of the perceived needs and expectations of
  the communities for whom the planning has been undertaken.  As a <p>
         result, the services that are available have neither attracted the
    attention, nor inspired the confidence, that would have ensured their
  appropriate utilization.<p>
<p>
     Therefore, the challenge is to find alternative ways of delivering primary
health care services, particularly to low-income families in both urban and
rural settings. One possible alternative is to integrate primary health care
into systems of early childhood care and education.  As an introduction to this
alternative, we will briefly examine some of the socio-demographic trends which
lend support to the idea that ECCE systems might provide an avenue to reaching
those most in need.<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>B. Socio-demographic trends</b><p>
<p>
     Throughout much of the Third World the pattern of family structure, female
employment, and residential mobility has been changing rapidly over the last
decade.  As a result of migration and industrial employment patterns, the
extended family system of traditional societies is being replaced by a nuclear
family system which often fails, by virtue of its limited number of adults, to
provide the care and support required by children.  In addition, in both urban
and rural environments, there is an increase in the number of women headed
households.      <p>
<p>
     New economic pressures on, and possibilities presented to, women in urban
areas means they increasingly work outside the home, often for long hours and
following finite schedules that limit their availability and the time they can
devote to child care.  In addition, siblings, who have traditionally been
responsible for the care of younger children, are attending school at an
increased rate, and grandmothers are themselves a part of the labor force.  In
rural areas women often work in the fields.  While in many cultures women have
historically consistuted a majority of the agricultural work force, in other
settings the out-migration of men, seeking employment in other locations, has
increased women's agricultural role.  In addition, in some agricultural
settings plantation economies and cash crop production have meant that there
too women are increasingly being exposed to demands of rigid time and work
schedules similar to those common in urban environments. While the literature
would suggest that women's work outside the home produces direct benefits for
children, there are also costs (Engle, 1980). <p>
<p>
     Women's changing role and entry into economically productive roles makes
new demands on women's time.  Yet, care of children, particularly young
children, is still the woman's responsibility. Her responsibility for the
well-being of the child starts with conception.  During pregnancy the woman's
diet and health are important in determining fetal outcome.  It is estimated
that a nutritional anaemia afflicts close to half of all women of childbearing
age in developing countries, and more than 70% of pregnant women suffer from
malnutrition (Sivard, 1985). These data suggest that more than half of the
children in developing countries enter the world under less than optimal
conditions.<p>
<p>
     After birth, the mother is responsible for the safety, care and feeding of
the child, and, to varying degrees, for providing stimulation for the child's
cognitive and psyco-social development. New demands on women's time and energy
make it increasingly difficult for women to provide the kind of <p>
care their children need. With the loss of the extended family as a support
system in caring for young children, there has been a rapidly increasing demand
for child care outside the home by individuals other than family members.<p>
<p>
     The response to the demand has varied;  it has reflected the socio-
economic conditions of those in need of day care, the countries in which they
live, the resources available to the health, public welfare, and education
sectors, and the involvement of private voluntary organizations. The response
has also been pervasive in the sense that peoples in all parts of the world
have developed systems of care for young children. For this, and a number of
other reasons to be described later,  it would appear that these systems of
child care could be utilized for the delivery of primary and maternal and child
health care services. This paper describes the range of programmes that exist
and suggests ways in which primary health care can become an integral part of
what is provided through these programmes. Before beginning the discussion,
however, it is necessary to define what is meant by the term "early childhood
care and education".<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>C. Definition</b><p>
<p>
     In the literature there are a range of terms that refer to care of young
children (from birth until the age at which the child enters the formal school
system--generally between the ages of 5 and 7), outside the home.  For example,
the word, "Creche", generally refers to services for children under the age of
2. "Child Minding" generally refers to care in the home by neighborhood women,
serving children from birth through the early primary years. "Daycare"
generally describes full-time care provided for children of women working
outside the home. And, there are "pre- school" programmes that are designed to
prepare young children for entry into the formal primary school system. Rather
than using any one of these terms to include the others, the term <u>Early
Childhood Care and Education, (ECCE)</u> has been chosen as the rubric under
which all the variations are to be considered.<p>
<p>
     Thus, for the purposes of this paper, early childhood care and education
will include all those situations where: (1) the care of the child is
tranferred from the parent to a caregiver who is outside the family system; (b)
this transfer is formalised in the sense that there is a recognized economic
value to the care being provided (whether or not the parent is actually
involved in direct payment); and (c) there is a definite pattern to the care
being provided over time.  This definition excludes situations where members of
the extended family take on care-giving responsibilities.  It also excludes
situations where occassional care is needed or given (e.g. babysitting) on an
irregular basis.  <p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>II. FACTORS AFFECTING THE USE OF EARLY CHILDHOOD CARE AND
EDUCATION</b><p>
<b>PROGRAMMES FOR THE DELIVERY OF MCH COMPONENTS OF PHC</b><p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
                             No sector involved in socio-economic development
<p>
                             can function properly in isolation. Activities in
one impinge on the goals of another...Primary health care, too, requires the
support of other sectors; these sectors can also serve as entry points for the
development and implementation of primary health care.<p>
<p>
                                                   WHO/UNICEF, 1978, p.16<p>
<p>
<b>A. The potential and the complexity</b><p>
<p>
     One sector that is an obvious point of entry for primary health care is
the early childhood care and education sector.  When one begins to examine that
statement, however, a problem is immediately apparent: ECCE is not a sector.
Those programmes that can be classified in one way or another as an ECCE effort
are found within more than one sector.  ECCE programming touches and relies on
a multiplicity of sectors. While this opens up possibilities, it also presents
problems since it is difficult to identify a single entry point for the
development of collaborative programming.<p>
<p>
     The difficulty of working within a variety of sectors is only one of the
dimensions to be considered in developing an intervention strategy. In order to
determine the reality of introducing primary and maternal and child health care
into existing ECCE systems, more information is needed about the supports for
integrating the systems, and the constraints to such a process. <p>
<p>
<p>
<b>B. Positive/Supportive factors</b><p>
<p>
     There are a variety of characteristics of early childhood education
programmes which would suggest and provide support for their usage for the
delivery of the MCH components of PHC.<p>
<p>
          1. <u>Early childhood care and education programmes exist in some
form in all parts of the world</u>.   They have been begun under the trees in
rural Africa, and organized in the steets of Chile. They have also been
developed through national initiatives devoted to promoting the healthy growth
and development of all children, as in Mauritius and parts of southeast Asia.
While in many instances an infrastructure exists to support these programmes,
they are frequently underutilized in terms of the range of services that could
be provided. In general, those programmes not sponsored by <p>
the health sector have not taken up the health care and health monitoring needs
of children and mothers.  Even fewer have responded to the opportunities
presented for complementing, and building on, existing primary health care
activities, and for creating opportunities for cognitive and psycho-social
stimulation. For example, many feeding programmes focus all their energy on
providing nutritional supplementation to young children; they are unaware of
the necessity for psycho-social stimulation, and the potential that their
programme offers to provide such stimulation.<p>
<p>
          2.  While ECCE programmes generally reach only a small percentage of
the eligible population, <u>they have the potential to reach a large percentage
of the population</u>.  In many developing countries approximately 40% of the
population is under the age of 15. More than a third of these are under the age
of 5 (World Bank, 1984, p.67).  By taking into account young children's
families, ECCE programmes can touch the lives of more than half the population.
         <p>
<p>
          3. <u>ECCE services are expanding rapidly</u> due to increasing
demand. The demand has come from urban and rural communities, from those
wanting better health care, from those concerned with supporting the child's
cognitive development, from those seeking a safe place for their child. The
demand is illustrated by the increase in the numbers of ECCE centers available
over the years.  For example, in Kenya in 1968, ECCE programmes served 175,000
children; by 1980 that number had increased to 300,000.  The increase is much
more dramatic in Tanzania. In 1969 there were only 280 centers.  By 1980 there
were 3,500.  Even so, the programmes which exist serve only 6% of the eligible
population. (Otaala, 1981, p.49) There is still a lot of room for growth, and
there is a demand that will lead to the development of an increased number of
ECCE programmes.<p>
<p>
          4. <u>Early childhood care and education programmes have a social
attractiveness and acceptability that invites participation from families that
might not avail themselves of primary health care services</u>.  For peoples in
many parts of the world, early childhood care and education programmes are a
priority. Given a choice, a community may well begin by creating an ECCE
programme. An example comes from Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia where the health sector
was interested in establishing health care services. But, the community was
interested in early childhood care and income generating activities.  Once
these were esablished, then the community was open to the development of health
care services. Thus, support for and the utilization of early childhood care
and education programmes, in many settings, may be more regular than is often
the case with health care and family planning services.<p>
<p>
          5. <u>Primary health care is a logical extension of the current
services</u> being provided within early childhood care and education
programmes--be they only custodial care or educational. For example, a
non-formal education programme for pre-school aged children in Puno, Peru, has
been used as the base for the implementation of a number of health programmes.
It provided a setting for a regional immunization programme, touching the lives
of families in the community as well as the children served in the programme.
Health care is a part of the child's total development, and as such should be
seen and provided within the context of children's services.<p>
<p>
          6. <u>Early childhood care and education programmes are a way of
promoting family and community as well as child development</u>, thus meeting
<p>
primary health care goals for the population in addition to meeting the needs
of the young child.  As noted in an evaluation of a parent education program in
Indonesia,<p>
<p>
          Clearly the programme, while concentrating on mental<p>
          stimulation of children, touches many other areas of<p>
          concern of women--health, nutrition, family planning,<p>
          participation in community affairs.  As confidence and<p>
          competence grow, women contribute not only to their own<p>
          development, but to community and national development.<p>
          A child development program becomes increasingly <p>
          connected to over-all development objectives. <p>
                                                Stein, 1985, p.10<p>
<p>
          7.<u>Early childhood care and education programmes are gaining
national and international support</u>. In a number of instances in Latin
America and South East Asia, national legislation exists which supports the
development of ECCE programmes. Frequently such enabling legislation is
connected with Labour Law which requires businesses with more than a given
number of women employees to provide day care.  Legislation supportive of ECCE
programming may also be promoted by the education sector.  In Southeast Asia
the result of government support for the development of educationally focused
pre-school programmes has lead to the lowering of the school entrance age; it
is now 5 years of age in Burma and Sri Lanka, and Thailand is aiming to achieve
the same goal (UNESCO, <p>
1983, p.7).<p>
         8. <u>Many of the health and nutritional problems associated with
conditions of poverty, if identified early, can be managed using appropriate
and simple technologies</u>.  Technology in this instance is meant to include
"not only scientifically sound equipment and information but also certain
organizational elements." (Rohde and Hendrata, 1982, p.212). These technologies
are currently available and can be managed by persons with relatively low
levels of training, and delivered through other than health care centres.
There is every reason to believe that the health and nutrition technologies are
suited to most early childhood care and education programmes which are in
place, or could be developed with a minimum of cost and back-up support. An
example of such technologies are the activities and strategies for health
promotion described in <u>Where There is No Doctor</u>. (Werner, 1977).<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>C. Constraints</b><p>
<p>
          l. The <u>multiplicity of mandates</u> which have lead to the
development of ECCE programmes make it difficult to identify an entry point for
primary health care.  Early childhood care and education, because it is closely
intertwined with childrearing, is a phenomenon in which almost everyone feels
he or she should have a say--from those in health to education to public
welfare to community development, to labour. What this means is that there is
no one group that can be approached to work with to better integrate health
care into ECCE service delivery. By looking at Thailand, for example, it is
possible to illustrate the issue. It is estimated that only 2% of the 0-6 age
group are being served through some type of ECCE effort (UNESCO, 1983, p.4).
Yet, even with so few children being served, programmes have been developed by
the following sectors: child nutrition centres are run by the Department of
Health; child development centres are  operated by the Department of Community
<p>
Development; kindergarten, or "head start" centres are run by the Department of
Education; day-care centres are operated by metropolitan city municipalities;
and private enterprise facilities provide services to yet another group of
children.<p>
<p>
     To make things even more difficult, those that are operating programmes
may not be aware of other groups in the community who are operating ECCE
programmes. Those in the private sector frequently do not coordinate their
efforts with those in health, education, or social welfare. And, since the
public sectors have different goals for offering services to young children,
parallel programmes may be developed. In some instances this leads to more
spaces being available within ECCE programmes than there are children in the
community, while in other communities there are no services. An example of this
comes from Iraq where, within two blocks of each other, there are day care
centres run by the General Federation of Iraqi Women and the Ministry of Labor
and Social Affairs.  Both centres operate at less than half of their capacity,
thus greatly increasing per pupil costs. (Evans, 1984).<p>
<p>
          2. The multiple needs of children, requires a <u>multi-sectoral
approach to the integration of the MCH components of PHC and ECCE
programming</u>. Such an approach is consuming of both time and energy, and can
only be developed with the cooperation of all sectors involved.  A successful
approach to multi-sectoral programming appears to be to begin by providing a
core service.  Once that becomes well established, it is then possible to add
additional services.  An example comes from Indonesia where a parent education
programme--which includes weekly meetings, a toy lending library and extensive
follow-up with families--was added to an already successful family planning and
nutrition programme. (Stein, 1985). The existence of the infrastructure
developed in the existing programme allowed the parent education programme to
succeed.<p>
<p>
          3. A primary constraint on using ECCE efforts to implement primary
health care components is that <u>many projects are developed on a pilot basis,
but they neither continue beyond the programme development phase, nor are they
disseminated to other communities</u>. Even though a project shows promise, it
may not have staying power and thus it may not be appropriate to expend limited
resources to integrate PHC/MCH components into the project. Reasons for the
failure of projects have been delineated by authors such as Pyle (1984). The
reasons fall within four categories: resource constraints, lack of political
commitment at various levels; weak demand for services; and organizational,
implementation and management problems (Myers, 1984, p.4).  There are also
issues related to how to take a successful pilot project and disseminate it to
a wider audience.  Many organizational characteristics of community-based
projects necessarily change if the project is to be implemented nationally
(Pyle, 1984).  Thus, before investing in projects it is necessary to ask the
question of whether or not they could successfully undergo these organizational
changes if implemented on a large scale. <p>
<p>
        4. Because of the scarcity of resources, low cost alternative
approaches are being sought for the delivery of health care. <u>Early childhood
care and education programmes are low-cost services</u>. The programmes
arefrequently developed by the community and rely on trained volunteer or
paraprofessional staffing for day-to-day programme operation. What this means
is that those who work in these programmes generally have low levels of <p>
education, and once they receive training they are able to find higher paid
employment in related fields.  This has three implications.  First, programmes
are constantly in the position of training new staff; it is difficult to build
on experience and develop a cadre that can provide role models, peer support
and supervision. Second, health care planners need to be realistic about what
health care components can be introduced in ECCE programmes. Paraprofessional
staff may not have the capacity to develop the skills necessary to deliver
sophisticated health care services, although, as will be described later,
health care technology makes it possible for people with low levels of
education to deliver a wide variety of services. Third, training materials and
methodologies have to be geared to a very practical level, with on-going
support and supervision built into the training system. <p>
<p>
    <p>
<b>D. Overall Perspective.</b><p>
<p>
     In developing a strategy for delivering primary health care to all, the
health care community has been aware of the limits on its resources in relation
to what is required to accomplish the task of providing health to all by the
Year 2000. From the beginning it has been clear that a range of alternative
delivery systems need to be developed. The range of early childhood care and
education programmes that exist offer tremendous potential for delivery of
primary and matenal and child health care into communities.  Where ECCE
programmes are centralized and receive public support, there is a national
system that can be utilized for the introduction of the MCH components of PHC.
Of more interest to the health sector, however, are those ECCE programmes that
serve those most in need of services--the urban and rural poor--that are
unlikely to avail themselves of health services that exist or who live in areas
where health services are scarce.  In some of these areas early childhood care
and eduation programmes have been begun, many through local initiative; others
through the efforts of private voluntary organizations who have implemented an
ECCE programme in response to a community-defined need.  <p>
<p>
     Those involved in planning health care programmes have looked to community
involvement as a way of promoting health care delivery. <p>
<p>
          At the beginning of the past decade, as a consequence<br>
          of the requirements of the extension of health services<br>
          coverage, Member States...concentrated their efforts<br>
          on the organization and training of community resources<br>
          for the promotion of health activities and the delivery<br>
          of some specific services.  The experience has shown <br>
          that these constitute a valuable instrument for the<br>
          extension of health services with primary health care,<br>
          in spite of the fact that their functions, their <br>
          relationship with the institutional system, and the <br>
          training methods show a great variation from country<br>
          to country. PAHO, 1980, p. 76.<p>
<p>
<p>
     Linkage of the MCH components of PHC with early childhood care and
education programmes is seen as an opportunity to further assess the role that
communities can play in delivering quality health and development services to
young children and their families.  In particular, there is interest in 
maximizing the extent to which persons from the community, with basic training
in screening, disease management and nutrition, can complement the health and
welfare sectors and provide a meaningful extension to primary health care
programmes.<p>
<p>
     In sum, while there are a variety of dimensions which must be taken into
consideration when attempting to successfully integrate health, education and
social services for young children and their families, there are some
compelling reasons for using ECCE programmes for the delivery of health care
components. These include the current demand for ECCE programmes and thus their
growth, the fact that these programmes are socially attractive and draw people
not currently served by MCH and/or PHC systems, the need for the identification
and use of low cost delivery systems, and the fact that there is the
possibility for the development of a multi-sectoral approach to meeting the
needs of young children and their families.<p>
     <p>
     So far in the discussion no reference has been made to the current
linkages between the health care community and early chidhood care and
education programmes.  In fact, linkages have been made in both directions.
There are health based programmes that have successfully integrated stimulation
and psycho-social concerns into their programming.  Likewise, there are early
childhood care and education programmes that have integrated a variety of
health care components into their activities.  In the section which follows
there is a more complete delineation of the continuum of linkages which
currently exist.  The continuum provides an understanding of the ways in which
the various services have already been linked, and makes it 
possible to identify the gaps in linkage.      <p>
<p>
<p>
<b>III. IN WHAT WAYS ARE EARLY CHILDHOOD CARE AND EDUCATION
PROGRAMMES</b><p>
<b>CURRENTLY LINKED TO THE HEALTH CARE COMMUNITY?</b><p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
     In the discussion to this point the current relationship between the
health care sector and ECCE programmes has not been described. There are
linkages in a number of instances.  It is important to know what linkages exist
in order to understand the state of the art and to know what can be built upon
to make the linkages more complete and useful. <p>
<p>
     The linkages can be envisioned along a continuum.  One end of the
continuum is represented by ECCE programmes that are run and/or financed by the
health sector.  At the other end are those ECCE programmes that have no linkage
with the health care community.<p>
<p>
<p>
<pre>
1___________2_____________3_____________4___________5__________
   Health         Served by            Workshops        Provider       No Linkage
    sector         health sector          by health          initiative
   sponsorship     monitoring              sector             training
</pre>
<p>
     1. Within the <u>ECCE programmes sponsored by the health sector</u> there
are two major categories:  programmes that are operated exclusively by health
personnel, and those that are part of multi-sector approaches, where the health
sector shares sponsorship. An example of the first type are nutrition
programmes where the primary goal is to rehabilitate malnourished children and
to prevent future malnutrition. Such rehabilitation centres have been
established in residential settings in Chile. The centres focus their attention
on children under the age of two. The child leaves the centre when weight and
height are within the normal range. While in the programme the child also
receives psycho- motor and some cognitive stimulation. (Mauras, 1979, p.18) In
general, these programmes focus almost exclusively on nutrition issues; only a
relatively small percentage have recognized the child's need for physical,
cognitive and psycho-social stimulation.<p>
<p>
     The other category of health sector sponsored programmes includes those
that are part of multi-sectoral efforts to bring integrated care services to
young children.  A good example of this type of ECCE effort is the Integrated
Child Development Services (ICDS) programme in India.  From the beginning, the
programme was designed to provide immunizations and health check ups, referral
services, supplementary nutrition, non-formal preschool education and nutrition
and health education for parents.<p>
<p>
<p>
     2. At the next point on the continuum are <u>ECCE programmes that are
served by health care providers</u>.  Service can be provided in two ways.
First, it can be provided directly to children and their families by health
care providers who come to the ECCE setting and deliver a given service.  For
example, in some instances there are regularly scheduled visits (weekly,
bi-weekly or monthly) to check on the children's general health.  This model of
monitoring children's development is used in Iraq, where a doctor makes a bi-
weekly visit to each ECCE centre to examine children. In other instances health
care providers come to ECCE settings on an irregular basis, but for a specific
purpose (i.e. to give immunizations, to check health standards in the ECCE
setting, etc.).  An example comes from Mauritius were UNICEF has sponsored a
nationwide screening of preschool children by the School Health Servcies.  The
screening takes place within the pre-primary schools.<p>
<p>
     Second, health care personnel can work directly with ECCE providers. The
most common activity within this category is the training and on- going support
of ECCE staff who are expected to deliver quality health care, monitor growth
and development, identify developmental problems, etc., as a part of their work
in the ECCE programme.  When health care personnel work with ECCE staff in this
way they are generally available on a regular basis and can be called upon if
the ECCE providers want more information, or feel a child needs further
observation.<p>
<p>
     3. Moving along the continuum are <u>one-time training courses/workshops
offered by health care staff</u>.  For example, in a given region health care
staff may give a short course on the identification of malnutrition, or on the
use of growth charts, or on necessary health standards for an ECCE setting. The
health care staff generally are not available for follow-up or consultation. At
some time in the future they may offer another course in the same or a
neighboring community.  In these instances it is unlikely for the health care
provider to actually see the ECCE setting, or to interact on a one-to-one basis
with the ECCE staff.  ECCE staff are expected to take what is presented in the
course and apply it in on their own, but they get no feedback from health care
personnel on how adequately they are performing their task.<p>
<p>
     4. Somewhat further along on the continuum are <u>early childhood care and
education programmes that have no formal connection with the health care
sector, but there is an informal linkage</u>.  In these instances ECCE
providers have taken the initiative.  They are aware of the importance of good
health care and attempt to provide a healthy environment for the children and
teach the children good health habits (i.e. to wash hands). In some instances
the health care information is a part of the curriculum.  In other instances
providers seek out and use information that is available to the general
public--pamphlets on nutrition designed to be used with parents, or information
on sanitation developed for the community as a whole, etc.  In addition, ECCE
providers may call upon health personnel to provide a specific service to the
programme (i.e. to test a given child, to teach the group something related to
health care).<p>
<p>
     5. At the end of the continuum are <u>early childhood care and education
programmes that have no linkage at all with the health care sector</u>.  No
services are provided to the ECCE programme by the health sector, and the ECCE
personnel have received no training in health care issues.  Neither have the
ECCE staff sought health care information.  There are a number of reasons why
<p>
the providers in this instance are not linked in any way with the health
sector. First, they may not be aware of the need to think about health care
beyond what they feel they themselves know and can do.  Second, they may be
aware of the need to know more, but there may not be any resources available to
help them learn more about and/or incorporate health care into their daily
work.   Examples of programmes with no linkages to the health community are
those which have been developed by communities with little or no assistance
from public or private agencies.  These "open air" programmes utilize only the
resources available in the community, and while the organizers may have some
sense of what children need, they generally do not have the skills and
knowledge to develop a curriculum to meet children's multiple health,
nutrition, and stimulation needs.<p>
<p>
<p>
     The continuum of health sector and ECCE linkages represents a simplistic
way of categorizing ECCE programmes. To develop useful intervention strategies,
however, more depth of understanding of ECCE programmes is needed. In the next
section three typologies, or classifications, of ECCE programmes are provided.
Each allows a systematic analysis of ECCE efforts that can be used by WHO to
best design intervetions to support the delivery of the MCh components of PHC
within the context of ECCE programming.<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>IV. DEVELOPING TYPOLOGIES FOR EARLY CHILDHOOD CARE AND 
EDUCATION PROGRAMMES</b><p>
<p>
<p>
     A typology is a systematic classification. It provides a way of taking the
range of early childhood care and education programmes that exist and examining
them in a systematic way. By creating a typology it is possible to delineate
some of the important features of ECCE programmes and then to make decisions
about the kind of interface that is needed to utilize ECCE programmes for the
delivery of health care.  In trying to develop a typology that would be useful
to WHO, it quickly became evident that there is no single typology of ECCE
programmes that provides all the information needed to work with ECCE
programmes. There are at least three dimensions that can be used to
systematically classify these programmes, all of which affect their ability to
be used in the delivery of MCH services.  For example, ECCE programmes can be
categorized based on where children are served-- the <u>setting</u>.  They can
also be classified according to who provides support for the programme--the
<u>sponsor</u>. Another classification can be made based on <u>programme
characteristics</u>-- the goals, target population, curriculum, staffing,
materials available, and degree of parental and community participation. <p>
<p>
     All of these typologies are useful and provide important information to
those working with ECCE programmes.  In this section of the paper we will
define the categories within each of these three typologies.  In Section V,
case studies of a variety of ECCE programmes will be provided to illustrate the
interaction between the three typologies.  The setting category will provide
the framework for the case studies. As the range of settings is described in
this chapter, reference will be made to countries within which that particular
setting has been used for the delivery of early childhood care and education
programmes. A more complete description of the programme will be provided in
Section V.<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>A. Typology I. <u>SETTING</u></b><p>
<p>
  This typology represents a classification of ECCE programmes based on
where they are located physically. Where ECCE programmes are located will
influence which health care components are delivered and how. In addition, from
the information available it is possible to determine what supports would be
needed if these settings were to be utilized for the delivery of primary health
care services.  The order in which the various settings are discussed does not
suggest priority settings for the delivery of ECCE services. It represents a
continuum of care from the home to the wider community.<p>
1.  In the <u>Home</u>. ECCE programmes where the child receives
the benefit of the programme in his or her home do not meet our earlier
definition of early childhood care and education programmes in the sense the
the parent is the primary caretaker and there is no out-of-home care for the
child.  However, these programmes are important to discuss since they represent
one viable way of providing quality health care and stimulation for the child.
These programmes generally focus on teaching parents or other family members
how to provide for the young child's health, nutrition, cognitive and
psycho-social needs.<p>
<p>
     There are three basic models that fall within this category.  There are
home-based parent education programmes where the ECCE provider-- generally
referred to as a home visitor or home teacher--works on a one-to-one basis with
the mother and child dyad. The primary example to be described in Section V
comes from Peru. Within the second model, parent education occurs in a
center-based setting.  Parent groups are organized and a course is provided,
generally with regular meetings over a defined period of time.  Such a
programme has been developed in Chile. The third model is the CHILD-to-child
system where children are taught basic health care and monitoring and use their
skills and knowledge with younger siblings.  Kenya has used the CHILD-to-child
approach in different ways in different communities.<p>
<b></b><p>
         2. In the <u>Neighborhood</u>.  Within this category are ECCE
programmes that operate in homes in the community. These are generally known as
Child Minding or Family Day Care. These may be developed (by the public or
private sector) as a part of a formal system of care or they may be created
informally as a result of the initiative of the provider. Examples of such
programmes come from Venezuela, Colombia, Ecuador and Maldive.<p>
<b></b><p>
         3. At the <u>Work place</u>.  These are ECCE programmes that have
been developed in conjunction with women's place of work--either within the
formal sector or in relation to the non-formal or traditional sector.  In some
instances governments have mandated that businesses in the formal sector, with
a given number of women employees, provide daycare for their employee's
children.  Where there have been mechanisms to enforce this legislation,
industry related daycare--either at the workplace or through the sponsoring or
subsidization of a variety of daycare programmes near the place of work--has
become a reality. These systems have been implemented extensively in the
developed countries.  They are becoming more common in the developing world.
Within India there are examples of industry related ECCE programmes. <p>
<b></b><p>
     In instances of early childhood care and education programmes within
the non-formal sector are those that have been developed in relation to women's
traditional work. A good example comes from Ghana where a programme was
developed in the market place. Another example comes from an agricultural
setting in Senegal. While industry sponsored daycare has been developed largely
as a result of national legislation and policy, the marketplace and
agricultural ECCE programmes have been developed on the community level in
response to a recognition of women's and children's needs in those particular
settings.<p>
<b></b><p>
         4. In <u>children's centres</u>. Within this classification are
all the ECCE programmes that are offered within a centre or building
specifically designed to provide some type of service to young children in the
community.   As can be imagined, this category encompasses a range of ECCE
efforts, and <p>
constitutes the numerical majority of ECCE programmes. Within this category
these are three sub-categories.  There is one that includes what are being
referred to as "open air" programmes.  What characterises these programmes is
the fact that, by and large, they are community initiated and rely primarily on
community resources for their operation and continuation.  Many of them began
in the out-of-doors because no other facilities were available; thus the name
"open air".  Examples come from Zimbabwe, Kenya, and Tanzania in Africa, and
from Chile, Brasil, and Mexico.<p>
<b></b><p>
    The second sub-category are all the ECCE programmes that have been
implemented in primary schools.  The focus of the majority of these programmes
is on preparing children for the primary school; they are offered to children
one to two years before they would enter school. A number of countries within
Southeast Asia (Thailand and Korea) provide examples of programmes operated in
primary school settings. An additional example comes from Haiti. <p>
<b></b><p>
    Integrated care programmes comprise the third sub-category.  These are
ECCE efforts that were developed in an attempt to, from the beginning, meet the
multiple needs of young children, and often their families. The Integrated
Child Development Services (ICDS) programme in India is an example, as are
programmes in Peru and Haiti.<p>
<b></b><p>
          5. <u>In adult and/or community centres</u>. Within this category
are the early childhood care and education programmes that have been developed
in conjunction with a service being provided for adults.  In some instances the
ECCE programmes offered in these facilities were an outgrowth of other center
activities.  In other instances, the ECCE programme was the first service
offered in what was meant to be a primary health care or community centre; it
then served as a drawing point for the community. <p>
<b></b><p>
    The sub-categories under this heading are based on sponsorship.  Those
included are: 1. early childhood care and education programmes operated in
health centres, as in Malaysia. 2. Another set have been developed in
connection with nutrition programming, an example of which comes from
Indonesia. 3. ECCE programmes have also been created in support of women and
development programmes.  Two examples illustrate this sub-category--Iraq and
Brasil.  4. ECCE initiatives developed as a part of community development
efforts constitute another sub-category.  Bolivia is used to exemplify the
case.  5. And last, but not least, are ECCE programmes operated by religious
denominational groups.  Programmes in Swaziland are described as an example of
the impact of programmes within this sub-category.   <p>
<b></b><p>
    Thus the typology based on <u>setting</u> provides five large
categories of programmes.  What becomes clear as the different programmes are
reviewed is that it is not enough to know <u>where</u> the ECCE programme is
located.  It is also important to know <u>who</u> in involved in creating and
implementing the ECCE programme. (In fact, within the fifth category of
setting, sponsorhip became a way of defining sub-categories.) Therefore, a
typology based on <u>sponsorship</u> <p>
is also an appropriate way to categorize ECCE programmes. <p>
<b></b><p>
<b>B. Typology II. <u>SPONSORS</u> (Funders and Implementers)</b><p>
<b></b><p>
     An important aspect of early childhood care and education programmes is
sponsorship. There are two aspects to sponsorship: programme funding and <p>
programme implementation or operation. It is not uncommon, for instance, for
those who provide initial funding and/or technical support for the programme to
have a time-limited involvement. The expectation is that after the programme is
established it will be maintained, at some level, by the population being
served. In other instances, funders and operators are one and the same. Those
responsible for funding the programme actually operate the programme and
maintain it over time.  <p>
<b></b><p>
     The ability to deliver MCH and/or PHC services through early childhood
care and education initiatives will depend on who funds and/or implemements the
programme. Thus, in seeking ways to introduce primary health care into ECCE
settings it is important to be able to differentiate between those who provide
initial support and those who maintain the programme over time.  It is
necessary to acknowledge and plan for the fact that funders and implementers--
in the short- and long-term--play different roles in ECCE programming, and they
would have different roles in the introduction and/or upgrading of public
health care services. More importantly, however, to develop a successful
intervention strategy, it is necessary to understand the organizational and
bureaucratic structure within which the sponsor operates.<p>
<b></b><p>
     Sponsors of ECCE programmes can be divided into four groups. 1. There
are the multi-national donors who do programme planning from an international
perspective.  2. There are governmental agencies and organizations whose
involvement in ECCE activities is based on nationally defined needs, goals and
resources. 3. There are also a range of non-governmental and private voluntary
agencies that operate either internationally or nationally.  4. And, last, but
not least, are community-based sponsors--existing groups that create an ECCE
programme or groups that have been organised specifically for the purpose of
developing an ECCE programme.<p>
<b></b><p>
         1. <u>Multi-national donor agencies</u> generally provide
short-term support.  Included in this category are agencies and organizations
such as WHO, UNICEF, UNESCO, USAID and other bi- lateral donor agencies.  In
general, these groups establish target populations to serve, develop an agency
policy about how that group is to be reached, and then work with appropriate
national ministries to develop programmes for the target population, based on
national goals and resources.  In general, these agencies provide funding and
technical assistance which supports programme development; they do not provide
funding for on-going programme support.<p>
<b></b><p>
         2. <u>Governmental</u> ministries, agencies and organizations
frequently play the role of funder and implementer.  These agencies are
mandated to carry out national policy.  If early childhood care and education
programmes are seen as a national priority, then a governmental ministry will
be charged with the responsibility for developing, implementing and operating
related programmes.  Sometimes only public sector funds are used in the
development of national programmes.  In other instances, the government
encourages private sector involvement as well.  One of the challenges of
working with ECCE programmes is that they have been developed by and operated
under the mandate of a variety of national ministries, including education,
welfare, health, labour, social affairs, women's affairs, agriculture, or some
combination of these.   <p>
<b></b><p>
     Within each of these ministries the rationale for the development of
ECCE programmes, the population to be served, specific programme goals, the

curriculum, staffing, and resources available to the programme are quite
different.  In order to work with government officials within the various
ministries, it is important to know their bias and concerns if they are to be
approached to expand the range of services they currently provide. For example,
it will take a different strategy to work with the Ministry of Education than
it will to work with the Ministry of Labour; the rationale for their
involvement in ECCE programming is different, they serve different
constituents, and implement different types of programmes.<p>
<b></b><p>
     It is also important to recognize that governmental involvement in
early childhood care and education programmes occurs at the regional or county
level, and at the city or local level, as well as at the national level. While
being responsive to national policy, the regional and local government groups
frequently have a great deal of autonomy in establishing priorities and
creating programmes designed to meet the specific needs of their constituency.
             <p>
     There is yet another set of quasi-governmental agencies/organizations
that have been very involved in the development of early childhood care and
education programmes.  These agencies are generally established through special
funding and have been created to fulfill a particular mandate. In many
instances those working in these agencies have the freedom and resources to
develop innovative programmes that can be put into place relatively rapidly;
they do not have to operate within the bureaucratic structure which exists
within many ministries. Examples of such agencies include the Children's
Foundation in Venezuela, a child welfare agency headed by the First Lady of the
Republic.  A comparable institute also exists in Ecuador (Instituto Nacional de
Ninos y la Familia). The General Federation of Iraqi Women is yetanother
example.  All of these agencies have had a significant role in the development
of early childhood care and education programmes in their country.<p>
<b>               </b><p>
        3. <u>Non-governmental (NGO), Private Voluntary Organizations
(PVO)</u>. These groups exist outside any governmental structure. They can be
found within the international community, or they may operate at the national
level,
<b>or their scope may encompass only the local community.</b><p>
              a. At the <u>international</u> level there are a variety of
groups, organized primarily around the provision of disaster relief and/or
nutritional supplementation. Included in this category are such groups as Save
the Children, Christian Children's Fund, Oxfam, The International Red Cross,
CARITAS, etc.  These groups were originally formed to address <u>survival</u>
issues. At this point in time some of the groups are examining the long-term
impact of their programmes and are in the process of attempting to create
additional programmes aimed at <u>development</u>. For example, Christian
Children's Fund, a child sponsorship organization, uses some of its monies to
create schools and community development centres which address the multiple
needs of the child and community rather than only providing nutritional
supplements to the sponsored child.<p>
<b></b><p>
               b. At the <u>national</u> level there are church-related and
welfare organizations that have developed a range of ECCE programmes.  In
addition, there are women's voluntary organizations which have seen the need
for early childhood care and education programmes and have taken the initiative
to develop such programmes within their country.  For example, the Botswana
Council of Women, a private voluntary membership organization, has raised the
funds necessary to establish day care centres to support women's increased
involvement in the wage economy. <p>
<b></b><p>
         4. At the <u>local</u> level there are programmes that are
developed by and from within the community.  These are either begun by an
existing group or a community group evolves to work specifically on the
development of an ECCE programme. In either instance, the community perceives a
need for child care and a programme is created. Sometimes the programme begins
with support from an agency or organization outside the community; it is
maintained by community members once it is underway.  This generally occurs
when international donor agencies are involved in community development efforts
within a community. In other instances the community begins the programme, and
once it has proven viable the community is able to secure resources from
outside the community (governmental or non-governmental) for continuation of
the programme.   This has occurred in Zimbabwe where communities have begun
schools in any space that is available. Both the government and national PVOs
have then provided some training and resources to upgrade the services
provided.<p>
<b></b><p>
     Private voluntary organizations and non-governmental agencies are
financed through a variety of mechanisms.  Some operate on the basis of
subscriptions. The UN related organizations are a primary example. A second
source of funds are individual gifts/private philanthropy.  In addition,
individual volunteer time and energy are critical to the operation of most PVO
organizations, particularly those that operate at the community level. Many
community-based ECCE programmes are able to exist because local resources are
available to the programme.  These take the form of: cash, in-kind goods, and
labour (meal preparation, construction and maintenance of facilities). Other
PVOs charge fees for the programmes they operate, recuperating the costs of the
programme by participant reimbursement.  The amount a given NGO/PVO is able to
spend on ECCE activities is determined by the organization's mandate and
related budget.  The potential for these groups to expand their service to
young children varies greatly among the NGO/PVOs.<p>
<b></b><p>
     In sum, there are a range of sponsors that can and have been involved
in the development of early childhood care and education programmes. Sponsors
play a variety of roles--from helping to make communities aware of the need for
ECCE programmes, to providing initial funding and technical assistance in
support of the effort, to providing the necessary on-going support to allow the
programme to operate.  Each organization has its own reason for being involved
in early childhood programming.  The motivation behind a group's involvement
will, to a large extent, determine the nature of the programme. Yet, by knowing
the sponsor it is not always possible to predict what happens on a day-to-day
basis with the children being served. There are a number of variables that help
to determine the nature of service provision. Within the third typology,
<u>programme characteristics</u>, an attempt is made to categorize ECCE
programmes on the basis a variety of these dimensions.<p>
<b>     </b><p>
<b>C. Typology III. <u>Programme Characteristics</u></b><p>
<b></b><p>
     This typology classifies ECCE programmes by the characteristics of the
programmes themselves, regardless of where they are located or who sponsors
them. This typology is based on what the programme looks like on a day-to-day
basis.   It is important to have an understanding of programme characteristics
in order to make an assessment of whether or not it would be worth investing
valuable resources to link with a specific effort, and if so, what would be
needed to add a health care component to an existing programme. There are
two major sub-categories within this typology: external programme
characteristics, which have to do with the position and acceptance of the
programme in the community; and internal characteristics, including the
existing focus, content, structure, actors and resources--all the things that
contribute to the day-to-day reality of the programme.  <p>
<b></b><p>
          1. <u>External</u> characteristics.  Included in this sub-category
are the elements of a programme that let you know whether or not it is an
integral part of the community.  If the ECCE programme is well respected and a
part of the fabric of the community--rather than on the periphery of people's
lives--then there is a much greater likelihood that additional programme
components will be accepted and utilized by the people. There are a variety of
dimensions to be examined to know whether or not the programme is an integral
part of community activities.  These include:<p>
<b></b><p>
               a. <u>The physical location of the ECCE programme</u>.  Is it
located within easy reach of those being served?  If not, then it is unlikely
that it is successfully serving those most in need. An example of an
inappropriately placed programme was a nutrition recuperation programme
operated in Chile. The programme was developed in response to public outrage at
high rates of infant mortality due to malnutrition.  A series of recuperation
centres were established in refurbished homes in upper class neighborhoods.
One of the reasons for using the homes was to create an atmosphere that would
be less intimidating and cold than many hospitals. It was presumed that mothers
would feel more comfortable visiting and spending time with their children in a
home rather than in a hospital. <p>
<b></b><p>
    Another reason for locating the centres in the upper class areas of the
city was to assure that the programme had high visibility, demonstrating the
government's responsiveness to the need. To further promote visibility,
volunteers--upper class women--were asked to provide stimulation to the
children in the centres. These women became very involved in the programme.
However, the parents did not.  While the atmosphere was less like a hospital
setting, the neighborhoods where the centres were located were more
intimidating than hospitals. There was a great sociological/psychological and
physical distance between the recuperation centres and the child's home. Thus,
mothers seldom visited their children.<p>
<b></b><p>
      When the child was ready to go home--after having gained weight and
attained appropriate developmental milestones--the child was returned to a
family to whom the child was a stranger. Nothing had been done within the
context of the child's environment to assure that malnutriton would not
re-occur. Not too surprisingly, many of the children returned to the
recuperation centres several months later, once again suffering from
malnutrition (Colombo, et al., circa 1979). Thus, while the programme met some
short-term goals--decreasing infant mortality and malnutrition during the
child's first year of life--long-term goals were not realised.  The
socio-cultural and environmental variables that were a part of the cause of the
malnutrition were not addressed.  The programme was never embraced by the
community; it remained on the periphery until it was redesigned to include
parents in a significant way.<p>
<b></b><p>
               b. <u>The history of the programme within the community</u>.
Do the people within the community talk about their programme with pride? Has
it been able to meet community needs over time?  If the programme is seen as
providing 
quality services, then it is likely that the addition of other programme
components will be accepted. An example of this is the Sang Kancil programme in
squatter settlements in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia.  In this instance the medical
community was interested in creating maternal and child health services, but
there was little community support for the effort.  However,community members
were interested in creating an early childhood care and education programme and
income generating activities for women.  Those developing the programme were
responsive to community expressed needs.  Then, once the preschool and income
generating activities were well established and an integral part of the
people's lives, maternal and child health services were initiated in
conjunction with the existing programme and readily accepted (Yusof, 1982).
<p>
<b></b><p>
               c. <u>The extent and type of parent/community participation
in the programme</u>. Within current development planning, one of the
strategies most frequently advocated is to have strong community participation
in programme development--from the definition of the need, to development of a
plan of action, to project implementation, to evaluation of outcomes.  While
this strategy is utilized in the development of many basic services programmes,
it is seen as particularly important in relation to early childhood care and
education.  Within developed countries a strong argument has been made that the
community is the most appropriate level of social organization to implement and
manage child care systems (Bronfenbrener, 1980; Center for the Study of Public
Policy, 1971). It is argued that since parents are the policymakers in most
areas of their young children's lives, their involvement in the design and
operation of a early childhood care and education centre increases the
likelihood of continuity of experience between the home and school for the
child. This same argument is being made for parental and community involvement
in the implementation and management of ECCE programmes in developing
countries.   In an evaluation of an ECCE programme in Thailand, Siegel
states:<p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
         
<pre>
          When parents and village leaders have participated
          in planning of a centre before it opened, utilization
          and development of such centres have been the greatest
          ...Moreover, where parents have provided funds for, 
          and helped in constructing the centre, mothers become
          more deeply involved in the programme and transfer
          some of the child's day care experiences to the home.
                                               1973, p. 396
</pre><p>
The general consensus is that the greater the level of community
involvement, the more likely it is that the programme will meet community needs
and become an integral part of community life.  <p>
     However, the extent to which parents can and will become involved in
early childhood care and education progrmmes is affected by a number of
variables.  For example, there is <u>cultural variance</u> in the extent to
which it is deemed appropriate for parents to be involved in the eduation of
their children. In some societies women are responsible for care of the child,
but do not play a role in educating the child. Thus, they would not feel they
should be a part of the child's on-going education.  Another influence on
parental involvement is <u>the colonial tradition of education</u>, which
directly and indirectly lets parents know that once the child enters the formal
school system, the school takes on the responsibility of educating the child;
parents are not a part of the educational process.  Yet another variable is the
<u>time</u> that parents have available to be involved. Where early childhood
care and education programmes have been developed in response to needs for day
care, women are likely to have little, if any, time to be involved in the
day-to-day activities of the programme.  Other variables that affect the extent
of parent and community involvement in ECCE programmes are related to the
<u>political structure</u> of the programme--how it is organized and the extent
to which control for the programme is centralized or decentralized.  Where the
programme is designed and introduced from outside the community, there may be
little room for parent and community involvement. <p>
<p>
     2. <u>Internal</u> characteristics. The second sub-category of
programme characteristics has to do with all the things that affect the day-
to-day operation of the programme. Included in this sub-category are: a. the
target population and programme goals; b. the curriculum and services offered;
c. staffing; d. regulations and monitoring; e. materials available; f.
evaluation mechanisms in place; and g. the potential for dissemination and
replication.<p>
<p>
               a. <u>The target population and programme goals</u>.  To a
great extent programme goals are derived from an assessment of what is needed
by the children to be served. From the literature on early childhood care and
education programmes it is clear that at least the following categories of
children are provided for in ECCE settings:<p>
<b></b><p>
               (1) Children within specific age groups (i.e. those who will
enter the formal school system the following year), attend ECCE programmes in
order to be better prepared to enter the formal education system and/or have
enough basic education to receive vocational training.<p>
<b></b><p>
              (2) ECCE programmes are developed for children from low
income families in order to ameliorate environmental differences that put them
at a disadvantage when they enter the formal school system. The ultimate goal
of many of these programmes is to break the cycle of poverty.<p>
<b></b><p>
              (3) ECCE programmes have been provided for children of women
involved in the wage economy and income generating activities.  Such custodial
care is also provided to children of women involved in educational/training
programmes, making it possible for them to participate in these activities in
order to gain new knowledge and skills.  At a mimnimum these ECCE programmes
provide a safe place for children when their mothers are not available to care
for them.<p>
<b></b><p>
               (4) Children suffering from malnutrition have been provided
for through rehabilitation programmes. In some instances, psycho- motor
stimulation is also a programme activity.<p>
<b></b><p>
               (5) Developmentally disabled children and those with special
medical, therapeutic and educational needs, are provided with the specialized
services that their condition requires.<p>
<b></b><p>
<b>               (6) ECCE programmes are designed to meet the special needs of
children at risk due to family stress or transition. The programme goal is to
give them a secure environment and consistent caregiver, for at least a part of
the day.               </b><p>
<p>
<p>
               (7) A programme may be developed for children within a given
geographic region, providing them with the services that will support their
growth and development and bring them to an equitable position with children
from other regions of the country (i.e for rural children who lack stimulation,
or for children in urban squatter settlements who may lack adequate
caregiving).<p>
               (8) Children from other than the dominant cultural group may
be provided with experiences that will better prepare them to participate in
the formal school system (which is generally designed on the values and norms
of the dominant culture).<p>
<p>
               (9) ECCE programmes are also designed to meet community
development goals. In these instances, while providing direct service to
children, the ECCE programme is used as a way of reaching parents and other
community members, and ultimately getting them involved in developing a range
of basic services for the community.<p>
<p>
<p>
     These categories of target populations and programme goals are not
meant to be exhaustive, nor are they mutually exclusive.  Rather, they are
illustrative of the ways in which people have defined specific child
populations in need of ECCE services, and the goals associated with different
ECCE efforts.                    <p>
<p>
<p>
              b. <u>The curriculum and services provided</u>.  In this
instance, curriculum refers to the child's total experience in the ECCE
programme. Services refer to the specific activities provided for the child.
Generally programme developers clearly define the services to be provided,
based on their perception of what will meet the particular needs of and goals
for the target population.  In many instances the service has a singular focus
(i.e. it is a feeding programme for the prevention of malnutrition; a cognitive
stimulation programme to prepare children for the primary school system; a
custodial care setting where children are kept from harm). In many settings,
programme developers are not seeing the "curriculum"; they are not addressing
the multiple needs of children--the need for safety, good health, and physical,
psycho- social and cognitive stimulation. Opportunities are lost when staff are
not aware of the range of developmental needs and the activities that could be
provided to promote children's overall growth and development.<p>
<p>
               c. <u>Staffing</u>.  In almost all countries of the world,
early childhood care and education programmes have access to very limited
resources. Thus, whenever possible, para-professionals and volunteers provide
the staffing. In many instances training opportunities are limited. This is
justified by statements to the effect that any woman, because she is a woman,
can "take care" of children; there is no need to give her training. As a result
of the assumptions that child care is women's natural work and that little
training is needed, the work of child care providers is not valued.  Thus, pay
is minimal, if received at all.  <p>
<p>
     Some of the consequences of the low status and low pay are that those
with education and a range of job options do not seek positions within ECCE
programmes.  Thus programmes are staffed by those with limited education and
few options for other employment. If they are fortunate enough to receive
some training, they frequently move on to higher paid positions in other
fields. Yet, to have a quality ECCE programme, that is meeting the needs of
young children, it is necessary to have well trained staff who receive on-going
training and supervision in a curriculum that they believe in and
understand.<p>
<p>
     The challenge to those interested in introducing a programme component
into an ECCE setting is to make a realistic assessment of staff capabilities in
order to create appropriately focused training methodologies and materials. The
next challenge is to create a training of trainers system that would allow the
pre- and in- service training of teachers to occur on a regional level in order
for it to be relevant to the geographic and cultural setting.  The need for
such a system has been identified by those currently involved in pre-school
education in Eastern and Southern Africa:<p>
<pre>
          Regional training of pre-school teacher trainers is
          a need which has been identified and expressed within
          the Eastern Africa Region...If this need is met, it 
          would contribute some solutions to some of the current 
          problems in Pre-schooling...Qualified teachers would
          enhance the existing low image of pre-school workers.
          In addition, governments would be more willing to
          employ trained personnel on permanent bases. This
          would solve some of the current renumeration problems
          as well as offer better conditions of service. 
                                  Mbikusita-Lewanika, 1982, p.33.
</pre>
<p>
          d. <u>Regulations and monitoring</u>.  The purpose of regulations
and monitoring is to assure that children are being provided for in a safe,
heathly environment. Within the early childhood care and education literature
there is considerable discussion of issues related to regulation and
monitoring, illustrating the inherent tension between adequate standards of
health care provision and what can realistically be provided within a given
context (Zigler, et al., 1983; Ruopp, et al., 1979; Nelson, 1982). A related
tension is between standardized national norms and allowance for regional and
local variation. These tensions exist even in developed countries where there
are relatively more resources available to providers to make adequate provision
for the care of young children. The issue is exacerbated in developing
countries with little or no resources available for ECCE programming.<p>
<p>
     There is no question that young children should have a safe, healthy,
stimulating environment within which to play and learn.  The problem is that
the definition of the "bottom line" in these areas differs, depending on the
value system of the definer (Steiner, 1981; Harman, 1978). To some extent value
differences can and should be worked out in the goal setting process.  As goals
are established, they can be translated into operational terms which then
define standards and regulations.  Standards and regulations are frequently
developed in the following areas:<p>
<p>
          - the physical environment (inside and out): size, structure,
light,             air, safety, sanitation, etc.<p>
<p>
         - staff-child ratio and/or group size<p>
<p>
<p>
          - staffing--structure, training and/or credentials of
providers<p>
<p>
         - months of operation, length of day<p>
<p>
          - fees and financing<p>
<p>
          - services to be provided<p>
<p>
      Unfortunately, the balance of attention in early childhood care and
education programmes is frequently given to regulations and monitoring of the
<u>static</u>, easily measurable dimensions of a programme (i.e. the number of
square feet/child, the number of toilets, etc).  The more <u>dynamic</u>
dimensions which speak to the programme process, and which are associated with
quality programming (i.e. the patterns of adult-child, child-child and
child-environment interactions) are not so easily addressed in regulations nor
accessible through simple monitoring techniques.  However, they should be
included in the monitoring process.<p>
<p>
     The over-arching issue in thinking about regulations and monitoring of
ECCE programmes is that they represent a mix of public sector developed and
supported programmes and private initiatives often characterized by families
and communities working to develop systems that meet their particular needs.
The early childhood care and education literature would suggest that on the one
hand early childhood care and education will remain far more personal and
informal than other kinds of social programmes, yet, on the other hand, there
needs to be a means for assuring that quality experiences exist for children.
It is necessary to develop regulations while recognizing that family and
community values will vary across the range of settings that will, of
necessity, continue to exist (OEF, 1979; Bruner, 1980; Bronfenbrenner, 1980;
Clarke-Stewart, 1977). <p>
               <p>
              e. <u>Materials and resources</u>.  Some ECCE settings have
enough resources to make a variety of materials available--to the providers and
the children.  More commonly, however, ECCE programmes have few materials.
Providers are encouraged to make use of locally found objects to create things
for the children to play with and learn from.  In introducing a health care
component into the range of settings, it will be necessary to think about the
materials and resources that need to be made available to providers to
appropriately implement health care activities.<p>
              f. <u>Evaluation</u>.  In the majority of cases those
involved in developing early childhood care and education programmes respond to
an expressed need, bringing to the situation their knowledge and experience,
and the programme either succeeds or fails--or lies somewhere along that
continuum.  Frequently programme developers are not able to step back from
their day-to-day actions and responsibilities in order to understand what is
happening in the process.  Thus, regardless of the outcome, they are not able
to look at what happened along the way.  In order to assess programme
effectiveness, it is necessary for programmes to develop a <u>formative</u>
evaluation process to monitor on-going activities, and a <u>summative</u>
evaluation procedure to be able to assess whether or not programme goals are
being met.  This will be particularly important as an attempt is made to add or
upgrade 
programme components--to know whether or not appropriate procedures are used
to introduce the components and to assess if health care services are being
delivered effectively in the ECCE setting.<p>
<p>
               g. <u>Dissemination and Replication</u>.  Because of its
commitment to meeting the basic health needs of all by the year 2000, the World
Health Organization is necessarily seeking ways to have a widespread impact as
effectively and efficiently as possible.  Thus, it is logical that they would
seek to coordinate their efforts with successful large-scale ECCE programmes.
Few of these exist, and they seldom reach those most in need.  Thus, a second
strategy is to seek out successful projects serving those most at risk which
have the potential for "going-to-scale".  In this instance, going-to-scale
refers to the process of taking small-scale projects and developing them into
programmes that attempt to reach as many potential beneficiaries as possible--
regionally, nationally or even worldwide (Myers, 1985, p.1).<p>
<p>
    One of the problems with developing linkages with ECCE programmes that
appear to have the potential to go-to-scale, is that it is difficult to predict
what needs to happen for small-scale efforts to be implemented on a broader
basis. For example, in Pyle's (1984) review of seven successful pilot projects
in India, he identifies project characteristics which would necessarily change
if the projects were to be implemented on a national scale.  The organizational
and political factors that would come into play once the project moved beyond
its current boundaries would dramatically change the way in which the project
would operate.  There is some question as to whether or not these changes could
be made while maintaining the integrity of the project.<p>
<p>
    For example, in many successful projects community participation is
sought and highly valued.  In fact, community members frequently have
administrative control of a project.  They have autonomy in decision-making and
are encouraged to be flexible in developing solutions to their problems. In
going-to-scale, project administration would change; it would become
centralized, more rigid and part of a beauracracy.  This raises the question as
to the role of community participation when successful small-scale pilot
projects go-to-scale and are implemented on a region- or nation-wide basis.
Community participation and involvement, as well as other dimensions of
successful small-scale projects,  needs to be carefully examined if the
intention is to develop primary health care components that can become an
integrated part of currently successful projects that apparently have the
potential to expand and be disseminated to a wider audience.<p>
<b></b><p>
<b>     In sum, there are a variety of programme characteristics that interact
with one another to produce an ECCE programme.  Because of the interaction of
the variables, each ECCE programme is unique.  This is evident in the next
section where case studies of a number of early childhood care and education
programmes are described in some detail. </b>
<p>
<p>
  <b>V. CASE STUDIES OF SELECTED EARLY CHILDHOOD CARE AND EDUCATION
PROGRAMMES</b><p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
     Within this section there will be a description of a range of early
childhood care and education programmes.  Programmes have been chosen to
illustrate the typology based on <u>settings</u> within which ECCE programmes
are most commonly found. Then, within the description of the programmes the
reader will be provided with information relevant to the other two typologies:
<u>sponsors</u> (funders and implementers/operators), and <u>programme
characteristics</u>.  The basic categories within <u>settings</u> are: in the
home; in the neighborhood; at the workplace; in centres for children; and in
facilities created for adults and/or the community at large. <p>
<p>
<b></b><p>
<b>A. In the home.</b><p>
<p>
     As was indicated earlier, the in-home setting somewhat violates our
criterion for an early childhood care and education programme in the sense that
the caretaking function has not been transferred from the mother to another
individual.  In fact, in many of these programmes there is an emphasis on
fortifying the role of the mother as the first and most important provider or
teacher for her child.  These programmes are included in the discussion
because: (1) they have been demonstrated to provide important care and
stimulation to the young child, (2) they are frequently designed to target the
hardest to reach children, and (3) the process of working with a family member
is an example of a way to deliver health care services--for the young child and
other family members. <p>
<p>
     There are three types of programmes included in this category. (1) There
are  those that are designed to work on a one-to-one basis with the mother in
the home. Here the example is from Peru. (2) There are those that work with
parents--usually mothers--in a group, as found in the <u>Padres y Hijos</u>
programme in Chile. (3) Third are the programmes that focus on training older
children who then educate their siblings and family. The CHILD-to-child
methodology, as illustrated by a programme in Kenya. <p>
<p>
<p>
          l. An example of <u>in-home parent training is home visiting</u>,
exemplified by the Non-formal Home-based Initial Education Project (PRONOEI-BH)
implemented in Peru.  The project, an adaptation of the Portage Model developed
in the U.S.A., was begun on a pilot basis in 1977, in 2 urban settlements
(<u>Pueblos Jovenes</u>) in Lima, and in four rural villages near the city of
Cuzco.  The goal is to affect the child's development through the parent. Thus
the parent is the immediate focus of the intervention. The programme "attempts
to assure that parents acquire adequate childrearing and <p>
caretaking skills and to guide and help them implement these skills in their
daily routine." (Jesien, et.al., 1979, p.7) Those designing the programme were
aware of all the demands on families living in poverty.  Thus, the intent of
the programme was not to create yet another demand on already scarce time and
energy resources, "but rather to enhance the quality of the interaction between
child and parent in the time that is available." (Jesien, et.al., 1979, p.7).<p>
<p>
     In the programme, non-professional community women are trained to provide
weekly home visits to the mother and child dyad.  In Lima, the home visitors
(<u>animadoras</u>) had an average of a tenth grade education; in the rural
area around Cuzco <u>animadoras</u> had a fifth grade education.  In both
instances the home visitors were provided a total of four weeks of training in
child development, teaching techniques, construction of educational materials,
(Loftin, 1979). <p>
<p>
     During the first project year, each <u>animadora</u> worked with ten
families and, with the aid of a supervisor, developed an individualized
curriculum for the child (between the ages of 3 and 5), based on his or her
developmental level.  The <u>animadora</u> used a developmental profile with
the child and mother.  The profile summarizes diagnostic indicators which
define the child's developmental level on a range of dimensions. From the
profile the <u>animadora</u> suggests specific activities that the mother can
use with the child during the week to stimulate the child's development. <p>
<p>
     During the pilot year home visits were made on a weekly basis and
generally lasted for an hour. (The average number of visits a family received
during the first year of the programme was 31.6 in Lima; it was 24 visits in
the rural areas.) During the year there was a teacher's strike, and high rates
of illness, both among home visitors and the families visited. These factors
contributed to the few number of visits.<p>
<p>
       A research design was implemented as a part of the project so that
outcomes could be determined. In both the urban and rural settings control
groups were established, permitting appropriate pre- and post-testing
comparisons.  The findings indicated that those children who participated in
the programme clearly gained from the experience. What was particularly
important from the findings was the fact that children in the rural areas that
were in the programme were at age-appropriate developmental levels at the end
of the year; the children in the control group lost ground developmentally over
the year.  Those operating the programme argue that this finding indicates the
importance of providing early childhood care and education programmes for
children living in poor rural environments (Jesien et. al., 1979, p.22). <p>
<p>
     A cost analysis was done to determine if a home visiting programme of this
type was a valid way to use limited resources. It was estimated that it cost
U.S. $47.60/family in Lima and U.S. $55.68/family in the rural areas (in 1979
dollars) to deliver the programme during the first programme year.  These costs
included the high costs of starting-up a programme. It was estimated that in
subsequent years the programme could be deliverd at the cost of U.S.
$25.13/family -- a cost less than or equal to other non- formal preschool
education programmes in Peru. The authors of the evaluation conclude their
report with the following statement:<p>
<p>
<p>
After reviewing the project's results the Peruvian educational authorities
validated the home- based methodology as a cost effective and viable
alternative strategy for providing preschool services to urban and rural
poverty families.  Plans are underway for a significant expansion of program
sites and the extension of services to families with children 0-3 years of
age.<p>
                         Jesien, et. al., 1979, p.23 <p>
<p>
The Ministry of Education is presently using an adaptation of the model with
children from birth to two years of age in several urban areas along the coast
and in Puno, a rural area in the altiplano. Funding for the project was
provided by the Peruvian Ministry of Education and the Cooperative Educational
Service Agency of Portage, Wisconsin (CESA 12), through a grant from USAID.
Project planning, development and implementation were carried out by the
National Institute of Educational Research and Development (INIDE), and the
General Directorate of Initial Education (DIGEI).  Technical assistance was
provided by a team from the U.S.A. based Portage Project.<p>
<p>
          2. The second type of in-home programme is where <u>parents are
worked with in groups and expected to apply what they have learned as they care
for their child at home</u>.  An example of this type of ECCE programme comes
from Chile.  Known as the <u>Padres y Hijos</u> programme, it focuses on
working with groups of parents, representing the poorest of the poor, to better
the quality of family and community life.<p>
<p>
     The programme was begun in 1979 by the Centro de Investigaciones y
Desarrollo de la Educacion (CIDE), a private research and development center in
Chile. They began by working with 50 groups of 20 families living in the
Province of Osorno. Later an additional 18 groups were established in Santiago.
All families who participate in the programme have children between the ages of
4 and 6. <p>
<p>
     The programme consists of weekly meetings led by local people who are
trained to run the groups.  During the meetings a series of "themes" are
introduced.  There are 12 themes presented during the year. Each is designed to
be the focus of discussion and activity for a month. At the weekly meetings the
leader presents pictures that depict common incidents from the people's lives.
The pictures portray daily events that offer opportunities for stimulating the
child's learning.  The leader guides the discussion, focusing on what the
picture shows, what the child is doing developmentally, and what the parent can
do to support the child's learning in that situation.  Parents then talk about
things they can do with the child during the week.  They come up with
activities and games they can use with the child.  Toys are also available.
Parents can take them home for the week, or use them as models and make their
own.<p>
<p>
     While the programme has not undergone a formal evaluation, those operating
the programme feel it is a cost-effective way of working with parents to
educate them about child growth and development. The group meetings also serve
as a catalyst for the development of other community-based activities that
ultimately improve the standard of living within the community (Mauras, et.
al., 1979, p.18).<p>
<p>
<p>
          3.  The third type of programme within this category are <u>those
that focus on teaching older children to educate and care for younger
siblings</u>. The best example of this methodology are the CHILD-to-child
programmes.  They are aimed at giving older children the skills and knowledge
needed to improve the health and nutritional status of their younger siblings,
and the family.  The CHILD-to-child programme was conceived during the
International Year of the Child (1979), and has been established in a number of
developing countries.  Funded by the Overseas Development Administration (ODA)
in London, it is jointly sponsored by the Institute of Education in London and
the Tropical Child Health Unit of the Institute of Child Health, University of
London. The idea behind the programme is that elementary school-aged children
can be taught basic health care that they can provide to their younger
siblings.  <p>
<p>
Simple preventive and curative activities as well as games, play and
role-playing can be taught to children in school, so that they may pass ideas
on in the family or community environment.  Initiatives and encouragement from
government and other official sources help support teachers and older children
in their activities.<p>
                 Morley, et. al., 1984, p.1          <p>
<p>
<p>
In various programmes children have been taught to identify malnutrition by
taking an arm measurement; they are taught the dangers of dehydration which is
associated with diarrhea and learn how to make the water, salt and sugar
solution to combat dehydration. They are also taught about safety and how to
prevent disease and other health problems.     <p>
<p>
<p>
     While the development of support materials has occurred at the University
of London, regional and national workshops are held so that the 52 countries
where the programme operates can adapt the programme to meet their particular
needs.  For example, a regional workshop was held in Kenya in 1979. When Kenyan
participants from the fields of education, health, and social work came
together they determined that management of diarrhea should be the first focus
of a CHILD-to-child programme in Kiambu Province. Training and support was
provided in how to implement such a project, and outcomes were monitored.  To
determine the success of the effort, the evaluation focused on measuring
changes in knowledge, attitudes and skills, and comparing the number of
diarrhea cases brought to the hospital before and during the project. (Otaala,
1981, p.94).  The pilot project proved successful; the model was then
implemented in other villages in the area.<p>
<p>
<p>
     The programmes described in the category of "in the home" settings all
illustrate ways in which family members have become the focus of early
childhood care and education programmes in an attempt to impact young
children's health, growth and development.  These programmes are all designed
to build upon and strengthen traditional patterns of caregiving.  They seek to
have an impact on the child's development within the most natural setting--the
home. In the next category are those early childhood care and education
programmes that operate within the next most natural setting--the
neighborhood.<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>B. In the neighborhood.</b><p>
<p>
     Within this category are early childhood care and education programmes
that most closely approximate home care.  Generally known as "family day care",
these programmes operate in homes in the neighborhood. The examples come from
Venezuela, Colombia, and Ecuador.  In all instances the provider or caregiver
is a woman who provides care for a small group of children in her own home.
There are two kinds of family day care providers.  First, there are women who,
under their own initiative, decide to care for other children.  These women may
or may not be connected with a formal network of providers.  Of more interest
in terms of the current review, however, is the second group.  These women are
part of a formalized system developed and supported by a public or private
organization. These systems would provide a means of reaching children and
families not currently receiving appropriate health care.<p>
<p>
     One of the largest systems of family day care was developed in Venezuela
where there is a tradition of commitment to meeting the needs of young
children.  This commitment is evident in the activities of the Children's
Foundation, a private sector, quasi-governmental organization, presided over by
the First Lady of the Republic.  Since its founding in 1964, the Foundation has
been responsible for developing a variety of programmes for children.  In 1974
the Day Care Home Programme (DCHP) became the focus of Foundation activity.
The DCHP was developed and implemented as an integral care initiative, in
collaboration with FUNDACOMUN, the National Housing Institute, the Ministry of
Public Works, the Ministry of Health and Social Services, the Venezuelan
Institute of Social Security, and the National Institute of Nutrition.<p>
<p>
     The programme was begun in recognition of the needs of women and children.
"In a society in which women are joining the workforce in massive numbers, a
system of day care provision which assures comprehensive care for young
children is a need that comes from the basic rights of both the mother and the
child."(Ruesta &amp; Vidal, 1980, p. ix)<p>
<p>
     In attempting to meet the needs of families living in poor neighborhoods
in and around Caracus, the Day Care Homes Programme was created. It was
designed on the premise that quality care could be made available to young
children (0-6 years of age) within their neighborhood. Thus, within the
programme children are provided with custodial care, nutrition, health, and
education in a family environment--a family day care home. The programme allows
mothers working outside the home to be assured that their children are safe and
well cared for during the hours the mother is away.  <p>
<p>
     The Care Mother, as the provider is called, is expected to provide care
for 5 children under the age of six. Frequently Care Mothers have children of
their own in the programme. Women chosen as Care Mothers are between the ages
of 18 and 50, in good health, and must enjoy working with children. They are
selected after an interview, a visit to see their home, an assessment of
theirfamily, and a determination of whether or not the home is convenient to
other children in the neighborhood. The home is open from 6:00 A.M. until 6
P.M. The Care Mother receives a stipend of U.S. $1.54/day (in 1979 dollars),
for the care and feeding of each programme child.  This is supplemented by U.S.
$.23/day/child from the child's mother.<p>
<p>
<p>
     From the beginning the programme was designed to be comprehensive.  The
intent was to serve families in the communities where they live, linking them
to appropriate health and social services as needed.  Thus, an elaborate
training/supervisory support system was developed to assist the Care Mother.
Each group of 20 day care homes is served by a technical support team
consisting of a social worker responsible for maintaining administrative and
quality control; a health worker who establishes linkages with the appropriate
public sector organizations to assure preventative and curative health services
for the child; and a teacher who develops educational activities to be carried
out in the home.  There is a neighborhood Coordinator for each 60 homes (or 3
technical teams). Legal services are also provided. For each 8 neighborhoods
there is a person responsible for providing legal services and consultation to
the Care Mother and the families being served.  At the height of the programme
there were 1,260 day care homes in existence, providing services to 3,000
families.<p>
<p>
     An extensive evaluation of the DCHP was conducted in 1978, under the
sponsorship of UNICEF.  The evaluation was conducted by the Planning Office of
the Children's Foundation, with technical assistance from High/Scope
Educational Research Foundation.  The evaluation documents the program's level
of implementation, the extent to which it was meeting defined needs, and the
usefulness of the model in providing integral care to young children. In
addition, it examined the strengths and weaknesses of the training/supervisory
support system that was established.  No pre- programme data were collected, so
a case study and community survey approach was taken in the evaluation.<p>
<p>
    Basically the evaluation was favorable.  It determined that children in the
programme were well cared for and were receiving needed nutrition and health
services.  It was more difficult to assess the degree to which they were
receiving needed educational services since there were no pre-programme
measures of children's cognitive development. Recommendations from the
evaluation focused on ways in which the training/supervisory support system
could be changed to clarify roles and be more effective. <p>
<p>
     Even though it was assumed that by using neighborhood homes it would be
possible to avoid some of the massive costs associated with the construction
and maintenance of centre-based programmes, the DCHP model developed in
Venezuela was costly ($1,029 U.S./child/year).  Of this $804 was paid by the
Children's Foundation, $59 by other institutions and $166 by the community.  Of
the Children's Foundation's contribution the break down of costs was as
follows:<p>
<p>
               Direct attention to the child           18%<p>
(stipend to Care Mother)<p>
               Equipping the home                       3%<p>
               Health sub-programme (including food)   39%<p>
               Education sub-programme                  9%<p>
               Social sub-programme                     9%<p>
               Legal sub-programme                      1%<p>
               Administration                          14%<p>
                              Ruesta &amp; Vidal, 1980, p.21<p>
<p>
<p>
     As noted, primary funding for the programme was provided by the Children's
Foundation, headed by the First Lady of the Republic.  What that <p>
means is that the directorship of the Foundation changes as a result of changes
in national leadership. Since the evaluation took place there was a change in
the national government. Thus there is a new First Lady.  She has her own
interests, and has not maintained the funding for the DCHP.  Some Care Mothers
are continuing to provide services on their own, but there is no longer the
financial or moral support they need to continue their work. Perhaps if the
collaboration with various ministries and national organizations which
characterised the work from the beginning had been financial as well as
programmatic, funding would have been more broad-based, allowing the programme
to continue even though one funding source decreased its support.<p>
<p>
     Fortunately there are successful models of family day care that are much
less costly, and because they are community initiated and supported, they may
be more durable as well. For example, there is the Home Day Care Center
Programme in Cartagena, Colombia.  In this instance team members from the
Cartegena Office of Slum Renewal were aware of the prevalence of working
mothers in a low-income area of Cartagena and the need for a "healthy and safe"
day care situation for the children.  Building on an informal network of
neighbors already providing care for one another's children, three women were
identified who were willing to provide care for 10 neighborhood children
between the ages of 2 and 4.  The day care home provider was given training,
and a "promotor" worked with each mother.  The promotor was in charge of the
menu, clean-up, monitoring children's health, and providing cognitive
stimulation for the children. In essence, the promotor modelled what could be
done with young children.       <p>
<p>
     The day care homes were never seen as formal school environments.
Further, there was an open door policy.  Neighbors were invited to come in and
take part in the activities with the children. And, they came. The open door
policy provides an arena within which community members can informally learn
about child care.  Over time, community involvement in the programme has
increased; neighbors assist the day care home provider.  The promotor's role
has been taken over by community people. (Note: from the materials reviewed, it
is unclear whether the promotor has withdrawn from the programme or maintained
a low-profile position.)<p>
<p>
     The Cartagena day care homes opened in August, 1976.  By December, 1978
costs for operation of the programme for the first 29 months of the programme,
were U.S. $161.40 (in 1978 dollars) for each child ($13.45/child/month).
Included in the costs were: preparation and equipment of the homes, salaries
for the programme promotors and one coordinator; subsidies to the day care
provider; food; medicine; educational aids; and maintenance (UNICEF, 1979,
p.14).<p>
     <p>
     The Cartagena Home Day Care Center programme had an interesting off-
shoot.  About 6 months after the programme began there was a community meeting
to evaluate what had been accomplished.  There was a great deal of interest in
and support for the programme that had developed.  Community members were
interested in expanding the services to other children in the community as
well.  Funds were not available to provide promotors to work with other
mothers; neither were there funds available to provide stipends for additional
providers.  So, members of the community volunteered to provide care for young
children in their homes.  These volunteers agreed to work with 10- 25 children
under the age of four.  These children are selected by the volunteers and come
to her home in the mornings.  They are provided with a morning snack by the
Colombian Institute of Family Welfare; this consists of bread and hot cereal.
  The volunteers receive some training and support from staff members of the
Office of Slum Renewal (OSR). The emphasis in training is on giving volunteers
a knowledge base in child care and basic health, and developing attitudes and
skills that will help the volunteers work with the young children.  They are
also trained to give vaccinations and do periodic growth monitoring. The cost
of this programme is U.S. $4.00/family/month.<p>
<p>
     An informal evaluation of the programme suggests that it has had an impact
on childrearing practices in the community. Parents appear to have a better
understanding of child development; they are less punitive and they spend more
time doing things with their children.  The programme has impacted the
community in other ways.  Community development efforts have evolved from the
programme.  For example, initiatives were taken to pave the roads near the home
day care centers, and money was raised to improve sanitary conditions in the
centers. (UNICEF, 1979, p.16)<p>
<p>
     Yet another example of a family day care programme can be found in Tarqui,
a small community on the outskirts of Quito, Ecuador.  Within this community a
day care center had been established for 3-5 year old children. It was meeting
the needs of many families in the community. Yet there were still children
being left at home alone while their mothers went to work.  A survey was done
in the community to identify families with children in need of care.  Community
leaders, who had participated in the survey, came together to determine how to
meet the needs of these families. In the meetings that followed, a family day
care system of provision was presented as an alternative to the creation of
another center.  The idea took hold.  <p>
<p>
     Based on their interest, their location in the community, the adequacy of
their homes, and their personal characteristics, six community women were
chosen to become day care providers.  These six mothers received some initial
training in child development, health, and nutrition; regular in-service
training is also provided.  They are supplied with a small table and chairs.
They are also given appropriate toys.  They are provided with food supplements
for the children, and regular medical check-ups are provided through the Tarqui
Cooperative, which serves as the base for the programme.  The Director of the
programme is responsible for programme administration, training and supervision
of the day care mothers, linkage with the Cooperative and other organizations
which provide support to the project, and monitoring of programme progress. She
has an assistant who works with her. An extensive evaluation has been conducted
since the project began.  Results of the evaluation will be available in
December, 1985.   <p>
<p>
     Through a grant from USAID, partial funding for the project and technical
assistance were provided by the High/Scope Educational Research Foundation.
The project was designed and implemented through a cooperative agreement
between the Fundacion Mariana de Jesus, the Cooperativa de Tarqui and
High/Scope. From the beginning, funds were sought for project continuation once
external funding was withdrawn.  These have been obtained from the Instituto
Nacional de Ninos y la Familia (INNFA) to support operational costs of the
programme. (It is interesting to note that INNFA is the Ecuadorian equivalent
to the Children's Foundation in Venezuela. Hopefully this programme will not
have the same fate as the Day Care Homes Programme in Venezuela.)<p>
<p>
<p>
     A somewhat different type of neighborhood early childhood care and
education programme is found in Maldive. In that country children are expected
to be able to read <u>before</u> they are admitted to primary school.
Traditionally it has been the responsibility of mothers--usually in small
groups--to teach their children (ages 4-6) to read the Koran in Arabic.  They
also teach the children to do basic reading in Divehi, the local language.
These activities occur in homes in the neighborhood and are called
<u>kiyavaage</u> schools. Even where Kindergartens have been established, many
of the <u>Kiyavaage</u> schools continue.  (UNESCO, 1983, p. 16, 20). This is
an example of a community initiative that could be built upon and supported by
the formal sector.<p>
<p>
<p>
     The programmes included in this category all provide some type of care for
the young child in his or her neighborhood in a form which most closely
approximates home care. Some of these projects were initiated from outside the
community; others have evolved as a result of individual and/or community
initiative. By and large, they are designed to provide care for children whose
mothers are working outside the home.  In the next category of early childhood
care and education settings are those programmes which have been developed in
response to the same need.  However, rather than being offered near the home,
the ECCE programmmes described are offered in connection with the workplace. <p>
<p>
<p>
<b>C. At the work place.</b><p>
<p>
          When describing ECCE programmes in relation to the work place there
are basically two sub-categories: programmes located at businesses which are a
part of the the formal sector, as illustrated by the Mobile Creche programme in
India; and programmes such as those found in Ghana and Senegal which have been
developed to support women's traditional work.<p>
<p>
               1. <u>Formal work sector child care</u>. One way in which
governments have given support to early childhood care and education programmes
is through legislation which mandates the development of employer sponsored
child care. In some countries there are mechanisms to enforce the legislation;
in other instances the legislation exists, but little or nothing is done to
make employers comply. <p>
<p>
     India is a country that has had legislation in support of employer
sponsored child care since 1964. For many years it was not enforced. However,
over the years there was pressure to comply.  Within the construction industry
there was particular concern.  Many women are employed within the industry, and
with the frequent moves required as buildings are completed and new ones begun,
women and children are forced to relocate.  Women are not able to rely on
extended family members to care for their children.  Thus a programme of early
childhood care and education was begun for these workers and their families. A
variety of private voluntary organizations, working with the construction
industry, created the "mobile creche" system, which began in 1969.   The early
childhood care and education programme is established where the women are
working, and moves with them from site to site. Mobile Creches have also been
established to serve the children of street clearners, rag pickers, and other
families representing the lowest social status groups in India.<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
     There are three levels to the programme.  The first is a creche for
infants and young chidlren (from 3-4 weeks to age three).  The second is called
a nursery programme and is for 3-6 year olds.  The third is an elementary
programme for children from 6-12 years of age.  Within the creche programme the
primary focus is on health and nutrition. The majority of the children are
malnourished when they enter the programme.  Thus, there is an emphasis on
providing them with proper foods and educating the parents about nutrition.
Within the nursery programme the health and nutritional status of the child
remain an important part of the programme.  The children are monitored weekly
by a physician, and growth charts are kept on the children. In addition,
however, there is an emphasis on cognitive and psycho-social development.  One
of the goals is to help prepare the children for the formal school system. <p>
<p>
     The third level, the elementary programme, was developed for children who
traditionally would have been taking care of their younger siblings.  Because
the siblings are now in an ECCE programme, the older children could be going to
school.  However, there is considerable prejudice against these children who
come from the poorest families.  Because their home environments have not
prepared them for school, they do poorly.  Teachers do not want them in their
classrooms.  The elementary programme was developed to prepare these children
to enter school and be placed within an age equivalent grade.  One part of the
teacher's role in the Mobile Creche programme is to help dispell some of the
prejudices.  She is responsible for creating linkages with the schools so that
local primary school teachers know what the children are learning in the mobile
creche system and have an understanding of what these children can learn.<p>
<p>
     Staff within the mobile creche system are from the lower middle class.
Originally the staff received their training within the traditional teacher
training institutes.  However, it was discovered that this training was not
adequate to meet the unique needs of the families and children served by the
mobile creche programme.  For example, they discovered that staff needed to be
able to do public relations work to convince parents to send their children to
the programme. They also needed training in basic health care and hygiene.
Thus, over time, the Mobile Creche programme developed their own training for
staff. Those with the aptitude are given additional training in nutrition,
community work and medical social work.<p>
<p>
     As the programme has evolved, classes in adult education have been added.
There are literacy programmes, nutrition classes, and political discussion
groups.  As of January, 1977 there were 68 creche programmes (UNICEF, 1979,
p. 7).  This provides important care and education for only a very small
proportion of India's more than 109 million children under six years of age. <p>
<p>
     While the development of employer sponsored early childhood care and
education in India was motivated by the need to provide care for children of
working women, a different motivation has led to the development of employer
sponsored child care in Swaziland, where few women are employed by industries.
A social worker employed by the largest pulp producing company in the country
argued that "the children of workers are the workers of the future.  By
providing them with preschool education they will have a solid educational
foundation and make better workers." (Evans, 1983, p.29). She convinced the
company to help support the development of preschool programmes.  They agreed
to donate company land, build the facility, and pay the teacher in one 
location.  In two other locations they have provided the land.  The Ministry of
Education provided the monies for constructing a building and paying the
teacher's salary at one of the sites.  At the other site a church is being used
and school fees pay the essentially volunteer teacher.<p>
<p>
     Another type of preschool has been developed within Swaziland in relation
to industries.  These are schools for the children of middle management,
indigenous staff and for the children of expatriates living on the estate.
These schools are designed to prepare the children for primary school; children
are taught English and socialized into the formal school system.<p>
<p>
     Thus, while there are a variety of purposes for the development of
employer-sponsored ECCE programmes, it is a phenomenon in both the developed
and developing world which is supported by national legislation. In many
countries legislation exists, but it has not been built upon.  The potential of
employer-sponsored ECCE programming has not been realised. There is no
legislation to support ECCE programming in the informal work sector, yet it too
is a growing phenomenon.<p>
<p>
<p>
               2. <u>ECCE programming in the informal work sector</u>.   In
general, planners have not understood the necessity of developing child care
programmes to support what has been viewed as women's work which is "compatible
with child care".  The question is, what work is compatible with child care? As
noted by Engle (1980) in a paper on the intersecting needs of working women and
their young children,<p>
<pre>
          The concept of "compatability" is desperately in need
          of definition.  Agricultural work, work in the home,
          work near to the home, and work in sales have all been
          considered to be compatible with child care.  However,
          it seems quite clear that a woman accompanied by one or
          more small children will be less efficient in her time
          use than a woman unaccompanied. p. 24.
</pre>
     Engle then goes on to describe a number of studies that have attempted to
look at the relationship between a woman's work efficiency and her productivity
as related to child care responsibilities.  The studies provide different
results, based on child and adult variables that must be considered in each
situation. But, regardless of what academic studies indicate, women involved in
the various activities have obviously felt a need for child care.<p>
<p>
     Examples of early childhood care and education programmes that are
included in this sub-category are found in the marketplace in Ghana and in
relation to agricultural work in Senegal. In Ghana, the Accra Market Women's
Association was interested in starting a child care programme for their
children while they were involved in buying and selling.  They approached the
Accra City Council, which agreed to fund the programme.  A committee was
formed, consisting of members from the Women's Association, the City Council,
the Department of Social Welfare (which is mandated to oversee ECCE
programmes), the Ministry of Health, and the Ministry of Water and Sewage.  A
building near the market was refurbished.  It now serves 200 children, from
infancy through 5 1/2 years of age. It operates under the Administration of the
Regional Medical Officer of Health.  Thus, it has a strong health and nutrition
focus.  Mothers of infants are encouraged to come to the centre to 
breastfeed them. Children are provided with a morning snack and a full lunch.
To enter the programme they must have a physical examination and appropriate
immunizations.  Once a month a public health nurse inspects the facilities,
provides immunizations as needed, and completes children's medical charts. In a
report on the project, the following conclusion was drawn:<p>
<p>
The Malata Market Day Care Centre experience has been a successful one largely
because of the support the centre has received from the very initial stages,
from appropriate agencies together with the keen interest of the mothers, who
work in close proximity to the centre.        <br>
                           WHO/UNICEF, 1982, p.23<p>
<p>
<p>
     Another initiative undertaken in relation to women's work place was begun
in Senegal in 1962.  Women who were part of an <u>Animation feminine</u>
center, proposed to those operating the centers (<u>animatrices</u>) that a day
care center be started, where children could be cared for while women worked in
the fields.  The day care was proposed by the women,
to resolve the problem of caring for their young children while they and their
older daughters under-took the arduous task of planting out the rice.
Entrusting the children to older sisters who were still too small to work in
the fields was a solution that did not provide sufficient guarantees of safety:
and leaving them on the edge of the rice fields meant they would be exposed to
all the vagaries of the climate--humidity, rain, direct sun, etc--as well as to
the attacks of wild animals, especially poisonous snakes.<br>
                        Bashizi, 1979, p. 166-167<p>
<p>
      The <u>animatrices</u> agreed to establish the day care programme as long
as the women's centre did not have to pay for the programme. So, mothers shared
responsibility for the programme.  Some planted a community garden from which
the children could be fed while they were in the centre.  Other women rotated
responsibility for taking care of the children and tending the garden.   The
first ECCE centre began in July, 1962, and operated for 2 1/2 months during the
most difficult part of the agricultural season--when the rice crop is
transplanted.  During the first year 110 children between one and five years of
age were provided for in the centre. Since that time day care centres have
spread throughout Casamance (one of eight administrative districts in Senegal).
By 1978 there were 58 centres, serving 6,004 children, ages 6 months to 5 1/2
years. The centres are open from 8:00 A.M. until 7:00 P.M., and generally
operate from one to three months during the year.  Parents pay a fee for the
programme in the form of money, rice, and oil or dried fish.<p>
<p>
      The centres operate under the Department of <u>Animation rurale,
Promotion humaine.</u>  Community developers within the Department quickly saw
the potential of these centres; they could be used as a base from which a
variety of social services could be offered. They began to offer training to
community volunteers who worked in the centres.  They also began to offer adult
education courses in nutrition, health, hygiene, disease prevention, water
purification, etc.  Through the centres they also offer treatment for such
diseases as malaria and conjunctivitis.  <p>
<p>
<p>
     Since the programme began it has received support from a variety of
national private voluntary organizations--ORANA, CRS, UNICEF, and the World
Council of Churches.  At this point an action research project has been
undertaken, with financial and technical assistance support from UNICEF, to
look at some of the following issues:<p>
<p>
          1. Should the ECCE programme operate on a year-round basis?  Or,
should other services be offered in the facility when the ECCE programme is not
provided?<p>
<p>
          2. In the poorest areas, women cannot afford to pay anything for
their children to be in a centre, thus the services are not reaching those most
in need. What can be done to help finance the programme in the poorest area
where women are most in need?<p>
<p>
          3. There is confusion about the division of responsibility for the
programme among the various governmental services; responsibilities need to be
clarified and resolved.<p>
<p>
          4. In some communities the programme has been operating for so long
that it is stagnating.  What needs to happen to rejuvenate the programme?<p>
<p>
          5. The goals for the programme need to be re-examined.  At the
present time there is an emphasis on preparing the children for primary school.
But currently there are not enough places in the primary school for all those
who complete preschool.  Thus, other goals need to be explored. <p>
<p>
     The key to this effort from the beginning has been that the programme is
"essentially and fundamentally a people's initiative". (Bashizi, 1979, p.171).
The goal is to keep it under the control of the community and to continue to
use the programme to support community development efforts while it provides a
much needed service to women and children.<p>
<p>
<p>
     Not discussed, but obviously tremendously important in terms of providing
a nationally mandated employer-sponsored systems of child care, are the ECCE
programmes implemented in Eastern European countries.  Among these countries
there are examples of universal pre-primary education as well as universal
systems of care for the very young child (0-3 years of age). These systems have
required tremendous government and private business investment; it is unlikely
that comparable systems could or should be created in developing countries.
Nevertheless, these systems should be understood in order to learn from the
experience of developing and operating such programmes.  It is also important
to understand the potential for developing ECCE programmes in relation to
women's traditional place of work.  These programmes, however, are more likely
to be unique to a given geographic area. It may be harder to find networks of
such programmes or an organizational structure within which one could work to
implement primary health care components in these community initiated
efforts.<p>
<p>
<p>
     In sum, early childhood care and education programmes operated at the
workplace represent both programmes developed from the top down--those mandated
through legislation--and those developed from the community up--based 
on women's defintion of their needs.   In both the developed and developing
world there is increasing pressure to create early childhood care and education
programmes in relation to the work place.  The systems being developed offer
tremendous potential for the integration of health care and psycho-social
stimulation into what too easily becomes custodial care.<p>
<p>
     <p>
     The <u>work place</u> setting is different from the <u>in home</u> and
<u>in neighborhood</u> setting in the sense that the ECCE programme that is
provided generally operates within a "centre" rather than in a home.  In the
next category there is a description of a variety of early childhood care and
education programmes which operate in centres specifically designed to serve
young children.<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>D. In centers for children.</b><p>
<p>
          This category includes all the early childhood care and education
centres that are created specifically to serve young children.  They can have a
variety of purposes and serve various populations within the 0-6 age range.
Obviously this category encompasses a wide range of programmes.  Thus, in order
to develop a strategy for working with these programmes, it is necessary to
create sub- categories, some of which are based on sponsor, and some of which
are based on programme focus. The three major sub-categories included are: 1.
Open-air programmes--those programmes which are generally initiated by the
community, and which rely heavily on community resources for their survival,
and are described in a case study of Zimbabwe.  Mention is also made of
programmes in Kenya, Tanzania, Chile, Mexico, and Brasil.  2. Early childhood
care and education centres--located in the primary school-- developed
specifically to prepare the pre-school aged child for entrance into primary
school. Examples come from Thailand, Korea, and Haiti.  3. Integrated care
center-based programmes for young children, as found in India, Peru, and
Haiti.<p>
<p>
               1. <u>Open air settings</u>. In many developing countries
resources are not available to build early childhood care and education
centres. Yet there is interest in creating an ECCE programme.  In these
instances, "centres" are created wherever a group of children can be brought
together. ECCE programmes that generally occur--or originally began--in open
air settings are included in this category.<p>
<p>
      The primary example to be discussed in this category is Zimbabwe, where,
since independence, massive strides have been made to promote and develop a
range of early childhood care and education programmes. For many years a small
percentage of Zimbabwe's children aged 0-6 years, mainly in urban areas, were
able, through private means, to attend preschools, play centres, and creches.
In the more rural areas, preschools did not exist.  In 1980, the government of
Zimbabwe, through the Ministry of Education and Culture, took the initiative to
plan a national early childhood care and education programme.  The Ministry
established a commission of inquiry into ECCE activities which undertook
intensive nationwide investigations, and produced a report in 1981.<p>
<p>
     According to the report, hundreds of women in the rural areas, with no
support from the government, have started some form of early childhood care and
education activity for their young children.  The push from rural areas for
ECCE programmes has come about as a result of: <p>
<p>
          1) the burgeoning population growth which stands<p>
          nationally at more than four percent; and according to
1982 Census projections, more than 23% of the total population is under 6 years
of age; 2) the need felt by parents to overcome the legacies of the colonial
past by giving children a "headstart" in the schooling and socialization
process; and 3) the pressure of mothers to free themselves for short periods
from child care in order to participate in wage earning or enterprise to
supplement family income. Whatever the reasons, proliferation of self-help
community- supported preschools is occuring in areas where health care,
sanitation and nutrition are marginal. <p>
                               Perry, 1983, p.1<p>
<p>
<p>
     The conditions under which the more than 1000 village programmes operate
vary considerably.  They range from programmes operated under trees, to
programmes in small buildings with mud-daubed walls and thatched roofs, to
programmes that take place in the church sanctuary, to elaborate facilities
constructed and maintained by municipal support.  Many programmes used to
operate in primary school classrooms, but with the rise in primary school
attendance, these rooms are no longer available.  <p>
<p>
     A typical ECCE programme consists of upwards to 85 children, with only one
or two mothers (generally untrained), caring for the children. Parents have
little or no resources to pay for the programme; many use the bartering system
to support their child's participation in an ECCE programme. What this means is
that most teachers receive little or no pay for their work.<p>
<p>
     The ECCE programmes are administered by Parent Committees who are
responsible for hiring the teachers, establishing school fees, and overall
administration of the programme.  The little equipment that is available has
been fashioned by parents, taking advantage of materials found in the area. In
general, equipment, furniture, salaries of teachers and helpers are provided by
parent and community donations.<p>
<p>
     Some of these programmes receive direct or indirect support from non-
governmental agencies, such as VOICE (Voluntary Organizations in Community
Enterprise), OXFAM/US/UK, church groups (Methodist, Catholic, Seventh Day
Adventist, Lutheran) and other special interest groups. At the present time the
Ministry of Community Development and Women's Affairs has been given the
mandate to coordinate ECCE programming throughout the country.  They are
seeking the most effective way to support the community initiative, while at
the same time assuring that quality services are provided. (Evans, 1983,
p.3).<p>
<p>
The Ministry is well aware of the energy generated by the self-help initiative
in the communities and the potential of this large pool of untrained workers
and volunteers to provide paraprofessional support to teaching, management,
building, health services, food and nutrition.  But, preservice and continuing
inservice training will be required for development of responsible and creative
leadership.<p>
                            Perry, 1983, p.6 <p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
     While the Ministry of Community Development and Women's Affairs has
primary responsiblity for coordination of ECCE activities, it is envisioned
that a range of other Ministries will be involved as well:<p>
<p>
          - The Ministry of Education and Culture will focus on education for
       the 0-6 year olds, and the training of provincial and district
trainers.<p>
<p>
          - The Ministry of Public Service Training, Management Bureau, will
      provide the necessary training facilities at its current centers.<p>
<p>
          - The Ministry of Youth, Sport and Recreation will make outdoor
   equipment.<p>
<p>
          - The Ministry of Labour and Social Services will be responsible for
        children's general welfare, and for the development of special
services for handicapped and problem children.<p>
<p>
          - The Ministry of Local Government and Town Planning is responsible
       for securing land for the programme. <p>
<p>
          - The Ministry of Health will ensure good health standards and
  inspect the facilities.  Health workers will examine children
periodically to identify malnutrition, non-immunization, physical           and
mental conditions.<p>
<p>
          - Voluntary organizations will continue to provide services, in
   accordance with ministry policies. (Ministry of Community
Development and Women's Affairs, 1981, p. 3-4).<p>
     In addition, support has been sought from international donor agencies.
UNICEF (with monies from the Italian government), is providing support for the
development and implementation of a large-scale training scheme to prepare
trainers to work with local teachers to upgrade their skills. The training
programme is currently underway.<p>
<p>
     In sum, Zimbabwe is an example of the evolution from community-based,
open-air initiatives to the development of a national programme in support of
ECCE activities. Communities were creating their own ECCE programmes at the
same time that national forces were moving toward a committment to
education--for young children as well as school-aged children and adults.  In
addition, non- governmental groups and international donor agencies were
willing to collaborate in the effort. Over the next few years it will be
important to follow the progress in Zimbabwe and to assess if the government,
with its limited resources, is able to maintain a coordinated system of ECCE
programmes that provide quality care for young children.     <p>
<p>
     Within other African countries there are other examples of open air
initiatives.  Most notable are those within Kenya, associated with the
<u>harambee</u> movement and in Tanzania in connection with <u>ujamaa</u>
villages. In both instances early childhood care and education programmes have
been developed as a result of self-help initiatives that characterize many
open-air programmes. However, as the programmes have become increasingly
popular, there has been increased national commitment to the further
development of systems of ECCE.<p>
<p>
With the spirit of <u>harambee</u> which followed <p>
<pre>
          independence in Kenya, there was a period of 
          emphasis on good citizenship.  Most recently the 
          major concern has been fostering self-reliance 
          and the full participation of women in development. 
          In this context women have participated fully in 
          developing <u>harambee</u> day-care centers throughout 
          the country.    
                                           Otaala, 1981, p. 30
</pre>
<p>
     In fact, at this point in time the <u>harambee</u> schools constitute 60%
of all the early childhood care and education programming that has been
developed in rural areas. (Otaala, 1981, p. 16).  The centers that have been
developed are operated by local parent committees, and the resources necessary
to implement the programme come from the community. Thus, the setting is more
than likely to be make-shift, at best.  In some communities where the ECCE
programme has been operating for several years the community has built a
facility specifically for the programme.  They are under the jurisdiction of
the Ministry of Culture and Social services, the department of Social Welfare
and Culture, the Department of Community Development and Self-Help Schemes, and
the Women's Bureau.<p>
<p>
     Within Tanzania the same spirit of self-help has led to the development of
ECCE programmes in rural areas.  In 1969, the government supported an
initiative that led to the creation of day care centers for pre-school children
(ages 4-6).  Emphasis was on developing programmes in crowded urban areas and
in <u>ujamaa</u> villages where "mothers are required to work in the villages'
cooperative schemes." (Otaala, 1981, p.49).  Responsibility for the programmes
resides within the Ministry of Labour and Social Services, the Social Welfare
and Probation Division.  A variety of local private voluntary
organizations--<u>Umoja wa Wanawake wa Tanzania</u>, local councils, missions,
and employing organizations--actually sponsor the programmes.  Many of the
centers began as open-air initiatives.  But as there has been increased
government commitment to the development of ECCE progrmmes, there has been
increased governmental support.  The support has taken the form of constructing
facilities and providing village-based training, sponsored by UNICEF. Julius
Nyerere, President of Tanzania, has been a force behind the development of ECCE
programmes.  His rationale for ECCE programmes as an important part of the
development process is based on his view that,"The maturity of a nation can be
judged by how it looks after its children and mothers." (as quoted in Otaala,
1981, p. 53).<p>
<p>
     A range of programmes from other parts of the world might well be
classified as open-air initiatives.  For example, in Chile the "Plaza
Preescolar" operates in an outdoor setting in a town.  The programme was begun
by a community that was interested in developing an alternative to the
expensive traditional pre-school programmes. With technical assistance from
<u>la Fundacion de Jardines Infantiles</u>, a private organization, the
community built a "plaza" or open space where children come together for a
half-day preschool programme. (In the winter time the programme frequently
takes place in the homes of community members.)  Adolescents (<u>monitores</u>)
in the community are trained to work with a professional teacher, providing a
semi-structured educational programme for children.  Those chosen to teach,
young men and women, have an average of seven years of schooling, and are
interested in 
working with children. The Foundation pays for the training and the salary of
the teacher.  They also supply food to supplement the children's diet.
Supplies for the center, and the on- going maintenance are the responsibility
of the community. (Mauras, et al., 1979, p.19).<p>
<p>
     Yet another example comes from Mexico.  It is known as "la Programa de
Atencion Prescolar al Aire Libre."  It was begun in 1974 by the <u>Sistema
Nacional para el Desarrollo Integral de la Familia</u> (DIF), an organization
which develops and supports programmes that meet the needs of
families--particularly those living in the poorest communities.  DIF has
developed a range of early childhood care and education programmes, one of
which is the open-air programme.  The programme is based on the assumption that
early childhood care and education can become a vehicle for community
development.  The programme is designed to make the best use of local
resources.<p>
<p>
     Within the open air programme a Mother's Group is formed; these women
serve as the Board of Directors for the ECCE programme, and they are
responsible for securing a place in the community for the programme--in the
open or in a covered space. Thus, if no other space is available, the programme
takes place in a local park.  Staff for the programme are volunteers--men and
women--who live within the community.  Children between the ages of 3 and 6 are
served by the programme, whose primary goal is to prepare the children to enter
the primary school system.  A curriculum has been developed that is presented
in a straight-forward way so that the volunteers can easily follow it.  Three
variations of the curriculum have been developed: one for urban areas, one for
peri-urban communities, and one for rural Mexico.  In 1979 the programme was
serving 25,000 in the federal district; an additional 140,000 were being served
in other states (Mauras,    et al., 1979, p. 18).<p>
<p>
     There is at least one example of an open-air programme that was initiated
from outside the community. This is found in the Santa Catalina area of Brazil.
In this instance the government was interested in mobilizing the community to
support the development of young children. They determined that one way of
doing this was to make children more visible in the community. In 1984 they
created open-air programmes (<u>La Gaviota</u>) that could be offered
anywhere--in the streets, in open areas, on the beach, in homes. In the
programme, the environment becomes part of the curriculum. People in the
community can see how much children learn from the world around them. Adults
are encouraged to become involved in these ECCE efforts. <p>
<p>
     In all the examples of open air programmes it is evident that they rely
heavily on community support if they are going to survive.  Additionally, they
have been developed in communities that are least likely to be reached by the
more formal traditional pre-school programmes. They also reach children and
families least likely to be served by the health sector. Yet there are many
problems. In describing these ECCE programmes in Africa, Mbikusita-Lewanika
(1982) summarizes some of the issues.<p>
<p>
                                                           <p>
Most of these centres are provided by the communities on self-help bases. The
communities are eager for their children to benefit from any kind of early
childhood care and education, and cannot wait for the governments to provide
these facilities...Since they are provided 
by the communities, they are the cheapest of all children's centres.  On the
other hand, these centres have the poorest facilities; ill constructed or
uncompleted buildings, poor ventilation, dangerous walls and floors,
overcrowding of children, lack of equipment and materials, under-staffed, and
untrained personnel.  p.23<p>
<p>
<p>
     She then proceeds to make an argument for why these programmes should, in
fact, receive the <u>most</u> governmental attention.  Included in her list of
reasons is the fact that those starting the programmes have the fewest economic
resources; early childhood care and education centres in these communities have
the potential to serve as a base for community development; these communities
receive the least in terms of all social services; children from these
communities are most in need of what a quality pre- school can provide; and
last, but not least, people in these communities have demonstrated their
commitment to their children and their ability to create a programme through
self-help initiatives; their efforts should be recognized and supported by the
government (Mbikusita-Lewankia, 1982, p. 23-24).<p>
<p>
               2. <u>In primary schools</u>.  Basically within this category
are programmes designed to meet the needs of "disadvantaged" children living in
urban squatter settlements and rural areas who are seen as having a
disadvantage when they enter primary school. These children, because of their
ethnic, social, regional, or family background, lack the experiences, skills,
and knowledge that more affluent peers bring to the school experience.  As a
result, they do poorly, drop out of school early, and are likely to continue
the cycle of poverty.  In the hopes of breaking that cycle, preschool
programmes have been developed for this group of children so that once they
enter the school system they can compete on an equitable basis with their
peers.<p>
<p>
      Within South east Asia there are a number of examples of national efforts
which have been developed to provide a pre- school experience in the primary
school for the urban poor and rural child.  In Thailand, for example, there
were a number of factors that led to the development of these pre-primary
classes.  First, there was an awareness of the fact that children come to the
formal school experience with very different life experiences, putting some
children at a "disadvantage" in terms of making the most of the school
experience. Second, there was a recognition of the value of quality pre- school
experiences to help prepare the child for later life. Third, there was a
declining birth rate which led to a demand for better education; with fewer
children, families have a high investment in their children's education. Last,
but not least, with the declining birthrate, there was also a decreasing
enrollment in primary schools, and thus classrooms were empty.       <p>
<p>
     In response to these factors the Ministry of Education, through the
National Primary Education Commission, determined to provide grants to target
communities to develop pre- primary programmes, in the primary schools, for 5-6
year olds, to prepare them for the formal school system.  Grants go to "areas
identified as the rural impoverished, the urban deprived, the remote and
barren, and the community with 50% of the children speaking other than Thai".
(Piya-Ajariya, 1983, p.47).  If other communities are interested in
establishing pre-primary programmes they can, but the local education committee
has to bear all the costs.<p>
<p>
<p>
     The Ministry prescribed pre-primary programme includes "fostering of
personality development, desirable values and socially accepted manners, mental
and physical development and nutrition...The emphasis on reading and writing
may be begun in the final phase of the programme." (Pija-Ajariya, 1983, p. 47).
<p>
<p>
     Thailand has other systems of ECCE programming as well. There is a system
of child development centres which are integrated programmes of care provided
for children from age 2- 6, operated by local education committees--consisting
of the health sector, community development workers, community leaders, and
parents.  There are also rural Child Nutrition Centres operated by the
Department of Health, and in urban areas ECCE programmes are run by the
Metropolitan City Municipality. (WHO/SEA, 1972, p.36). <p>
<p>
     As the primary school-based programme has evolved, it has drawn children
away from the child development centres.  To a large extent this has occurred
because parents see the pre-primary programme as "teaching" the child.  Child
development centres are seen as places to "play".  What is currently being
proposed is that the two systems come together and form a continuum of care for
the child from age 2 until entrance into the primary school.  Children would
begin in the child development centres, and at age 5 or 6 they would enter the
pre-primary programme.  The philosophy, curriculum and activities would be
coordinated across the two programmes. (Pija-Ajariya, 1983). (Note: there was
no discussion of how the Ministry of Health programme would or would not be
included in this continuum approach.)<p>
<p>
     Korea represents another example where a pre-school programme, offered in
the primary school, has been developed specifically to meet the needs of the
urban and rural poor. Korea has Kindergartens in the urban areas. Primarily
these serve the child least in need of them--children from affluent families
who could afford to pay the costs of the programme. The Ministry of Education,
again because of decreased primary school enrollment and available space in
schools, is proposing that kindergartens, or pre-primary programmes be offered
in Korea to all children. <p>
<p>
     To help develop the pre-primary programme the Korean Institute for
Research in Behavioural Sciences (KIRBS) has been provided support by UNICEF to
create an appropriate curriculum for the rural and urban poor (ages 3-5), and
to implement the curriculum in areas of most need. (With earlier support from
UNICEF, KIRBS developed a curriculum for 5 year olds that is now the nationally
prescribed curriculum for kindergartens.)  A mid-term evaluation of the project
indicated that "the KIRBS programme is an innovative and effective contribution
towards setting up early childhood education in disadvantaged and remote
areas." (Crellin, et al., 1984, p. 29).  <p>
<p>
     One of the issues raised by the evaluation was the fact that, as
originally proposed, the project was to focus considerable attention on parent
involvement.  When the evaluation occurred there was little evidence of parent
education and/or involvement.  The programme seems to be evolving along the
lines of traditional preschool education. The evaluators raised the question of
whether or not it is most cost-effective to invest in the development of
kindergartens in all areas; they suggested that alternative approaches to the
provision of ECCE should be more fully explored, such as home based teaching
and parent education.<p>
<p>
<p>
     A similar issue was raised at the regional training workshop for
supervisors and administrators of ECCE programmes, held by UNESCO in Bangkok in
l983, where the effectiveness of providing traditional kindergarten programmes
was discussed. It was aptly noted that:<p>
<p>
          Many attempts to prepare children for entry to primary school are
premised on the assumption that there is no need to change the primary school
system but that there is a need to change the child to fit that system.<p>
<p>
                                       UNESCO, 1983, p.6<p>
<p>
     In some countries there is an awareness that the primary school may need
to be changed, or at least an awareness that "compensatory programmes", which
simply introduce children to the traditional system a year earlier, are not the
answer. Malaysia, which, as a result of a 1972 study of drop outs, instituted
many rural day care centres and kindergartens is currently looking at the
effectiveness of these programmes. They are doing a national survey to look at
the status of ECCE programmes in order to make recommendations about future
investment in the field (UNESCO, 1983, p.2). <p>
<p>
     In sum, while a number of countries have developed early childhood care
and education programmes which are an extension of a costly formal educational
system, there is some question about the long-term value of creating these
systems of ECCE provision.  With alternative models it may be possible to
achieve multiple goals--in terms of health care, nutrition, parent education
and community development, as well as education.      <p>
<p>
     Haiti is an example of a country where there have been substantial
development of both single-purpose (educational), and integrated early
childhood care and education programmes. There has been a long history of pre-
school provision in Haiti.  Originally it was developed by the Ministry of
Agriculture and was provided for rural children in order to prepare them to
enter the primary school system.  These were called <u>class enfantines</u>.
The primary focus of the programme was on teaching children to read and write
in French, the language of the primary school system.  In rural areas children
had to complete the <u>class enfantine</u> in order to enter the primary school
system.<p>
<p>
     More recently, however, there has been a national commitment to the
provision of early childhood care and education to all children.  In the
Educational Reform of 1982, a Reform Curriculum was developed, and the primary
school was re-structured.  In this process emphasis was placed on developing
pre-primary programmes, known as Community Integrated Nutrition and Education
Centres (CINEC), for 5 years olds. These are operated by the Ministry of
Education.  In 1984, the Haitian Ministry of Education adopted the CINEC
programme as the official pre-school programme for the country.<p>
<p>
     The CINEC programme was actually proposed in 1976, and between 1978 and
1983, 121 centres were built and equipped by CARE, which worked with the
Ministry of Education to create the programme. Ninety-six of the centres were
built in conjunction with primary schools being constructed with funds from the
World Bank; an additional 25 were built in conjunction with existing primary
facilities.  The CINEC centres currently serve 6,050 of the 146,000 five year
olds.       <p>
<p>
<p>
     The CINEC programme has two levels: the <u>extern</u> programme, designed
to serve those under 5; and the <u>intern</u> programme, designed to serve the
5 year old. Each centre is to serve groups of 50 children in each age group.
When enrolled in the <u>extern</u> programme, children come to the centre once
a month for health and nutrition check-ups. Growth charts are kept on all
children.   In addition, mothers are given food allocations and information on
health and nutrition on a monthly basis in the hopes that children's nutrition
will be improved. In the <u>intern</u> programme, five year old children are
provided with a half-day educational programme in addition to the health and
nutrition programme. When the children enter the programme they are given a
series of tests to establish where they are developmentally. They are measured
in 21 areas; this creates a profile which becomes a way of monitoring
children's performance over time. Those who successfully complete the CINEC
intern programme are guaranteed a place in the public primary schools. (This is
a significant guarantee since at the primary level the public sector serves
only 40% of the children who are in primary schools. The private sector serves
the other 60%.) <p>
<p>
     Teachers (<u>responsables</u>) for the CINEC programme are employed by the
Ministry of Education and receive a salary in accordance with the ministry
scale for primary school teachers.  They generally have completed a minimum of
three years of secondary school and have 6 months of specialised training at a
teacher training college.  Supervision is provided by the Ministry of
Education. Thus, the CINEC system of pre-primary education is well integrated
into the primary school system.<p>
<p>
     Haiti has an equally large system of ECCE programmes which represent
examples of the next sub-category of ECCE center- based programmes--programmes
of integrated care, designed to meet the multiple needs of young children 0-6
years of age.<p>
<p>
               3. <u>In integrated care centres</u>. Within this sub-category
there are two basic types of programmes: those that are provided by an
individual to a single group of children; and those developed on a larger
scale, designed to meet the multiple needs of children from the poorest of the
poor families.<p>
<p>
     Private enterprise schools are developed by the owner/director of the
school.  Generally the individual running the school, expatriate or national,
has received training in early childhood education in a Western country, and
sets about to establish a pre-school in the developing country based on that
training.  In many country surveys of early childhood care and education
programming, these pre-schools are under-reported.  Unless the country has a
good system for registration and monitoring of pre-schools, these schools may
not be counted; they seldom have any formal connection with governmental
agencies or other early childhood care and education systems.  And, while the
pre- schools developed by individuals may be linked to international ECCE
affiliate organizations (such as Montessori), they seldom reach many children
in the country. Thus the programmes of greatest interest in this category are
those which have been developed to meet the needs of large groups of at risk
children-- the poorest of the poor--nationally or regionally.  There are some
notable examples.  There is the Integrated Child Development Services (ICDS)
programme in India.  There is also the non-formal education programme begun in
Puno, Peru.  Yet another example comes from Haiti.<p>
<p>
<p>
     The need for masssive programmes which address the needs of young children
in most evident in a country like India where there are more than 109 million
children under the age of 6--constituting 16% of the population (Sadka, 1984,
p.5.). In 1974 India adopted a National Policy for Children. In the policy
statement, India indicated its commitment to ensure the delivery of
comprehensive child development services to all children. One of the first
targets for the effort were the "poorest of the poor found in urban slums and
urban areas", particularly children in "scheduled cases and tribes." (Sadka,
1984, p.3).  <p>
<p>
     To develop a comprehensive service for these children, the Planning
Commission, in 1972, created 8 inter-ministerial teams that were charged with
the task of developing a programme to meet the following goals:<p>
          o to reduce the incidence of low birth weight and severe
malnutrition among children;<p>
<ul>
          <li> to bring down the mortality and morbidity rates among children 0-6
          years old;<br>

          <li> to reduce school dropout rates through early stimulation
programmes for children 3-6 years old;<br>

          <li> to provide the environmental conditions necessary for mental,
     physical and social development of children;<br>

          <li> to enhance the ability of mothers to provide proper care for their
          children; and<br>

          <li> to achieve effective co-ordination at the policy and
implementation levels among government departments to promote             child
development. (Sadka, 1984, p.12)<br>
</ul>
<p>
     In order to meet these goals it was determined that the comprehensive
programme needed to provide:  non-formal pre-school education; immunizations,
regular, periodic health check-ups, supplementary nutrition; appropriate
medical referral services; and nutrition and health education for women.<p>
<p>
     As the inter-ministerial teams met, it became evident that there were
models of early childhood care and education within which these services could
be provided.  What was lacking was an organizational framework which would
assure that the services were delivered in the community.  Thus within the
programme it was determined that an <u>Anganwadi</u> would be constructed.
(Each <u>Anganwadi</u> is designed to serve a population of 1,000 in rural and
urban areas and 700 in tribal areas.) It serves as the base of operations
within the community. <p>
<p>
     The programme operates through a three tiered staffing system. At the
community level is the <u>Anganwadi</u> worker (AWW).  This person plays the
key role in the community; she is the primary link between community members
and the government. She is responsible for the day-to-day operation of the
programme within the community.  Above the AWW is a Supervisor responsible for
20-25 AWWs. She provides them with on-going training and support.  Above her is
the Child Development Project Officer (CDPO), who provides the linkage between
the ICDS programme and government administration.  The CDPO is responsible for
the 
work of 4 Supervisors (100 AWWs).  A system of pre-and in-service training has
been developed for all staff. The programme operates within the Ministry of
Social Welfare, and is monitored by the Ministry as well as the All India
Institute of Medical Science and the National Institute for Public Cooperation
and Child Development.<p>
<p>
     All families in the area to be served are surveyed to identify the
poorest. Those families with children under 6 and/or where the woman is
pregnant or lactating, are served in the <u>Anganwadis</u>. Regular
examinations are provided by Lady Health Visitors and Auxiliary Nurse Midwives.
Children and pregnant women are immunized on a scheduled basis. Three hundred
days a year food is distributed; the menu is prepared in accordance with local
foods and traditions. Families are encouraged to bring the children to the
centres for regular feeding.  Children's  weight and height is monitored.
Those with severe malnutrition are given additional food supplements, and acute
cases are referred to medical services.<p>
<p>
          A pre-school programme has been developed for 3-5 year olds who
attend the centre three hours a day.  While there is no formally structured
curriculum, the local staff are encouraged to develop activities that stimulate
the child. Frequently there is parental pressure to teach the alphabet and
beginning numeracy.  An additional educational service is non-formal training
in nutrition and health organized for mothers and pregnant women.  These
sessions are open to all women, aged 15-45, with priority given to pregnant and
nursing women and women whose children suffer from repeated malnutrition.<p>
<p>
     Two major evaluations of the programme have been conducted.  One occurred
in 1978 and the second was in 1982. Both indicated positive results from the
programme--in terms of the programme's impact on children, women, and the
community at large (Sadka, 1984 p. 26-35).  Funding for the progrmme has come
from both governmental and non-governmental sources.  The initial costs of
establishing a programme are provided by the Ministry of Social Welfare. The
costs of the supplementary feeding programme are borne by the state
governments; and the on-going operational costs are the responsibility of the
Central government.  International donor agencies have also been involved in
funding aspects of the programme: UNICEF assisted in planning and
implementation beginning in 1975. Since 1982 other international agencies--WFP,
CARE, NORAD, USAID--have been contributing in a variety of ways.<p>
<p>
     The programme began on a pilot basis in 33 of India's 5000 administrative
blocks.  By March of 1985, 100,000 <u>Anganwadis</u> for 100 million people,
were to be established, with the ultimate goal being the delivery of
comprehensive services to all children under the age of 6 by the year 2000.<p>
<p>
     Another community-based programme designed to provide health, nutrition,
and education services is one of the non-formal education programmes which has
been developed in Peru.  Prior to the early seventies, the majority of
pre-school programmes which existed in Peru were available to urban middle and
upper-middle class children. Few attempts had been made to bring early
childhood care and education programmes to other populations in other parts of
the country. In 1972, however, as a part of the Educational Reform, there was a
commitment to providing pre-school education to all children in Peru.  The term
used to refer to education for children ages 0-5 was "initial education". As a
part of the initial education movement two types of programmes have been <p>
developed: there are those which are referred to as formal centres (Centros de
Educacion Initial-CEIs), staffed by professionals; and the non-formal centres
(Programas No-formal de Educacion Inicial-PRONOEI), which are staffed by para-
professionals.<p>
<p>
     Of particular concern in the development of initial education was the
provision of pre-primary education to children in marginal areas--in densely
populated urban areas and in remote rural zones. These areas have been reached
primarily through the non-formal system.  Two basic models of non-formal
provision have been developed. There is a home-based model which was described
earlier in this chapter, and there is a centre-based model. Within the
centre-based programme children participate in a half-day programme, five days
a week.  Within the programme they engage in educational activities, have a
snack or noon-day meal, and are monitored in terms of health and nutrition. <p>
<p>
     Recognizing the diversity of cultures represented in the various regions
of Peru, communities were encouraged to develop models of pre-school education
that met their particular needs. Within Puno, Peru, a non-formal model evolved
that has been disseminated to other parts of the country.  The Puno programme
began in 1967 as a community-based effort to provide nutrition education to
women. But when the initial education movement began, the programme shifted its
focus to the development of a pre-school for Quechua and Aymara children 3-6
years of age.  In 1973 it became known as the "Proyecto Experimental de
Educacion Initial No-Escolarizada de Puno"(PROPEDEINE). Located in the
altiplano region around Lake Titicaca, the programme operates in simply
constructed Children's Houses (<u>Wawa Wasis and Wawa Utas</u>). The children's
house is constructed by community members, who donate the materials as well as
their time and skill.<p>
<p>
     Pre-school aged children are provided with an educational programme, basic
health care, and nutritional supplementation. The national pre-school
curriculum has been adapted to reflect the local culture. Within the programme,
staff make use of natural activities in the children's lives--planting, hoeing,
herding of llama and sheep, etc.  There is also extensive use of local music,
songs, dances, and folk tales.<p>
<p>
      Staffing for the programme is provided by "volunteers", who receive a
small stipend. These young men are chosen by the community to work in the
pre-school. They generally have an elementary school education. They receive
two months of pre-service training and on-going supervisory support from
Ministry of Education personnel. On a rotating basis, mothers come to the
centers to cook a noon-time meal.    <p>
<p>
       While the original purpose of the centres was to provide nutrition
education, at this point in time they serve primarily as educationally focused
pre-schools. (However, they were used as a base of operation for a national
immunization campaign.) This is probably due to the fact that funding for the
programme comes from the Ministry of Education.  UNICEF has been involved in
the provision of training and vehicles which allowed the programme to be
developed in remote areas.  CARITAS has provided the nutritional
supplementation.<p>
<p>
     Because of the success of the program in the altiplano region, it has been
disseminated to other parts of Peru as well.  Beginning in 1980, the <p>
Ministry of Education modified the programme and extended it to other regions
in Peru, including metropolitan Lima, Cuzco, Apurimac, San Martin, and Huarez,
spreading the network of non-formal pre-school education programmes. <p>
<p>
     Currently within Peru there is a system of formal education and systems of
non-formal education which are being implemented to serve the needs of a range
of pre-school aged children.  Both the systems receive support from the
Ministry of Education, and fall within its mandate for supervision and support.
   <p>
<p>
     Within Haiti there are also two major systems of provision--the formal and
the non-formal.  While the formal system is supported by the Ministry of
Education, the non-formal system is under the mandate of the Ministry of Social
Affairs, and is called <u>Timoun Byen Vini</u> (Welcome Little One). It is a
UNICEF supported community-based programme. In October, l984 there were 140 of
these programmes operating in 47 locations, serving about 6,000 children. The
programme is managed by the Center for Special Education, associated with the
Haitian Association of Rehabilitation of the Handicaped. The focus is on
reaching children at risk of developmental problems--estimated to be 75% of the
age group.<p>
<p>
     <u>Timoun Byen Vini</u> integrated care programmes are implemented at the
request of community organizations which must make a commitment to maintain the
programme once it is begun.  They must provide a place for the group to meet,
obtain health services for the programme, and identify a source of food for the
feeding part of the programme. Staff from the Ministry of Social Affairs work
with the community to help them obtain these services.      <p>
<p>
     Teachers in this programme are <u>monitors</u>, assisted by mothers, on a
rotating basis.  Monitors have generally completed primary school.  Their
training occurs over an 18 month period of time-- three weeks of initital
training, followed by two weeks of training six months later and another two
weeks of training one year later.<p>
<p>
     The programme is designed to serve two different groups of children: those
between three months and three years, and those between three and five years of
age. Communities generally develop a programme for the older group first.  When
additional resources are available, a programme is developed for the younger
age group.  Curriculum is based on an adaptation of the Portage Model.  A
checklist, based on developmental milestones, has been developed to monitor
progress.  The children attend the centre for three and a half hours a day,
five days a week.  In addition, there is a strong emphasis on working with
parents so that they can provide appropriate activities for their children in
the home.  Mothers have a copy of the checklist so that they can follow the
child's progress.  The Monitor works with the mother, suggesting <p>
activities that she can do with the child and encouraging her to do so.  <p>
<p>
     In sum, the examples presented in this sub-category illustrate ways in
which centre-based programmes have been developed specifically in order to
provide integrated care to the young child.  Integrated programmes are designed
to include health, nutrition, and education services.  The emphasis given to
the different components depends, to a large extent, on the sponsoring agency.
In the next sub-category are early childhood care and education programmes that
have been implemented in conjunction with services being provided for adults or as an entry point
into the community in order to
develop a range of community based services.<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>E. In adult or community development centres.</b><p>
<p>
     In this sub-category are early childhood care and education programmes
that are provided in centres where the primary goal is to provide a service to
adults or the community at large. The ECCE programme has either evolved as an
adjunct to services being provided, or it is created to serve as a base for the
future development of a range of community services. What is true in both
instances is that at some point in time, the population being served has
expressed a need for an ECCE programme.  The examples to be described in this
section have been developed by different sectors--public and private.  Included
is a description of a health sector programme developed in Malaysia; an ECCE
initiative developed in conjunction with a nutrition programme in Indonesia;
women and development efforts in Iraq and Brasil; a community development
effort in Bolivia; and church-sponsored ECCE programmes in Swaziland.<p>
          <p>
          1. <u>Within the health sector</u>. An innovative programme, the
<u>Sang Kancil</u> proejct, has been developed within the squatter settlements
of Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia.  The project was begun in 1978 by the health sector
in an attempt to meet the health needs of those living in urban squatter
settlements.     <p>
<p>
     Squatter settlements are a growing phenomenon in the developing world.
"The current estimate of the population in slums, squatters and shanty towns in
developing countries is 50% of the total urban population." (Yusof, 1984, p.7)
At the policy level there is difficulty in providing services for squatters.
Urban squatters occupy the land illegally. Therefore they are not entitled to
city services--water, sewage, medical care, education, etc. On the other hand,
many squatter settlements are stable communities, including people from a
variety of income levels.  Even those who have the finances to leave the area
often stay. There are a variety of reasons for this: affordable housing may not
be available outside the settlements; families may have a well developed
support system within the settlement that would be lost to them if they moved
elsewhere, and/or individuals may have acquired a leadership position within
the settlements that they could not obtain in other parts of <p>
the city. <p>
     It is widely recognized that the environmemt within squatter settlements
is threatening to people's health--physically, mentally and in terms of
psycho-social development.  Thus, strategies are being sought to meet the needs
of squatter populations--strategies which recognize, value, and build upon the
complex social systems which exist in the settlements. Developers of the
<u>Sang Kancil</u> project were able to do this.      <p>
<p>
     The project was begun by health sector personnel interested in
establishing primary health care centres within <u>kampungs</u>, or districts,
in the settlements.  Meetings were held with community members to determine
their needs and priorities.  They were most interested in having a child care
system for young children, and for creating income generating activities for
women.  Health care was not seen as a priority.  Those involved in developing
the project listened to the community.  Rather than building a health centre,
they 
established a pre-school and an income generating project.  When these were
well established, then it was possible to introduce primary health care, which
is now widely accepted.  One person involved in the project summarizes the
experience as follows:<p>
<pre>
          Listening to the community is an important step...It
          has the advantage of providing information quickly on
          areas of concern...it also has the role of validating
          information received from more formal sources...The
          development of <u>Sang Kancil</u> has illustrated clearly
          (that) the initial thrust of the programme to introduce
          MCH had to be changed...Entry was channeled through the
          preschool system and income generating activities.
                                             Yusof, 1984, p.26
</pre>
     The <u>Sang Kancil</u> model now consists of three components--maternal
and child health clinics, a pre-school programme, and income generating
activities which have become self-supporting.  The project began as an action
research effort at 3 sites. It is now a national programme model and is being
implemented in 13 settlements.<p>
<p>
     The Malaysian example illustrates the way in which a part of the national
health sector has been able to meet their own goals by establishing an ECCE
programme.  There are also examples of international health organizations that
have begun to meet their own goals by implementing early childhood care and
education programmes. In Mauritius, for example, the Family Planning
Association (FPA) of Mauritius recognized that many women needed child care.
The existing programmes were too expensive for women with low incomes. So, the
FPA created a day care centre next door to their own facilities.  The
centreprovides care for 40 children from 3-5.  When mothers bring their
children to the centre they are encouraged to participate in meetings held at
the family planning clinic. There are weekly lectures on child health and
family planning.  In addition, home visits can be arranged to accomodate the
schedule of working mothers.<p>
<p>
     The centre also provides on-the-job training for young women interested in
working in early childhood programmes.  After the young women have participated
in the training programme for two years they can establish their own child care
centre.   The City Council of Port-Louis is interested in the ECCE model as
developed by the Family Planning Association and has expressed an interest in
establishing similar programmes in other parts of the city. The Mauritius
Women's Self-Help Association has plans to set up similar centres in other
towns.  Thus, in response to the needs of women in the community, a service was
created by the Family Planning Association.  As women brought their children to
the centre they began to take part in other FPA actvities. In this way the
goals of the FPA are being realised.<p>
<p>
     Another example comes from the International Red Cross.  The Swaziland Red
Cross Society created 8 regional primary health care centres in 1980. Early
childhood care and education programmes are a part of these centres. An ECCE
programmes has been included for a variety of reasons: a. it was recognized
that multiple purpose centres are more cost-effective; b. there was a demand
for quality care from working women; c. there was an awareness that within
Swaziland it is important for children to have a pre- school experience if they
hope to enter first grade; and d. having an ECCE programme in the <p>
health centre assures that children's health can be monitored, immunizations
can be kept up to date, nutritional supplementation can be provided, children
can be taught good health habits, and there is the possibility of identifying
developmental problems. (Evans, 1983, p.20)<p>
<p>
     The Red Cross is working closely with the Ministry of Health to develop
appropriate materials to be used in the centres.  They are also working closely
with the Ministry of Education.  Their policy is to have multiple donor
collaboration in building and equipping the centres.  The Red Cross will match
funds provided by other agencies, ministries and organizations. For example,
when one of the centres was built, the U.S. embassy provided funding for the
construction of the building, the Ministry of Education provided technical
assistance in the design of the building, the Red Cross contributed funds for
equipping the facility, and the commmunity actually built the structure.
       <p>
<p>
          2. <u>In conjunction with nutrition programmes</u>. In addition to
the development of early childhood care and education programmes in connection
with health programmes, there has also been an attempt to integrate ECCE
activities into nutrition programmes.  An interesting example comes from
Indonesia. In the early 1970s a nutrition project was initiated, the Applied
Nutrition Program (ANP), designed to produce more protein foods and to increase
children's protein intake.  The programme was evaluated in 1973 (Sayogyo,
1975). From the evaluation it was evident that protein supplementation would
not solve the problem.  There was a recognition of the relationship between
malnutrition and poverty. Thus in the next five year plan (l974-l979), known as
the REPELITA II, there was a social marketing emphasis. An attempt was made to
make people aware of the problem of malnutrition--its causes and effects--and
an effort to get all sectors involved in addressing the issues.  A variety of
approaches were tried. The programme which finally evolved is known as the
National Family Nutrition Programme, which, during REPELITA III (1979-1984),
was expected to be implemented in 40,000 of the 65,000 villages in Indonesia
(Rohde &amp; Hendrata, 1982, p.212).<p>
<p>
     It is within the context of this nationally implemented nutrition
programme that the <u>Bina Keuarga and Balita</u> (BKB) project was
implemented. Begun in 1982, the BKB project is an attempt to add an early
childhood education component to the existing structure of services to
families. The focus of the BKB project is on parent education.  The purpose of
the project is to "enhance the knowledge, awareness and skills of mothers of
children under five and other members of the family so as to enable them to
provide [a] conducive educational environment to ensure the comprehensive
development of children under five." (Stein, 1985, p.1).  Field workers--women
from the community being served--are provided with training in child
development and adult education.  They then provide workshops for mothers at
the nutrition centres.  In the workshops mothers receive child development
information, their role as primary eduators of the child is emphasized, and
they are provided with easy activities that they can do with their children at
home.  In addition, a toy library has been established.  Mothers can take toys
home with them and use them with their chidlren.  When they return the toys the
following week, they can take out something else.  Local toys have been created
which are adaptations of the toys modelled by CINDE, the Latin American group
which developed the programme being implemented in the BKB project. <p>
     <p>
<p>
     The BKB project was initiated by the office of the Associate Ministry for
the Role of Women.  As the programme was developed a number of sectors were
involved--Women's Development, Education, Health, Socio-cultural Development,
and Welfare.  Although ultimate responsibility for the programme has remained
within the office of the Associate Minister for the Role of Women, as the
programme has been implemented on a wider scale, the leading sector has shifted
from year to year. For 1983-1984 it was under the Directorate General for Rural
Development, and for 1984-1985 the Directorate General for Non-Formal
Education, Youth and Sports took the lead. Currently the National Family
Planning Co- ordinating Board has the responsibility for wider implementation
of the programme. <p>
<p>
     To assure that the programme will continue to have inter-sectoral support,
working groups at the central and provincial level are being created which
include as many sectors as possible.  In an evaluation of the project a list
was provided of the potential departments and programmes with which the BKB
programmme could be integrated.  It included: Home Affairs, Health,
Agriculture, Social Affairs, Education and Culture, Religion, Information,
Ministry Coordinator for People's Welfare, Industry, Justice, Manpower and
Transmigration...and the list goes on. (UNICEF Board Report, 1985, II. p.1-3)
<p>
<p>
     In essence, the BKB project is an example of how early childhood care and
education efforts can be added on to existing organizational structures, taking
advantage of systems already in place, while adding an important  component in
support of children's overall development. It is also an example of a programme
which relies on and receives multi-sectoral support for its continuation.<p>
<p>
<p>
               3. <u>Within women in development  programmes.</u>  During the
last 20 years there has been an increased recogntion of women's role in
development, and efforts have been made to support women's greater involvement
in the wage economy.  Support for women's development has come from national
governments and the international community. On the national level policy has
been created in many countries which focuses on involving the total population
in development. Examples of this come from Kenya and Tanzania, where, after
independence, there was an emphasis on community self-help. All people were
encouraged to work together to promote the country's development. In other
instances policy changes have come about as the result of the changing
structure of manpower within the country.  For example, in Iraq, where the
country is at war, there is a need for women to enter the work force and take
the place of men who are at the front. Thus women are being given new training
opportunities, and there are expectations that they will be involved in overall
development efforts.  <p>
<p>
     Within the international community, the UN Decade for Women, begun in
1975, provided the impetus for a number of government and international donor
agency sponsored projects whose explicit focus was on increasing women's
opportunities for development. The conference in Kenya, celebrating the end of
the first Women in Development decade, 1975-1985, set some new programme
directions, building upon what was learned in the first decade.<p>
<p>
     Some of the projects designed to promote women's development have been
successful; others have not met intended goals.  By and large, those that have
met with the most success are those that have provided women with the supports
they have needed to take on new roles.  The primary support required is a
recognition of the fact that even though women are being given new
opportunities, their traditional responsibilities remain intact--those related
to the household and child care.  In order for women to fully participate in
development, quality child care must be available.<p>
<p>
     In most instances those developing the programmes have not recognized the
importance of developing a care situation for the child. More commonly, women
themselves have realised their need and created their own programmes. The
Malata Market Place programme in Ghana, described earlier, is an example. The
child care centre developed in relation to women's agricultural work in
Senegal, also described earlier, is yet another example. Both the Ghana and the
Senegal initiatives were developed by women in a given community, to meet their
own needs.  <p>
<p>
     Efforts have been made to create child care centres on a national level as
well. An example is the system of training and provision being developed in
Iraq. There have been two major thrusts to the development of child care in
Iraq. Since the mid 1970s there has been a government policy to increase
women's participation in development. More recently, since the war with Iran,
there has been a need for more women to enter formal employment because men are
involved in military activities.  There are two major organizations responsible
for the development of child care which will allow women to work outside the
home: the Ministry of Labor and Social Affairs and the General Federation of
Iraqi Women (GWIF)--each of whom operate about half of the 162currently
registered child care centres. (Evans, 1984, p.3) At this point in time the
Ministry and the GFIW are seeking ways to integrate their systems of child care
and to develop lower cost alternatives that will make child care available to a
larger percentage of the eligible children.     <p>
<p>
     Another example of early childhood care and education programmes developed
in relation to women and development programmes and centres comes from Brasil.
In 1979 the <u>Centro de Estudos Supletivos de Narandiba</u> (CESUN) was
established to provide nonformal education and vocational training to
low-income peoples. One of the group's activities has been the development of
women's programmes. As CESUN began to plan programmes, a problem arose.<p>
<pre>
          One of CESUN's original ideas was to provide vocational
          training to the women in non-traditional areas, such as
          plumbing or electricity. Although the women expressed
          interest in such training, they asked what they would
          do with their children while they attended sessions.
                                         Rocha et al., 1983, p.10
</pre>
Following a series of discussions it was determined that CESUN should not only
establish a child care centre, but it should also develop a caregivers training
course to provide staff for the centre and to provide trained staff to other
child care centres that were being developed in the community. Thus, one of the
vocational training courses offered through CESUN is Caretaking. Within the 160
hour training course women are taught child development, nutrition, health and
first aid, and techniques for helping children learn.  They also discuss the
economic and social context of women's work, legislation relating to labour and
women's rights, the relationship of women's economic activity to family
planning, and community relations. (Rocha, et.al., 1983, p. 7-8).  Thus, in
addition to meeting the immediate needs of women who wanted to <p>
participate in training, a course was developed that provided women with
marketable skills and knowledge. Not incidentally, what they learned in the
course also helped them in their own parenting role.<p>
<p>
<p>
          4. <u>As a part of community development efforts</u>. There are a
range of international donor agencies that have been involved in community
development efforts.  The general design of such projects is to work with the
community to identify needs, and then to create a range of services to meet
these needs. In a variety of instances the community defines early childhood
care and education programmes as a priority. As a result, ECCE programmes are
created, either in support of existing services, or as an entry point into the
community and a base from which other community development activities can
evolve.<p>
<p>
     An example of an ECCE programme which is part of an overall community
development effort is the <u>Centro Socio-Educativo Los Andes</u> in Oruru,
Bolivia.  Oruro is located in an area of Bolivia which suffers from extreme
poverty.  The Christian Children's Fund (CCF), a child sponsorship
organization, has been working in the community to improve the life situation
of young children.  The focus of the effort in this particular community is on
improving the health and general development of children under 6 years of age.
Rather than providing financial subsidies to individual families, CCF decided
to take a part of each family's subsidy and to create a community service
centre. When the programme began adult education courses were offered and
medical and dental services were provided. Child care was provided in the
centre for the children of adults attending the courses.     <p>
<p>
     Over time the child care component became of increasing interest to the
community.  They wanted to establish a pre-school for those between the ages of
3 and 6.  When it began, the pre-school served 20 children full-time, five days
a week.  However, this provided an important service to only a small percentage
of the children who could potentially benefit from the programme.  So, after
much discussion, the format for the pre-school was changed so that 240 children
could be served in a year.  In groups of 30, children attend either the A.M. or
P.M. sessions offered Monday- Wednesday or Tuesday-Saturday. Thus 120 children
participate each week. These children attend the pre-school for 6 months.  An
additional 120 children attend in the next six months.  In this way far more
children are served.<p>
<p>
     Now there is also a home visiting programme as a part of the centre's
activities. Essentially the home visitor, a trained community volunteer, is
responsible for monitoring the family's use of the services offered through the
centre.  When a child is accepted for sponsorship by CCF, an initial home visit
is made, during which the home visitor explains the sponsorship and what
services the child and family can receive through the programme.  Based on the
family's needs, the home visitor makes recommendations regarding their
participation.   In addition, the home visitor makes bi-monthly visits to the
families of 0-3 year olds to check and advise on health, nutrition, and child
development. She also follows up family participation at the centre.
(Schaefer, et al, 1984, p.16).<p>
<p>
     The programme is newly begun.  However, the funding and technical
assistance--provided through a USAID grant--which supported programme
development, will end in fall, 1985.  CCF will continue to provide funds for <p>
the operation of the community center through its child sponsorship programme.
In addition,  CCF is looking at the Oruro project as a model programme for
enhancing the overall provision of child care within other centres world-wide
which are operated with CCF funds. Thus, one of the products of the technical
assistance process provided in the Oruro project will be a manual providing
guidance to others wishing to create similar projects.<p>
 <p>
<p>
          5. <u>Religiously affiliated ECCE programmes</u>.  Religious groups
concerned with providing a service within their community will either create
their own ECCE programme, or allow someone to operate a programme within their
facility. Generally the curriculum for the programme includes religious
material. If the day care is the only one available in an area, parents will
enroll their children, even if they are of a different religion.  In instances
where there is a strong social service or conversion thrust to the work of the
denomination, ECCE programmes are seen as a way of reaching the community.<p>
<p>
     A good example of this comes from Swaziland--a small country in southern
Africa, where there are a number of protestant and catholic groups which have
established systems of early childhood care and education.  The Baptists have
developed a demonstration centre with seven classrooms and a training facility
where they train approximately 30 teachers a year.  People coming to the
training are sponsored by the Ministry of Education, private industry, and
other private agencies.  The Baptist training facility is the only in-country
training available.  The training and child curriculum are based on religious
teachings.  Because they have already developed their own training, the Baptist
Church is in a strong position to influence the develoment of a national
curriculum for both teachers and young children.  However, there are other
denominations which have begun to develop their own programme.<p>
<p>
     The Lutheran Mission is in the process of establishing a training centre
as an alternative to the Baptist training. The Lutherans have created a
demonstration classroom as a part of an evolving multi- purpose facility. The
Bahai faith is another dominant force in early childhood in Swaziland.
Although they have more recently begun to create pre-schools, the national
committee appears to be committed to the development of a pre-school programme
for Swaziland.  The Catholic Church has also developed several pre- schools.
At this point their teachers are sent to Kenya for training or they are being
trained through Montessori correspondence courses. Clearly a number of costly
facilities and programmes are being created. What is needed are national,
rather than denomination, guidelines for the development of early childhood
care and education programmes in the country. (Evans, 1983).     <p>
<p>
     Another example of religious-affilated early childhood care and education
sponsorship is the YWCA in the South Pacific.  For the past twenty years the
YWCA has been supporting the development of ECCE programmes (for children ages
2 to 6) throughout the Pacific Islands.  The curriculum reflects adaptations of
Western, traditional, half-day pre-school programmes, with an emphasis on
Christian teachings. The Pacific Pre-School Council, a membership organization
with representation from all the Pacific islands, receives its primary support
from the YWCA. Periodically workshops are held so that those involved in ECCE
programmes can share their experiences and learn from one another.  Such a
workshop was held in 1980, sponsored by the YWCA South Pacific Area.  Other
public and private groups were also involved, yet the religious influence of
the pre-schools is evident in reports of current activities.  It is also <p>
evident in a summary of the workshop where the organizer commented:<p>
<pre>
          I believe that the outcome of this Workshop has 
          really been to lay a solid foundation for Pre-
          school work in the Pacific. The spiritual life
          of the Workshop was enriched by sharing in
          morning devotions.
                                  Goodwillie, 1980, p.iii
</pre>
     The denominational beginnings of the early childhood care and education
movement in any country can exert a lasting influence on the development of
regional or national curricula--for the children and for teacher training. This
must be taken into consideration when attempts are made to collaborate with
these groups in order to include other curriculum components into the ECCE
system.<p>
<p>
<p>
     Within this chapter a typology of early childhood care and education
programmes has been presented.  The typology is based on the <u>setting</u>
within which the ECCE programme is established.  However, within the
<u>setting</u> typology it quickly becomes evident that <u>sponsorship</u> and
<u>programme characteristics</u> are equally, if not more, important in the
development of a strategy for the implementation of a wider range of health
care components into existing systems.  Thus, in the next chapter an attempt is
made to map out the implications of the typology. 
<p>
<p>
<b>VI. THE POTENTIAL FOR DELIVERY OF PHC/MCH COMPONENTS THROUGH
EARLY
CHILDHOOD</b><p>
<b>CARE AND EDUCATION PROGRAMMES; RECOMMENDATIONS FOR
ACTION</b><p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
     This section begins with a brief description of the maternal and child
health care components of primary health care that could be delivered through
early childhood care and education programmes.  This is followed by a
discussion of the relative ease with which the various components could be
provided, based on the <u>setting</u> of the ECCE programme.  The section ends
with a set of recommendations for action, based on an assessment of the
potential for actually being able to work within the <u>settings</u>, taking
into consideration <u>sponsorship</u> and <u>programme characteristics</u>.
The recommendations are offered as alternative courses of action.  They are
provided to promote discussion within the WHO.  The specific actions undertaken
will need to be derived from those discussions.<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>A. Health care components.</b><p>
<p>
     There are two different issues related to the delivery of MCH care.  One
has to do with making technologies--techniques, equipment, actions and
activities--available to all people.  For example, it is possible to prevent a
number of debilitating diseases through immunization.  A relatively simple
action gives people the protection they need.  Another set of actions is
associated with the treatment of diarrhea--Oral Rehydration Therapy.  The
action, in this case, provides a cure to an immediate problem.  It does not
address what caused the problem.  One of the ways to make the technologies
available to people is through social marketing.  Campaigns with slogans and
simple, appropriate presentations of information are designed to capture
people's attention.  They are made aware of an action they can take to solve a
problem.  Many social marketing strategies are highly effective.  Yet they deal
with only one aspect of health care.<p>
<p>
     At quite a diferent level, the issue in health care provision is how to
change attitudes and alter people's decision-making patterns that are related
to the cause of the problem and/or provide a long- term solution.  Here the
concern is to help people understand how their behavior affects health
outcomes.  The focus is on prevention of problems. For example, birth outcomes
is a concern in many parts of the world.  How do you help women understand the
impact of their eating habits on a child's growth and development? Another
issue is the high rate of malnutrition and infectious disease among infants and
young children which come about as a result of poor feeding patterns.
Breastfeeding is one solution. How do you best promote the idea of
breastfeeding?  What is there within the culture that affects attitudes and
practices related to breastfeeding?  Another issue to address has to do with <p>
cognitive and psycho-social development.  Few children receive from the
environment the stimulation needed for optimal development.  How do you work
with parents to help them understand the importance and value of time and
energy given to creating opportunities for children's learning?<p>
<p>
     In essence, the technologies associated with behavioural and attitudinal
change are much less well developed.  The challenge in attempting to deliver
health care components through early childhood care and education programmes is
to determine which <u>actions/activities</u> can be provided and which
<u>attitudes and decision-making processes</u> can be affected.  In briefly
describing the health care components, an attempt will be made to differentiate
between the two.<p>
<p>
     In considering the MCH care components that can be delivered in ECCE
programmes it is necessary to differentiate what might be offered to two
different age groups--children from birth to under three years of age, and
children from 3-6 years old.  Often these age groups are served in different
contexts, and different emphases are given to the various health care
components.  For example, nutrition is often a focus of programmes for children
under three. With children between the ages of 3 and 6, more emphasis is given
to the development of good health habits.  In both instances there are
opportunities for cognitive and psycho-social stimulation.<p>
<p>
     It is also necessary to differentiate between the health care components
that can be delivered by ECCE personnel, and those that require the skills and
knowledge of health care personnel.  Personnel within ECCE programmes can be
trained to provide a range of health care components, particularly those
associated with prevention. In other instances, however, someone from the
health sector needs to be available to provide the services.  Given these
considerations, the health care components that could be provided within ECCE
programmes consist of:<p>
<p>
          1. Custodial care that would assure the basic <u>safety and
well-being</u> of the child.  In the most basic care situation, the child
should be provided with shelter and be free from physical danger.  This is not
always the case when the programmes are offered in inadequate facilities.<p>
<p>
          2. In most ECCE efforts, basic <u>monitoring of growth and
development</u> could occur.  Monitoring would consist of periodically
measuring children's weight and height, and recording the information on growth
charts developed in relation to national reference values. Growth monitoring
would give providers some "bottom line" information on the child's general
level of development.  It is an action that can lead to behavior change only if
those doing the monitoring are able to interpret the information it provides.
Currently the WHO is developing a prototype of children's growth and
psychosocial development record which will incorporate culture-appropriate
indicators (milestones/landmarks) of development which can be used by primary
health care workers (PHWs).  The study is also investigating the factors which
promote optimal growth and development and also factors of risk.  The training
of ECCE providers and PHCWs on these issues will lead to a better understanding
of and stimulate action with reference to growth and development.<p>
<p>
          3. Within the context of some ECCE programmes more sophisticated
<u>screening</u> could take place that would allow for the <u>early
identification of specfic problems in growth and development</u>, including
such things as mental <p>
retardation, loss of hearing, speech problems, vision problems, developmental
delays, and learning disabilities.  In general, ECCE providers can refer
someone for testing, but the detailed screening would be provided by PHCWs and
health care personnel at first or second level referrals.<p>
<p>
          4. In collaboration with the health sector, <u>immunization
programmes</u> could be established with ECCE providers working with PHCWs,
health care personnel and parents to assure timely immunization of children and
pregnant women.<p>
<p>
          5. The nutritional status of children could be <u>assessed</u> either
ECC providers or health care personnel. Nutritional <u>supplementation</u>
could be provided by ECCE personnel to the child who is mildly or moderately
malnourished. For there to be a real chanage in the child's nutritional status,
however, parent education must also be a part of the ECCE effort.<p>
<p>
          6. <u>Basic health care</u> needs could be met within the context of
the ECCE programme--sanitation, personal hygiene, etc.  In addition, education
of the young child (particularly in the 3-6 year old group) could occur which
would help create good health habits.  Some of these habits might well be
brought into the home by the child.<p>
<p>
          7.  Some level of <u>physical, cognitive and psycho-social
stimulation</u>  could be provided for the child in  all ECCE settings.  Within
this area there are no simple technologies or actions.  To provide adequate
stimulation, the person working with the child has to have basic knowledge of
child growth and psychosocial development.<p>
<p>
     In addition to being able to provide direct delivery of health care
actions and activities to young children, it would be possible to deliver a
number of services to women of childbearing age and other community members
through the ECCE programme.  The specific services that could be provided
within the ECCE setting include: 1. <u>family planning</u>; 2. <u>nutritional
assessment of women and nutritional supplementation</u> for pregnant and
lactating women who are malnourished or anaemic; 3. <u>Tetanus immunization</u>
for pregnant women, in collaboration with health care personnel; 4. information
on and support for <u>breastfeeding</u>; and 5. <u>education</u> on health,
nutrition, and children's growth and development.<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>B. The ease of delivering the MCH components of PHC in the range of ECCE
settings.</b><p>
<p>
     Using the <u>setting</u> typology, it is possible to do a mapping of the
relative ease of introducing the different health components into the various
settings.  A mapping is presented in Table 1.  A rating of "low","medium" or
"high" has been made for each health care component, in each setting category.
A rating of "low" indicates that it is highly unlikely that the health care
component could be delivered in that setting; "medium" indicates that, with the
proper supports, the health care component could be introduced, and "high" means that
there is a good probability that the health care component could be
successfully delivered.  The ratings are based on what is known about the
setting itself and the characteristics of programmes generally found in those
settings.  (Obviously there is room for a great deal of discussion around these
ratings.)<p>
<p>
<b>C. Recommendations for action.</b><p>
<p>
     If some agreement can be reached about the relative ease of delivering the
various health care components through ECCE programmes, the next question
becomes, what would it take to make it happen--in terms of training, materials
and on going support?  What is the cost?  Obviously the cost of developing an
appropriate intervention for each setting would be prohibitive.  Thus, given an
assessment of the likelihood of successfully introducing the MCH components of
PHC in a given setting, and the costs associated with each strategy, a decision
can be made about priorities for investment.  Recommendations about the
investment of resources in creating strategies for delivery of PHC/MCH
components is done by <u>setting</u>.<p>
<p>
          1. <u>In the home</u>.  This setting includes three different types
of programmes.  First, there are home visiting programmes where providers work
on a one-to-one basis with the parent, giving her child development information
and suggesting activities that can be done with the child to promote the
child's develoment.  Even though these programmes are targeted to work with
those most in need of services, they do not reach many families.  Thus, <u>it
is recommended that resources not be invested in developing materials and/or
training for home visiting programmes</u>.<p>
<p>
     The second type of "in the home" programmes are the parent education
efforts where parent groups are created and meet on a regular basis over a
given period of time.  In the group meetings parents are given information on a
range of topics related to early childhood care and education.  They are
expected to take the information given and apply it in their homes.  The
curriculum for the parent education courses vary, depending on who sponsors the
course.  Courses are offered by a variety of sectors-- education, health,
welfare, community development.  Thus, there are many groups that could be
worked with to introduce and/or upgrade current coverage of primary and
maternal and child health issues.  <u>It is recommended that the possibility be
explored of developing a set of materials that could be delivered through
parent education courses--either creating a complete course of its own, or by
developing materials that could supplement current efforts.</u>.<p>
<p>
     The third "in the home" set of programmes are represented by the CHILD-to
child initiatives.  These are based on primary health care concerns, and are
well developed.  However, <u>it is recommended that the current training and
support materials used in the CHILD- to-child programmes be reviewed with an
eye to whether or not they include support for cognitive stimulation and
psycho-social activities</u>.<p>
<p>
          2. <u>In the neighborhood</u>.  The programmes in this category
(known asfamily day care or child minding), can be divided into two
groups--those that fall within the non-formal and those that are included in
the formal systems of provision.  The former are characterized by providers who
have developed a programme on their own initiative.  The latter are providers
who are linked to an agency or organization which sponsors provision for young
children through family day care homes.  Those providers who have initiated
their own programme seldom have linkages to a formal network of child care
provision.  Thus, while there are many individual providers, they are hard to
reach.  Therefore, <u>it is recommended that family day care providers who are
part of the non-formal system not be a priority for action</u>.<p>
     <p>
     A diffferent recommendation is being made in terms of working with the
formal system of family day care provision.  There are an increasing number of
systems of family day care provision-- generally operated by welfare and/or
community development groups.  Family day care provides a low-cost alternative
to the building of expensive ECCE facilities, and is a model of provision that
is becoming an attractive alternative to centre- based ECCE programmes. <u>It
is recommended that resources be invested in creating materials and/or training
packages for family day care providers who are part of a system of ECCE
provision</u>.  These materials can then be made available to providers from
the non-formal system who wish to use them.<p>
<p>
          3. <u>In the workplace.</u> Once again, a distinction needs to be
made between the formal and non-formal systems.  The formal system is
represented by employer-sponsored ECCE programmes.  These programmes are
frequently mandated to provide child care for children of employees.  The
mandate comes from national policy, and is further defined through related
legislation.  In many developed countries, particularly in Eastern Europe,
employer- sponsored day care is pervasive.  At this point in time, outside of a
few countries, employer-sponsored child care is not a moving force in ECCE
provision in developing countries.  However, because these ECCE programmes can
develop into large systems of care, <u>it is recommended that there be
involvement in working closely with national governments who are developing
policy and ligislation in support of employer-sponsored child care, to develop
appropriate training and materials for use in that context</u>.<p>
<p>
     Further, <u>it is being recommended that the difficulty of becoming
involved with the non-formal work sector be recognized, and work be done with
indigenous groups interested in developing ECCE systems</u>. Many of the
programmes that characterize the non-formal work sector--the market place and
agricultural settings--tend to be unique to the geographic region and the
specific needs of a relatively small group of women.  While market place women
all around the world need child care, these women are not linked together in
any way that would support promotion of ECCE programmes in the marketplace.
Thus, rather than focusing efforts on the unique non-formal work setting, it
would be more appropriate to work with nationally organized indigenous groups
which provide linkages within a country and/or regions of the world.<p>
          4. <u>In children's centers</u>. The programmes within this category
are all centre-based ECCE efforts which are found in facilities developed,
built, or refurbished specifically to meet the needs of young children. There
are three major sub categories: the "open-air" programmes; the programmes that
operate in primary schools; and integral care services designed to meet the
child's multiple needs.<p>
<p>
     The open-air category consists of programmes which rely primarily on
community support for their existence.  Some of the programmes have been
developed with support from public and private organizations from outside the
community, but, in general, these programmes are based upon community
initiative.  What that means is that they are not adequately supported in any
way.  The facilities, if they exist at all, are make-shift and sometimes
unsafe.  Staffing generally consists of community para- professionals who may
or may not receive any training.  In addition, they either provide their time
to the programme on a voluntary basis, or they are paid a small stipend derived
from school fees.  Materials are non-existent.  These programmes lack 
the resources necessary to develop a curriculum and could not afford to pay for
the training and materials which would give them the skills and knowledge
necessary to promote health care activities. <p>
<p>
     Despite these contraints, there is a need to deliver or assist in
delivering MCH care services within these ECCE settings. First of all, the
open-air, non-formal ECCE programmes represent the fastest growing category of
programmes.  Second, these programmes are being created in places not currently
served by either formal ECCE provision or health care centers.  Thus, they are
reaching those most in need. Third, the community has made a commitment to
these programmes.  They utilize the resources available to them to implement
and maintain the programme. This commitment can be built upon for the
development of health care services, as evidenced by the Malaysia experience.
Fourth, the door is open for multi-sectoral involvement in these programmes.
For most of the programmes there is no formalized curriculum that would have to
be adapted, although informally the programme may be linked to education,
health and welfare. There is an opportunity to create a comprehensive
programme. The drawback is that open air programmes are the responsibility of
different sectors in different countries.  Thus a variety of strategies will
have to be developed to work with these programmes.  In sum, <u>it is
recommended that investment be made in supporting the development of
community-based ECCE efforts and strategies be developed for working with
different sectors to promote and/or up-grade community-based ECCE
programmes</u>.<p>
<p>
     The next sub-category of center-based programmes is represented by those
found in primary schools.  In this instance the programmes are sponsored almost
exclusively by the education sector and operate as a part of the formal school
system. In all probability it would be difficult to work with these programmes.
The curriculum has been set. While it is more than likely that it includes a
health education component, it is unlikely that the systems would be open to
the delivery of a range of health care services.  <u>It is recommended that
ECCE programes found in primary school settings be given support for the
delivery of health care components only after support for higher priority
settings is provided</u>.<p>
<p>
     The third sub-category, those programmes designed to provide integral care
to young children, is, by and large, already providing a range of health,
nutrition and education services. However, because they are developed under
different sponsors, the emphasis will vary. An appropriate course of action
would be to assess the materials currently being used in these efforts, and to
bring together the most useful materials for dissemination to similar
programmes.  In addition, it would be useful to create a training package that
could be used across sectors and adapted regionally. Thus <u>it recommended
that an analysis of training and support materials for integrated care
programmes be completed to assess their completeness, their ease of use, and
their applicability, with the goal of creating packages that can be
disseminated to the different sectors involved in the development of integral
care settings</u>.<p>
<p>
<p>
          5. <u>In adult/community centres</u>. The sub-categories within this
grouping tend to represent sponsors.  For example, there are programmes
developed and implemented by the health sector.  Obviously these are already
delivering many of the health components.  One area that may be neglected,
however, is the cognitive and psycho-social stimulation needs of young
children. Work could be done to examine current curriculum in health sponsored
ECCE programmes, and the to develop materials and supports for a broader
curriculum in these settings. Likewise, ECCE programmes operating in nutrition
centers may well need the same kind of support to implement the full range of
activities that support the child's total development. Thus, <u>it is
recommended that an assessment of current health and nutrition sponsored ECCE
programmes be made to determine the extent to which they are providing optimal
experiences related to children's multiple needs</u><p>
<p>
     Another sub-category of ECCE programmes are those found in connection with
women and development projects.  In the description of some of the programmes
developed in relation to women's place of work, it was noted that these efforts
may be unique to a given location, given the nature of woman's work in that
setting and the supports that are available to her.  Thus, it may be hard to
reach enough children to justify developing programmes in relation to the
non-formal work sector.  <p>
     However, it may be worth approaching these programmes from a different
angle. There are an increasing number of women and development programmes--many
of which have come to an awareness of the need to develop child care programmes
if women are to avail themselves of training and education opportunities and
secure work in the formal sector. There is a growing network of women and
development programmes.  While many of those in the network will not be
directly involved in creating and operating child care programmes, they may
well be involved in such efforts within their countries.  In addition, these
programmes have an important role to play in terms of maternal and child
health.  They are able to address a number of women's needs; health is a basic
issue. This network should be a part of developing training and materials that
can be used to establish quality child care programmes   Therefore, <u>it is
recommended that work be done with women in development programmes to create
ways of introducing primary and maternal and child health care components into
the range of services they offer</u>. This collaboration should have a
relatively high priority since women's groups are able to reach many
populations currently not being reached by health centres.<p>
<p>
     In programmes which have a community development focus there is likely to
be an awareness of the multiple needs of children and families, and an ability
to develop a range of programmes in response to community needs. What tends to
happen within the community development field, however, is that many involved
in working with a given community do not think that programmes and services
offered in their setting are applicable in other settings.  But, in fact, there
are important principles and guidelines that can be derived from the wealth of
community development experience over the past twenty years.  What is needed is
a systematic examination of the ways in which early childhood care and
education programmes have served the goals of community develoment,
particularly as these efforts relate to the introduction and acceptance of
health components. <u>It is recommended that work be done with community
development experts to derive models that can be applied in other contexts</u>.
It would appear that training and support materials developed for multi-
sectoral early childhood care and education programmes, and for women in
development programmes, would also be applicable in the community development
context.<p>
<p>
<p>
          5. <u>In religious centres</u>.  In the case study section there was
a description of church groups that have been involved in the development of
ECCE programming as a way of providing a service to the community.  In some <p>
instances the efforts have been local; in other cases national programmes have
been developed.  By and large, these religious groups, while representing
internationally operating denominations, have not created a network of early
childhood care and education programmes. For the most part these groups do not
reach large numbers of children, nor do they have the resources to create large
systems of care.  Therefore, <u>it is recommended not to become involved in
working with denominations groups within countries to promote the delivery of
health care through their programmes</u><p>
<p>
     On the other hand, there are several large systems of early childhood care
and education programmes which have been developed by religiously affiliated
organizations.  An example of this is the YWCA and the network of programmes
that they have supported in the South Pacific.  Another set of examples come
from within the community of private voluntary organizations--Catholic Relief
Services, Christian Children's Fund, and many more.  By and large the focus of
these international organizations has been on the development of relief and
survival programmes. However, many of these groups are attempting to examine
the overall impact of their programming and are becoming involved in efforts
that raise the quality of life for everyone in the community.  There is
increased interest in developing programmes for young children that include
cognitive and psycho-social stimulation as well as nutritonal rehabilitation
and supplementation. Thus, <u>it is being recommended that work be done with
private voluntary agencies in support of this expansion of their services, and
that the support of these groups be sought in the development of appropriate
training and materials to bring health to all</u>.<p>
<p>
<p>
     In sum, there are a variety of strategies that can be developed to extend
the MCH components of PHC through early childhood care and education
programmes. The strategies to be developed rely on an understanding of the
context within which ECCE programmes currently operate, and an assessment of
the potential of these programmes to deliver health care components. This paper
has provided information on the context of ECCE programmes, the sponsors, and
the day-to-day experience for children and families being served by the
programme. The typologies presented provide a framework within which strategies
can be developed. In this concluding section an assessment has been made of the
probability of meeting world health goals by working within a range of settings
with different public and private agencies and organizations.  Further, a
series of recommendations for action were made. These are not meant as policy.
They have been developed as a point of departure for debate and discussion,
with the expectation that, as a result of the process, appropriate actions will
be undertaken. <p>
<p>
