</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>IMPROVING PROGRAM ACTIONS TO
MEET THE INTERSECTING NEEDS OF WOMEN AND CHILDREN
IN DEVELOPING COUNTRIES:</title>
</head><body><center><b>IMPROVING PROGRAM ACTIONS TO<br>
MEET THE INTERSECTING NEEDS OF WOMEN AND CHILDREN<br>
IN DEVELOPING COUNTRIES:<br>
<p>
A POLICY AND PROGRAM REVIEW</b><br>
<p>
Judith L. Evans<br>
<p>
with the collaboration of Robert G. Myers<br>
<p>
The Consultative Group on Early Childhood Care and Development<br>
High/Scope Educational Research Foundation<br>
November, 1985</center><br>
<p>
<p>
This paper was written under a grant from the Carnegie Corporation. It is
intended to stimulate discussion and does not represent the official position
of the Carnegie Corporation.<p>
<p>
MISSING PAGE I.<p>
<p>
programming related to the intersecting needs of women and children and to make
recommendations in terms of actions that might be taken to assure that women's
and children's intersecting needs are recognised, considered, and planned for
in future development efforts.<p>
<p>
	A review of policies and programs of selected international agencies was
carried out in order to identify successful efforts which benefit both women
and children. It consisted of "desk" reviews of a variety of women in
development projects and early childhood care and education programs, journal
reviews, and interviews with donor agency personnel, private foundation
staff,
and individuals from non-governmental organizations. The following statements
summarize the findings:<p>
<p>
	1. <b>Historically.</b> The premises and assumptions that have provided the
conceptual base for the development of women's and children's programs have not
taken into account the intersecting needs of the two groups. However, program
experience over the past decade has brought increasing awareness that projects
developed for one group may not be supportive of the other group's needs. Today
there are programs which successfully meet the needs of both groups, but they
are scarce.<p>
<p>
	2. <b>Programmatically.</b> In general, those programs which are successfully
meeting the needs of both women and children have evolved as a single-focus
program has been implemented and a wider range of needs have emerged and
appropriate components added. It is wore common for a women in development
program to eventually include a child care component than it is for an early
childhood care and education program to include programming for women.<p>
<ol>		a. Where a program has been developed for women, child care is a likely add
on; it develops as a result of women's expressed need for child care support.
The primary focus of the child care program is on the child's safety. While
many women are aware of the multiple needs of children that should be met
through these programs, they seldom have the expertise and/or
resources to assure that a full range of services is available for children.<p>
<p>
		b. If an early childhood care and education program develops a component for
women, programming focusses on her nurturing and reproductive role, not her
productive role. Thus only a limited number of women's needs are addressed. In
fact, there are times when the program component being developed in support of
the reproductive role is in conflict with women's
productive role.</ol><p>
<p>
3. <b>Organizationally.</b> In terms of donor agencies, the further free the
field one goes, the less awareness there is of the intersecting needs of women
and children. Further, personnel within agencies and organizations that work
with national governments generally have loner levels of awareness of the
issues than those working in non-governmental agencies. This may be because
many governments have a conservative perspective on women's role in
development. On the other hand, governments may be willing to invest in
programs which promote children's survival; few have made an investment in
programming for children's on-going development,
<p>
    4. <b>In the literature.</b> Journals which focus on women's development
seldom refer to children, except in terms of child care centers that have been
created in support of women's changing role. Likewise, early childhood journals
generally focus on how to create effective programs for young
children; little or no consideration is given to the needs of parents. A
theoretical awareness of some of the potential trade-offs in current
programming is found in a few articles from within a variety of academic
disciplines (anthropology, economics, education, community development,
psychology, agriculture, sociology), illustrative of the fact that the issues
cut across traditional academic boundaries.<p>
<p>
	5. <b>Conceptually.</b> There is an examination of the position which
separated women's productive and reproductive role. There is a move to validate
both roles. Today arguments are being made to the effect that:<p>
<p>
<ol>		a. It is legitimate to support the development of women&#146;s productive
role by strengthening women's reproductive role. This is being done by:
providing monetary or work-related rewards for child care and
education--recognizing that these activities are productive as well as
personally rewarding--and by recognizing women's participation in the provision
of child care as a valid farm of work for women that should be judged as other
jobs are judged--in terms of pay, incremental knowledge, skill development,
security, training, self-esteem, etc.<p>
<p>
		b. It is legitimate to support children's development by focusing on the
development of women in their productive roles. Those characteristics which
facilitate women's development as producers also enhance their parenting role.
By providing better health, increasing women's educational opportunities,
providing access to technical training, assuring that women have access to
income, providing women with credit and land, and freeing women from the long
hours required for household maintenance, children's situation will improve.</ol><p>
<p>
	6. <b>The future.</b> There are some forces at play within the development
world that will have an effect on future programming for women and children. By
in large these forces will lead to a closer examination of women's and
children's needs and their intersect. The changing climate could allow women's
and children's intersecting needs to be brought together conceptually and
programmatically. Put those currently concerned with the issues will have to
provide support to the effort through continued research, through dissemination
of information and through networking and advocacy.<p>
<p>
	7. <b>Strategies.</b> There are a series of strategies that should be employed
to support policy makers and program implementers.<p>
<p>
<ol>		a. There needs to be a distinction made between how programs are
conceptualized and how they are implemented. While it is important at the
design level to consider how to meet the intersecting needs of women and
children, in terms of implementation, adding on may be preferable to trying to
satisfy both sets of needs from the outset. There is a greater likelihood of
success if a program begins with one component, with the early intention of
adding additional components.<p>
<p>
		b. Within some agencies policy is built upon (or evolves from) successful
field projects. Thus it can be argued that the lessons learned from successful
programs need to be crystallized and disseminated. In addition, innovative
field projects need to be developed and implemented to provide further examples
of the ways in which the intersecting needs of women and children can be met
successfully within a range of development efforts.<p>
<p>
		c. It is important to present program planners and implementers with
practical information on how to implement complimentary and supportive program
components; some are willing but have no understanding of what is needed or how
to accomplish the task.<p>
<p>
		d. In both conceptualization and implementation, it is important to be
sensitive to current frames of reference. In working with policy makers it is
important to frame the issue in a Hay that helps them respond to the pressures
they are under within their organization. Likewise, in working with a
community, programs for women and/or children must be begun within the
framework of culturally sanctioned activities.</ol><p>
<p>
<center>*  *  *  *  *</center><p>
<p>
	Within the paper there is a more complete discussion of what has been learned
to date from project reviews, journals, and interviews with individuals
representing a variety of perspectives, There is a brief description of how
programs for both women and children have evolved over the past fifteen to
twenty years. In addition, there are a range of program examples which have
been cited to illustrate the different ways in which women's and children's
programming has emerged, with some hypotheses about the resulting trade-offs
and/or benefits. In the final section there is a description of current
emphases and themes in the development world that may lend support to or put
constraints on a new conceptualization of the intersecting needs issue. In
addition, a number of suggestions are made regarding strategies which could be
undertaken to help shape policy and programming.<p>
<p>
<b><center>I. INTRODUCTION</center></b><p>
<p>
<b>A. The Problem.</b><p>
<p>
	Mothers and children, children and mothers; their lives are inextricably
intertwined. The experiences of one closely affect the other. Yet the programs
and policies affecting women and young children have usually focused on one
group or the other--seldom on both--despite what would appear to be overlapping
needs, and sometimes, important trade-offs between the two.<p>
<p>
	The potentially conflicting effects of programs focused on the survival and
healthy development of children, or the social and economic well-being of
women, are seldom recognized or admitted by planners and policy makers. The
general lack of awareness is reinforced by organizational and intellectual
compartmentalization which creates barriers to understanding a problem which,
in people's day-to-day lives, cuts across bureaucratic and academic lines. The
ability to conceptually merge the intersecting needs of women and children
could lead to programming that would forestall trade-offs and waste and result
in more effective action for women and children.<p>
<p>
	One step in developing a new conceptualization of programs for women and
children is to look at current programs far both groups and to examine the ways
in which the potentially competing needs have or have not been addressed in
these efforts. Another step is to assess the level of awareness of policy
makers within major donor agencies and to make some educated guesses about the
ways in which current initiatives will play into the issue--either by
maintaining a conceptual and programmatic split between efforts for women and
children, or by providing a new conceptualization of needs and how they can be
met for both groups.<p>
<p>
	Within this paper an attempt will be made to look at the ways in which women
in development programs have evolved and what that has meant in terms of
meeting children's needs, and how early childhood care and education systems
have developed and what that has meant for women. Examples will be provided to
illustrate the evolutionary process and the current state of the art in
programming for both women and children. There will also be a review of current
thinking within major donor agencies which will affect future programming for
women and children. The paper concludes with some suggestions as to appropriate
actions that might be taken to clarify issues and develop policy in support of
programs which promote women's <b>and</b> children's development.<p>
<p>
<b>8. The Methodology</b><p>
<p>
	To gather information on historical trends, current programming efforts and
policy developments three sources of information were used; 1.  journals
related to young children and women in development efforts; 2. project reports
describing program components, and, where they existed, project evaluations;
and 3. interviews with program people within donor agencies, private
foundations, and non-governmental organizations (NGOs) funded by those 
agencies.<p>
<p>
	Of the three procedures, the interviews were the most productive. Journals
provided very little useful information, By and large, those journals which
focus on women's issues refer to child care only as a support to women's
development; there is no questioning of the child's needs or the
possible effect of such care on the child. On the other hand, journals which
focus on child development, if they make mention of the mother, describe her in
her role as main support for the child; her productive role is not described.<p>
<p>
	 Project documents provided limited information. In reviewing <b>general
development projects</b>--those designed to benefit all those in a given
community-- it was seldom possible to assess how the project affected women,
and almost never was mention made of how if affected children. The problem of
looking for the impact of a program on women in general development programs
has been identified by people doing reviews of a range of efforts (Dixon, 1980;
Helzner, 1984). One of the primary reasons it is hard to identify the effects
of these projects on women and children is that they have not been the focus of
the intervention. If no provision has been made for meeting the needs of women
and children as a project is conceptualized, then the impact of the project on
their lives is likely to go unexamined. As noted by Dixon, "If girls and women
are not specifically identified in project papers as intended beneficiaries,
they are likely to remain invisible in planning and evaluation documents"
(1980, p. 48).<p>
<p>
	Thus, one is forced to look almost exclusively at those projects designed
specifically for women or children, and within these to ask the question of how
the program affected the other group. Once again, however, the issue of
original program focus prevents an intersecting needs analysis of project
effects. In <b>women in development</b> projects child care may be mentioned
as a component of the program that evolved as a project got underway. In a
summary of the Women in Development Office's analysis of USAID projects and how
they did or did not involve women, it was noted, "...several projects have
included facilities for child care which enable women to participate in skills
training or employment and income generating activities." (Horizons, 1985, p.
17). Thus, while project documents let the reader know that child care was
developed in connection with women's projects, there is no information on the
child care system and whether or not it met the needs of either the women or
the children. In order to have any understanding of how the project might
affect women and children it was essential to talk with
someone who actually knew the program.<p>
<p>
	A similar issue occurred in reviewing early childhood care and education
programs (efforts to support the development of young children from birth until
the age at which they enter primary school). Where women were mentioned it was
in terms of (1) how they provided support to the program--through volunteering
in the classroom, preparing meals, making toys for the classroom;
or (2) how there were components in the program designed to educate the mother
in terms of health and nutrition practices--presumably supporting her nurturing
role. Once again, when those who knew the program through first hand experience
could be interviewed a much better understanding of the dynamics of the
situation was provided.<p>
	Thus, overall, interviews proved to be the most beneficial activity--in terms
of learning what has happened in practice during the past ten years; in terms
of assessing current understanding of the issues relating to women's and
children's intersecting needs; and in terms of looking to the future in terms
of both policy and practice and what that will mean for women and
children.<p>
<p>
<b><center>II. PUTTING THE ISSUE IN CONTEXT: A BRIEF HISTORY</center></b><p>
<p>
<b>A. Women in Development: Changing perspectives and Conceptualizations</b><p>
<p>
	It was not until the mid to late 60's that the development world began to look
at women's role in development. At that point in time attention was focused on
designing and implementing projects that could support women's increased
involvement in the development process.<p>
<p>
	As women began to enter the formal wage economy there was an awareness by some
that women's traditional responsibilities would remain intact while women took
on new roles. There was a recognition of the fact that women needed support for
their current child care and household responsibilities in order to fully
participate in development efforts. One area where support was provided was
child care. There was the development of legislation to support the creation of
systems of child care in an attempt to respond to women's needs. What that
would mean for women and children was unclear.<p>
<p>
	Early in the 1970's, a number of people began looking at what it meant for
women to be involved in development projects. The reports were disappointing.
The literature contains many examples of development projects that were
actually having a negative effect on women. As summarized in Tinker &amp;
Bramsen (1976), development planning erred:<p>
<p>
<ol>(a) By omission--that is by failing to notice and utilize the traditional
productive roles which women are playing;<br>
(b) By reinforcement of values already in existence in the society which
restrict women's activities to household, child-bearing, and child-rearing
tasks; and<br>
(c) By addition--that is, by superimposing Western values of what is
appropriate work for women in modern society on developing societies. (p. 5)</ol>
	By and large, the early development programs for women fell within a "welfare"
orientation. As defined by Buvinic (1985),<p>
<p>
<ul>Purely welfare projects are those designed to deliver information, education,
sometimes free handouts (money, food, technology) to poor women in their roles
as homemakers reproducers, and child rearers. Examples are projects in maternal
and child health, hygiene, nutrition, home economics, and home-based
appropriate technologies. (p. 5)</ul><p>
<p>
	Clearly, for women to benefit from development projects, there needed to be a
new way of conceptualizing women's role. In 1975, with the beginning of the
United Nations Decade for Women, there began to be a shift in the way in which
women in development was conceptualized. Ideologically and politically it was
important to get the development world to separate women out--from men, and
from their reproductive role--and focus on women as women.<p>
<p>
	There was a shift in the way women's work was described. There was a new
emphasis on productivity rather than welfare. Women were described in terms of
their <b>productive</b> roles to shift people from seeing women only in their
<b>reproductive</b> role. In addition, it was argued that women should be a
part of the development planning process, not merely "targets of intervention".
Women began to be described and conceptualized as <b>agents</b> of change, not
passive recipients of development programs.<p>
<p>
	As a result of the activities stimulated at the beginning of the decade, many
governments realised they needed to acknowledge and expand the role of women in
national development. Toward this end, programs were developed which focussed
specifically on meeting the needs of women. Women in Development offices were
created within major donor agencies and separate funding was provided for
women's programs. Many things were accomplished during the decade. In the
UNICEF report from Nepal for 1985, there is a statement that summarizes much of
what was accomplished.<p>
<p>
<ul>One of the greatest achievements of...many of the women's projects undertaken
worldwide during the decade of women has been the shift in focus from welfare
to development. The extension of women's areas of concern from an almost
exclusive concentration on the social service sectors...to encompass also the
critical areas of economic development, agriculture, and rural development, and
access to training and investment resources is of key importance... The role
women have played as recipients of services is slowly changing to the role of
equal contributor in the overall process of development. (UNICEF, Nepal Annual
Report, 1985, p. 28)</ol>
	While there has been increased participation of women in the economy of Third
World cultures over the past ten years, to a large extent, this is the result
of the rising poverty of women and families rather than the increased rights of
women. Women's economic survival and the hope of economic progress for women
will depend on their access to formal education, modern labor, and financial
and technological markets. A major challenge to the success of future women in
development efforts lies in reducing the double day still faced by most women,
in improving their health, and in moderating the competing demands on their
time--demands that increase with poverty because women are required to work in
the marketplace to sustain or contribute to the
family budget. To meet that challenge, improvements are required in household
technologies and in child care arrangements.<p>
<p>
<b>8. Children and Development: Early Childhood Care and Education
Programs</b><p>
<p>
	During the last twenty years the situation of the young child in many
developing countries has become an increasing concern due to the rapid rise in
population growth rates. In some countries as much as 30-40% of the population
is under the age of 4. These children are being raised in situations where
health care, sanitation, and nutrition are marginal in spite of massive efforts
by government and citizens to improve conditions. Funds for additional services
are scarce at best. At the same time, there is a realization of the importance
of children's early years in setting the stage for their future growth and
development, and a recognition of the need to consider the country's future
development by investing resources in programs for young children.<p>
<p>
	In an attempt to deal with these facts, a variety of intervention programs
have been designed to specifically target the needs of young children--from
infancy through the pre-school years. There are programs which focus on health
and nutrition issues during the early months and years. There are other early
intervention programs which focus on development issues by providing activities
that will help foster the child's psycho-social and cognitive development. Some
of these programs have shown moderate success rates; most have been
disappointing.<p>
<p>
	Over time, among those whose primary focus has been on the development of
programs for young children, there has been an increasing awareness of the fact
that children cannot be "treated" in isolation. In order for programs for young
children to be effective, the family--in particular the mother--must be seen as
a part of the child's life. In essence, programs designed to
affect children's nutrition and/or survival are dependent on the adults in the
child's life for their success. The younger the child, the truer the
statement.<p>
<p>
<b>C. Women and Children and Development</b><p>
<p>
	Both women's and children's needs tend to be Pet when economic and social
conditions are favorable. In "ideal" conditions, a program directed to
satisfying women's needs meets to some extent the needs of children, and vice
versa. Potential conflicts are easily mediated by the presence of adequate
support systems or by exercising available options. However, when conditions
are harsh, there are competing demands to be met with limited resources;
choices have to be made. This presents a dilemma to policy makers and program
developers. They must assess the trade-offs of investment in one arena rather
than another. A range of women's and children's programs will be described in
the next section to illustrate some of the potential trade-offs which have
resulted from a variety of well-intentioned programs designed to meet the needs
of poor women or children.<p>
<p>
<p>
<b><center>III. WOMEN AND CHILDREN IN DEVELOPMENT: PROGRAM EXAMPLES</center></b><p>
<p>
<p>
	A range of women in development and early childhood care and education
programs have been reviewed in an attempt to assess the effect of a program for
one group on. the other group, in all the programs included there is a clear
connection between women's and children's needs. Within some of the programs
described it has been possible to successfully meet the intersecting
needs of the two groups; there are other programs where components have
developed components with no real understanding for what they might mean for
women and/or children. Program examples have been grouped into five categories
that represent different ways of including women and children in development
programming. To facilitate differentiation of the types of programmes each
category has a pictoral representation. Categorizations are based on different
combinations of the following symbols, each of which represents one or more
aspects of women or children's development that has historically served as a
program focus.<p>
<p>
<img src=balls1.gif alt="Figure 1">
<p>
<b>A. Single-focus Programs</b><p>
<p>
	Within this category are those programs that have sought to have a significant
effect on <b>either</b> women <b>or</b> children by developing a program that essentially
provides survival or development opportunities for one group without regard for
the other group.<p>
<p>
<img src=balls2.gif alt="Figure 1">
<p>
	<b>1.</b> The <b>child health and nutrition</b> efforts can beet be exemplified by
some of the early nutritional rehabilitation programs designed to decrease
infant mortality during the first year of life. A classic example of an effort
where the child was treated in isolation was developed in Chile in the early
70's. A rehabilitation program was developed for malnourished infants.
Children's
nutritional, health and stimulation needs were provided for within nutrition
centers. Once the child gained age-appropriate weight and recovered some of
his/her developmental delays, the child was returned to the family. Within few
months, however, many of the children re-appeared at the nutrition centers,
once again malnourished. What happened was that children were returned to the
environment within which they originally became malnourished. During the time
that the children were being rehabilitated, nothing was happening to change
their home environment. Thus the conditions which produced the malnutrition
continued to exist. Returning to that environment,
the children once again became malnourished. As a result of these experiences,
those implementing the program realized the importance of looking at the family
system and including the mother in the program (Evans, 1977).<p>
<p>
<b>	2. Child development</b> programs for children are found world-wide. They
most commonly take the fore of a pre-school program designed to provide the
child (ages 3-5 or 6) with a range of experiences that better prepare the child
for the primary school experience.<p>
<p>
	Within Southeast Asia there are a number of examples of national efforts which
have been developed to provide a pre-school experience for the urban poor and
rural child. In Thailand, for example, the Ministry of Education provides
grants to target communities to develop pre-primary programs. Grants go to
areas identified as "the rural impoverished, the urban deprived, the
remote and the barren, and the community with 50% of the children speaking
other than Thai." (Piya-Ajariya, 1983, p.47).<p>
<p>
	Korea represents another example where a pre-school program, offered in a
primary school, has been developed specifically to meet the needs of the urban
and rural poor. To help develop the pre-primary program, the Korean Institute
for Research in Behavioral Sciences (KIRBS), has been provided support by
UNICEF to create a curriculum for the rural and urban poor and to implement it
in areas of most need. A mid-term evaluation of the project indicated that the
program was successful in reaching poor children. One of the issues raised by
the evaluation was the fact that parent involvement was to be an important part
of the project, but when the evaluation occurred there was little evidence of a
parent education or parent involvement program. (Crellin, et.al., 1984, p. 29)
Most likely this is because the program was developed without consideration for
parental needs.<p>
<p>
	<b>3.</b> In terms of<b> programs that focus on women only</b>, there are a number of
examples of income-generating, agricultural, and home management projects that
are designed to provide women with more income and/or decrease the demands on
women's time. While it can be anticipated that the projects may, in fact,
address the needs of children, there is no discussion of this in project
documents.<p>
<p>
	A primary example of this is found within a recent series of case studies on
<b>Women's Roles and Gender Differences in Development</b>, supported by the
Population Council. While the authors were able to identify ways in which women
had been affected in a range of development projects, no attempt was made to
look at the ways in which the projects might have an impact on the
lives of young children.<p>
<p>
	Besides the fact that children were not defined as project beneficiaries at
the beginning, and thus their lives were not looked at over time, there appears
to be another issue operating here. In several of the interviews it was made
clear that one of the reasons that children and/or women
reproductive role are not discussed is that the authors of the documents are
aware of the attitudes of their readers. The reports are written for policy
makers, planners, current and potential funders who the writers feel do not as
yet take women seriously as producers. If mention is made of women's
reproductive role it is felt it would weaken the case for viewing women as
producers. However, those operating women and development programs, are aware
of the trade-offs for women and children that exist within the program on a
day-to-day basis. Some of them are concerned about the effect of these
trade-offs over time, but don't feel they have an arena within which to sake
their concerns known without raising major questions about women in development
programming.<p>
<p>
	By in large, what we have learned from single-focused programs is that they
seldom have hoped-for success rates. While many of these projects show
short-term gains, they seldom have outcomes that endure. This is frequently
because the programs do not acknowledge all the things that impinge on people's
lives. A broader perspective is needed. To some extent the programs in the next
category take this broader perspective. But as is evident from project
descriptions, they miss the mark in critical ways.<p>
<p>
<b>B. &#148;Support&#148; programs</b><p>
<p>
	Within this category are those efforts where programming has been created for
one group in support of the other groups' development. However, in taking this
approach, the needs of the first group may not be recognized and/or taken into
consideration.<p>
<p>
<img src=balls4.gif alt="Figure">
<p>
	1. In support of the child's survival and development,<p>
<p>
		a. <b>Women's involvement in child survival.</b> The current efforts to
support children's basic survival needs build on important technological
advances promising major reductions in infant and child mortality. However, the
successful delivery of the activities associated with child survival depend on
the availability, knowledge, skills and competencies of a significant care
giver in the child's life. (For example, among the BOGI strategies,
<b>G</b>rowth monitoring, <b>O</b>ral Rehydration Therapy and <b>I</b>mmunization can
be provided by care givers other than the mother. <b>B</b>reast-feeding, however,
requires the mother.) Focussing on the woman (mother) in these efforts comes
from a recognition of women's traditional role in the provision of health
care.<p>
<p>
<ul>The role of women in maintaining the health of the family, especially children,
is paramount. They administer the first line of treatment in the home and
usually decide the following steps that may need to be taken. They are largely
responsible for the feeding and nutrition of the family and most aspects of
child care, including mental as well as physical development. (WHO, 1984,
p.3)</ul><p>
<p>
	No one would argue with this statement. Women have been responsible for the
health and well-being of young children. A few questions do come to mind,
however. "Is it possible for the majority of women -- overworked, physically
weak and emotionally strained -- to acquire and apply these new techniques? How
do <b>women</b> benefit from the scientific advances for improved health and
nutrition of children?" (Mauras, 1985, p.2).<p>
<p>
	To answer these questions it is necessary to look at the reality of women's
lives in terms of their limited resources (time, money, education, and health),
economic needs and opportunities, work requirements, and household
responsibilities. Then it is possible to determine whether or not, and in what
ways, they can actually participate in the child survival activities and of
what benefit they are to women. Few of those agencies promoting child survival
have begun to address how the requirements for implementation of the strategies
affect women positively and/or negatively.<p>
<p>
		b. <b>Women's involvement in child development.</b> Not only are women
expected to be involved in child survival efforts, it is also assumed that they
can be involved in child development programs once survival has been assured.
Programs within this category are generally viewed as some type of "parent
education".<p>
<p>
			(1) One example of a program that clearly requires extensive maternal input
is <b>in-home parent training</b>, as exemplified by the Non-formal Home-based Initial
Education Project, implemented in Peru. The goal of which his "to assure that
parents have adequate childrearing and caretaking skills and to guide and help
them implement these skills in their daily routine." (Jesien, et.al., 1979,
p.7) Recognizing the demands on families living in poverty, the intent of the
program is not to create yet another demand on already scarce time and energy
resources, "but rather to enhance the quality of the interaction between child
and parent in the time that is available."
(Jesien, et. al., 1979, p.7).<p>
<p>
	In the program, non-professional community women are trained to provide weekly
home visits to the mother and child dyad. These home visitors
(<b>animadoras</b>) work with 10-12 families and, with the aid of a supervisor,
develop an individualized curriculum for the child (ages 3-5), based on his or
her developmental profile. The <b>animadora</b> uses the developmental profile
with the mother. From it she suggests specific activities the mother can do
with the child during the week to stimulate the child's development, The mother
is required to make note of the activities she does with the child and to
assist the <b>animadora</b> in charting the child's progress within the
profile.<p>
<p>
	A research design has been implemented as a part of the project so that
outcomes for children can be determined, What is not found in the evaluation is
any assessment of what the program has meant for the mothers involved. Has it
required additional time? If so, what has that meant for their other
activities? How has the project affected women's view of themselves--as mothers
and as women? Clearly if this type of program is to become a vehicle for
supporting children's overall development, there needs to be an understanding
of what the program weans for women and their role as agents of development.<p>
<p>
			(2) <b>Parent education can also be done in groups.</b> An example comes from
Indonesia where a parent education program, the <b>Bina Keuaraga and Balita</b>
(BKB) project, has been implemented in connection with the National Family
Nutrition Program. As the EKB project was developed a number of sectors were
involved--Women's Development, Education, Health, Socio-cultural Development,
and Welfare. The purpose of the project is to "enhance the knowledge, awareness
and skills of mothers of children under five and other members of the family so
as to enable them to provide [a] conducive educational environment to ensure
the comprehensive development of children under five." (Stein, 1985, p. 1).
Field workers--women from the community being served--are provided with
training in child development and adult education. They then provide workshops
for mothers at nutrition centers. In the workshops mothers receive child
development information, their role as primary educators of the child is
emphasized, and they are provided with easy activities that they can do with
their children at home. In addition, a toy library has been. established.
Mothers can take toys here with them and use them with their children. When
they return the toys the following week, they can take out something else.
(UNlCEF Board Report, 1985)<p>
<p>
	There is no evaluation of the program in terms of how it affects women. It is
unclear what type of women participate in the program--whether the hours of the
meetings have been established to meet their needs, whether or not women are
actually able to carry out the activities with their children, and if so, with
what level of success. These are just some of the questions that need to be
asked.<p>
<p>
			(3) Another type of <b>group focused parent education</b> program comes from
Chile. Known as the <b>Padres y Hijos</b> program, it focuses on working with
groups of parents, representing the poorest of the poor, to better the quality
of family and community life. The program uses parents' interest in supporting
the child's development as a way of getting parents involved in larger
community development efforts. It consists of weekly meetings where a series of
child care "theses" are introduced. The leader presents pictures that depict
daily events that offer opportunities for stimulating the child's learning. The
leader guides the discussion, focusing on what the picture shows, what the
child is doing developmentally, and what the parent can do to support the
child's learning in that situation. Parents up with activities and games they
can use with the child (ages 9-6). Toys are also available. Parents can take
them home for the week, or use them as models and make their own.<p>
<p>
	The program was begun in 1979 by the <b>Centro de Investigaciones y Desarrollo
de la Educacion</b> (CIDE), a private research and development center in Chile.
Those operating the program feel it is a cost-effective way of working with
parents to educate them about child growth and development. The group meetings
also serve as a catalyst for the development of other community-based
activities that ultimately improve the standard of living within the community
(Mauras, et. al., 1979, p.18). Current documentation provides no indication of
how the overall program affects the lives of women or children.<p>
<p>
	2. The equivalent program for women in this category, while not quite
analogous, is<b> nationally mandated/sponsored day care</b>. In this instance
the ultimate goal is women's participation in the formal wage economy. Programs
for children are developed to support women's productive role, not necessarily
to promote the child's development. It is assumed that children's needs will be
adequately met in the child care situation. Put, in reality the child care
program may or may not take into account children's needs.<p>
<p>
	Not only may this strategy have a detrimental effect on children, but it may
not support women's development either. Many national governments, in
recognition of the day care needs of working women, have passed legislation
requiring businesses employing more than a given number of women to provide
daycare for the children of their employees. One result of this legislation has
been for companies to limit the number of women they are willing to hire. Thus,
an initiative designed to support women's entrance into the labour market may
have the unintended consequence of restricting women's opportunities.<p>
<p>
	Another approach is for the government itself to support the costs of daycare.
An example comes from Iraq. There have been two major thrusts to the
development of child care in Iraq. Since the mid 1970s there has been a
government policy to increase women's participation in development. To support
women taking on new roles, day care programs were developed. More recently,
since the war with Iran, there has been a need for more women to enter formal
employment because men are involved in military activities. This gave added
impetus to the development of day care.<p>
<p>
	There are two major governmental organizations responsible for the development
of child care within Iraq: the Ministry of Labor and Social Affairs and the
<b>General Federation of Iraqi Women</b> (GWIF)--each operating about half of
the 162 currently registered child care centers. The current systems of
provision are modeled after center-based programs as found in Eastern Europe
and Western countries. They are not being used to capacity and are costly to
operate. They are generally available to middle-income professional women.
Those women most in need of day care for their children cannot afford the
current systems of provision, nor are their hours of operation conducive to the
needs of many women. At this point in time the Ministry and the GFIW are
seeking ways to integrate their systems of child care and to develop lower cost
alternatives that will make child care available to a larger percentage of the
eligible children and provide the necessary support poor women need to enter
the wage economy.<p>
<p>
	In sum, the efforts for women and children included in this category exemplify
an awareness that programming for one group will have an effect on the other.
However, these programs are built on some untested assumptions about the needs
of and appropriate services for both groups.<p>
<p>
<b>C. Programs with Components for both Women and Children</b><p>
<p>
	Within this category are programs within which there is, to some extent, a
recognition of the intersecting needs of women and young children, where an
attempt has been made to address at least some of those needs within a single
delivery system. But, for the most part, these programs represent a "lost
opportunity" in the sense that they are not doing the most they could to meet
the multiple and intersecting needs of both groups. This imbalance is found
primarily among early childhood care and education programs where there is
integrated programming for the child while the programming for women focusses
only on strengthening their reproductive role.<p>
<p>
<img src=balls5.gif alt="Figure"><p>
	An example of a program within this category is the <b>Integrated Child
Development Services</b> (ICDS) program in India. The need for massive programs
which address the needs of young children is most evident in a country like
India where there are more than 109 million children under the age of
6--constituting 16% of the population. In 1974 India adopted a National Policy
for Children. The policy statement is an expression of India's commitment to
insure the delivery of comprehensive child development services to all
children. One of the first targets for the effort is the "poorest of the poor
found in urban slums and urban areas", particularly children in "scheduled
castes and tribes." (Sadka, 1984, p.3).<p>
<p>
	To develop a comprehensive service for these children, a program was created
to meet the following goals which, incidentally, illustrate the imbalance in
terms of addressing women's and children's needs.<p>
<p>
<ul><li>  to reduce the incidence of low birth weight and severe malnutrition among
children;<br>
 <li>to bring down the mortality and morbidity rates among children 0-6 years
old;<br>
<li> to reduce school dropout rates through early stimulation programs for children
3-6 years old;<br>
 <li>to provide the environmental conditions necessary for mental, physical and
social development of children;<br>
 <li>to enhance the ability of mothers to provide proper care for their children;
and<br>
<li> to achieve effective co-ordination at the policy and implementation levels
among government departments to promote child development. (Sadka, 1984,
p.12)</ul>
	In order to meet these goals it was determined that the program needed to
provide: non-formal pre-school education; immunizations, regular, periodic
health check-ups, supplementary nutrition; appropriate medical referral
services; and nutrition and health education for women.<p>
<p>
	An <b>Anganwadi</b>--a children's house--serves as the base of operations
within the community. The program operates through a three tiered staffing
system. At the community level is the <b>Anganwadi worker</b> (AWW). This
person plays the key role in the community; she is the primary link between
community members and the government. She is responsible for the day-to-day
operation of the program. Above the AWW is a Supervisor who provides AWWs with
on-going
training and support. Above her is the <b>Child Development Project Officer</b>
(CDPO), who provides the linkage between the ICDS program and government
administration.<p>
<p>
	All families in the area to be served are surveyed to identify the poorest.
Those families with children under 6 and/or where the woman is pregnant or
lactating, are served in the <b>Anganwadis</b>. Regular examinations are
provided by Lady Health Visitors and Auxiliary Nurse Midwives. Children and
pregnant women are immunized on a scheduled basis. Three hundred days a year
food is distributed. Families are encouraged to bring the children to the
centers for regular feeding. But the fixed hours do not always respond to the
work needs of women. Children's weight and height is monitored. Those with
severe malnutrition are given additional food supplements, and acute cases are
referred to medical services.<p>
<p>
	A pre-school program has been developed for 3-5 year olds who attend the
center three hours a day. While there is no formally structured curriculum, the
local staff are encouraged to develop activities that stimulate the child.
Frequently there is parental pressure to teach the alphabet and beginning
numeracy. An additional educational service is non-formal training in nutrition
and health organized for mothers and pregnant women. These sessions are open to
all women, aged 15-45, with priority given to pregnant and nursing women and
women whose children suffer from repeated malnutrition.<p>
<p>
	Funding for the program has come from both governmental and non-governmental
sources. The initial costs of establishing a program are provided by the
Ministry of Social Welfare. The costs of the supplementary feeding program are
borne by the state governments; and the on-going
operational costs are the responsibility of the Central government.
International donor agencies have also been involved in funding aspects of the
program: UNICEF assisted in planning and implementation beginning in 1975.
Since 1982 other international agencies--WFP, CAFE, NORAD, USAID--have been
contributing in a variety of ways.<p>
<p>
	Two major evaluations of the program have been conducted. One occurred in 1978
and the second was in 1982. The evaluations focus on health indicators for both
women and children. However, there is no further discussion of how the program
affects either women or children.<p>
<p>
<b>D. Programs Meeting the Intersecting Weeds of Women and Children</b><p>
<p>
	Within this category are the programs that appear to be meeting the multiple
and intersecting needs of women and children. Included are 1. examples of
programs that have evolved overtime to meet both needs, and 2. programs that
were begun with a clear conceptualization of the potentially competing needs
and trade-offs where specific program components were created
to assure that both sets of needs were met.<p>
<p>
<img src=balls5.gif alt="Figure"><p>
	1. Evolutionary programs.<p>
<p>
		a. <b>Child care programs created to support women's employment that then
evolve to support women's broader development and/or provide income for other
women.</b><p>
<p>
			(1) The <b>Mobile Creche</b> program in India is interesting in that it
began as an integrated program of child care to support women employed in
industry. Once the child care system was established, additional program
components were developed to support women in other ways.<p>
<p>
	India is a country that has had legislation in support of employer sponsored
child care since 1964. For many years it was not enforced. However, over the
years there was pressure to comply. Within the construction industry there was
particular concern. Many women are employed within the industry, and with the
frequent moves required as buildings are completed and new ones begun, women
and children are forced to relocate. Women are not able to rely on extended
family members to care for their children. Thus a program of early childhood
care and education Has begun for these workers and their families. A variety of
private voluntary organizations, working with the construction industry,
created the "mobile creche" system, which began in 1969. The early childhood
care and education program is established where the women are working, and
moves with them from site to site. Mobile Creches have also been established to
serve the children of street cleaners, rag pickers, and other families
representing the lowest social status groups in
India.<p>
<p>
	There are three levels to the program. The first is a creche for infants and
young children (from 3-4 weeks to age 3). The second is called a nursery
program and is for 3-6 year olds. The third is an elementary program for
children from 6-12 years of age. Within the creche program
the primary focus is on child health and nutrition. The majority of the
children are malnourished when they enter the program. Thus, there is an
emphasis on providing them with proper foods and educating the parents about
nutrition. Within the nursery program the health and nutritional status of the
child remain an important part of the program. The children are monitored
weekly by a physician, and growth charts are kept on the children. In addition,
however, there is an emphasis on cognitive and psyche-social development. One
of the goals is to help prepare the children for the formal school system.<p>
<p>
	The third level, the elementary program, was developed for children who
traditionally would have been taking care of their younger siblings. Because
these children are now in an ECCE program, the older children should be going
to school. The elementary program was developed to prepare these children to
enter school and be placed within an age equivalent grade.<p>
<p>
	Staff within the mobile creche system are from the lower middle class.
Originally the staff received their training within the traditional teacher
training institutes. However, it was discovered that this training was not
appropriate. For example, they discovered that staff needed literacy training
and training in basic health care. Thus, over time, the Mobile Creche program
developed their own training for staff. Those with the aptitude are given
additional training in nutrition, community work and medical social work. Thus,
the Mobile Creche program meets the needs of low-income women, providing some
with child care and job opportunities and training for women who are not likely
to have qualified for training within the formal educational system.<p>
<p>
	As the program has evolved, classes in adult education have been added. There
are literacy programs, nutrition classes, and political discussion groups. Thus
the program can be envisioned as a spiral--it evolved in response to women's
needs and then cycled back to meeting a wide range of women's needs at a higher
level while appropriately meeting the needs of young children.<p>
<p>
			(2) Another example comes from Tarqui, a small community on the outskirts of
Quito, Ecuador. Within this community a <b>family day care</b> program designed to
meet child care needs of women working outside the home also meets the
employment needs of community women.<p>
<p>
	Within the community of Tarqui a child care center had been established for
3-5 year old children. It was meeting the needs of many families in the
community. Yet there were still children being left at home alone while their
mothers went to work. A survey was done in the community to identify families
with children in need of care. Community leaders who had participated in the
survey came together to determine how to meet the needs of these families. In
the meetings that followed a family day care system of provision was presented
as an alternative to the creation of another center. The idea took hold.<p>
<p>
	Based on their interest, their location in the community, the adequacy of
their homes, and their personal characteristics, six community women were
chosen to become day care providers. These six mothers received some initial
training in child development, health, and nutrition; regular in-service
training is also provided. They are supplied with a small table and chairs.
They are also given appropriate toys. They are provided with food supplements
for the children, and regular medical check-ups are provided through the Tarqui
Cooperative, which serves as the base for the program.<p>
<p>
	An extensive evaluation has been conducted since the project began. There have
been some clear project impacts in terms of women's development. The mothers
who have been trained as day care providers have, in essence, established small
businesses, In the process of the project these women have learned bookkeeping
and record-keeping skills. They also have a new image of
themselves as wage-earners. While they began by seeing their work as an
extension of their care giving role within their own family, they soon began to
see their work with the young children as a legitimate job. They began to see
their worth and to recognize the skills and knowledge that they have and are
acquiring as a result of being involved in the project.<p>
<p>
	One example of the way in which this new image has manifested itself is the
women's demand to be recognized as employees of the Cooperative. At the
beginning of the project it was decided that parents would pay fees to the day
care mothers. It soon became evident that parents could not pay the full fee.
Thus a sliding-scale fee schedule Has established. The monies received from
parents were then supplemented by the Cooperative. As the project progressed,
the day care mothers realized that although they were getting money from the
Cooperative, they were not receiving the benefits that other Cooperative staff
were receiving (health care, insurance, and job security). The women began
arguing that they should be paid a regular salary. Many cooperative members
made the case that the women should not be paid salaries because their work is
a "contribution" to the community. The day care mothers were not willing to buy
this argument. When the providers actually resigned they gained public support
for their position. Clearly the women are finding their "voice" within the
community and coming to value their work in economic terms, and so are other
members of the community.<p>
<p>
			(3) Another example comes from Brazil. In 1979 the <b>Centro de Estudos
Supletivos de Narandiba</b> (CESUN) was established to provide nonformal
education and vocational training to low-income peoples. One of the group's
activities has been the development of women's programs. As CESUN began to plan
programs, a problem arose. While "the women expressed interest in the training,
they asked what they would do with their children while they attended
sessions." (Rocha et al., 1983, p.10).<p>
<p>
	Following a series of discussions it was determined that CESUN should not only
establish a child care center, but it should also develop a care givers
training course to provide staff for the center and to provide trained staff to
other child care centers that were being developed in the community. Thus, one
of the vocational training courses offered through CESUN is Caretaking.
Within the 160 hour training course women are taught child development,
nutrition, health and first aid, and techniques for helping children learn.
They also discuss the economic and social context of women's work, legislation
relating to labor and women's rights, the relationship of women's economic
activity for family planning, and community relations. (Rocha, et.al., 1983, p.
7-8). Thus, in addition to meeting the immediate needs of women who wanted to
participate in training, a course was developed that provided women with
marketable skills and knowledge. Not incidentally, what they learned in the
course also helped them in their own parenting role.<p>
<p>
			(4) Another example copes from Mauritius where the <b>Family Planning
Association</b> (FPA) of Mauritius recognized that many women needed child
care. The existing programs were too expensive for women with low incomes. So,
the FPA created a day care center next door to their own facilities. The center
provides care for 40 children from 3-5 years of age. When mothers bring their
children to the center they are encouraged to participate in meetings held at
the family planning clinic. There are weekly lectures on child health and
family planning. In addition, home visits can be arranged to accommodate the
schedule of working mothers. Thus, in response to
the needs of women in the community, services were created by the Family
Planning Association. As women brought their children to the center and
received training, they began to take part in other FPA activities. In this way
the goals of the FPA are being realised.<p>
<p>
	To some extent the center has also begun to address the need for women to
engage in income generating activities. The center provides on-the-job training
for young women interested in working in early childhood programs. After the
young women have participated in the training program for two years they can
establish their own child care center. The City Council of Port-Louis is
interested in the ECCE model as developed by the Family Planning Association
and has expressed an interest in establishing similar programs in other parts
of the city. The Mauritius Women's Self-Help Association has plans to set up
similar centers in other towns.<p>
<p>
			b. <b>Programs developed in response to community defined needs.</b><p>
<p>
	A good example comes from Malaysia, where an innovative program, the <b>Sang
Kancil</b> project, has been developed within the squatter settlements of Kuala
Lumpur.<b>[*]</b> The project was begun by health sector personnel interested in
establishing primary health care centers within<b> kampungs</b>, or districts,
in the settlements, Meetings were held with community members to determine
their needs and priorities. They were Rest interested in having a child care
system for young children, and in creating income generating activities for
women. Health care was not seen as a priority. Those involved in developing the
project listened to the community. Rather than building a health center, they
established a pre-school and an income generating project. When these were well
established, then it was possible to introduce primary health care, which is
non widely accepted. One person involved in the project summarizes the
experience as follows:<p>
<p>
<ul>Listening to the community is an important step...it has the advantage of
providing information quickly on areas of concern...it also has the role of
validating information received from more formal sources...The development of
<b>Sang Kancil</b> has illustrated clearly (that) the initial thrust of the
programme to introduce MCH had to be changed...Entry was channeled through the
pre-school system and income generating activities. (Yusof, 1984, p.26)</ul>
	The <b>Sang Kancil</b> model now consists of three components--maternal and
child health clinics, a pre-school program, and income generating activities
which have become self-supporting, The project began as an action research
effort at 3 sites. It is now a national program model and is being implemented
in 13 settlements,<p>
<p>
	The Malaysian example illustrates the way in which a part of the national
health sector has been able to meet their own goals by establishing programs
for women and children which fall outside the health sector.<p>
<p>
	<b>[*]</b>	It is widely recognized that the environment within squatter settlements is
threatening to people's health--physically, mentally and in terms of
psycho-social development. Squatter settlements are a growing phenomenon in the
developing world. "The current estimate of the population in slums, squatters
and shanty towns in developing countries is 50% of the total urban population."
(Yusof, 1984, p.7) At the policy level there is difficulty in providing
services for squatters. Urban squatters occupy the land illegally. Therefore
they are not entitled to city services--water, sewage, medical care, education,
etc. On the other hand, many squatter settlements are stable communities,
including people from a variety of income levels. Even those who have the
finances to leave the area often stay. There are a variety of reasons for this:
affordable housing may not be available outside the settlements; families may
have a well developed support system within the settlement that would be lost
to them if they moved elsewhere, and/or individuals may have acquired a
leadership position within the settlements that they could not obtain in other
parts of the city. Thus, strategies are being sought to meet the needs of
squatter populations--strategies which recognize, value, and build upon the
complex social systems which exist in the settlements. Developers of the
<u>Sang Kancil</u> project were able to do this.<p>
<p>
	2. Programs where the initial conceptualization included awareness of and
plans to meet the intersecting needs of women and children.<p>
<p>
		a. The <b>Melka Oba Cooperative</b> in Ethiopia is a good example of how the
income-generating needs of women were meshed with infants' and young children's
needs for quality care. Within Melka Oba a cooperative was started; both men
and women are members of the cooperative. The work of the cooperative centers
around a fruit orchard. As work schedules were being developed it became clear
that provision had to be made for the children. Women did not want to leave
them at home alone, nor did they want to take them to the orchard with them.
The members of the cooperative requested that the government provide a day care
for children from 45 days through 6 years old. Various government agencies got
involved and funds were provided by UNICEF for the development of a creche and
pre-school program for 104 children.<p>
<p>
	To this point, the description of the <b>Melka Oba Cooperative</b> program sounds
like the way in which other child care programs have been developed. But this
program has a new twist. Women are given time off from their work to
breast-feed their youngest children and to take their children to and from
school. However, this does not mean that they lose wages because they are
providing care for the children. The system is set up so that women can earn
work points by providing this care. Thus women do not have to give up income to
provide care for their children; in fact nurturing activities can provide them
with income. The program is being replicated in Yetnora, and other districts
are interested in implementing similar programs.<p>
<p>
		b. A second example comes from <b>Nepal</b>, which has been the site of a
number of successful women in development program efforts. The <b>Production
Credit for Rural Women</b> project has been successful in providing women with
the economic support they need to develop income-generating activities. In
addition, quality care programs have been created for young children as a
result of the work of Save the Children. A new project that is still on the
drawing board is known as GATE (<b>Girls Access to Education</b>). The GATE
project revolves around women's centers in rural villages. The design of the
project includes explicit attention to child care through the centers, (1) as a
way of freeing girls (older siblings) to continue in school; (2) as an impetus
to getting women to organize; and (3) as a means of improving the survival and
healthy development of young children--particularly girls for whom it is hoped
that preparation for school will reduce the chance of their dropping out.<p>
<p>
	As the project has been designed, a number of national and international
organizations have been involved in supporting the different components. The
project has recently received approval from the Nepali government and,
apparently, is to be implemented through a women's association, rather than the
Ministry of Education. The project has been slow getting started. One reason
for this may be the multi-sectoral involvement. Many "agendas" have to be
fulfilled and there may be difficulty in determining who should take the lead.
The hope is that even though the women's association will manage the project,
the other sectors will continue their involvement and maintain
their commitment to the overall effort.<p>
<p>
<b>E. Women Initiated Programs</b><p>
<p>
	This category stands apart from the others in the sense that it includes
programs which have been developed by the community itself. The program that
has evolved Has begun because the group or community members felt a need for a
program. Over time outside assistance may or may not have been provided to
support the initiative. Many of the programs in this category have the
potential to meet the intersecting needs of women and children, but there are
come real trade-offs for both groups as a result of the ways in which the
programs are evolving.<p>
<p>
<img src=balls7.gif alt="Figure">
<p>
	1. <b>In Ghana, the Accra Market Women's Association</b> was interested in
starting a child care program for their children while they were involved in
buying and selling. They approached the Accra City Council, which agreed to
fund the program. A committee was formed, consisting of members from the
Women's Association, the City Council, the Department of Social Welfare (which
is mandated to oversee ECCE programmes), the Ministry of Health, and the
Ministry of Water and Sewage. A building near the market was refurbished. It
now serves 200 children, from infancy through 5 1/2 years of age. It operates
under the Administration of the Regional Medical Officer of Health. Thus it has
a strong health and nutrition focus. Mothers of infants are encouraged to come
to the center to breast-feed then. This is relatively easy since the women work
only a few steps from the child care facility and have some flexibility in
terms of being able to take the time necessary to come to the center.<p>
<p>
	Children are provided with a morning snack and a full lunch. To enter the
program children must have a physical examination and appropriate
immunizations. Once a month a public health nurse inspects the facilities,
provides immunizations as needed, and completes children's medical charts. In a
report on the project, the following conclusion was drawn:<p>
<p>
<ul>The Malata Market Day Care Centre experience has been a successful one largely
because of the support the centre has received from the very initial stages,
from appropriate agencies together with the keen interest of  the mothers, who
work in close proximity to the centre. (WHO/UNICEF, 1982, p.23)</ul>

	2. Another <b>initiative undertaken in relation to women's work place was
begun in Senegal</b> in 1962. Women who were part of an Animation feminine
center, proposed to those operating the centers (animatrices) that a day care
center be started where children could be cared for while women worked in the
fields. The day care was proposed by the women,<p>
<p>
<ul>to resolve the problem of caring for their young children while they and their
older daughters under-took the arduous task of planting out the rice.
Entrusting the children to older sisters who were still too small to work in
the fields was a solution that did not provide sufficient guarantees of safety:
and leaving them on the edge of the rice fields meant they would be exposed to
all the vagaries of the climate--humidity, ran, direct sun, etc--as well as to
the attacks of wild animals, especially poisonous snakes. (Bashizi, 1979, p.
166-167)</ul>
 	The <b>animatrices</b> agreed to establish the day care program as long as the
women's center did not have to pay for the program. (An interesting position
for a women's center to take!) So, mothers shared responsibility for the
program. Some planted a community garden from which the children could he fed
while they Here in the center. Other women rotated responsibility for
taking care of the children and tending the garden. The first ECCE center began
in July, 1962, and operated for 2 1/2 months during the nest difficult part of
the agricultural reason--when the rice crop is transplanted. During the first
year 110 children between one and five years of age were provided for in the
center. Since that tire day care centers have spread throughout Casamance (one
of eight administrative districts in Senegal).<p>
<p>
	The centers operate under the Department of <b>Animation rurale, Promotion
humaine</b>. Community developers within the Department quickly saw the
potential of these centers; they could be used as a base from which a variety
of social services could be offered. They began to offer training to community
volunteers who worked in the centers. They also began to offer adult
education courses in nutrition, health, hygiene, disease prevention, water
purification, etc. Through the centers they also offer treatment for such
diseases as malaria and conjunctivitis.<p>
<p>
	The key to this effort from the beginning has been that the program is
"essentially and fundamentally a people's initiative". (Bashizi, 1979, p.171).
The goal is to keep it under the control of the community and to continue to
use the program to support community development efforts while it provides a
much needed service to women and children.<p>
<p>
	3. A third example, which represents the <b>initiative of women in rural
communities</b>, comes from Zimbabwe. For many years a small percentage of
Zimbabwe's children aged 0-6 years, mainly in urban areas, were able, through
private means, to attend pre-schools, play centres, and creches. In the more
rural areas, pre-schools did not exist. In 1980, the government of Zimbabwe,
through the Ministry of Education and Culture, took the initiative to plan a
national early childhood care and education program. The Ministry established a
commission of inquiry which undertook an extensive nationwide investigation of
current ECCE activities and produced a report in 1981.<p>
<p>	According to the report, hundreds of women in the rural areas, with no support
from the government, have started some form of early childhood care and
education activity for their young children. The push from rural areas for ECCE
programs has come about as a result of:<p>
<p>
<ul>1) the burgeoning population growth which stands nationally at more than four
percent; and according to 1982 Census projections, more than 23% of the total
population is under 6 years of age; 2) the need felt by parents to overcome the
legacies of the colonial past by giving children a &#147;head start&#148; in
the schooling and socialization process; and 3) the pressure of mothers to free
themselves for short periods from child care in order to participate in wage
earning or enterprise to supplement family income. Whatever the reasons,
proliferation of self-help community-supported pre-schools is occurring in
areas where health care, sanitation and nutrition are marginal. (Perry, 1983,
p. 1)</ul>
	The conditions under which the more than 4,400 village ECCE programs operate
vary considerably. They range from programs operated under trees, to programs
in small buildings with mud-daubed nails and thatched roofs, to programs that
take place in the church sanctuary, to elaborate facilities constructed and
maintained by municipal support.<p>
<p>
A typical ECCE program consists of upwards to 85 children, with only one or two
mothers (generally untrained), caring for the children. Parents have little or
no resources to pay for the program; many use the bartering system to support
their child's participation. What this means is that nest teachers (all of whom
are women) receive little or no pay for their work.<p>
<p>
	Some of these programs receive direct or indirect training and support from
non-governmental agencies, such as VOICE (<b>Voluntary Organizations in
Community Enterprise</b>), OXFAM/US/UK, church groups (Methodist, Catholic,
Seventh Day Adventist, Lutheran) and other special interest groups. At the
present time the Ministry of Community Development and Women's Affairs has been
given the mandate to coordinate ECCE programming throughout the country.<p>
<p>
<ul>The Ministry is well aware of the energy generated by the self-help initiative
in the communities and the potential of this large pool of untrained workers
and volunteers to provide paraprofessional support to teaching, management,
building, health services, food and nutrition. But, preservice and continuing
inservice training will be required for development of responsible and creative
leadership. (Perry, 1983, p.6)</ul>
The governmental and non-governmental agencies and organizations involved in
ECCE activities recognize some of the issues involved in providing the
necessary support to the vast range of ECCE efforts which exist in Zimbabwe.
They are seeking the most effective way to support the community initiative,
while at the same time assuring that quality services are provided. (Evans,
1983, p.3).<p>
<p>
	While community based programs have many positive characteristics, there are
some dangers in assuming that this approach Hill adequately meet the
intersecting needs of women and children. One plus is that they are frequently
developed in communities which are not reached by current services. A second
plus is the fact that these programs are developed in response to community
felt needs--a program has not been imposed on the community from outside. The
fact that the programs rely heavily on community support if they are going to
survive can be seen as positive and negative. It is positive in the sense that
the community has to take ownership for the program. It can be seen as negative
if people--primarily women--volunteer their labor and thus have decreased
opportunities to engage in income-generating activities. As noted by
Mbikusita-Lewanika,<p>
<p>
<ul>Most of these centres are provided by the communities on self-help bases. The
communities are eager for their children to benefit from any kind of early
childhood care and education, and cannot wait for the governments to provide
these facilities...Since they are provided by the communities, they are the
cheapest of all children's centres. On the other hand, these centres have the
poorest facilities,...overcrowding of children, lack of equipment and
materials, under staffed and untrained personnel. (1982, p.23)</ul>
	She then proceeds to make an argument for why these programs should, in fact,
receive the <b>most</b> governmental attention. Included in her list of reasons
is the fact that those starting the programs have the fewest economic
resources; early childhood care and education centers in these
communities have the potential to serve as a base for community development;
these communities receive the least in terms of all social services; children
from these communities are most in need of what a quality pre-school can
provide; and last, but not least, people in these communities have demonstrated
their commitment to their children and their ability to create a program
through self-help initiatives; their efforts should be recognized and supported
by the government (Mbikusita-Lewanika, 1982, p.23-24).<p>
<p>
	What she has failed to note, but which is consistently true, is that these
programs are staffed by women who "volunteer" their services. This clearly has
implications for their own development. The <b>first</b> has to do with the
potentially lost opportunity cost since they are not able to be involved in
other activities. The <b>second</b> has to do with assumptions about the skills
and knowledge that women have that would make them appropriate providers of
care in an ECCE program. In reference to assumptions about women's roles in a
variety of development efforts, Buvinic (1984) provides the following
analysis:<p>
<p>
<ul>A common belief in development circles related to the use of women volunteers
is that cultural proscriptions dictate that work with low-income women should
be done <b>by</b> women. This belief has been put into practice throughout the
Third World, but its validity has gone largely untested, while it is clear that
the lack of technical expertise of volunteer women staff is a major hindrance
to the success of projects directed to increase women's productivity and
income. (1984, p.21)</ul>
	The same analysis applies to women working in child care centers. In terms of
ECCE programmes, it is commonly assumed that community women can and should
volunteer--or receive a very small stipend--to provide the care for the
children. This assumption takes into consideration neither the needs of women
nor the children. Community-based programs are an important part of the
development process. But without looking at the quality of care for children,
and the costs and benefits of the programs for women these programs can be far
more negative than positive for both groups.<p>
<p>
	In sum, there are a range of program efforts which have been designed to
promote women's and children's development. Historically these programs have
been developed in isolation; at best, complimentary programs have evolved.
Within the past decade, policy makers, planners, and implementers have learned
what is needed to create effective programs for each group independent of one
another. What is much less clear is what it means to create development
programs from which both groups benefit. Within a few of the current efforts,
innovative approaches are being tried which ate built on an emerging awareness
of how to address the multiple and intersecting needs of women and children.
But, there is much to be learned and applied. In the final section of this
paper some of the forces in the development world that would support, or
constrain, a new conceptualization of programs for women and children will be
described, and some action strategies suggested.<p>
<p>
<center><b>IV. MOVING FORWARD: SOME REALITIES AND STRATEGIES</b></center><p>
<p>
	In this section of the paper an attempt will be made to: A. look at the forces
that are at play currently that will constrain or provide support to
conceptualization of the issues and programming to meet the intersecting needs
of women and children; B. look at the ease with which current programming for
women and children can be extended appropriately to meet the needs of the other
group; and C. look at what needs to be done in the near future to move us ahead
in our understanding of the issues and in promotion of policy in support of
women's and children's development.<p>
<p>
<b>A. The Forces at Play</b><p>
<p>
	There are a number of forces operating within the development world at the
present time that could be used to support a new conceptualization of the
intersecting needs of women and children. These include an awareness of
people's day-to-day lives and what that means for their involvement in new
programming; an understanding of the limits of many of the development
approaches to date; research and evaluation data which provide a greater
understanding of some of the variables involved and how they interact; and a
recognition of the costs of development programs, resulting in the creation of
programs that build upon current delivery systems. These forces do not operate
in isolation of one another; they are intertwined. The discussion that follows
highlights current issues and awareness that, while evident in the most recent
literature, emerged primarily through the interviews.<p>
<p>
	1. <b>There is an increasing awareness of the intersecting needs of women and
children in relation to child survival.</b> For example, of the variables that
are important to child survival, clearly half of them are related to factors
associated with the mother's pregnancy; the other half require the mother's
attention once the child is born. Yet current programming focuses only on the
child once the child is born, and relies on the mother to deliver the service.
Child Survival monies have not been invested in supporting the mother during
her pregnancy, nor has adequate attention been given to the potential costs,
and benefits, to the mother of her involvement in implementing the
strategies.<p>
<p>
	In terms of looking at women's own development, her involvement in the child
survival effort may have a cost. For example, one of the "costs" to a woman may
be the cost in terra of her own health and nutritional status. There are a
range of other costs. Those currently responsible far developing and delivering
Child Survival programmes are aware of sore of the potential costs for women.<p>
<p>
<ul>[Cost] can be defined, for example, as either a monetary value, an opportunity
cost, a status loss, or a consumer's time. Because a rural woman pays no money
for a vaccination does not mean that it "costs" her nothing. Indeed, the day of
travel or the abandonment of the family, and the arguments with her husband can
be high prices to pay for a product which is frequently perceived to have such
a low consequence. (Academy for Educational Development, 1985, p. IV-37)</ul>
	Recognizing the potential costs, proponents of the current Child Survival
strategies have attempted to identify potential benefits to women of their
involvement in the program. A number of benefits have been hypothesized. They
include some of the following, paraphrased in a variety of ways:<p>
<p>
<ul><li>		  <b>knowledge.</b> Women gain knowledge that previously was guarded by the
medical profession; information and the process of problem solving are
democratised; women gain new health delivery skills. (Mauras, 1985)<p>
<p>
<li>		  <b>responsibility/control.</b> Women are called upon to take on increasing
responsibility; Child Survival programmes enhance the capabilities of women to
act; they become decision-makers. "Women become active agents in program
delivery." (UNICEF, 1985, p.9)<p>
<p>
<li>		  <b>status.</b> Participation in such programs can advance women's sphere of
influence. (WHO, 1984)1 by participating in these programs women gain an
enhanced sense of self and control over their environment. Women have organized
and developed a "voice" within the community. (Mauras, 1985, p.6)<p>
<p>
<li>		  <b>savings.</b> Successful implementation of the strategies saves valuable
time, energy and money (Mauras, 1985, p.5); women save money by not needing to
buy expensive formula (0'Gara); there are potential benefits to women of less
child sickness, improved child health and a lower incidence of infant and child
mortality. (UNICEF, 19854 p.23-24)<p>
<p>
<li>		  <b>income.</b> Child Survival projects which have lead to the production of
weaning foods have provided income generating activities for women. Examples
include projects in Thailand, Sri Lanka, the Dominican Republic, Botswana, and
Paraguay (UNICEF, 19854, p.13)</ul>
	However, before jumping on the bandwagon of the benefits side of women's
involvement in Child Survival and Development Revolution (CSDR) strategies, it
should be noted that at the present time these are, by and large, hypothesized
benefits. As one UNICEF staff person noted, currently "there is more
justification than analysis" in the definition of benefits. Another UNICEF
person expanded on this same observation by stating that the CSDR approach does
not begin with an analysis of women's needs, then ask how the CSDR program
responds to them. Rather, it begins with the position that CSDR is good because
it saves the lives of children, <b>then</b> asks what benefits it may have for
mothers, more by way of justifying decisions taken than by way of seeking
adjustments that could improve the mutual benefit. Clearly core research is
needed to understand the real trade-offs for women as a result of their
involvement in CSDR activities.<p>
<p>
	2. <b>Within some of the donor agencies there is a love away from focusing on
individuals to either looking at the mother-child dyad or to seeing the
household as the focus of program efforts.</b> The major impact of this
movement has been to decrease the amount of funding directed to "women only"
programs. One USAID official saw this as a positive move since women's programs
were funded at a relatively low level; few women in development efforts could
be funded. She felt that women could benefit more by the current funding
pattern because they would have access to a much wider range of development
funds. Others, however, felt there was great danger in the household focus.
Historically, programs designed to promote development within a community have
had a neutral, and in some instances negative, effect an women's development.
Unless there is some system of accountability within this new framework--in
terms of addressing and meeting both women's and children's needs--the
household focus could be a real step backwards for women's and children's
development.<p>
<p>
	3. <b>Research on the relationship between women's and children's development,
for the most part, provides a strong basis for the argument that a program
designed to promote women's development will have a positive outcome for
children.</b> (Unfortunately there is no corollary of this for children.)<p>
<p>
	The literature contains numerous examples of the positive relationship between
maternal <b>health</b> and children's well-being, particularly during the pre- and
peri-natal stages.<p>
<p>
<ul>Women's own nutritional and health status affects the health of their infants
and risks of morbidity and infant mortality, as well as increasing their own
risks of maternal mortality. (Kobes &amp;  Scott, 1982, p.2)</ul>
In addition, there is a positive relationship between maternal education and
child outcomes. The following come from a report by the Office of Women in
Development (USAID):<p>
<p>
<ul><li>  the better educated the mother, the less likely the child is to die in
infancy. The children of educated mothers are better nourished and healthier.<p>
 <li> the children of educated mothers are more likely to succeed in school, core
so than if only the father is educated.<p>
<p>
 <li> educated women are more receptive to family planning and tend to have later
marriages and fewer children.<p>
<p>
 <li>primary education opens the way to further education or vocational training in
agriculture, health services, etc., and thereby increases the opportunities to
find remunerated employment. (1985, p. 6)</ul>
But to create a program that focuses only on promoting women's health or
education ir order to promote her and the child's development, is not
sufficient. It does not address any of the variables that lead to poor health
and lack of education--primarily poverty. Program experience gives support to
the research findings.<p>
<p>
<ul>Many of the earliest attempts to reach poor women in India were through health
programs. While some of these initiatives have achieved outstanding success,
many others, because of their narrow health focus, have proved to be difficult
to sustain organizationally and financially. The realization that for families
in poverty the overriding concern is economic survival has stimulated program
efforts to enhance women's ability to earn income. However, a focus on economic
activities need not be at the expense of a concern for health. In fact, income
generation programs can create both the demand and the delivery mechanism for
genuine community-based health care. (Ford Foundation, 1985, p.4)</ul>
	The experience of Ford Foundation is in accord with the experience of many
funding organizations. There is a beginning recognition of the
inter-relationship between health, education, income-generating activities and
the demands made on women living in poverty. In terms of health and education
there appears to be a clear relationship between these variables in women's
lives and what that means for children. In teres of women's involvement in
income generation activities and the effect on children, the evidence is being
gathered. Then, there is another set of questions being asked about the
distribution of income once it enters the household and what that means for
women and children.<p>
<p>
	Research concerns and program initiatives are not unrelated activities. It is
not incidental that much of the research is currently focused on intra-familial
or household dynamics and that the household is now the focus of development
activities for one of the major donor agencies.<p>
<p>
	The Ford Foundation experience also touches upon one of the other forces
currently operating that would support future programming to meet the
intersecting needs of women and children--an interest in developing
multi-sectoral programming.<p>
<p>
	4. <b>There is a move toward multi-sectoral programming.</b> One of the
outcomes of development projects over the past twenty years is a realization
that single-focus programs--either in terms of those to be included, or the
content of the programs--are likely to have short-term benefits, at best. At
worst, they are likely to have negative effects on the groups of people not
included in the effort. Evidence to this effect was described earlier in
discussions of the effect of early development programs on women. Thus, in
current efforts there is an attempt to conceptualize a program effort in terms
of its multi-sectoral dimensions, and to implement programs that take
into account the totality of a person's life.<p>
<p>
	But conceptualization and programming don't always go hand-in-hand. Sometimes
conceptually a program can take into consideration multiple needs, but when it
comes to programming, a single focus is pursued. One cause of the discordance
between conceptualization and programming may be differences in thinking at
various levels in an organization, as is described by Bennett in summarizing
many of the experiences encountered in women's programs.<p>
<p>
<ul>There is a deep and legitimate uncertainly about the relationship between
women's mothering role and their role as economic providers. This uncertainly
has lead to what can almost be described as schizophrenic programming on the
part of development agencies... While at the policy level copious recognition
is given to the importance of both roles, at the operational level,
implementation activities carried out by specialized agencies or divisions tend
to ignore one aspect or the other. (1983, p. 1)</ul>
	On the other hand there are good program examples of efforts which began as
single-sector projects that, in implementation, became multi-sectoral. A good
example is the <b>Sang Kancil</b> project in Malaysia that was described earlier. The
project was begun by the health sector to improve maternal and child health. As
it evolved, it addressed children's issues, women's need for
income, and finally introduced primary health care to the community at large.<p>
<p>
	It was suggested in one review that women would be very open to multi-sectoral
programming because, "Women's multiple roles and responsibilities in the family
and in the community put them in a position where they are deeply involved in
almost every area of development." (WHO, 1989, p.5). However, the stronger
argument for multi-sectoral programming is that people do not live in isolation
of one another, and each activity in their life affects and is affected by a
range of variables. The question is, what is the most effective way of
providing multi-sectoral programming? In leaking at successful program efforts,
it would appear that it is more effective to begin small (i.e. by addressing a
specific problem first) and then adding to that effort to meet a wider range of
needs. This would suggest that in terms of meeting the intersecting needs of
women and children, it is important to begin with a conceptualization that
addresses both sets of needs, but in terms of implementation, it ray be
necessary to begin with a program for one group with the intent of adding on
other components. The danger in this is that the additions way never be
made--because of the need to strengthen existing components, or because of the
lack of expertise about how to implement the addition, or because of increased
project costs which leave little or no resources available when it is time to
add the other components.<p>
<p>
	5. <b>One of the forces that operates throughout programming for women and
children is costs.</b> Social service and development programs are expensive.
While recognizing this, large donor agencies have established goals for
themselves in terms of reaching the poorest of the poor. Current resources are
not sufficient to meet those goals--particularly if the organization has to
create new delivery systems to meet its goals. Thus, there is an interest in
working with existing delivery systems to enhance their capability to deliver a
wider range of services. A good example of this is found within the <b>World
Health Organization</b> (WHO).<p>
<p>
	The World Health Organization (WHO) has made a commitment to bring health to
all by the year 2000, in terms of both survival and <b>primary health care</b>
(PHC). The costs of developing primary health care centers accessible to all
people would be prohibitive. Thus, the WHO has taken another approach. They are
looking at two different delivery systems that can be found throughout the
world, sometimes in the remotest areas: early childhood care and education
programs, and women's groups or organizations. In both instances, current
activities have been reviewed with an eye toward how they right be utilized for
the delivery of the maternal and child health components of primary health care
services. (See Evans, 1985, for a review of ECCE activities, and WHO, 1984, for
an assessment of the ways in which women's organization might be utilized.)<p>
<p>
	The rationale for using women's groups for the delivery of primary health care
(WHO, 1984), includes some of the following:<p>
<p>
<ul><li> women have a natural and traditional role in health care<p>
 <li>women's organizations are a natural entry point for PHC<p>
 <li>involving women's organizations in PHC activities will raise the status of
women and make them more effective leaders in the community<p>
 <li>women can reach other women and break down barriers<p>
 <li>women have stronger roots in their community<p>
<li> women's organizations are already oriented towards the intersectoral
approach<p>
 <li>women can mobilize community resources (p.2)</ul>
There are also some constraints to women's organizations playing this role.
Some of those noted include:<p>
<p>
 <ul><li>the low status of women<p>
 <li>women in developing countries are usually in poor health and overburdened with
work<p>
 <li>socio-cultural traditions can hinder women's involvement in PHC<p>
 <li>activities in PHC are not perceived as giving rise to immediate economic
benefits<p>
 <li>women's efforts are not integrated with national development programmes, (WHO,
1984, p.5-8)</ul>
	There are pros and cons to the utilization of existing systems. Clearly it
means reduced costs because new systems are not being created. One of the
potential dangers, however, is that the current focus and activities of the
systems could be lost as the result of the infusion of resources that would
take the program in a new direction.<p>
<p>
	6. <b>Appropriate policy is Emerging.</b> At the policy level there is
beginning awareness of the intersecting needs of women and children as
evidenced in <b>UNICEF's Response to Women's Concerns</b> (1985a). The document was
written in support of UNICEF's (a <b>child</b> focussed donor agency) programming for
women, and argues the case that programs which enhance women's development will
have a positive effect on children's development. In fact, the argument is made
that if you are really going to sake a significant change in children's lives,
it is essential to support women's development.<p>
	Within the UNICEF document a series of activities are recommended, which, if
implemented, would "reflect UNICEF's integrated approach to problems
confronting low-income women and children". Those which are most directly
related to the intersecting needs of women and children include:<p>
<p>
<ul><li> strengthening linkages between children's welfare and women's status<p>
 <li>promoting an integrated approach to nutrition<p>
 <li>revising support to income-generating programmes<p>
 <li>expanding women's education<p>
 <li>providing technical. resources to increase household food production<p>
 <li>supporting new directions in training programmes and skills<p>
 <li>community-centered approaches to family planning (UNICEF, 1985a, p.29-33)</ul>

	In sum, there are a number of forces within the development world at large
which would allow for conceptualization and programming which would focus on
meeting intersecting needs. In the majority of instances it would not take the
development of totally new strategies, Rather it would take building on what
exists, for both women and children, asking, what would it take to
expand/enlarge/redefine this effort to better meet a range of needs? In the
next section, there is a brief discussion of the ease with which
conceptualization and programming could be expanded for both groups in order to
meet the needs of the other group.<p>
<p>
<b>B. The Ease of Extending the Focus from one Group to Another--at the Policy,
Research and Implementation Levels</b><p>
<p>
	1. <b>Expanding the focus from child only, to child and woman.</b> There seem to be
some real possibilities for expanding early childhood care and education
programs to include women in development issues. Supports for this line of
activity include the fact that:<p>
<p>
		a. <b>Young children are dependent on their mothers</b>, at least during the first
months of their lives. There are a number of assumptions that underlie thinking
at this point. These assumptions color how program developers think about
creating and implementing activities which focus
primarily on supporting young children's development. The basic assumptions are
well summarized by Nieves (1982, p.8):<p>
<p>
<ol>1. Child rearing and child care are invariant and exclusive responsibilities of
the biological mother; that is, biological mothers are the universal and
primary caretakers...<p>
<p>
2. ...therefore, mothering and bonding or "nurturing" beyond the biological
acts of giving birth, nursing and bonding during the first days of the infant's
life, are not substitutable activities...The biological imperative continues to
rule women's behavior...</ol>
Mothers are a necessary part of the child's life. While others could do the
caretaking, by and large, the responsibility will, for the foreseeable future,
remain primarily with the biological mother. Thus, it is easy to make an
argument that programs for children should be expanded to include the mother.
The DANGER, however, is well illustrated in the examples described earlier.
Programming for women tends to focus only on their reproductive role; little or
no consideration is given to their productive role.<p>
<p>
		b. <b>Funding and support for ECCE programs is increasing.</b> While this is
primarily true in terms of child survival, in some Third World countries there
is also recognition of the importance of young children's development. Thus,
building on what is known about the relationship between women&#146;s
development as women and how it relates to children's development, monies may
be available to support women's development out of these funds.<p>
<p>
		c. At the practical level <b>there are staff within child focused agencies
(i.e. UNICEF) that are concerned with women's issues.</b> They can work from
within their agencies to push for integrated planning around intersecting
needs. They have an understanding of what women need to develop their
productive role and what this will mean for children now and in the future.<p>
<p>
	2.<b> From women focused programs to the inclusion of child issues.</b> Within
this category there are both constraints and supports.<p>
<p>
		a. A constraint is the <b>political reality</b> of needing to ideologically
separate women's productive role from her reproductive one. In order to
increase women's visibility in the development world it has been necessary to
present them as <b>producers</b> and to consistently illustrate the ways in
which they are agents of change. By introducing children, it reinforces the
<b>reproductive</b> role. In the latter role nomen are taken less seriously.<p>
<p>
<ul>There has...been a marked tendency to explain women's subordinate status and
dependence on men in modernizing societies in terms of their reproductive
roles, and in terms of the fact that the place of work (or the place of
production) and the place of reproduction become separated in the course of
modernization and capitalist development. Women must remain in the place of
reproduction and, as a consequence, their role in production decreases and
their independence on those who are engaged in production increases. Once a
woman is no longer directly engaged in production, her social status decreases
accordingly. (Nieves, 1982, p. 2)</ul>

		b. A related constraint is the <b>costs associated with adding a child care
component</b> to a women's program. Those seeking funds for women's programs
are being asked to justify the costs and benefits of their program within the
economic framework used to judge the effect of development programs on men.
While the issue of costs and benefits is a complex one, suffice it to say that
in today's economic reality, women's programs are more costly; women need basic
education, leadership and management skills, and increased self-confidence
before they can take advantage of technical training programs. Comparatively
speaking, men bring many of these skills to the program. One of the contractors
interviewed then went on to say, "If on top of this we have to add the costs of
child care, the costs would be prohibitive, and we'd never get a project
funded."<p>
<p>
		c. In support of the integration of children's needs into women's program is
that fact that <b>if child care is not available within the program, women create
it for themselves</b>, Sometimes this is with the support of the funding agency
(i.e. funds are shifted to cover the cost) and sometimes it is done in spite of
the funding source (as was the case in Senegal). In other words, women
participating in development programs know they need care for their children.
In fact, they want quality care. They want to know that their children are
safe, that they are getting good foods, and that they are "learning"
something.<p>
<p>
		d. In support of the development of <b>child care is that it can become the
focus of income-generating activities</b>. In a number of cases cited above, the
child care center became an income generating activity. Women receive training
in the operation of a child care program. The center say also serve as a base
for training other community women to operate their own child care
centers.<p>
<p>
		e. Another support comes free the fact that <b>those involved in development
planning have an increased awareness of women's reality</b>. There is a
recognition of the fact that to address women's needs as women, consideration
must be given to women's nurturing role.<p>
<p>
<ul>Poor women in developing countries have no choice but to be increasingly more
productive in the cash economy and at the sane time to fulfill their domestic
responsibilities, including hose production for family or household consumption
and childcare. (Nieves, 1982, p. 1)</ul>
		f. A constraint is the fact that <b>there is no demand for the inclusion of
children's issues in women's programming outside of the need to support women's
development</b>. In expanding children's programs to focus on women, it can be
argued that what is good for women Hill be good for children. The
corollary--that what is good for children is good for women--while intuitively
appealing, is not backed up with research evidence.<p>
<p>
		g. A constraint related to (f) is that<b> in agencies and offices that focus
on women in development programs there are no staff who are advocates for young
children</b>. There is no one free within the organization that is working to
build a case for consideration of the intersecting needs; in fact, there is
little organizational knowledge about what children need beyond basic
survival.<p>
<p>
	3. <b>A new dimension.</b> Within recent years there has been increased focus
on the needs of girls in Third World countries. (An example is the GATE project
being developed in Nepal.) While the following quote represents UNICEF's
perspective, an interest in supporting the development of girls comes from
other donor agencies and foundations as well (the Carnegie Corporation
and WHO, for example).<p>
<p>
<ul>From the UNICEF perspective, programme action for girls and adolescents is
important for three basic reasons: (a) to rectify the disadvantages girls face
relative to boys in education, nutrition, health and survival; (b) as means to
ensure proper infant/child care and nutrition, given that young girls often
care for younger children; and (c) because of the benefits that improvements in
the health and nutritional status of today's girls and adolescents will have on
the next generation... The foundation of a healthy mother is laid early; ages
10-15 are crucial. Health problems leading to foetal or child death, maternal
depletion and low birth weight babies often begin before and during
adolescence. (UNICEF, 1985a, p.25, 30)</ul>
	In some ways "girls" represent an intersect of women's and children's needs,
and they are certainly important to future development. Programming for
adolescents may be an entry point for addressing many of the identified
concerns.<p>
<p>
<b>C. Proposed Action</b><p>
<p>
	Obviously in order to move forward our understanding of and programming for
women and children there will need to be concerted effort on several fronts--in
terms of research, in terms of policy development, and in terms of programming.
The question is how to do this? The following are some possible action areas
that would help to advance the field.<p>
<p>
	1. <b>There is a need to increase our knowledge base in order to create a new
conceptual framework about the relationship between women's and children's
development.</b> To do this we must continue research on the relationships
between the types of work that women engage in and what that means for
children; research on the kinds of support systems that women have developed on
their own and what they mean for both women's and children's development; and
research on what young children need and how that can be provided by a range of
caretakers.<p>
<p>
	In addition, there is a need to <b>evaluate</b> what has already happened. While one
USAID official stated that we have all the data we need, we simply need to look
at it in a new way, recent experiences in reviewing projects for their effect
on women and children would suggest that we don't have all the data we need.
Data are collected in response to questions asked as a project begins. If there
were no questions asked about the costs and benefits of a program to women and
children, then the data necessary to assess that relationship will not be
available. What needs to happen now is to work with current and new contractors
to ask the right questions as the projects get underway, using a variety of
techniques to look at potentially significant variables. A range of disciplines
have been involved in the development of formative and summative evaluation
strategies that would be appropriate to use in such an effort (see Booth &amp;
O'Gara, 1989; Lassen, 1984; and Buzzard, 1984).<p>
<p>
	2. <b>There is a need to continue to identify exemplary programs, and to do
in-depth case studies of innovative efforts so that issues and answers can be
explored.</b> One way to pursue this would be to hold a series of regional
meetings where those nest closely involved in program implementation provide
information on exemplary programs in the region. From these meetings issues in
conceptualization and programming would be clarified. In addition, information
on the most comprehensive programs, and/or those within which the most lessons
were learned, should be written up and disseminated to policy makers, planners
and practitioners. (Perhaps the <b>SEEDS</b> format would be appropriate.) This is a
particularly important step since the interviews revealed that, to some extent,
policy is derived from successful projects.<p>
<p>
	3. <b>Networking</b> needs to occur among those currently interested in
exploring the issues. What we found in the interviews is that many people are
sensitive to the issues as they were discussed. However, by in large, these
individuals did not have anyone within their immediate work environment with
whom they could discuss the issues. Clearly a greater constituency could be
created if there was a mechanism for getting people together with common
interests and concerns, among whom there is a wealth of knowledge, expertise
and experience.<p>
<p>
	4. <b>The strategies that have been developed need to be disseminated.</b>
This is different from the case studies where in-depth information on a
specific project is provided. What is being referred to here is a &#147;how
to&#148; booklet. One frequent response during the interviews was, "I'm sure
people would begin a child care program/income-generating activities if they
knew how." There was a sense that program people right well be aware of the
need, but that they did not have the expertise to go about establishing a
needed program component. This is certainly understandable; those that have
been involved in child care programs have little or no awareness of the range
of variables that are important in promoting women's development, and vice
versa. Perhaps two booklets could be prepared--one for those working in women's
programs that provides a list of "things you eight think about" in terms of
meeting the needs of children, and a parallel set of guidelines could be
provided for those operating early childhood care and education programs. The
booklets could also include vignettes of successful programs and include a list
of resources that could be drawn upon to add an appropriate component to an
existing program.<p>
<p>
	For example, in the booklet for those creating child care centers, they could
be challenged to think about:<p>
<p>
<ul><li> the hours of operation of the day care and how that meets the needs of the
families they hope to serve.<p>
<li> ways to create income-generating activities for women in support of the
program (through making and selling toys, by providing training so that women
can operate a child care center or provide child care in their own home).<p>
<li> ways to promote the development of women's organizations--perhaps starting
with the child care facility, but then expanding the focus to meet a range of
needs.</ul>

	The booklet for those operating women in development programs could include:<p>
<p>
 <ul><li>ways to build in monetary rewards for supporting the child's development (i.e.
receiving work credits for breast-feeding)<p>
 <li>a series of questions to ask women about the current situation of care for the
child to determine what the needs of women and children are in a given
community.</ul>

	Obviously the questions and strategies in each booklet would not be
appropriate for every project and community. But enough examples could be
provided so that program planners and implementers could make decisions
appropriate to the intersecting needs of women and children in their setting.<p>
<p>
<center>* * * * *</center><p>
<p>
	In sum, in pursuing information on policy and programs which support women's
and children's multiple and intersecting needs, there was great frustration.
From written project descriptions and from the interviews, it was clear that
very little effort has gone into the framing of optimal programs for women and
children. However, those interviewed were very receptive to a discussion of the
issues. It was also clear that those closest to programs as they are being
implemented have the greatest awareness of trade-offs that are made each day.
Those at the policy level are being made aware of the issues as they learn
about field experiences, but frequently they are part of bureaucratic
structures that limit their ability to act in accordance with their knowledge
and understanding. What is also evident is that people at all levels need
support in creating policy and programs that will maximize benefits to women,
children, and the community.<p>
<p>
