<p>I</p>

<p><b>ANTECEDENTS</b></p>

<p>Over the past two years, the Latin American Council of Bishops (CELAM),
the United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF), and the Consultative Group
on Early Childhood Care and Development have collaborated in a project
whose overarching purpose is to improve programs of attention to young
children living in conditions that put them at risk of delayed or debilitated
physical, mental, social and/or emotional development. The specific approach
to improving programs taken in this project begins with the study of childrearing
practices and patterns affecting early childhood development, from conception
to about the time children are ready to enter primary school. As the title
of this report suggests, however, knowledge about childrearing is not sought
for knowledge sake but is, rather, to be translated into action. Accordingly,
the explicit purposes of the project were taken to be:</p>

<p>1. To gather, synthesize and draw implications from information about
childrearing practices and beliefs in such a way that the knowledge will
be useful to people charged with planning and implementing programs intended
to improve child care and to enhance early childhood development. </p>

<p>2. To describe methods that can be used by practitioners to gather information
locally and to incorporate it into their activities.</p>

<p>3. To develop materials that will help the Roman Catholic Church and
UNICEF incorporate childrearing information into their program activities.</p>

<p>4. To identify gaps in knowledge that should be filled.</p>

<p>The childrearing project was conceived in three phases. Phase I consisted
of a pilot review of the literature on childrearing practices and patterns
in one country (Mexico), and the development of a general framework for
collecting information. In addition, a workshop was held to discuss results
and to plan the next phase. Phase II, reported upon in this document, has
involved additional reviews of the literature and field work in nine Latin
American countries where case studies were carried out using a variety
of methodologies for collecting and analyzing information. A third phase
of the project will involve application of the results to adjusting planning
and programming procedures, creating materials, training, and applying
what has been learned in specific institutional and community settings.</p>

<p>The main purpose of this document is to bring together results from
the country reviews and case studies carried out during the first half
of 1992. The synthesis is based both on the presentation and discussion
of study results at a workshop in Bogot&aacute; in early September 1992
and on reading of the case studies from each country. A complete set of
references to the studies is included as Attachment 1.</p>

<p>Common elements and differences in practices, patterns and beliefs will
be identified and the methodologies used will be described, with an eye
to their broader relevance and application. To begin the process of translating
that knowledge into action, implications for practice will also be drawn.</p>

<p>In order to orient readers who have not participated in the project
and who did not attend the Bogot&aacute; meeting, the remainder of this
introductory section will be devoted to: 1) a brief statement about why
the study of child-rearing practices is important, 2) an explanation of
how practices, patterns and beliefs were defined in the project, and 3)
a very synthetic treatment of results from Phase I of the project, upon
which the second phase was constructed. The introduction will be followed
by a section describing the several forms in which the study was approached
in different countries, both in terms of the selection of the population
that was included and in terms of the methodology used. Section IV will
attempt to synthesize results about who cares for children, about childcare
practices and about why practices are as they are. Finally, a set of conclusions
will be drawn about: 1) methods that seem useful and/or promising to pursue
in working with communities to examine, to reflect on, and to reinforce
or change their childrearing practices, 2) actions that can be taken to
strengthen childcare and development in the region.</p>

<p><b>Why Is Knowledge of Childrearing Practices, Patterns and Beliefs
Important?</b></p>

<p>1. <b>To understand, support and improve the childrearing process.</b>
A child develops in interaction with the surrounding environment. An important
part of that environment consists of family members and of others who care
for a child. Caregivers not only initiate interaction and provide direct
responses to the needs of the child, they also help to arrange a child's
physical environment and to protect the child from aspects of the environment
when necessary.</p>

<p>In this process, a caregiver brings to the task: 1) a certain technology
(set of practices), 2) an idea about what should be done, that is, of accepted
practices (normative patterns), and 3) beliefs about why one or another
practice and pattern is better than another. These affect the style and
quality of care-giving. For instance, the practice of carrying a child
has a different effect on the development of that child than the practice
of placing the child in a cradle or playpen. A social and parental belief
that children are given by God and therefore should be treated in a particular
way has effects that are different from the belief that children are human
creations.</p>

<p>Unless the effects on development of different practices, patterns and
beliefs are detected and understood, in context, the sometimes salutary
but often discouraging and flawed process of early childhood development
cannot be under-stood, properly supported, or constructively imported upon.</p>

<p>2. <b>To respond to diversity.</b> Children grow up in such different
physical, social and cultural circumstances and are themselves so different
at birth that there can be no one &quot;right way&quot; to bring up children.
Still, many programs intended to help young children survive and grow and
develop are conceived as if all children and circumstances are the same
-- as if there is only one right way. Understanding practices and patterns
and incorporating that knowledge into programs is, then crucial if programs
of early childhood development are to serve the variety of children and
families and circumstances that any program is bound to encompass. </p>

<p>3. <b>To respect cultural values.</b> Practices, patterns and beliefs
define the manner in which children are socialized to particular cultural
values and ways. The rhetoric of most programs includes a plea to respect
cultural differences. Indeed, the Convention of the Rights of the Child
indicates that children have a right to their cultural identity. If this
is to occur, a much greater effort must be made to describe and understand
the reasons for cultural differences in the up-bringing of children. Unfortunately,
ideas about practices to be promoted in a program frequently come from
individuals who are not part of the culture or group that the program is
intended to serve.</p>

<p>4. <b>To overcome negative effects of change.</b> Knowledge of practices,
patterns and beliefs is also important because environments and practices
are changing, sometimes rapidly and sometimes with important effects on
development. In the process, some practices are being lost that continue
to have both cultural and scientific value. Other practices that appear
to be &quot;deviant&quot; practices, but which represent novel adaptations
to particular settings, may be followed for good reasons and with good
results; they should not be suppressed. Conversely, old practices are being
applied in new settings or new practices are being adopted that may not
be appropriate to the changing settings in which a child is growing up.
Unless these changes in circumstances and in forms of childrearing are
identified and understood, policy and programs may take a misguided view.</p>

<p><b>Where is this knowledge located and how can it be tapped?</b></p>

<p>There are at least two main sources of knowledge about childrearing
practices, patterns and beliefs -- in a scientific literature and in everyday
life, i.e., in experience and folkways.</p>

<p><b>Science.</b> The accumulated &quot;scientific&quot; literature includes
basic studies of child development which are often directed toward identifying
universal principles of development. However, that literature also includes
psychological, medical, anthropological, and sociological and other studies
of how people in particular cultural and geographic settings care for their
young children.</p>

<p>Unfortunately, this literature dealing with childrearing practices and
patterns, although in written form, is not easily captured and put to work.
First, it is very dispersed because child development cuts across many
disciplinary lines. Second, the form of presentation is often academic
and requires translation into a form that is useful to program and policy
people. Third, for the most part, the existing literature is derived from
a Western or Northern conceptual base that can distort some of the findings.
Fourth, some of the literature is outdated. Nevertheless, this literature,
placed in perspective, provides an important starting point. In the project,
a concerted attempt has been made to locate and synthesize results from
studies in various countries.</p>

<p><b>Experience.</b> Another source of knowledge about childrearing is
experience. This experience is of two types. One is based on immediate,
personal experience, reflecting the particular circumstances of particular
individuals in particular families and communities. A second type is accumulated
experience adding up to a &quot;traditional wisdom.&quot; Usually, experience
is not brought together in a systematic way or written up. A major challenge
of this project has been to capture current experience and to describe
&quot;traditional wisdom&quot; without making a prior judgement about its
value. </p>

<p><b>How are practices, patterns and beliefs defined?</b></p>

<p>The question of how to define practices, patterns and beliefs was the
subject of considerable debate as the project developed. Along the way,
a relative consensus developed which, put in the simplest terms, was as
follows:</p>

<p>o practices are what people actually do</p>

<p>o patterns are what people think they should do (roughly equal to norms)</p>

<p>o beliefs are accepted explanations, rooted in the religious or magical,
for why patterns and practices are as they are or as they should be.</p>

<p><b>Practices: What and How?</b> For children to survive, grow and develop,
they need to be nourished, to avoid disease and accidents, to be nurtured
and to learn the ways of the world that surrounds them in order to adapt
to, cope with and transform that world. Practices are actual activities
that caregivers use in daily life to respond to these needs.</p>

<p>At a general level, one can specify areas of practice common to all
societies, such as: feeding, sleeping, handling and carrying, bathing,
preventing and attending to illness, protecting from harm, nurturing, socializing
and teaching skills.</p>

<p>But at a more specific level, &quot;what&quot; is done to help a child
survive, grow and develop merges with &quot;how&quot; it is done to define
and distinguish practices that vary widely from place to place. For instance,
in responding to the need for food, the practice of breastfeeding contrasts
with the practice of bottle feeding. Feeding &quot;on demand&quot; contrasts
with scheduled feeding. The practice of constant carrying differs dramatically
from the practice of placing a child in a crib, cradle, hammock or playpen
for prolonged periods. Or, the practice of talking to a child about what
should be done contrasts with an emphasis on non-verbal forms of communication
in the socialization process.</p>

<p><b>Patterns: What should be done?</b> Childrearing patterns are the
generally-accepted ways of care that guide caregivers in responding to
the needs of children in their early months and years in a way that assures
the survival and maintenance and development of the group or culture as
well as of the child. These childrearing norms may or may not be followed
by individuals, reflecting the particular circumstances in which a child
is being raised and/or differences in the beliefs and knowledge of individual
caregivers.<b>[1]</b></p>

<p>Having set out reasons why knowledge of childrearing practices is important,
having noted where such knowledge may be found, and having provided the
reader with definitions, we now turn to the project, beginning with Phase
I. </p>

<p><b>Results from Phase I</b></p>

<p>Within the larger project, Phase I was directed toward the elaboration
of a framework and strategy to guide the gathering of information from
an existing literature. The pilot exercise also produced a range of information
about childrearing in Mexico. The strategy and results of its application
are incorporated into a discussion document written by Maria Eugenia Linares.<b>[2]</b>
That document was discussed in a workshop held at CELAM in April 1991,
and was revised to reflect comments made in the workshop.</p>

<p>As a result, a three-dimensional framework was developed for systematizing
and analyzing information about childrearing.</p>

<p>o A first dimension derives from the fact that child development is
a continuing process, beginning with conception and in this case, carrying
through to the period of entry into school. That period was divided roughly
into the following periods: pregnancy, birth, post birth, newborn, infant,
child less than three, and child less than six.</p>

<p>o The second dimension derives from the definition of development as
a multi-dimensional and integral process including physical as well as
mental and social development and requiring attention, at a minimum, to
health, nutrition, and psychosocial wellbeing of a child.</p>

<p>o A third dimension is defined by economic and cultural differences
among groups. The three rough categories or groups chosen for analysis
were: urban marginal, rural indigenous, and rural transitional. </p>

<p>Figure 1 illustrates an adaptation of the framework worked out at the
April 1991 workshop. The adapted framework incorporates the idea that practices
can be judged from both the viewpoints of science and of popular wisdom.</p>

<p>With the framework as a base, a set of index cards were designed, each
with a set of questions pertinent to the particular category. (For the
cards and questions, please see Attachment 3.) These categories and questions
not only served for reviews of the literature, but also helped to organize
attempts in Phase II to systematize experience.</p>

<p>The Phase I pilot study and literature review:</p>

<p>o Confirmed the utility of the framework as a starting point.</p>

<p>o Uncovered, as expected, tremendous variety in the topics and groups
studied, in the methods used to study practices and in the practices. This
tended to confirm the idea that there is no formula with respect to childrearing
practices.</p>

<p>o Identified gaps in the study of, and information about practices,
patterns and beliefs, particularly in urban marginal populations. For instance,
a weakness was found in the treatment of practices related to psychosocial
development, as contrasted with the more extensive treatment of health
and nutritional practices.</p>

<p>o Suggested that the healthiest, and most effective practices did <b>not</b>
show an unequivocal linear relationship to degree of &quot;modernization&quot;
or to family structure. Breastfeeding, for instance, is most common in
less-industrialized settings. </p>

<p><b>Figure 1. Categories for the Analysis of Childrearing Practices</b></p>

<p><b>and Child Development</b></p>

<p>The review of the literature suggested the importance to programming
of having current and situation-specific information about practices, something
that a broad academic literature cannot easily provide. This led naturally
into Phase II with its focus on development of a field-based methodologies
for recovering and systematizing local information.</p>

<p>From the discussion of the pilot study came two specific suggestions
for approaches that seemed to merit testing. One suggestion was to work
with community &quot;agents&quot; (including, for example, community educators
and health workers, animators of grassroots organizations, parish priests)
who have long experience in communities and who have presumably acquired
a deep knowledge of practices and patterns in the specific communities
in which they have worked. It was not clear, however, whether this approach
would lead to the conclusion that most agents, because they are part of
or work closely with a community, are knowledgeable about childrearing
practices, or are not.</p>

<p>The second suggestion was to turn more directly to parents and other
community members in a process of discovering and describing local practices.
More specifically, it was suggested that attention be given to the utility
of a participatory method used by the Roman Catholic Church in its planning,
termed &quot;The Study of Reality.&quot; This method, which is similar
to popular education approaches, involves community members in a process
of 1) seeing (collecting information), 2) judging (analyzing) and 3) acting
(using the information to play and carry out activities). It was felt that
the method, with which the Church has had wide experience, could be focussed
on examining the condition of children, ages 0 to 6, and the childrearing
practices that affect that condition in a particular community. Doing so
would not only provide knowledge about childrearing but would also, presumably,
provide a basis for action by the practitioners and caregivers participating
in the process. </p>

<p>As the reader will see, other methods were also applied in Phase II.</p>

<p><b>Phase II in Context</b></p>

<p>The social and institutional contexts within which the studies of Phase
II were undertaken are important to describe for two reasons.</p>

<p>First, a set of common social conditions can be identified that seem
to cut across the extra-ordinarily diverse settings in which the study
was carried out and that help to moderate diversity. Therefore, it seems
reasonable, in spite of the major differences among settings, to be able
to make general statements about childrearing which, if not applicable
in 100% of the settings, nevertheless characterize conditions and practices
in a majority of the communities.</p>

<p>Second, location of the study within the institutional structure of
the Roman Catholic Church has influenced its organization and conduct.
In particular, at the time of the study, the Church was considering a proposal
to institutionalize a new pastorate within the Church called &quot;Pastoral
de la Infancia.&quot; In several countries of the continent this pastorate
has been accepted and is being tried out. It was hoped that the Fourth
General Conference of Latin American Bishops would give its general endorsement
to the idea of a pastorate at its meeting in October in Santo Domingo.
It was felt that the studies could contribute to development of activities
related to this initiative.</p>

<p><b>Common influences on childrearing practices</b></p>

<p>Several historical and contemporary influences cut across cultural and
geographic settings, moderating differences. Among the general influences
identified in the studies and in the Phase II workshop were:</p>

<p><b>1. 500 years of Spanish cultural hegemony.</b> Even the most resistant
native cultures of Latin America have been influenced to some degree by
the Conquest and its long aftermath. Perhaps foremost among these influences
has been that of the Roman Catholic church which, over the centuries, has
influenced beliefs and values, including those affecting childrearing (CELAM,
1992)</p>

<p><b>2. Economic decline during the &quot;lost decade&quot; of the 1980s.</b>
Without exception, the countries included in the study suffered major economic
declines during the 1980's, affecting employment levels, increasing the
number of people living in poverty (IDB, 1990).</p>

<p><b>3. The impact of the neo-liberal economic policies</b> applied in
an attempt to overcome the economic problems of the 1980s. The so-called
neo-liberal economic policy has been characterized by economic programs
providing incentives to attract local and foreign investment, and favoring
large scale industry and a shift to cash cropping, while increasing economic
inequalities, placing additional burdens on the poor and reducing social
spending.</p>

<p>The combination of the economic recession and of the neo-liberal policies
has led to a marked increase in the level of poverty in the region and
has forced more and more families to pursue survival strategies. Economic
pressures not only lower the level of resources available to meet daily
needs, but also affect livelihood and work patterns, family structures
and relationships, and childrearing practices and patterns. </p>

<p><b>4. The growth of conflict in the region.</b> Major strife in Central
America, the Southern Cone Sur, Colombia and Peru has created difficult
conditions of life for a growing number of Latin Americans, affecting basic
beliefs and patterns as well as daily routines, introducing new survival
and socialization needs.</p>

<p><b>5. The continuing growth of urban areas.</b> This long term trend
has been accelerated by economic declines and civil disturbances over the
last decade or more. With the move to urban areas, old ways of doing things
do not always apply. The space and conditions in which children are reared
change dramatically requiring shifts in practices.</p>

<p><b>6. The continuing move of women into the paid labor force and into
non-formal employment</b>. Associated with economic pressures and changes,
urban growth and shifting values is an increase in the participation by
women in the paid labor force. Because society still assigns primary responsibility
for child-rearing to mothers, this shift, when combined with a decrease
in extended families and with longer periods of children in school has
brought with it a demand for alternative forms of childcare and rearing
outside the home. Or, it has forced adjustments in practices and patterns
of child care which allow women to combine work and care. </p>

<p><b>7. The rapid advance of technology on many fronts</b> -- in transportation,
communication, education as well as in industry and commerce -- has not
only brought new ways of doing things, including raise children; it has
also helped to provoke a general clash of values. That advance, with origins
in &quot;science&quot; and an occidental culture places competition, individualism
and consumerism against cooperation, solidarity, and spiritualism. It has
helped to dampen the force of tradition and experience. It has brought
bottle feeding and plastic toys and television other accoutrements of childrearing
that were not available in the past and which often substitute today for
more traditional childrearing technologies. </p>

<p>8. <b>An impressive reduction has occurred in the rate of infant mortality
--</b> even in a time of economic difficulties. With this reduction has
come an in-creasing shift from a cultural orientation focussed on accepting
death and promoting the survival of children, with its harsh tone based
on a high probability of an early death, to a more optimistic and open
cultural orientation toward growth and development.</p>

<p>In brief, all of the above widespread conditions have had their influence
on practices by affecting the immediate physical and social environments
in which children are reared, by affecting the values toward which childrearing
is directed and some of the beliefs that underpin traditional practices,
and by affecting the technologies available to be applied in the process
of childrearing. In so doing, these increasingly common conditions provide
pressures for common responses.</p>

<p><b>II</b></p>

<p><b>THE PHASE II CASE STUDIES:</b></p>

<p><b>WHERE WERE THEY DONE AND WHO PARTICIPATED</b>?</p>

<p>In Phase II of the Project on childrearing practices and patterns, case
studies were carried out in 35 communities in 9 countries: Bolivia, Chile,
Costa Rica, Ecuador, El Salvador, Guatemala, Honduras, Mexico and Peru.
Included were low-income urban and rural communities, communities with
varying ethnic compositions and of different sizes and degrees of community
solidarity, communities directly affected by war and or civil strife, and
communities located in very different geographic conditions. Table 1 provides
basic information about the specific communities studied in each country.</p>

<p>The information presented suggests a relatively even split between urban
and rural communities. Aymara, Quechua, Mapuche, Shipiba, and Negro cultures
are represented as well as predominantly mestizo and hispanic cultures.
Urban groups included both communities on the periphery and in the central
city. Rural communities included isolated communities and those relatively
near to major cities but still involved in agriculture. Ecuador contributed
the greatest variation within a single country, with information from 14
different communities located in five different areas of the country and
covering Indian, mestizo, and Negro cultures, and various mixtures of these
cultures.</p>

<p>More than 600 people provided information within the various studies.
Almost all of the participants were mothers. In Honduras, Peru and Chile,
a conscious effort was made to select both younger and older mothers for
interviews. Only in Chile (with the temporary workers) and in Ecuador,
were a handful of fathers included. In various locations, men were among
the experts or community agents consulted. </p>

<p>The population with whom researchers worked in each country is not a
statistically representative population. Communities were not selected
randomly, nor were people; rather, a purposive approach was taken, linking
selection to particular conditions. Criteria differed by location, influenced
by a desire to provide variation (Chile, Peru, Bolivia, Ecuador, and Central
America taken as a whole), to include a particular cultural group (for
example, the Negro culture in Ecuador), to work with communities in which
the Catholic Church was active (Mexico), or to study communities undergoing
a particular change (as in the resettlement situation in El Salvador).
In Chile and Peru, an effort was made to select individuals for participation
in the study who had <b>not</b> been involved in a program run by non-governmental
organizations.</p>

