<p><b>Analyzing the existing literature</b></p>

<p><b>How it was done.</b> All countries included in their studies a literature
search and analysis. Most took as the starting point the framework developed
by Linares in the pilot phase of the project (Figure 1, p. 6, and Attachment
3). Methods used to locate material included: computer searches, reviews
of theses and of library holdings in major universities, and consultation
with experts with a knowledge of the literature.</p>

<p>In general, identifying apparently relevant studies and obtaining them
in order to examine their content was an onerous task, carried out with
varying energy and success in the different countries. The process was
complicated by the dispersion of sources across disciplines, by the uncatalogued
nature of many sources, by breakdowns in computer search systems or difficulty
in selecting appropriate key words, and by a general lack of previous attempts
to search the literature upon which current efforts could build.</p>

<p><b>Results.</b> Although some excellent studies of childrearing practices,
patterns and beliefs were encountered as a result of the literature search,
these were few and far between, were often found embedded in a larger work,
and tended to concentrate on certain communities or groups. Consistently
greater attention was given to health and nutritional practices than to
practices related to early education or to psycho-social development. Studies
also tended to be more descriptive than analytical, failing to get at why
practices are as they are. In too many cases, studies included an interpretation
of findings based on a normative position rooted in the dominant culture,
prejudging practices and beliefs without looking closely at real outcomes
of &quot;different&quot; practices and without searching for the reasons
why practices are as they are.</p>

<p>One unfortunate conclusion that might be drawn from the above is that
turning to published or unpublished writings as a source of information
is not worth the effort. However, in spite of the difficulties noted, the
process did seem to be useful in several ways. First, it did uncover some
excellent work that could be drawn upon. Second, in some cases the written
work provided quantitative results, complementing the essentially qualitative
approaches taken in most of the country studies. Third, particular studies
were found that served as a check on field work results. Indeed, a look
at the nine country reports suggests that descriptive results found in
the literature were generally consistent with results found in field work,
giving credence to results of the field work or complementing it. Fourth,
the process helped to identify gaps in information that should be filled.</p>

<p>In the Bogot&aacute; meeting, it was felt that literature searches should
be extended to include information found outside the scientific literature
-- in such sources as novels, biographies and catequesis -- none of which
were included in the present exploration.</p>

<p><b>Going to the field: two approaches</b></p>

<p>Two purposes guided field work in the project: collecting information
and promoting reflection and change. The main purpose adopted in eight
of the studies was to collect information about childrearing practices
and patterns. Directly promoting change as part of that process was, at
best, a secondary goal in these studies. In the Mexican study, by way of
contrast, the information collecting purpose was subordinated to promoting
reflection and change, resulting in a different methodological approach
from the others. </p>

<p><b>Collecting information</b></p>

<p>The two most common methods used to collect information in the project
were questionnaires and interviews. Structured questionnaires served as
the basis for work in the Central American countries and in Ecuador. In
Central America an extensive instrument was carefully constructed to cover
each of the contextual and developmental variables for which information
was desired. This instrument was administered to individual mothers. In
Ecuador, a briefer questionnaire served as the basis for interviews in
family settings. In group settings, it became a kind of semi-structured
interview schedule. Whether individually or in group, an attempt was made
to use questionnaires and conduct interviews in such a way that they began
with the concerns of the families interviewed about the up-bringing of
their children. Thus, an attempt was made to avoid &quot;extracting&quot;
information from people and, rather, to place the emphasis on helping people
to understand better and to satisfy their concerns. </p>

<p>The questionnaires produced quantitative results, allowing a description
and comparisons among groups with respect to some standard categories and
questions.</p>

<p>In Chile, Peru and Bolivia, a semi-structured interview schedule provided
the starting point for conversations in focus groups. The schedule was
followed more closely in Bolivia, in order to help systematic recording
of information, than in Chile and Peru, where conversations were tape-recorded
and then transcribed. The Chilean approach allowed group interviews to
flow spontaneously. Tapes were analyzed after a first interview and gaps
in information were identified that could then be filled at a second or
third session with the group. The results of these interviews were submitted
to a content analysis and are presented in qualitative terms.</p>

<p>In all of the above cases, instruments were field tested and adjusted
before being used. Adjustments continued during the period of application.
</p>

<p>The instruments all included information about the people interviewed
and about the general conditions of life in the family. In addition to
obtaining an idea about the economic situation and work patterns, family
structure, and educational levels, instruments included questions about
family relationships, about the distribution of roles and responsibilities,
and about alcoholism and abuse. With respect to practices, patterns and
beliefs, information was sought at different periods of development (pregnancy,
birth, infancy, early childhood and the preschool period), about practices
related to health, nutrition, and psycho-social development. </p>

<p><b>Promoting reflection and change</b></p>

<p>The Mexican study differed from the other eight studies in several respects.
First, because it took as its main purpose promoting reflection and change,
the methodology used was a participatory one in which the subjects of the
exercise were accompanied in a process of constructing their own set of
questions and answers about childrearing practices, patterns and beliefs.
The basic premise of this methodology is that, in the process of gathering
and discussing information, those involved will identify areas in which
action is desirable and will be motivated to carry out those actions. Accordingly,
the <b>process</b> used to carry out the study took on even greater importance
than the <b>content</b>. Applying the participatory methodology meant that
the outside &quot;researchers&quot; began by discussing basic concepts
with the community workers rather than by administering a questionnaire
or semi-structured interview schedule or accepting the categories developed
in Phase I, as given.</p>

<p>Second, the study in Mexico focussed on community agents rather than
on parents. This focus was adopted because community action is the business
of community agents. Working with agents to understand and apply a participatory
methodology to examining explicitly the well-being of young children and,
as part of that, at the childrearing practices and patterns in their community,
constitutes a strategy for improving the condition of young children. But
the focus was also taken in order to test out an assumption that is often
made -- that because community agents come from a community or have lived
for a long time in a community they will have absorbed and can articulate
the traditional wisdom of that community. In this case, the emphasis was
on traditional wisdom about childrearing. To some extent, the Ecuadorian
study also incorporated this dimension, by involving people from different
communities and/or governmental agencies in the process of collecting information.</p>

<p>Third, the Mexican study was more directly related than others to the
activities and thinking of the Roman Catholic church. The communities chosen
were communities in which a system of &quot;comunidades de base&quot; were
functioning and entrance to these communities was sought through the local
parish priest or another representative of the church. The community agents
with whom the project worked were primarily church workers and lay members
active in the comunidades de base. The methodology employed was consistent
with the church's method of analyzing community problems through use of
&quot;An Analysis of Reality,&quot; involving the three steps of &quot;looking
(gathering information), judging (analyzing the information), and acting
(identifying solutions to problems identified and carrying them out).&quot;
To a limited degree it provided a test of that methodology, as applied
to childrearing.</p>

<p>Another feature of the Mexican project that sets it apart is that the
groups with whom community agents were working in one of the communities
were groups of older children; the approach to childrearing in families
was through these children rather than through parents.</p>

<p>The participatory methodology applied in Mexico called for several different
techniques of gathering and processing information and for working in the
community. For instance:</p>

<p>o Group exercises to motivate and aid reflection were used, such as
games or role playing or creating posters that expressed a viewpoint about
childrearing (or about the role of the community agent). One of the most
successful and insightful of these involved asking participants to act
out something from their childhood, or to reflect on what their childhood
was like. This method helped to bring out inter-generational comparisons,
a comparison that was sought in other studies by working with groups of
older and younger women.</p>

<p>o A rough instrument was constructed to record &quot;A Day in the Life
of a Child.&quot; This was found to be useful when working with the older
children to observe their younger siblings.</p>

<p>Finally, the Mexican study involved working closely and continuously
with a limited number of people, in only two communities, over a period
of several months, as contrasted with other studies that involved interaction
during, at most, several hours, at one or two points in time.</p>

<p>To record observations and conversations over time, detailed notes were
taken and a field diary was kept. Notes from periodic meetings with community
agents were analyzed and a systematic reformulation was provided to the
group as a basis for discussion at the next session.</p>

<p><b>Observations from the Bogot&aacute; meeting and some lessons learned</b></p>

<p>1. There was general agreement that questionnaires and interview schedule
should not be used rigidly because this inhibits responses and limits conversation.
Rigid adherence to a format with a particular order and categories does
not allow important issues and practices to emerge that might not have
been included in the original instrument. It also increases the chances
that respondents will say what they think the interviewer wants to hear.</p>

<p>2. Reliance of all of the above methodologies on verbal responses was
noted and the validity of this method was questioned. What people say they
do or believe is not necessarily what they actually do or believe. Indeed,
none of the studies described relied on systematic observation, nor were
they set up as experimental studies.</p>

<p>In reply, researchers pointed to a set of &quot;validity checks&quot;
that were used to determine whether answers provided were distorted. Results
of the interviews and of the participatory process were compared with what
was found in the literature, with opinions of local informants, and with
opinions of specialists in the field. In some cases (in addition to Mexico)
results were also discussed directly with the people from whom the information
was originally obtained. In addition to helping spot incorrect interpretations
and to look for explanations, this process was intended to aid the second
purpose mentioned above - to promote reflection and change.</p>

<p>This discussion of dependence on verbal responses and personal recounting
of experience rather than on direct observation led to several conclusions:</p>

<p>o Checks on the validity of the information obtained did support the
quantitative and qualitative findings based that were based on &quot;the
word&quot; and the findings were, therefore, thought to be reasonably accurate.
Such checks should form part of any exploration of childrearing practices.</p>

<p>o Some form of systematic observation of what people actually do should
be incorporated into methodologies whenever possible.</p>

<p>o Organizing discussions of systematized results of interviews and/or
group conversations is an important methodological device that should be
incorporated into childrearing studies. Such discussions not only provide
a validity check, but can begin to move knowledge toward action by promoting
reflection and change in the group.</p>

<p>3. The feasibility of adopting a time consuming process of &quot;accompa&ntilde;amiento&quot;
such as was employed in the Mexican study was questioned. Indeed, the process,
which covered four months in Mexico, did not run its full course because
time ran out. It was not possible to accompany participants in the third
step in the process; that is, of acting on what was being discovered.</p>

<p>In response, it was noted that community workers, who are continuously
present in a community and who are not limited by a project's time table
would be able to carry through such a methodology. The Mexican study was,
in effect, a kind of training for community workers to do that, incorporating
it into their regular work. At the same time, it was suggested that the
process of acompa&ntilde;amiento is much more feasible in communities that
are strong and have already achieved some level of organization autonomy.
The method is less appropriate for weak and dependent communities.</p>

<p>4. A number of useful techniques were identified that can be drawn upon
in future work. These include:</p>

<p>o Asking adults to reflect on their own childhood. Remembering childhood
helps to establish key themes, can identify continuity and change in practices,
contributes to the empathy of the parents with the child, and can provide
an easy way of including men in the conversation. This exercise seems particularly
important because of the marked tendency for parents to repeat practices
applied to them when they were children, even if they do not think those
practices were appropriate or just.</p>

<p>o Comparing practices and beliefs across generations by seeking out
older and younger parents. This technique also helps to identify continuities
or discontinuities in practices across generations -- the &quot;generational
matrix&quot;.</p>

<p>o Group dynamic exercises. Such exercises help to get members of a group
involved and serve also as a form of expression with respect to particular
topics.</p>

<p>o Constructing a &quot;day in the life of a child.&quot; This technique
helps to make observations more systematic.</p>

<p>5. Community workers are not necessarily a good source of information
about childrearing practices. Neither parish priests nor nuns nor health
workers showed a firm grasp of traditional practices. Nor was traditional
knowledge incorporated into planning and daily work.</p>

<p>6. The framework and sets of questions developed in Phase I (Attachment
3) provided a good point of departure for exploring childrearing practices
in a community. It is important in each study, however, to re-examine the
relevance of particular questions and, to the extent possible, involve
participants in the reconstruction of a framework and questions. This process
both helps to promote understanding of the process and the outcomes and
to make adjustments to local realities. </p>

<p>7. The Mexican study suggests that a participatory methodology, similar
to the &quot;Analysis of Reality,&quot; applied to examining the well being
of young children in a community, is potentially useful. </p>

<p><b>IV </b></p>

<p><b>WHAT HAVE WE LEARNED ABOUT PRACTICES, PATTERNS AND BELIEFS?</b></p>

<p>The following synthesis brings together results and conclusions that
appeared in the various reports and conclusions that were presented at
the Bogot&aacute; meeting in September of 1992. Results will be reported
that deal with: who cares for young children; how they are cared for; what
the perceived norms for care are; beliefs; and the conditions affecting
practices, patterns and beliefs.</p>

<p>About Practices, Patterns and Beliefs</p>

<p><b>Who cares for the child?</b></p>

<p>1. It is obvious that the mother continues to be the main person who
cares for children, but that her role varies a great deal according to
the age of the child (less time is spent with the passing of time) and
according to social economic, cultural and family circumstances. In many
places, grandmothers and older siblings have an important role in care.
In the post-natal period, the mother-in-law is important in some places.
</p>

<p>2. The father rarely participates directly in early childrearing. The
degree and presence and support varies from place to place but, in general,
the contribution seems to be minimal and for the sake of appearance. There
are exceptions. For example, fathers frequently participate directly in
the birthing process in the Andean cultures of Bolivia and Peru. In El
Salvador, rural Bolivia and the Mapuche culture in Chile, fathers take
on a more important role in socialization of boys during the later pre-school
years. Among the temporary laborers studied in Chile, the work routine
demands that fathers take an active role in the care of their children.</p>

<p>The opinions of mothers regarding the help they receive from their partner
in caring for children is marked by a cultural pattern that, in the main,
protects the positive image of the male even though his participation is
minimal or missing. This opinion may or may not be based on the financial
help that males provide. Also appearing in the studies is a general opinion
that men do not know how to, and do not have the capacity to, participate
in the childrearing process. </p>

<p>3. In many of the places studied, the role of the honorary mother or
of the mid-wife continues to be important during pregnancy and birth.</p>

<p><b>How is the child cared for?</b></p>

<p><b>Pre-natal</b></p>

<p>1. Birth control is rarely practiced in the groups studied. Many mothers
wish to have less children and they are in favor of birth control but do
not practice it. Men are particularly resistent to the use of anti-conceptives.</p>

<p>2. The practice of abortion is not accepted as a norm nor followed in
the groups studied, with very few exceptions.</p>

<p>3. Although there is variation from place to place, in many places no
change in dietary practices occurs during pregnancy. This is especially
so in Peru and in Bolivia. In Central America, between 50% and 60% of the
participants in the case studies changed their eating practices.</p>

<p>4. It is common to have cravings and to believe that they ought to be
satisfied. In Peru, there exists a belief that cravings come from the fetus
and therefore one has to respond. Apparently, cravings serve to insure
that a pregnant woman will eat more and that the father, in helping to
satisfy the cravings, participates in the process.</p>

<p>5. In general, a high percentage of women use either the formal or informal
health systems at their disposal for monitoring pregnancy, but in some
rural areas, a very low percentage of women seek attention (e.g., Bolivia,
Per&amp;; y Cotopaxi in Ecuador). Moreover, the monitoring, many times,
is partial. According to the Ecuadorean study, less than 40% of the women
practiced &quot;integral&quot; control; that is to say, monitored their
health, ate better and reduced physical labor during pregnancy. In Chile,
among the Mapuches, women avoid heavy labor but continue working until
the last minute at habitual chores.</p>

<p>6. The use of formal vs informal (mid-wives and honorary mothers) systems
varied a great deal among places, including within countries.</p>

<p>7. In general, pregnancy is seen by the mothers as a natural process
rather than as an abnormal process or as a sickness. This &quot;normal&quot;
vision is not shared by the formal health system.</p>

<p><b>Birth and Post-partum</b></p>

<p>1. As with pregnancy, birth is viewed by the women studied as a natural
process, whereas the health system treats it as an equivalent of sickness.</p>

<p>2. The place of birth and the person who attends the birth varies a
great deal in the case studies. In Costa Rica, 100% gave birth in hospitals
and were attended by trained personnel. In Bolivia, almost all births occurred
at home, attended by members of the family, neighbor women with experience
or a mid-wife.</p>

<p>3. Only in the cases of Andean and rural Peru and Bolivia, was the physical
presence of the father notable during birth. In other cases, the father
&quot;accompanied&quot; the birth by remaining nearby or by taking care
of other children. Frequently, the father was absent.</p>

<p>4. In the case of births attended by mid-wives, there exists a variety
of traditional methods that facilitate the birthing process.</p>

<p>5. In the majority of the places studied, the mother is given the baby
immediately after birth. Also, colostrum is given. At the same time, there
exist areas in which a high percentage do not follow these practices. There
are also areas, as in Peru, in which colostrum is seen as harmful.</p>

<p>6. A range of beliefs was found regarding causes of problems at birth,
many related to magic or to religion.</p>

<p><b>The First 40 days and the Lactation Period</b></p>

<p>1. A special period of 40 days (&quot;la cuarentena,&quot; related to
the idea of &quot;quarantine&quot; in which people are isolated) is observed
in some places, with the help of grandmothers, friends, or mothers-in-law.
These women help with household chores and with other parts of the mother's
normal work load. But in other places, such as rural Bolivia for example,
the return to routine work is almost immediate.</p>

<p>2. Almost all mothers breastfeed their babies. But marked differences
exist in practices and beliefs about the timing of introduction of supplementary
food and the time of weaning. In urban areas, weaning frequently occurs
before 6 months. In Chile, the health system advises new mothers to stop
breastfeeding after 6 months.</p>

<p>3. Although weaning occurs in a gradual form in most cases, the practice
of abrupt weaning was also found with some frequency in the studies, accompanied
by the use of disagreeable substances applied to the breasts, or in conjunction
with sending the baby outside the home for a period.</p>

<p>4. In the majority of the cases, babies sleep with their mothers; in
some cases until two years of age or later. This practice facilitates breastfeeding
on demand. </p>

<p>5. The practice of constant carrying of the young child is common, especially
in Bolivia, Per&amp;;, Ecuador, and Guatemala.</p>

<p>6. The practice of binding the baby appeared frequently in Bolivia and
Peru, and among the Mapuches of Chile. Information about this practice
was not sought in all of the studies. The origin of the practice is not
given. In Peru, it is linked to a belief that children who are closely
bound will grow up strong and straight.</p>

<p>7. Health check-ups during the first months vary greatly from place
to place, related to the availability of health posts, but also to attitudes
toward the formal health system (or attitudes of the health system toward
the people) and toward the need for check-ups.</p>

<p>8. Comments related to practices of stimulation or of play with the
small child included:</p>

<p>Peru: Mothers do not have an idea of the need for stimulation.</p>

<p>Chile: In urban areas children are not played with because there is
a belief that they do have social or psychological needs before 8-10 months.
Among the Mapuches, the young child is considered a &quot;person,&quot;
and this translates into loving and attentive treatment, including talking
to the baby.</p>

<p>Ecuador: Undervaluing of child's play is estimated at 53% among respondents
in rural areas and 41% in urban marginal areas.</p>

<p>Honduras: 76% of the mothers interviewed showed colorful objects to
their children.</p>

<p>9. The great majority of the mothers said that they talked to their
small children. In Costa Rica, 100% affirmed this practice; in Guatemala,
92%. In Ecuador 85% said they help their child learn to talk, but only
72% assigned importance to talking with their child during the first six
months. In Chimborazo and Cotopaxi in Ecuador, only 33% and 28%, respectively,
considered it important to talk to the child before six months of age.
</p>

<p><b>Infancy</b></p>

<p>1. The practice of health check-ups varied greatly according to availability
and beliefs. Health attention was more frequent for emergency treatment
than for prevention. A certain lack of confidence in the formal health
system continues in various places. Also, the practice of using the informal
system of health continues with respect to such problems as &quot;mal de
ojo&quot; or &quot;susto&quot; which appear in almost all the places studied
but which are ignored by the formal health system. </p>

<p>The percentage of people who recognized the value of immunization is
high, but in some places the percentage of vaccinations completed had not
reached the 80% level.</p>

<p>2. Feeding. There was little information in the studies about feeding
practices for this period in the child's live.</p>

<p>3. According to the Central American studies, children crawl and walk
&quot;on time.&quot; In the Guatemalan case, a delay in the development
of language was identified.</p>

<p>4. In Bolivia and Peru, the studies found that the parents (particularly
the fathers) did not express affection to their children because this was
thought to result in a lack of respect and disobedience. </p>

<p>5. The practice of physical punishment is very generalized. In many
cases, this practice represents a repetition of what parents experienced
in their infancy. While the use of physical punishment is common, there
exist important differences in the frequency, the severity, and the occasions
in which punishment is applied, as well as in the forms of application.
In some cases, use is related to the belief that punishment permits learning
in the child. The tendency to use physical punishment appears to be stronger
than the use of rewards to reinforce desired behaviors.</p>

<p>6. The manner in which young children are helped to learn to talk appears
to be restricted to repeating words in some places (e.g., Ecuador) while
in others (Costa Rica) in includes such activities as telling stories and
singing.</p>

<p>7. For the majority of people, the ability of a child to use &quot;reason&quot;
is thought to appear between 3 and 7 years of age. Among the Shipiba of
Peru, reason begins with the ability to walk, and among the Mapuches, the
child is thought to begin learning from birth.</p>

<p><b>The Pre-school Period</b></p>

<p>1. Little information exists in the studies about health practices or
nutrition during this period.</p>

<p>2. Beginning at three years of age (or a little earlier in some of the
areas studied) it is common to assign errands or tasks to children, particularly
in rural areas.</p>

<p>3. In the games that children play during this period, gender differences
begin to appear.</p>

<p>4. The general use of physical punishment continues.</p>

<p>5. Major differences exist in the physical space that is available and
free from danger in which children can play.</p>

<p>6. Differences were also found in the importance of television as an
influence on young children. In Chile, the influence has become very strong;
in other places, the clear tendency is toward an ever greater influence
over childrens' lives. </p>

<p><b>Why Are Practices As They Are</b>?</p>

<p>In this section, we will present four categories of response to the
question, &quot;Why Do They Do What They Do?&quot; The answers focus, respectively,
on the influence of: &quot;scientific&quot; knowledge; social norms (patterns);
beliefs, and the conditions in which children live. We make these distinctions
even though the relationships among categories makes it difficult, from
time to time, to distinguish norms from beliefs or from levels of knowledge.
</p>

<p><b>1. Lack of Knowledge</b></p>

<p>One premise of many programs is that there exists a lack of scientific
knowledge and that it is possible to change practices by introducing people
to new scientific information. It is not difficult, using the results from
these studies, to locate practices and patterns that, from a scientific
viewpoint, seem to be &quot;wrong.&quot; For example: science shows us
that the development of the brain is influenced by the exercise of the
senses. But the studies show that, in many cases, there is a lack of interaction
between mother and child and little stimulation of the child during the
first months. This seems related to a perception of babies as incapable
of using their senses or as incapable of learning or understanding during
their first months.</p>

<p>Other gaps in caregiver Knowledge that exist, from a scientific viewpoint,
include knowledge about:</p>

<p>o feeding habits during pregnancy and lactation</p>

<p>o the most appropriate time to introduce supplementary foods</p>

<p>o the importance of talking to the child</p>

<p>o effects of play on intellectual development</p>

<p>o emotional effects of physical punishment</p>

<p>Although there are gaps in the presentation and understanding of scientific
information, it is evident that the process of filling these gaps would
be a partial solution to the problem. It is clear that some of the ideas
and/or scientific technologies are not accepted because other ideas continue
to be dominant about the established ways of bringing up children. Also,
concrete conditions of life for each family plan a role. </p>

<p><b>2. Existing cultural patterns serve as norms of conduct.</b></p>

<p>In the studies it is possible to identify some general patterns that
evidently influence practice, such as:</p>

<p>o Care of the child is the responsibility of women. Men do not know
how to provide care and should remain on the margin.</p>

<p>o Breastfeeding is good and necessary.</p>

<p>o Physical punishment is necessary (at least every once in awhile) in
order for a child to develop well.</p>

<p>Other patterns are more limited in their extension but appear to have
an influence on practice. For example, in some parts of Peru, one should
not show love to children because they will lose their respect for adults
and become disobedient. In this case, the norm is related closely to the
social values: respect and obedience. Separating these values from &quot;beliefs&quot;
is difficult.</p>

<p>At the same time, a main conclusion of these studies is that norms vary
a great deal from place to place and that, frequently, there is a difference
between the norms (what &quot;should be&quot;) and the practices (what
&quot;is). The congruence between norms and practices actually seems to
be greater in rural areas with groups that are more isolated and homogeneous.
In urban areas, it is common to find discrepancies between norms and practices.</p>

<p>It is apparent that some cultural practices have become diffuse and
confusing in some places. The confusion is evident in <b>inter-generational
</b>differences. For example, the older and younger mothers in urban marginal
areas of Peru follow different patterns with respect to use of the formal
health system and with respect to the custom of binding children. The confusion
is evident also <b>among people of the same age living in the same community
but coming from very different cultural and geographic areas.</b> Indeed,
in the study of urban areas in Chile, it seemed difficult to find common
patterns. </p>

<p>In other places, patterns continue to be more or less clear, but the
practices do not correspond to these supposed norms or patterns. For example,
there exists a consensus that breastfeeding is good and necessary, but
many women stop breastfeeding very early.</p>

<p>3<b>. They do what they do because of their beliefs.</b></p>

<p>Even in the more &quot;modernized&quot; places in Latin America, &quot;rational-empirical&quot;
ways of thinking exist side by side with dogmas based in the magical or
supernatural. In order to understand the &quot;why&quot; of practices it
is necessary to understand beliefs, whether magical or religious in origin.</p>

<p>In the studies many examples appear of beliefs that influence childrearing
practice:</p>

<p>o Abortion is a sin.</p>

<p>o What is done with the umbilical cord has an influence over the life
of the child.</p>

<p>o &quot;Mal de ojo&quot; is a cause of sickness. It is possible to protect
oneself from &quot;mal de ojo&quot; by putting on a bracelet (or using
another magical remedy).</p>

<p>o A child who is abnormal at birth represents a divine punishment (rather
than, for instance), a problem caused by such vices as smoking or drinking).
</p>

<p>o A small child is &quot;weak.&quot;</p>

<p>o A child is (or is not) a &quot;person&quot; at birth. Or, only with
baptism does a child acquire the character of a person.</p>

<p>o To bind up babies produces strong and straight children.</p>

<p>In many cases, the magical beliefs do not have any effect that contradicts
science; to the contrary, in some cases it is possible that they can be
called upon to support a scientific belief. For example, the belief in
the use of a bracelet to avoid &quot;mal de ojo&quot; is a form of prevention
and can be related to the broader scientific concept of prevention.</p>

<p>On the basis of these studies, it seems that <b>the lack of a sense
of what &quot;should be&quot;</b>&quot;(whether defined by science or by
traditional wisdom or by religion), may be present in some cases but <b>is
not the main cause of deviation of practices from norms.</b> These deviations
between norms and practices seem linked to changes in beliefs and in the
conditions in which children are brought up.</p>

<p><b>4. Practices depend on the conditions of life</b></p>

<p>There are many conditions that influence practices, patterns and beliefs.
These include geographic (climate, topography, etc.), economic (level of
poverty), social (the use of alcohol and drugs) y political (the level
of violence) conditions at a general level. At the level of each family
there are special conditions influencing practices such as: the work situation
and the conditions of work, the structure and size of the family, the particular
moment of a family in its cycle, alcoholism in the home, etc.</p>

<p>Of equal (or greater) importance in the interpretation of the results
of the studies are<b> changing conditions</b> -- a generalized phenomenon
in Latin America as in other parts of the world. Among the more important
of these changes, mentioned in the first section of this document, with
an effect on practices, patterns and beliefs are:</p>

<p>o <b>migration to cities</b> (where practices that served will in rural
areas do not serve so well);</p>

<p>o <b>changes in information and in available services in rural areas</b>
related to the advance of the communications media, to re-migration or
periodic visits from the cities, and to the arrival of services such as
the school, and health centers (bringing with them modifications in practices
and norms that do not necessarily conform to the rural context);</p>

<p>o <b>violence and war</b> (that dislocate people and which define new
priorities and means of seeing the world, affecting practices and patterns;
and </p>

<p>o <b>social and economic changes</b> such as the neo-liberal economic
strategies that have been accompanied by increased poverty. The conditions
of poverty demand, frequently, strategies of accommodation in practices
of childrearing to precarious conditions of life. These accommodations
are functional in terms of the survival of family members, but negative
from the point of view of the health of the child. That is to say, the
up-bringing of children does not always occupy first place in the list
of priorities of a family pressured by the need to survive.</p>

<p>All these changes in conditions were found in the case studies.</p>

<p>Constant change creates a tension between practices that represent,
on one hand, belonging to and the preservation of a particular culture
and, on the other hand, a cultural adjustment to actual and future changes.
</p>

<p>Therefore:</p>

<p>o When judging practices, the prevalence of change makes it necessary
to distinguish the desire to maintain &quot;traditional&quot; patterns
and practices simply in order to maintain them, from a desire to maintain
them because the continue to respond to basic and real needs of the people.
</p>

<p>o In some situations, it is difficult to identify norms.</p>

<p>o in many cases practices diverge from norms, creating contradictions
and guilt in daily life.</p>

<p>o it is necessary to put in context the findings of the case studies
and the recommendations to improve childrearing practices.</p>

<p><b>Traditional and Scientific Viewpoints</b></p>

<p>1. It is possible to find &quot;traditional&quot; patterns and practices
in many places that, in spite of marked differences in geographic and cultural
differences, have at the same time a &quot;scientific&quot; and a &quot;cultural&quot;
value. These traditional patterns and practices may not be accepted by
all people in a particular place but they are common. They represent a
form of adaptation to precarious conditions and should be supported. For
example:</p>

<p>o Treating pregnancy as &quot;normal&quot; and not as a &quot;disease&quot;
or as an abnormal condition.</p>

<p>o The psychological help provided to a pregnant woman by mid-wives.
</p>

<p>o The creation of a friendly and familial atmosphere in the home at
the time of birth.</p>

<p>o The use of certain herbs to facilitate birth.</p>

<p>o The practice of reserving &quot;forty days&quot; for recovery and
of substituting for the mother in her daily work during the post-partum
period.</p>

<p>o Breastfeeding on demand.</p>

<p>o The practice of carrying the child (which facilitates breastfeeding
and the possibility of interaction with the general surroundings as well
as with the mother).</p>

<p>o The practice of sleeping with the child (which facilitates touch and
breastfeeding will helping the process of attachment). </p>

<p>o Gradual weaning (in many places).</p>

<p>o The presence and use of natural toys.</p>

<p>o Assigning tasks to the young child, consistent with ability and with
a progression in difficulty.</p>

<p>2. At the same time, there exist patterns and practices that represent
tensions between a &quot;scientific&quot; point of view and a cultural,
traditional, popular point of view. For example:</p>

<p>o During pregnancy, many times the lack of check-ups and the failure
to change eating habits is associated with problems. </p>

<p>o At birth, in a significant number of cases, the baby is not brought
to the mother right away.</p>

<p>o In Peru, colostrum is seen as harmful.</p>

<p>o The idea that the small child is not capable of learning appears often
in popular wisdom. </p>

<p>o Abrupt weaning occurs with some frequency.</p>

<p>o Delay in the introduction of supplementary foods is common. </p>

<p>o There is a lack of stimulation and verbal interaction between parents
and their babies.</p>

<p>o There is little recognition that babies are sensitive to their surrounding
emotional environment.</p>

<p>o Physical punishment is seen as necessary.</p>

<p>o Play is often seen as a waste of time.</p>

<p>3. There also exist patterns, practices and beliefs that have a high
cultural value but, according to science, do not have a major affect on
the physical or psycho-social development of a child. </p>

<p>o The practice of saving and/or burying the placenta. </p>

<p>o The use of a bracelet as a protection against &quot;mal de ojo.&quot;</p>

<p>o The ritual cutting of hair (in Bolivia and Per&amp;;).</p>

<p>o The application of eggwhite if the child does not walk (Honduras).</p>

<p><b>V</b></p>

<p><b>IMPLICATIONES</b></p>

<p>In the studies of each country and in the discussion of results in Bogota,
some implications for programming and action were identified.</p>

<p><b>General implications for programming</b></p>

<p>1. <b>There are no formulas.</b> The rich diversity of the studies is
difficult to capture in a summary. The breadth of conditions and contexts,
and the variation encountered in practices, patterns and beliefs confirms
the general conclusion that programs of early childhood care and development
need to be adjusted to local variations and realities. If not, it will
be impossible to respect cultural differences. If not, it will be impossible
to &quot;begin with the knowledge of the people.&quot;</p>

<p>2. <b>Methods of work at the local level should be reinforced that permit
description and analysis of practices, patterns and beliefs and that promote
changes in the process.</b> The emphasis on methods that can be applied
at the local level is of equal or greater importance than an emphasis on
the discovery of general patterns with the goal of setting policies related
to the entire population. Therefore; in the preparation of plans, in training
materials, and in field work, processes should be promoted that permit
educational agents to work with community groups in investigating, reflecting
on, and acting in accordance with their childrearing practices. This is
more important than dictating practices.</p>

<p>3. <b>It is necessary to revive those &quot;traditional&quot; practices
and popular wisdom that favor healthy and integral development of the young
child.</b> In the process, it is important to avoid value judgements about
popular wisdom that, if made from the beginning, would not permit understanding
and the revival of such practices.</p>

<p>4. <b>Emphasis should be placed on work and discussion in groups in
order to make information about childrearing practices.</b> The presentation
of practices derived from scientific and/or ecumenical ideas ought to be
seen as the source of &quot;themes&quot; for discussion and dialogue (more
than as the basis for &quot;messages&quot;) with communities. The dialogue
should not be based on the attempt to convince people to accept certain
practices or patterns or beliefs originating in science or church doctrine,
but should require identification, valuing and appropriating practices
with roots in the popular wisdom of various cultures.</p>

<p>5. <b>It is neither valid nor just to continue to use &quot;marginal&quot;
to put a label on certain social groups.</b> The fact that poverty defines
the conditions of life for a major proportion of the population in many
societies makes it necessary to question the concepts of &quot;normality&quot;
and of &quot;marginality,&quot; reserving the latter for conditions in
which the people lack services that can better their life. </p>

<p>6. <b>There is a tension between a &quot;global vision&quot; in which
everything seems inter-related and important and a necessity to assign
priorities.</b> One form of overcoming this tension is to distinguish short
term and long term actions, focussing on areas of priority in the short
run and working with the integrated vision for long term plans. In such
a process, it is necessary to recognize that short-term priorities will
not be the same in all places and that all priorities should be chosen
with participation of the people. </p>

<p>7. <b>It is not sufficient to speak only of &quot;preventive&quot; actions
in conditions that offer little opportunity of avoiding the future problems
that preventive actions are supposed to prevent.</b> In order to evaluate
the effects of childrearing practices, it is important to look not only
at immediate effects but also to evaluate effects of the practices in later
years.</p>

<p>8. <b>A &quot;constructive&quot; vision is needed.&quot;</b> It is important
to maintain a positive and constructive vision. Accordingly, emphasis should
be placed on recognizing good practice rather than on punishing bad practice.</p>

<p>9. <b>More attention should be given to the entire family in childrearing.</b>
Programs should not only be directed to mothers. Also:</p>

<p>o Much more attention should be given to fathers.</p>

<p>o The care given by grandparents and siblings should be recognized.</p>

<p>10. <b>Working with parents and other members of the family is essentially
a matter of adult education.</b> Therefore, professionals and other people
with experience in work with children also need training in how to work
with adults.</p>

<p>11.<b> There is a need to examine the influence on childrearing practices
of the social construction of gender roles, with emphasis on the role of
the male.</b></p>

<p>12. <b>There are examples of efforts made by communities to respond
to change with new forms of childrearing that combine the traditional with
new arrangements and methods.</b> One example was found in the resettlement
community of El Cen&iacute;cero studied in El Salvador. Another is the
community of San Jos&eacute; Nacahuil in Guatemala which shows the incorporation
of many &quot;modern&quot; practices while maintaining other &quot;traditional&quot;
practices.&quot; </p>

<p>13. <b>Alliances should be sought out among institutions seeking to
better the welfare of young children.</b> Neither the government nor non-governmental
institutions , nor the church can expect the desired results working alone.</p>

<p>14. <b>Greater effort needs to be made to integrate the intellectual,
social and emotional part of development of children into programs of health
and nutrition.</b></p>

<p>15. <b>It is necessary to take into account, more than has been done,
the force and potential which television has as an influence over young
children.</b> </p>

<p><b>Implications according to developmental stages</b></p>

<p><b>Pre-natal y birth</b></p>

<p>o Greater attention to &quot;birth spacing&quot; is necessary.</p>

<p>o Greater attention to food habits and nutritional status in the pre-natal
period is called for.</p>

<p>o Practices with a high cultural value, such as burying the placenta
ought to be respected in the birthing process.</p>

<p>o The training of traditional mid-wives should continue, respecting
practices that have served well and incorporating elements from formal
medicine into their reparatory.</p>

<p>o It is necessary to produce a radical change in the attitudes of doctors
and others working in the formal health sector who should stop treating
pregnancy and birth as abnormal or as a condition of illness.</p>

<p>o It is worthwhile strengthening such existing practices as:</p>

<p>- birth at home (with, however, training of mid-wives, birthing &quot;kits&quot;
and provision of contingencies for possible problems)</p>

<p>- the use of traditional methods that facilitate giving birth.</p>

<p>o Hospitals should be reorganized in order to permit a more &quot;human&quot;
environment, including the participation of family members and facilitating
the nearness of mother and child from the moment of birth onwards. </p>

<p><b>Forty days and Lactencia</b></p>

<p>o Nutritional campaigns have had very little effect on the practice
of introducing supplementary food on the maintenance of breastfeeding and
on weaning. The ways in which information about these practices is presented
would be re-examined.</p>

<p><b>Infancy and Pre-school</b></p>

<p>o More space is needed in communities dedicated to play.</p>

<p>o It is possible to strengthen learning by reinforcing the practice
of assigning children errands and daily tasks.</p>

<p>o The practice of physical discipline requires additional attention.</p>

<p><b>Implications for Organizations</b></p>

<p><b>UNICEF</b></p>

<p>A. <b>Situation Analysis</b>. Information about childrearing practices
should be included systematically in Situation Analyses. This implies incorporating
qualitative information and suggests a need to look for links with (and/or
to strengthen links with) groups that have an institutional capacity for
continuing analysis. </p>

<p>B. <b>Publications</b> such as &quot;Facts for Life&quot; dealing with
child development need to be re-examined from the perspective of childrearing
practices and need to be seen as an invitation to dialogue rather than
as a presentation of universal truths.</p>

<p>C. <b>Training</b></p>

<p>o A large challenge and necessity exists to help reorient health personnel
in the formal sector toward a more humane position incorporating also into
their work elements of traditional wisdom.</p>

<p>o It is important to continue support for the training of traditional
mid-wives.</p>

<p>o In programs of training for community agents, whether in nutrition,
health, psycho-social development or community promotion, it is worthwhile
including a participatory exercise dealing with the collection of local
childrearing practices. This would help to raise the consciousness of these
agents and could also provide them with a methodology for promoting change
with participation. </p>

<p>D. The emphasis of UNICEF on <b>&quot;baby friendly hospitals&quot;</b>
is very limited and should be redefined as &quot;baby-friendly birthing&quot;
in order to include attention to births that occur in locations outside
the formal system.</p>

<p>E. <b>Integration.</b> A continuing challenge exists of seeking greater
integration across sectors in the work of UNICEF, and more particularly
of incorporating a psycho-social dimension of development into existing
programs.</p>

<p>F. <b>Definition of &quot;scale.&quot; </b>It is necessary to modify
or extend the concept of &quot;going to scale&quot; that predominates in
UNICEF if the organization wishes to resolve the tension in the process
of programming between broad coverage and work in interaction with communities,
respecting their cultural history and their particular life conditions.
The idea of &quot;scale&quot; as the extension to all of one solution at
a national level ought to be revised to include the idea of &quot;scale&quot;
as the sum of various efforts and programs directed toward the same goal
but different in their operation and directed to different groups at the
local or regional level. (This is consistent with an idea of decentralization.)
The fact that UNICEF also helps small projects and basic service projects
taking the child as a central focus ought to help the appreciation of scale
as the sum of various activities.</p>

<p>G. <b>Complementary strategies.</b> If a profound change is expected
in childrearing practices, it is not sufficient to work with the topic
of practices at the level of the child and the family; it is also necessary
to look for changes in patterns and beliefs at the community level, in
social institutions and in the culture at large. In order to work at all
of these levels, it is necessary to formulate a set of complementary strategies
including:</p>

<p>o work in institutions or centers, directly with the child;</p>

<p>o work with adults and others who care for the child;</p>

<p>o work with the conditions and organization of the community;</p>

<p>o work with social institutions (and with professionals in the institutions)
y</p>

<p>o work at the level of the culture.</p>

<p>H. <b>From institutions toward families.</b> In many programs, the tendency
is to offer an institutional service that converts community members into
&quot;users&quot; of services that are offered from inside the institutions.
The user must go to the institution to obtain the service. The study of
childrearing practices suggests that, in order to obtain better results,
the emphasis should shift &quot;from and toward the institution&quot; to
&quot;from and toward the family.&quot; That is to say, actions should
be adjusted to the needs of the population as expressed by family members
and the locus of action for programs should be moved ever closer to the
family and the child in their own living space.</p>

<p><b>CELAM</b></p>

<p>A. A need exists to <b>mount a general strategy </b>for the promotion
of attention to young children, at a regional level and in each country.
A process of conscientization is needed within distinct levels of the church.</p>

<p>B. <b>Promote intra-institutional collaboration.</b> Forms need to be
sought in which existing institutional spaces and practices can be used
to work with the topic of the young child. For example, the content of
the social pastorate and of family programs includes activities pertinent
to children. Practices such as the preparation of parents for the baptism
of their child or of young couples for marriage gives an opportunity to
include material oriented toward improving the welfare of young children.</p>

<p>C. There is a need to <b>create new institutional spaces</b> within
the church for the attention to young children, such as the &quot;pastorales
de la infancia.&quot;</p>

<p>D. There is a need to <b>reorient some of the materials</b> about child
development produced by the church in order to incorporate men in the process
and to open out the limited concept of what constitutes a &quot;family.&quot;
At the same time, new materials can be developed to assist training courses
(see the following point) and the process of educational communication
in the community work of the church. </p>

<p>E. <b>Training</b> courses are needed for parish priests and others
working at the village level in:</p>

<p>o fundamentals of child survival and development</p>

<p>o application of the method &quot;Analysis of Reality&quot; to the situation
of children.</p>

<p>o application of other methods to describe and analyze childrearing
practices and patterns. </p>

<p>F. <b>Community agents.</b> It is important to work with nuns and lay
groups as well as with parish priests.</p>

<p>G. The existing <b>catechism</b> should be examined with respect to
its treatment of the child and new forms should be sought for including
the topic in the catechism. (A useful example comes from the work of Padre
Bravo in Mexico.)</p>

<p>H. <b>Community.</b> It would be worthwhile re-examining the definition
of &quot;community&quot; to extend the concept beyond those who are active
in the church. Children and families who do not participate in the activities
of the church have needs and, up to a certain point, influence practices
and the condition of those who are part of the church. In order to work
at the level of the community ( and not only at the level of the church)
it links to other organizations in the Civil Society and with the government
are suggested.</p>

<p>I. The church should look for new forms and mechanisms of assistance
to the family related to the changing context in which more women are working
outside the home.</p>

<p>J. A re-examination of the <b>role of men</b> in childrearing should
be undertaken and new ways sought of strengthening the role of men in the
childrearing process.</p>

<p><b>Governments</b></p>

<p>A. In order to moderate the negative effects of programs of economic
adjustment, greater attention is needed to investment in the social sector.</p>

<p>B. Formal health systems need to be reoriented in order to work more
closely with the informal health sector and in order to change attitudes
of the health personnel.</p>

<p>C. The psycho-social component of development should be incorporated
into health and nutrition programs.</p>

<p>D. Governments should give greater support to the efforts of non-governmental
organizations working for the benefit of young children.</p>

<p><b>Non-governmental organizations</b></p>

<p>A. It would be worthwhile to re-examine the tension between external
agents paid for by NGOs and local volunteers with respect to the effect
of the differences on the process of &quot;accompaniment&quot; that is
at the heart of many NGO programs.</p>

<p><b>Implications for further study and experimentation</b></p>

<p>1. The role of fathers in childrearing merits further study, including
study of the actual role and of the process that leads to his marginal
involvement.</p>

<p>2. The area of psycho-social development should be treated more systematically.
For instance, the theme of &quot;stimulation&quot; should be examined not
only in relation to play and the presentation of stimuli such as colors,
but also in terms of the stimulation that occurs (or does not) in relation
to the practices of feeding, carrying, bathing, etc.</p>

<p>3. Relatively little information was found in the studies reviewed about
the communication between young children and those who care for them. When
there are results, these seem to identify a pattern of neglect. Given the
apparent delay in linguistic development for many children, systematic
study is required.</p>

<p>4. The topic of child abuse came out in all of the studies even though
this was not originally included as a topic for study. Even recognizing
that the topic is a difficult one, it seems critical to try and quantify
the problem and to study causes.</p>

<p>5. Related to the previous point is the theme of alcoholism. The development
and testing of materials dealing with that topic should be undertaken and
activities should be developed to try and deal with this widespread problem
affecting the early development of children.</p>

<p>6. Older children. The experience in the Mexican case study with older
children in communities suggests that it would be worthwhile to experiment
in programs of the &quot;Child-to-Child&quot; type with activities focussed
on childrearing practices. </p>

<p>7. The search for pertinent information contained in secondary sources
ought to be extended to bibliographies and other sources not included in
Phase II that might illuminate the &quot;why&quot; of certain patterns
and practices.</p>

<p>Attachment 1</p>

<p>Lista de Estudios: Fase II</p>

<p>Bonilla O., Yadira y Servio Ru&iacute;z Dinarte, &quot;Informe de Investigaci&oacute;n:
</p>

<p>Pautas y Pr&aacute;cticas de Crianza en Ni&ntilde;os Cero a Cinco A&ntilde;os
de El Salvador,&quot; El Salvador, Centro Coordinador de Evangelizaci&oacute;n
