<p>DESCO, Unidad de Desarrollo y Proyectos, &quot;Pautas y Pr&aacute;cticas
de Crianza de Ni&ntilde;os de 0 a 6 A&ntilde;os de Zonas Urbano-Marginales
y Rurales,&quot; Lima, Per&amp;;, DESCO, Junio de 1992.</p>

<p>_________________, &quot;Sintesis Anal&iacute;tica de la Investigaci&oacute;n
Bibliogr&aacute;fica, Informe Final,&quot; Lima, Per&amp;;, DESCO, Enero
de 1992.</p>

<p>L&oacute;pez Rivera, Oscar A. &quot;San Jose Nacahuil, Guatemala: Las
Pautas y Pr&aacute;cticas de Crianza de los Ni&ntilde;os Menores de Cinco
A&ntilde;os. Informe presentado al Centro Coordinador de Evangelizaci&oacute;n
y Realidad Social -- CEDOERS,&quot; San Jos&eacute;, Costa Rica, 6 de Setiembre
de 1992.</p>

<p>Navarro Rojas, Orlando, Nidia Rom&aacute;n y Rafael Alfaro Alpizar,
&quot;Informe Investigaci&oacute;n sobre Pr&aacute;cticas de Crianza en
Ni&ntilde;os de Cero a Cinco A&ntilde;os: Costa Rica,&quot; San Jos&eacute;,
Costa Rica, Centro Coordinador de Evangelizaci&oacute;n y Realidad Social
(CEODERS), Agosto de 1992.</p>

<p>Roloff, Gerardo, Pilar Nu&ntilde;uz y Juan V&aacute;sconez, &quot;Pr&aacute;cticas
de Crianza del Ni&ntilde;o Peque&ntilde;o en Zonas Rurales y Urbano-Marginales
del Ecuador,&quot;Quito,Ecuador, UNICEF, Setiembre de 1992.</p>

<p>Subirats, Jos&eacute;. et.al., &quot;Pautas y Pr&aacute;cticas de Crianza
Infantil en Comunidades Rurales y Urbanas Marginadas de la Regi&oacute;n
Andina de Bolivia: Informe Final,&quot; La Paz, Bolivia, Centro Boliviano
de Investigaci&oacute;n y Acci&oacute;n Educativas (CEBIAE), Junio de 1992.</p>

<p>Tabora, Rocio, &quot;Informe de Investigaci&oacute;n: Pautas y Pr&aacute;cticas
de Crianza en Ni&ntilde;os de Cero a Cinco A&ntilde;os: Honduras,&quot;
Tegucigalpa, Honduras, Agosto de 1992. <b>[1]</b> The definition of childrearing
<b>patterns</b> used in the study differs from two others that might have
been adopted. One alternative to the normative definition used is to define
patterns statistically, adding up individual practices in order to identify
the most common practice for a group (which would then be labled as characteristic
of the group) or looking at the statistical distribution of practices labeling
that as a &quot;pattern.&quot; Another use of &quot;pattern,&quot; not
adopted in this study, is defined by looking at the ways in which practices
responding to different needs cluster or group together. Clusters occur
because practices evolve together within particular settings, because a
child's needs are intertwined, and because the practical choices made to
satisfy one need help to set limits on what it is possible to do to satisfy
another. For instance, the choice of breastfeeding on demand requires a
kind of physical proximity to the mother at all times that scheduled bottle
feeding does not. That requirement affects carrying and sleeping practices.
It may also affect work options and schedules, or vice versa. The physical
closeness of mother to child also permits, or reinforces, a kind of nurturing
that is different from that employed when there is greater physical separation.</p>

<p><b>[2]</b> Maria Eugenia Linares, &quot;Pautas y Practicas de Crianza:
Recopilaci&oacute;n de Informaci&oacute;n de Fuentes Secundarias. Poblaci&oacute;n
Mexicana.&quot; Documento de discusi&oacute;n preparado para El Taller
de Trabajo sobre Pautas y Pr&aacute;cticas de Crianza, Bogot&aacute;, Colombia,
Abril 29-31, 1991. </p>
