<html><body BGCOLOR=00FFFF><head></head><title>World Bank Conference</title><body>
<table><td><IMG SRC=kids.gif></td>
<td><p><p><b><h2>Investing in the Future</H2><Tr><H1>EARLY CHILD DEVELOPMENT</h1></td></table></b>
<basefont=2>  The World Bank's Vice Presidency for Human Capital Development (HCD), together with the Economic Development Institute (EDI), 
          is pleased to annouce a global invitational conference.<br><p>
                    <p>
               <fontsize="+2"><b>R<basefont></b>esearch over the last thirty years has amply demonstrated the 
          benefits derived from enriching the experience of very young 
          children. Children who take part in early childhood programs 
          are far more likely than their less fortunate peers to enter 
          and stay in school, to score better on aptitude tests, to 
          become more valued and better-paid workers, as well as productive members of 
          their community. Dollars spent on early childhood programs 
          further cut down on countries' expenses to alleviate poverty 
          and increase the value gained from dollars spent on later 
          education and training designed to enhance human capital.<br><p>
 
              <fontsize="+2"><b>B<basefont></b>ut while the merit of preschool enrichment programs is now
 well-established, data on the cost-effectiveness of
various programs and methods remain thin.<br><p>
     <fontsize="+2"><b>P<basefont></b>articipants in the Atlanta conference <b>Early Child Development: Investing in the 
          Future</b> will therefore not only discuss the relative and 
          synergistic effects of interventions in health, nutrition, and 
          education but whether these programs are cost-effective.  The 
          conference will introduce participants to the latest research 
          in the field and its implications for programs operating in the 
          context of various economic and social conditions.<br><p>
              <fontsize="+2"><b>U<basefont></b>nder the conference format, presenters will summarize and 
          analyze papers written by experts in the fields of young 
          children's health, nutrition, and education. Following each 
          presentation, participants will be given ample time to discuss 
          with both presenters and authors.<br><p><p><hr noshade width=95%><p><p>
          
          <b><h2>Preliminary Conference Agenda</h2><br><p>
          April 8, 1996</b><br><p>
          <ul><li>Welcome	
          <li>Opening Lunch Address: Armeane M. Choksi, Vice President, Human 
          Capital Development, The World Bank
          <p>
          <li>Keynote Address:  Investing in the Future: Jacques van der 
          Gaag, Adviser, Human Development Department, The World Bank
          <p>
          <li>Session One:  Synergistic Effects of Nutrition, Health, and 
          Education<br>	Papers by Reynaldo Martorell, David Weikart,Don 
          Bundy, and Robert Sternberg  
          <p>
          <li>Session Two: Program Options<br>	Papers by Cigdem Kagitcibasi, 
          Avima Lombard, Moncrieff Cochran, and Judith Evans 
          <p>
          <li>Dinner:"From Survival to Development"<br> Bill Foege, 
          Chairman, The Task Force for Child Survival
          <p><p>
          <b>April 9, 1996</b><p>
          <li>Session One: Cost and Effectiveness of ECD Programs<br>Papers by 
          Steve Barnett, Asher Ben Arieh, and Patricia Olmsted
  <p>        
       <li>Session Two:  Country Examples: Colombia, India, Kenya, 
          Hungary, and the Philippines<br>
          <p>
          <li>Session Three:  Policy Implications<br>	To be determined.
          <p>
          <li>Closing Session<br>To be determined.
<p><p> </li><br>         
          If you are interested in attending or need additional information, 
          please contact Mary Young at the World Bank, e-mail address: 
          <A HREF="MAILTO:MYoung3@WorldBank.org">Myoung3@worldbank.org.
          
          
