                                                         186.4 of 640.3        1336.0  
Subtotal                                                                               

</pre>
<p>
<p>
<p>
Some new Bank initiatives:<p>
	<b>in Africa&#151;</b>a regional sector study on parenting and early child
care in Kenya, Mauritius, and South Africa; an integrated early childhood
services project in Kenya.<p>
	<b>in Asia&#151;</b>policy discussions on integrated early childhood
development projects in Indonesia, the Philippines, and Vietnam.<p>
	<b>in Latin America&#151;</b>a project in Paraguay and Colombia to expand
community and home based day care centers.<p>
	<b>in Middle East&#151;</b>a project requested by the Government of Turkey on
parental education to ready young children for primary school.<p>
<a name="A_Toc310065684"></a><a name="A_Toc310065716"></a><a name="A_Toc310751023"></a><a name="A_Toc314284488"></a><a name="A_Toc315155749"></a><a name="A_Toc315155793"></a><p>
<b>Five Reasons for Investing in Early Childhood Development</b><p>
Problems faced by poor children in their earliest years&#151;such as stunted
mental development and unpreparedness for primary education&#151;lead later to
low achievement, high dropout rates, and functional illiteracy.  Programs that
can tackle these critical deficiencies are fundamental to a child&#146;s
learning and success in life; and research suggests that such programs can
indeed be effective.  <p>
Scientific support.  Scientific research demonstrates that the early years are
critical in the development of intelligence, personality, and social behavior.
50 percent of intelligence potential is developed by age four.  The impact of
early childhood development programs on personality and behavior is
long-lasting.<p>
<b>Socio-economic rationale</b>.  Early childhood education can increase the
return on primary and secondary school investments.  It can raise
participants&#146; productivity and income levels and reduce public
expenditures.  It can also reduce social costs in such areas as school
repetition, juvenile delinquency,
and drug use.<p>
<b>Social equity rationale</b>.  Investing in human capital, especially in
early development, attacks some of the most entrenched causes of poverty.
Providing a &#147;fair start&#148; can modify distressing socio-economic and
gender-related inequities.  Girls can  be particularly important beneficiaries.
Studies from diverse cultures show that girls who participate in early
childhood programs are more likely to attend and to continue in school.  They
are better prepared for school and parents change their expectations, allowing
girls to continue their education for longer periods.  Moreover, early
childhood development programs can help increase primary school attendance
where older siblings, generally girls,  have been forced to drop out of school
to help take care of their younger brothers and sisters. <p>
<b>Program efficacy rationale</b>.  The success of other programs (for example,
survival programs emphasizing health and nutrition or primary education, or
programs for women in development) can be enhanced by incorporating early
childhood interventions focused on healthy mental and social development.
Sound psycho-social development increases the chances of survival, makes
educational programs more efficient by reducing repetition.<p>
<b>Intersecting needs of women and children</b>.  Female participation in the
labor force throughout the developing world in both formal and informal sectors
is substantial and increasing.  And more and more households are headed by
women.  The need for safe child care has correspondingly grown.  Making child
care available can increase the productivity and earnings of both self-employed
women and those engaged in agriculture, as well as opening up opportunities for
women for addit
ional
learning and education.<b>  
</b><p>
<b>Freestanding Early Childhood Development Projects</b><p>
Projects on early childhood development have several different, though
complementary,  objectives; these in turn, call for different designs and are
directed towards different participants.  As well as delivering services to
children, projects are designed to educate caregivers, and to inform and
persuade the public of  the need for interventions.  Some projects concentrate
on one of these interventions, others combine them.<p>
<b><i>1.	Delivering Services to Children
</a></i></b>
<p>
<p>
<b>Colombia Community Child Care and Nutrition Project.
</a></b>
<p>
The Colombia program of &#147;Homes of Well-Being&#148; is a large-scale,
community-based response to malnutrition and delayed development that plagues
many of the country&#146;s five  million children under the age of six.
Children under six are cared for in groups of  fifteen  in homes in their own
neighborhoods. As well as meeting the care and development needs of the
children, the program improves the community&#146;s economic base by providing
paid employment to neighborhood caregivers, by freeing other women to seek (or
upgrade) employment, and by directing funds to local businesses for economic
activities related to the home day care (for example, improving homes,
supplying food).<p>
The program is firmly based in the community.  Community members participate in
an initial analysis of the needs for services, taking into account the
children&#146;s ages, family income and employment, and physical and
environmental variables.  If services are needed that the program cannot
provide,  connections are made with other organizations that can assist. The
community also decides how many homes are needed, and selects local women to
become home day care mothers.  A board of parents is responsible for local
management of  purchases and payments to the community mothers.<p>
This innovative program has responded to a substantial demand for home-based
child care centers in low-income neighborhoods in urban areas.  The program has
evolved from a pilot scale in 1987 to a national level,  reaching close to 0.8
million children by 1994.  It has become the flagship program of the Colombian
Institute of Family Welfare.  Funding comes from a payroll tax levied on all
Colombian businesses, with additional support, for project evaluation and for
nutritional supplementation through  a loan from the World Bank.<p>
The lessons learned in the Colombian project are being applied in Bolivia.
Bolivia&#146;s <b>Integrated Child</b> <b>Development Project</b>, which is
supported by the Bank, USAID, and public and private donors, targets poor
households in urban and semi-urban areas with populations over 10,000.   By the
end of its sixth year, 1999, the project is to have installed about 9,000
day-care centers to provide non-formal, home-based, integrated child
development services to over 200,000 children aged six months to six years
annually, or about 16 percent of all children living in urban areas.  An
estimated 16,000 pregnant women will be direct beneficiaries, either as
caregivers or as mothers of  children in day care centers. <p>
Special features of the Bolivian project are: <ul>
	a built-in system for evaluating impact through the Integrated Household
Survey, which will compare outcomes for participants and non-participants;
and<br>
	a high supervision ratio of one supervisor to 10 centers.<br>
</ul>
<b><i>2.	Educating caregivers 
</a></i></b>
<p>
<p>
<b>Mexico Initial Education Project.
</a></b>
<p>
This  project targets the most disadvantaged population groups in rural and
urban areas in ten states in Mexico.  It aims to improve quality and efficiency
of non-formal initial education through educating parents in home-based
childrearing practices.  The project centers on training about 900,000 parents
through periodic group meetings and home visits.  The training is done by
community educators, who are locally selected and paid a stipend; each works
with 20 families.  Teaching materials will include comprehensive illustrated
guidebooks and other educational materials to teach skills for caring and
stimulating children for cognitive, psychosocial, and social development, and
to provide basic education in health and nutrition.  Radio programs,
promotional and educational, are broadcast regularly by local stations to
advertise the project and motivate families to participate.  The project
finances training, design, and production of education and audiovisual
materials, and technical assistance to design an educational data and
evaluation system.  Even though children under three are the intended
beneficiaries,  they do not participate directly in the educational activities,
except during the home visits.  The parents are the direct participants in the
project.<p>
<p>
<b><i>3.	Creating Awareness and Demand
</a></i></b>
<p>
<p>
<b>Nigeria Development Communications Project.
</a></b>
<p>
Targeted to preschool children aged three to six in rural and urban areas, the
Nigeria Project pilots the use of mass media in early childhood development.
It will reach four million preschoolers of whom 36 percent already have access
to television.  For those who do not, access will be provided in child care
centers in fifteen local government authorities in ten states. <p>
The project supports:
<ul>
	the design, production, dissemination, and evaluation of instructional
materials to preschoolers and women; and <br>
	the development of institutions to produce materials and to manage and
evaluate educational television.<br>
</ul>
Instructional materials are disseminated by distributing videos through network
transmission, &#147;video on wheels,&#148;  and local viewing centers. The
newly established Educational Television Unit of the Nigerian Television
Authority will produce 130 episodes for preschool children with topics
including development of language expression and comprehension; skills to
observe, explore, and solve problems; prenumeracy, preliteracy, and social
behavior skills; and basic health and hygiene.<p>
<b><i>4.	Integrated Approach
</a></i></b>
<p>
<p>
<b>India&#146;s First and Second Integrated Child Development Projects</b>, the
largest program in the world,  illustrate the power of political commitment to
achieve significant rates of coverage for children under six.  These two
Bank-assisted projects are intended to reach about seventeen million preschool
children and seven million pregnant and nursing women in four States: Andhra
Pradesh, Orissa, Madhya Pradesh, and Bihar.   The goals of the projects are to
provide a range of basic services to children, to expectant and nursing
mothers, and to other women aged fifteen to forty five; to create a mechanism
at the village level through which the services can be delivered; and to give
priority to India&#146;s low-income groups, including the scheduled tribes and
castes.  The two projects work through a network of Anganwadi
(&#147;Courtyard&#148;) Centers, each run by an Anganwadi Worker and helper,
usually selected from the local village. The Anganwadi workers provide
non-formal pre-school education, supplementary feeding, health and nutrition
education, parenting education through homevisiting, and maternal and child
health referrals.  The projects use existing services of diverse governmental
departments and of voluntary agencies, but overall administration
responsibilities lie with the Department of Women and Child Development within
the Ministry of Human Resources Development.  <p>
<b>India Second Tamil Nadu Integrated Project</b>.  This is one of the best
examples of  add-on programs which  not only enhance the development of young
children, but empower women.  It now reaches two million women and five million
children under three in 20,000 villages of this southern Indian State.  The
project objectives are to provide essential nutrition and health services to
pregnant women and young children, to educate caregivers, and to create
awareness and increase public demand for the services.  Community nutrition
workers were trained to provide services to children including monitoring child
growth, food and vitamin A supplementation, and deworming.   They teach mothers
and other caretakers on topics such as nutrition, breastfeeding and weaning,
diarrhea control and oral rehydration. The community nutrition workers are
carefully trained and supervised to help women in the community to form support
groups. These Women&#146;s Groups assist in spreading messages and encouraging
resistant mothers and caretakers to avail themselves of the services.  Many
groups also began food processing operations that not only provided
supplemental food for the nutrition program but gave women additional income
and employment opportunities as well.
<a name="A_Toc310065685"></a><a name="A_Toc310065717"></a><a name="A_Toc310751021"></a><a name="A_Toc314284491"></a><a name="A_Toc315155751"></a><a name="A_Toc315155795"></a><p>
<b>Early Childhood Development Work in Other Social Sector Projects</b><p>
Bank funding for early childhood development components in other social sector
projects has ranged from US$ 4.4 to 62.5 million.  The projects encompass a
broad range of activities, including revising preschool curriculum, expanding
preschools and day care centers,  and improving delivery of basic social
services such as water supply, sanitation, and food.  Some examples include:<p>
Brazil Innovations in Basic Education Project.  The early childhood component
of this project supports development of new curriculum for lower primary
schools, expansion of low cost pre-primary education provided by
municipalities, and reforms in the school health program to emphasize
screening, referral, and health education.  It also assists in developing a
six-year municipal preschool expansion plan.<p>
<b>Venezuela Social Development Project and Ecuador First Social Development
Project. </b>  Contributing to the general objective of establishing a social
safety net are projects to  support social programs including basic education
and health care services.  They finance rehabilitation of  basic health care
networks, expansion of pre-school education, community day care, school
feeding, and nutrition services for pregnant and nursing women and children
under six.<p>
<b>El Salvador Social Rehabilitation Project.  </b>As part of  its work on
poverty alleviation, the project expands coverage of primary health care
programs and pre-primary and primary education. The project is cofinanced with
USAID and UNICEF.<p>
<b>Guyana Health, Water, and Sanitation Project. </b> Designed to assist the
government in cushioning the social costs of the adjustment process,  the
project aims to improve  health and nutrition of women and children, through
financing food supplementation programs for children under five years and for
pregnant and lactating women.  It also finances the  rehabilitation and
equipping of health care centers and day care centers and the construction of
water supply and  sanitation drainage.  Over the medium term, the project as a
whole will assist the government to formulate a sustainable social sector
policy and program.<p>
<b>Chile Primary Education Improvement Project.  </b>In addition to improving
primary education, the project allocates funding to expand preschool education
for about 16,000 urban and 30,000 rural five-year-old children of low-income
urban and rural families.  It trains 23,400 rural parents in early child
stimulation; trains teachers and paraprofessionals;  and provides daily food
rations and learning materials. A study to ascertain the cost-effectiveness of
available preschool options for children&#146;s learning skills is also included.
<a name="A_Toc310065682"></a><a name="A_Toc310065714"></a><a name="A_Toc310751019"></a><a name="A_Toc314284489"></a><a name="A_Toc315155752"></a><a name="A_Toc315155796"></a><p>
<b>Working with NGOs </b><p>
Numerous nongovernmental organizations (NGOs) have actively supported and
implemented early childhood development services in developing countries.
Nongovernmental  involvement has often been a key element in encouraging
community participation. The Bank&#146;s early childhood development projects
would be enriched by more NGO involvement; already,  NGOs have been useful in
assisting regional and local governments to develop the managerial capability
needed to move toward decentralized administration and management&#151;for
example, in several projects such as those in Colombia, Bolivia, and India.  By
making greater use of NGOs, the projects can reduce administration bottlenecks,
therefore reaching  more people more rapidly.  They can also assist in
implementing projects, for example in training of paraprofessionals,
caregivers, and in the monitoring of project progress. 
<a name="A_Toc310751017"></a><a name="A_Toc314284493"></a><a name="A_Toc315155753"></a><a name="A_Toc315155797"></a><p>
<b>The World Bank Group</b><p>
<b></b>The International Bank for Reconstruction and Development (IBRD),
frequently called the &#147;World Bank,&#148; was conceived in July 1944 at the
United Nations Monetary and Financial  Conference in Bretton Woods, New
Hampshire, USA.<p>
The World Bank operates under the authority of a Board of Governors.  Each of
the World Bank&#146;s 178 member countries is represented by one governor, who
is usually a ministerial-level government official.  The Board of Governors
delegates its authority to a small group of representatives, the Board of
Executive Directors, which is based in Washington.  The Board of Executive
Directors is responsible for decisions on policies affecting the World
Bank&#146;s operations and for the overall approval of all loans.  The World
Bank&#146;s president is the chairman of the Board of Executive Directors.<p>
The World Bank has three affiliated institutions:  the International
Development Association (IDA), the International Finance Corporation (IFC) and
the Multilateral Investment Guarantee Agency (MIGA).  The headquarters of the
World Bank and its affiliates are in Washington, D. C.<p>
IBRD	The International Bank for Reconstruction and Development has 178 member
countries as of July 1994.  The interest on World Bank loans to developing
countries changes every six months.  The current rate is 7.27 percent.  Loans
generally have a five-year grace period and must be prepaid during periods
ranging from 15 to 20 years.  In fiscal 1994, which ended on June 30, 1994, the
IBRD approved loans totaling US$14.2 billion for 124 economic development
projects and programs designed to restructure national economies in 44
countries.  Some of the money that the IBRD lends to developing countries comes
from contributions from the institution&#146;s member countries.  But the
majority comes from bonds issued in world financial markets.<p>
<p>
<b>IDA</b>	The International Development Association, established in 1960, has
157 member countries as of July 1994.  The World Bank affiliate provides
no-interest loans to the world&#146;s poorest countries.  Only countries with
annual per capita incomes of less than US$1,305 can borrow from IDA.  However,
most of IDA&#146;s loans are provided to countries with annual per capita
incomes of  US$805 or less.  IDA loans, which are known as &#147;credits,&#148;
have a 10-year grace period and must be repaid in 35 or 40 years (according to
the borrowing country&#146;s credit-worthiness).  In fiscal 1994, IDA approved
credits totaling US$6.6 billion for 104 development projects and economic
restructuring programs in 45 countries.  The money that IDA lends comes as
contributions from wealthier nations, an occasional contribution from the
profits made by the IBRD, and repayments of IDA credits.  Although legally
separate from the World Bank, IDA shares the World Bank&#146;s staff and
facilities.<p>
<p>
<b>IFC</b>	The International Finance Corporation, established in 1956, has 161
member countries as of March 1994.  It promotes economic growth through the
private sector.  Unlike the IBRD, it lends without government guarantees.  The
IFC may also take equity positions in companies to which it lends, play the
role of catalyst to other investors from the private sector, and work to
develop capital markets in developing countries.  In fiscal 1994, this World
Bank affiliate approved US$ 2.5 billion for financing for 231 projects and
other activities carried out by the private sector.<p>
<p>
<b>MIGA</b>	The Multilateral Investment Guarantee Agency, established in 1988,
has 118 member countries as of March 1994.  This affiliate promotes private
investment in developing countries and provides investment guarantees to
protect investors from noncommercial risk.  In fiscal 1994, the total direct
investment associated with the 38 guaranteed projects amounted to  US$1.3
billion.<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<b><i>Population, Health, and Nutrition Department,
</a></i></b>
