<title>EDUCATION DEVELOPMENT CENTER (EDC), INC
</title></head>
<body><h3>EDUCATION DEVELOPMENT CENTER (EDC), INC.</h3>
 
<b>Selected Projects from EDC's Corporate Capability</b>
 <br>
<b><i>International</i></b>
 <br>
<i>ongoing</i>
 <br>
<b><u>EARLY CHILDHOOD DEVELOPMENT FOR INDIGENOUS PEOPLE</u></b> <br>
 
<b>Project Field(s):</b>	Early childhood development, community involvement <br>
<b>Products/Services:</b>	Training, Technical Assistance <br>
<b>EDC Project Director:</b>	Andrea Bosch, Jill Aviles <br>
<b>Funder:</b>	Plan Internacional <br>
<b>Duration:</b>	1995 - 
<b>Location:</b>	Bolivia <br>
 <br>
EDC is developing training materials for adult caregivers and young children
and policy directions for Bolivian decision makers around ECD for use with
Aymara speaking populations nationally.  Some of the interactive radio
instruction materials developed with USAID funds are being adapted for these
people and work is being done to develop strategies for a national plan of
action which coordinated all the groups working in the field of ECD in
Bolivia. <br>
 <br>
 <br>
<b><u>ADVOCACY IN EARLY CHILDHOOD DEVELOPMENT PROJECT</u></b> <br>
 <br>
<b>Project Field(s):</b>	Early childhood development <br>
<b>Products/Services:</b>	Promotional materials for AID 
<b>EDC Project Director:</b>	Andrea Bosch <br>
<b>Funder:</b>	USAID - Global Bureau <br>
<b>Duration:</b>	1995 <br>
<b>Location:</b>	Global - South Africa, Bolivia, India, Romania, Jamaica, and
Croatia <br>
 <br>
Early childhood development activities have been proven to have a positive
impact on children, families, communities and national policies.  While a few
activities have demonstrated how integrated, community-based services promote
sustainable development, there is little knowledge of their existence or
understanding of the basic principles that drive them.  This project introduces
holistic early childhood development concepts, including education, health,
nutrition and delivery systems to an audience of policy makers and implements
and facilitates dialogues around them. <br>
 <br>
A multi-media presentation on early childhood development highlights
USAID-supported activities in South Africa, Bolivia, Nepal, India, Romania,
Jamaica and Croatia.  The video presentations will be used to educate and
increase understanding of early childhood development.  A particular focus is
the intersecting needs between women and children. <br>
<b><u>EARLY CHILD EDUCATION FOR THE RURAL ALTIPLANO</u></b> <br>
 <br>
<b>Project Field(s):</b>	Early childhood development, Families/Parental
Involvement <br>
<b>Products/Services:</b>	Materials Development, Curriculum Development,
Professional Staff Development, Interactive Radio Instruction 
<b>EDC Project Director:</b>	Jill Aviles/Andrea Bosch <br>
<b>Funder:</b>	UNICEF/La Paz <br>
<b>Duration: </b>	1994 - <br>
<b>Location:</b> 	Bolivia, Ecuador <br>
 <br>
UNICEF and EDC are working together to adapt educational materials developed by
EDC for Quechua speaking populations in rural Bolivia.  An anthropologist and
linguist are working closely with an EDC team of early childhood development
specialists to produce the active learning interactive radio instruction
curriculum and conduct formative evaluation with primary caregivers, parents
and children.  The integrated curriculum introduces health and educational
information and professional information about running an integrated early
childhood development program.  These programs will also be used in Ecuador. <br>
 <br>
<b><u>EARLY CHILDHOOD DEVELOPMENT AND THE MEDIA:  SOUTH AFRICA</u></b> <br>
 
<b>Project Field(s):</b>	Early childhood development, Health, Families/Parental
Involvement <br>
<b>Products/Services:</b>	Technical Assistance, Training, Curriculum
Development 
<b>EDC Director:</b>	Andrea Bosch <br>
<b>Funder:</b>	USAID/Pretoria <br>
<b>Duration:</b>	1994 - <br>
<b>Location:</b>	South Africa <br>
 <br>
As South Africa changes to address the needs of black South Africans, new
opportunities to meet the needs associated with early childhood development.
In this three prong project, EDC is working with local NGOs to develop methods
to support integrated early childhood development.  1) EDC is providing
technical assistance to 10 training NGOs which work in the area of early
childhood development and designing a program which will use health clinics,
center and home-based programs and the media together to train parents and
caregivers in early childhood development practice.  2)  EDC is also providing
a series of workshops to teach learning theory and share ideas in the field. 3)
EDC is also piloting an educational curriculum in Zulu in two regions: the PWV
and Natal.   <br>
 <br>
 <br>
<b><u>SOUTH AFRICA ACTIVE LEARNING NETWORK</u></b> <br>
 
<b>Project Field(s):</b>	Early childhood development, Active Learning
Capacity <br>
<b>Products/Services:</b>	Training, Interactive Radio Instruction
(IRI) 
<b></b>EDC Project Director:	Bonnie Kittle <br>
<b>Funder:</b>	USAID PVO Office <br>
<b>Duration:</b>	1994 - 1997 <br>
<b>Location:</b>	South Africa <br>
 <br>
In the REX/South Africa Project, EDC is working with a network of local NGOs to
demonstrate the links between nutrition, deparasitation and education in their
efforts to support over 800 early child development programs in the rural
Natal/Kwazalu region.  EDC is training these organizations to help them develop
new interventions and approaches to enhance the active learning capacity of
young children by increasing attention to micro-nutrients, nutrition, and
health inputs. <br>
 <br>
 <br>
<b><u>NEW EDUCATIONAL OPPORTUNITIES (NEO)</u></b> <br>
 
<b>Project Field(s):</b>	Early childhood development, Health, Nutrition <br>
<b>Products/Services:</b>	Evaluation, Technical Assistance, Training, Materials
Development 
<b>EDC Project Director:</b>	Andrea Bosch 
<b>Funder:</b>	American Jewish World Service <br>
<b>Duration:</b>	1993 - 1997 <br>
<b>Location:</b>	Guatemala <br>
 <br>
The NEO project provides an integrated approach to improving the quality of
preschool and primary school education in Guatemala by focusing on child
health, environmental health, community empowerment, and social factors that
enhance and support education. <br>
 <br>
EDC responsibilities include designing the evaluation process, providing
technical assistance to support documentation of project activities, developing
and implementing nutrition-related interventions, and training local project
staff in nutrition and health-related issues.  The EDC evaluation of the NEO
project is based on an action research model which measures the change in
indicators and findings over time.  Some factors affecting the Active Learning
Capacity of children include nutritional levels, parasitation, general health,
the school environment, and parental attitudes. <br>
  <br>
The objectives for health-related interventions include reducing the incidence
of Vitamins A and C, iron and iodine deficiencies, parasitation, the number of
children who suffer from visual and auditory impairments and increasing the
knowledge and improving the practices of schoolchildren in the areas of
nutrition, hygiene and health. <br>
 <br>
 <br>
<b><u>PARTNERSHIP FOR CHILD DEVELOPMENT</u></b> <br>
 <br>
<b>Project Field(s):</b>	Early childhood development, Nutrition, Health <br>
<b>Products/Services:</b>	Technical Assistance 
<b>EDC Project Director:</b>	Beryl Levinger <br>
<b>Funder:</b>	Rockefeller Foundation and the United Nations Development
Programme, with additional support from the World Health Organization, the Edna
McConnell Clark Foundation, and the James S. McDonnell Foundation <br>
<b>Duration: </b>	1993 -  
<b>Location:</b>	Global - Colombia, Ghana, Indonesia, Tanzania, Jamaica, and
several other countries	 <br>
 <br>
EDC is providing technical assistance to the Partnership for Child Development,
a joint venture of donor agencies, participating governments, and technical
institutions concerned with the relationship between health and school success.
The Partnership is carrying out research on a program that gives micronutrient
supplements to children, treats them for intestinal parasites with the drug
anthelmintic, and offers community-centered health education.  Colombia, Ghana,
Indonesia, Tanzania, Jamaica, and several other countries are expected to
participate in the program.  In each country, a pilot program will reach
between 50,000 and 100,000 children and will result in new information on how
health programs can contribute to learning outcomes for children in the
developing world. <br>
 <br>
<b><u>INTERACTIVE EDUCATION FOR EARLY CHILDHOOD DEVELOPMENT IN
BOLIVIA</u></b> <br>
 
<b>Project Field(s):</b>	Early childhood development <br>
<b>Products/Services:</b>	Materials Development, Interactive Radio Instruction,
Training 
<b>EDC Project Director:  </b>Andrea Bosch 
<b>Funder:</b>	USAID (LearnTech) <br>
<b>Duration:</b>	1993 - 1994 
<b>Location:</b>	Bolivia <br>
 <br>
EDC is working with the Bolivian NGO, ONAMFA (Organismo Nacional del Menor
Mujer y Familia), to prepare early childhood materials to help caregivers learn
how to conduct developmentally appropriate activities.  A pilot project was
done to assess the effectiveness of audio-cassettes, games, stories and posters
in inspiring learning in children under the age of six and their caregivers.
EDC developed <i>Jugando en el Pidi</i>, an interactive radio program designed
for use with young children in child care centers serving children under the
age of six.  In Bolivia these are known as PIDIS (Programa Integrado por
Desarrollo Infantil).  The PIDI centers operate under ONAMFA through a World
Bank loan.  The interactive radio project was conceived of as a way to provide
appropriate learning for both the children and the teachers and to foster
interaction between them.  The curriculum has recently become integrated into
the national education curriculum for the PIDI project. <br>
 <br>
 <br>
<b><u>MULTI-CHANNEL LEARNING; THE EDC-INNOTECH CONNECTION</u></b> <br>
 
<b>Project Field(s):</b>	Primary School Education, Multi-channel Learning <br>
<b>Products/Services:</b>	Technical Assistance<b>  </b> <br>
<b>EDC Project Director:</b>	Stephen Anzalone <br>
<b>Funder:</b>	UNICEF, USAID <br>
<b>Duration:</b>	1994 -  <br>
<b>Location:</b>	The Philippines <br>
 <br>
EDC and INNOTECH have been collaborating during the past two years in
developing and applying the concept of multi-channel learning.  The Philippines
Department of Education, Culture and Sports, UNICEF, and INNOTECH  are working
with IMAGE in developing multi-channel learning activities in the Philippines.
The first area of collaboration will be developing and testing a multi-channel
learning approach that will aim at providing the means for students living in
the areas of &#147;incomplete&#148; primary schools to finish fifth and sixth
grade.  In the Philippines, fully one third of all primary schools are
classified as &#147;incomplete.&#148; <br>
 <br>
 <br>
<b><u></u></b> <br>
<b><u>ACTION GROUP FOR SCHOOL NUTRITION</u></b> <br>
 
<b>Project Field(s):</b>	Health, Nutrition, Primary School Education 
<b>Products/Services:  </b>	Technical Assistance 
<b>EDC Project Director:  </b>Ronald C. Israel <br>
<b>Funder:</b>	USAID, UNICEF, The World Bank, World Food Programme 
<b>Duration: </b>	1992 - 
<b>Location:</b>	Global - Bolivia, Ecuador, Burkina Faso, Kenya, and the
Philippines <br>
 <br>
Finding ways to improve the health status and educational achievement of
elementary school students is a global challenge.  The Action Group for School
Nutrition and Health is a working group of donor agencies which have agreed to
collaborate to support operational activities in developing countries.  The
Action Group is concerned with projects that demonstrate the extent to which
school nutrition and health interventions can have an impact on primary school
educational outcomes.  Members of the Action Group include CIDA, UNICEF, USAID,
the World Bank, and the World Food Programme. EDC staff serve as senior
advisors to the Action Group, and EDC carries out a Secretariat function for
the consortium.  In this role, EDC is charged with coordinating the design and
implementation of country projects;  keeping the Action Group appraised of new
and noteworthy development in the field; and developing technical reports and
position papers.  The Action Group has recently decided to initiate projects in
Bolivia, Ecuador, Burkina Faso, Kenya, and the Philippines. <br>
 <br>
 <br>
<b><u>WOMEN AND INFANT NUTRITION SUPPORT PROJECT (WINS)</u></b> <br>
 <br>
<b>Project Field(s):</b>	Health, Nutrition, Maternal and Child Health <br>
<b>Products/Services:</b>	Technical Assistance, Training 
<b>EDC Project Director:</b>Bibi Essama <br>
<b>Funder:</b>	USAID	 <br>
<b>Duration:</b>	1990 - 1995	 <br>
<b>Location:</b>	Global - Niger, Nigeria, Bolivia, Uganda, Burkina Faso, Togo,
Zambia <br>
 <br>
The Women and Infant Nutrition Support (WINS) Project assists developing
countries in their efforts to improve infant feeding practices and reduce
malnutrition in women and young children.  The project provides a range of
services to host-country nutrition and primary health care projects.  In order
to promote sound growth and development, the WINS Project addresses the entire
continuum of nutritional needs from birth through three years of age, i.e., the
period of exclusive breast-feeding and the complete transition to the family
diet.  WINS also concentrates on meeting the nutritional needs of women before
and during pregnancy and lactation, and supporting women and families to meet
the nutritional needs of their children. <br>
 <br>
 <br>
<b><u>WOMEN AND INFANT NUTRITION SUPPORT PROJECT (WINS):  BOLIVIA</u></b> <br>
 <br>
<b>Project Field(s):</b>	Health, Nutrition, Maternal and Child Health <br>
<b>Products/Services:</b>	Technical Assistance, Training 
<b>EDC Project Director:</b>	Bibi Essama <br>
<b>Funder:</b>	USAID  (WINS)	 <br>
<b>Duration:</b>	1993  	 <br>
<b>Location:</b>	Bolivia <br>
 <br>
Under the WINS Project, EDC provided technical assistance to USAID/Bolivia's
food security program in improving the monitoring an evaluation of USAID funded
food security activities at the national and household levels.  The project
incorporated a food security component into USAID's Urban Food for Work
Program. <br>
 <br>
 <br>
<b><u>WOMEN AND INFANT NUTRITION SUPPORT PROJECT (WINS): NIGERIA</u></b> <br>
 <br>
<b>Project Field(s):</b>	Health, Nutrition, Maternal and Child Health <br>
<b>Products/Services:</b>	Technical Assistance, Training 
<b>EDC Project Director:</b>	Bibi Essama <br>
<b>Funder:</b>	USAID (WINS)	 <br>
<b>Duration:</b>	1993 <br>
<b>Location:</b>	Nigeria <br>
 <br>
The WINS Project's program in Nigeria addressed the need for a better, higher
nutrient weaning food to improve the nutrition status of weaning-age children.
In collaboration with local and international NGOs and Nigerian government
agencies, EDC provided technical assistance to the Temitope Biscuit Industry, a
Nigerian private sector food manufacturer, in developing and marketing a
commercial weaning food called &#147;Joyvita.&#148;   It is composed of
indigenous raw materials, distributed through traditional market vendors, and
within the financial reach of the low income population. <br>
 <br>
 <br>
<b><u>WOMEN AND INFANT NUTRITION SUPPORT PROJECT (WINS): TOGO</u></b> <br>
 <br>
<b>Project Field(s):</b>	Health, Nutrition, Maternal and Child Health <br>
<b>Products/Services:</b>	Technical Assistance, Training 
<b>EDC Project Director:</b>	Bibi Essama <br>
<b>Funder:</b>	USAID (WINS)	 <br>
<b>Duration:</b>	1992 - 1993	 <br>
<b>Location:</b>	Togo <br>
 <br>
WINS provided technical support to a local NGO, the Association Togolaise
Groupe Nutrition (ATGN), in their efforts to address micronutrient deficiencies
in women and young children, specifically to control vitamin A and iodine
deficiencies and to reduce anemia in women and preschool children.  This
project was part of a USAID-funded Child Survival and Population Project. <br>
 <br>
<b><u>REX (REACHING THE EDUCATIONALLY EXCLUDED):  BOLIVIA</u></b> <br>
 
<b>Project Field(s):</b>	Early childhood development, Active Learning
Capacity <br>
<b>Products/Services:</b>	Training, Materials Development, Interactive Radio
Instruction 
<b>EDC Project Director:</b>	Andrea Bosch <br>
<b>Funder:</b>	USAID 
<b>Duration:</b>	1994 - 1997 <br>
<b>Location:</b>	Bolivia <br>
 <br>
REX/Bolivia is designed to improve the links between psychosocial support for
and health/nutrition status of children under the age of six by providing
training to caregivers, parents and children.  The population served in Bolivia
is predominantly periurban.  REX/Bolivia takes a highly successfully EDC pilot
project now ongoing, and augment and expand it.  The results will be improved
Active Learning Capacity for 12,500 young children, and training and continuing
support for 1,200 caregivers on how to put child development theory into
practice and guide interactive educational activities.  To help fill the gap in
the nationwide home-based integrated child development program now being
implemented with World Bank funding, REX will develop audio programs
distributed on cassettes using interactive radio instruction (IRI), posters and
a guide for follow-up activities to be used in training of trainers and direct
interaction with children. <br>
 <br>
 <br>
<i>completed</i> <br>
 <br>
<b><u>RESOURCE HANDBOOK ON INTEGRATED EARLY CHILDHOOD DEVELOPMENT</u></b> <br>
 
<b>Project Field(s):</b>	Early childhood development <br>
<b>Products/Services:</b>	Resource Handbook <br>
<b>EDC Project Director:</b>	Beryl Levinger, Cornelia Janke <br>
<b>Funder:</b>	World Bank <br>
<b>Duration:</b>	1995 <br>
<b>Location:</b>	Global <br>
 <br>
EDC has designed a Resource Handbook on the Design, Implementation and
Evaluation of Integrated early childhood development programs to be used by
Task Managers at the World Bank.  Jointly with other initiatives, this effort
will contribute to the World Bank's Office of Population, Health and
Nutrition's Fiscal Year 1995 Work Plan.  This is the first of a number of
similar papers that EDC will prepare for the World Bank. <br>
 <br>
<b><u>ECD IN THE NEWLY INDEPENDENT STATES</u></b> <br>
 
<b>Project Field(s):</b>	Early childhood development 
<b>Products/Services:</b>	Technical Assistance, Training 
<b>Project Director:</b>	Joanne Brady <br>
<b>Funder:</b>	Soros Foundation <br>
<b>Duration:</b>	1994 - 1995 <br>
<b>Location:</b>	Romania, Russia, Ukraine, Bulgaria, Macedonia, Albania,
Belarus, Croatia, the Czech Republic, Estonia, Hungary, Kyrghyzstan, Lithuania,
Moldova, Slovakia and Slovenia. <br>
 <br>
EDC staff provided direct training and technical assistance to NGOs in several
NIS countries which are exploring how to adapt the Head Start model for their
own early childhood development programs. The training and technical assistance
stressed integrated child development practices and inter-institutional
linkages to reach their goals.  Teams of NIS trainers were trained in
Washington and then EDC staff went to Romania to follow-up with training for
all these countries. <br>
 <br>
 <br>
<b><u>JAMAICA SOCIAL SECTOR SUPPORT PROJECT</u></b> <br>
 
<b>Project Field(s):</b>	Early childhood development, Education Administration,
Curriculum Development, Information Management 
<b>Products/Services:</b>	Training, Evaluation, Technical Assistance <br>
<b>EDC Project Director:</b>	Lola McKinley <br>
<b>Funder:</b>	World Bank <br>
<b>Duration:</b>	1990 - 1994 <br>
<b>Location:</b>	Jamaica <br>
 <br>
The objective of the Government of Jamaica's Social Sectors Development Project
was to improve the efficiency, delivery, and management of social services.
EDC staff provided technical assistance in educational administration, testing
and measurement, and information systems.  EDC also developed and administered
overseas fellowship training programs for Ministry of Education staff in
curriculum design, early childhood education, educational administration,
guidance and counseling, computer-based management information systems,
technical and vocational education, special education, and program
evaluation. <br>
 <br>
 <br>
<b><u>PRIMARY HEALTH CARE LEADERSHIP TRAINING PROJECT</u></b> <br>
 
<b>Project Field(s):</b>	Health Education, Leadership Development <br>
<b>Products/Services:</b>	Training, Materials Development 
<b>EDC Project Director:</b>	Charles Deutsch <br>
<b>Funder:</b>	World Health Organization <br>
<b>Duration:</b>	1987 - 1993 <br>
<b>Location:</b>	Global <br>
 <br>
In developing countries, and increasingly in industrialized nations as well,
health care and health education are conducted primarily by community health
workers.  villagers are given technical training in how to weigh and immunize
babies, teach family planning, demonstrate oral rehydration techniques, or
perform similar health care functions.  However, they are rarely trained in
human relations, communications, and leadership skills, which will enable them
to influence behavior changes in families and communities.  To build these
skills, EDC has developed a training manual for community health workers and a
second manual for their supervisors.  The materials are based on the assumption
that the ultimate success of the primary health care system depends on how each
health worker treats each client each day.  The manuals have been tested and
revised and used in a training workshop in Kenya.  The manuals are distributed
through the World Health Organization. <br>
 <br>
 <br>
<b><u>STRENGTHENING SCHOOL NUTRITION AND HEALTH IN THE AMERICAS</u></b> <br>
 
<b>Project Field(s):</b>	Nutrition, Health 
<b>Products/Services:</b>	Technical Assistance, Newsletter<b> </b> <br>
<b>EDC Project Director:</b>  Ronald C. Israel, Meg Wilcox 
<b>Funder:</b>	Pew Charitable Trusts; Pan American Health Organization 
<b>Duration:</b>	1990 - 1993 
<b>Location:  </b>	Latin America <br>
 <br>
EDC carried out a series of activities to prepare for a hemisphere-wide program
in school nutrition and health.  The project worked with the Ministry of
Education and Ministry of Health in Honduras to help strengthen school
nutrition and health policies and programs.  It also published <i>Action for
School Nutrition and Health</i>, a regional newsletter for policy makers and
programs managers that provided information about innovative school health
programs and intervention options available to improve health and learning. <br>
 <br>
 <br>
<b>Social Marketing in Health: Curriculum Design and Training Project</b>  <br>
 <br>
<b>Project Field(s):</b>	Health; Social marketing <br>
<b>Products/Services:</b>	Training <br>
<b>EDC Project Director:</b>	Ronald C. Israel <br>
<b>Funder:</b>	Unesco <br>
<b>Duration:</b>	1984 - 1992 <br>
<b>Locations:</b>	Africa and Asia <br>
 <br>
EDC produced a set of curriculum guidelines for teaching a social marketing
approach to health education.  The materials focus on case examples from family
planning, nutrition, and high blood pressure education campaigns, as well as
the links between nutrition and the environment. They are intended for use by
faculty at schools of public health in Asia and by health education
practitioners in Africa. <br>
 <br>
 <br>
<b><u>WHO/UNESCO/UNICEF: EXPERT CONSULTATION ON STRATEGIES FOR IMPLEMENTING
COMPREHENSIVE SCHOOL HEALTH EDUCATION PROGRAMS</u></b> <br>
 
<b>Project Field(s):</b>	Health, Health Education<b> </b> <br>
<b>Products/Services:</b>	Materials Development, Technical Assistance, Policy
Document 
<b>EDC Project Director:</b>	Cheryl Vince-Whitman <br>
<b>Funder:</b>	World Health Organization <br>
<b>Duration:</b>	1991 - 1992 <br>
<b>Location:</b>	Global <br>
 <br>
Schools have the potential to reach a billion children worldwide.  Delivering
comprehensive school health education to these children must be a high
priority.  Yet, too few children have access to such programs and their
implementation remains a major challenge throughout the world.  EDC assisted
the WHO by developing background materials and conference documents for a
November 1991 consultation in Geneva, Switzerland.  The conference was attended
by 60 health and education specialists from Africa, Asia, Europe, and North
America and focused on the development of policies and action plans to make
comprehensive school health a priority for children throughout the world.  In
early 1992, EDC prepared a final document, including general principles to
guide action, as well as specific strategies.  It was widely disseminated as a
tool to advance comprehensive school health education on both the international
and individual country levels. <br>
 <br>
 <br>
<b>Vitamin A Supplements Distribution Project</b> <br>
 <br>
<b>Project Field(s):</b>	Child nutrition; Child health <br>
<b>Products/Services:</b>	Technical Assistance <br>
<b>EDC Project Director:</b>	Ronald C. Israel <br>
<b>Funder:</b>	WHO <br>
<b>Duration:</b>	1990 - 1992 <br>
<b>Location:</b>	?? <br>
 <br>
EDC assisted the World Health Organization's Expanded Program for Immunization
in testing a new strategy to incorporate the distribution of Vitamin A
supplements into existing health care delivery systems.  The strategy calls for
children to receive vitamin supplements when they visit their local clinic for
routine immunizations.  EDC helped WHO develop a manual to educate health care
workers about vitamin deficiencies and train them to carry out the new
procedures. <br>
 <br>
<b><u></u></b> <br>
<b><u>SCHOOL NUTRITION AND HEALTH PROJECT</u></b> <br>
 
<b>Project Field(s):</b>	Health, Nutrition 
<b>Products/Services:</b>	Technical Assistance, Research 
<b>EDC Project Director:</b>  Ronald C. Israel <br>
<b>Funder:</b>	Carnegie Corporation, UNESCO 
<b>Duration: </b>	1987 - 1991 
<b>Location:  </b>	Global <br>
 <br>
Since 1987, EDC has been assisting UNESCO in an international school nutrition
and health initiative.  This initiative is aimed at researching the extent to
which the nutrition and health status of primary school students constrains
their academic performance and at assisting ministries of education to improve
their capabilities to assess student nutrition and health needs and to design
effective interventions to address priority problems.  EDC provides technical
assistance and research support to this effort. <br>
 <br>
 <br>
<b>Resources for Child Health (REACH)</b> <br>
 <br>
<b>Project Field(s):</b>	Child Health; Parental Awareness <br>
<b>Products/Services:</b>	Training; Technical Assistance <br>
<b>EDC Project Director:</b>	Mrudula Amin <br>
<b>Funder:</b>	USAID <br>
<b>Duration:</b>	1985 - 1990 <br>
<b>Location:</b>	Bangladesh <br>
 <br>
REACH was designed to lower infant, child, and maternal morbidity by improving
the delivery of key disease control technologies.  EDC was responsible for
social marketing and mass media strategies in Bangladesh.  EDC worked with
Bangladeshi counterparts to design and implement competency-based health
professional training programs and to develop and implement of social marketing
and mass media strategies to promote immunization coverage of vulnerable
populations.  EDC completed a strategy paper, <i>The Use of Education,
Communications, and Training in EPI</i> and had a resident advisor stationed in
Bangladesh to assist the Ministry of Health in developing appropriate social
marketing campaigns. <br>
 <br>
<b>Cameroon Weaning Project</b> <br>
 <br>
<b>Project Field(s):</b>	Child nutrition <br>
<b>Products/Services:</b>	Training; Technical Assistance; Materials <br>
<b>EDC Project Director:</b>	Christine Hollis <br>
<b>Funder:</b>	USAID <br>
<b>Duration:</b>	1985 - 1989 <br>
<b>Location:</b>	Cameroon <br>
 <br>
The Weaning Project used a social marketing approach to improve infant feeding
practices in several villages in the Extreme North Province of Cameroon, which
is marked by great linguistic diversity.  Only 30% of households in the target
area own radios, and most village women have difficulty in understanding
broadcast Fulfulde, the only local language on the radio.  Further, literacy,
particularly among women, is quite low.  As a result, alternative channels of
communication had to be used.  EDC devised a strategy, with associated
&#147;Train the Trainer&#148; activities, that involved frequent and regularly
scheduled visits by community health workers for group discussion sessions,
combined with individual counseling, cooking demonstrations, and usable
pictorial materials. <br>
 <br>
<b><u>ASSESSMENT OF THE MODERN MANAGEMENT TECHNOLOGICAL COMPONENT OF THE
VILLAGE DEVELOPMENT FAMILY SERVICES PROJECT</u></b> <br>
<b><u></u></b> <br>
<b>Project Field(s):  </b>Social Services, Community Development, Management <br>
<b>Product/Services:  </b>Technical Assistance, Evaluation 
<b>EDC Project Director:  </b>Janice Brodman <br>
<b>Funder:</b>	USAID <br>
<b>Duration: </b>	1988 <br>
<b>Location:</b>	Indonesia	 <br>
 <br>
This project had two major goals: (1) to assess the progress and impact of the
Modern Management Technology Component (MMTC) of the Village Development Family
Services Project, within the National Family Planning Agency (BKKBN); (2) to
test an interview and observation instrument as a means for revealing impacts
on decision-making within the BKKBN.  <br>
 <br>
The assignment involved interviewing staff of BKKBN, evaluating the design of
the MMTC, and examining hardware, software, training organizational structure,
communications system, and data management capabilities. The Final Report
provided conclusions regarding the effectiveness of the MMTC, the &#147;key
success factors&#148; contributing to that success, the areas in which the MMTC
required strengthening or redirection of effort, the future needs of the
program, and recommendations for future efforts and allocation of resources. <br>
 <br>
 <br>
<b><u>JAMAICA PRIMARY SCHOOL NUTRITION EDUCATION PROJECT</u></b> <br>
 
<b>Project Field(s):</b>	Nutrition, Primary School Education, Families/Parental
Involvement <br>
<b>Products/Services:</b>	Curriculum Development, Materials Development,
Evaluation  
<b>EDC Project Director:</b>	Christine Hollis <br>
<b>Funder:</b>	UNESCO, USAID <br>
<b>Duration:</b>	1985 - 1987 <br>
<b>Location:</b>	Jamaica <br>
 <br>
The goal of the Jamaica Primary School Nutrition Education Project was to
integrate nutrition education into the existing primary school curriculum,
specifically the language arts sector.  The project was carried out in
collaboration with the Jamaica Ministry of Education, UNESCO, and USAID.  The
project used social marketing techniques to provide formative research and a
planned approach to designing and testing the educational program.  A
community-based approach was also used to involve teachers and parents in the
actual development of innovative curriculum materials.  The reading manual and
support aids designed were as self-explanatory as possible and focused not only
on relevant nutritional concepts but also on realistic and appropriate actions
that students could take to improve their own health behaviors, thereby
becoming &#147;nutrition magicians.&#148; Evaluations showed gains in students'
nutritional knowledge, adoption of better eating habits and strengthened
reading skills. <br>
 <br>
<b><u>INTERNATIONAL NUTRITION COMMUNICATION SERVICE (INCS)</u></b> <br>
 
<b>Project Field(s):</b>	Nutrition, Health, Maternal and Child Health, Health
Education, Community Development <br>
<b>Products/Services:</b>	Training, Technical Assistance, Communications,
Organizational Development, Evaluation 
<b>EDC Project Director:  </b>Ronald C. Israel 
<b>Funder:  </b>	USAID 
<b>Duration:  </b>	1979 - 1986 <br>
<b>Location:</b>	Global - over 30 countries, including Bolivia, Costa Rica,
Honduras, 	Guatemala, Chile, Jamaica, Egypt, Tunisia, Cameroon, Burkina Faso,
Senegal, Kenya, Indonesia, the Philippines, Thailand, Fiji, India, and
Bangladesh <br>
 <br>
For seven years, the INCS program provided technical assistance and project
support to maternal and infant nutrition projects in 42 countries throughout
the Third World.  It focused its educational, communications, and social
marketing skills on improving the health and well-being of low-income families
overseas.  The project successfully undertook a variety of nutrition-education
activities including the organization and implementation of training sessions
in communication skills and nutrition-related topics for staff from ministries
of health, international agencies, and private organizations; the development
of a wide variety of training materials, including a counselors' guide on
breast-feeding; a text and guides for teaching nutrition in schools of
agriculture; a guide to the use of nutrition-related training, mass media, and
other support materials; and the design and implementation of research to
assess factors affecting infant and maternal nutrition behavior. <br>
 <br>
<b><u>IMPROVING BREASTFEEDING PRACTICES IN THAILAND</u></b> <br>
 
<b>Project Field(s):</b>	Nutrition, Health <br>
<b>Products/Services:</b>	Training, Technical Assistance <br>
<b>EDC Project Director:</b>	Ronald C. Israel <br>
<b>Funder:  </b>	USAID <br>
<b>Duration:</b>	1982 - 1985 
<b>Location:</b>	Thailand <br>
 <br>
INCS collaborated with the Faculty of Public Health in Mahidol University on
the design and implementation of a hospital-based breastfeeding promotion
project.  The project resulted in improved breastfeeding support practices in
nine major hospitals where 78% of all births in Bangkok take place. <br>
 <br>
The project began with lactation management workshops for health professional
teams.  As part of their training, each team developed an action plan for
improving infant feeding practices in their hospital.  A series of targeted
infant feeding promotional materials for health professionals and mothers was
developed by a professional advertising agency; a set of infant feeding
guidelines for public health hospitals was issued by the Ministry of Health;
and hospital specific lactation management workshops were organized by those
who already had been trained by the project.   The results of this intensive
eighteen- month effort have been more supportive hospital policies for
breastfeeding mothers.   <br>
 <br>
<b><u>KAREN CULTURAL LEARNING PROGRAM</u></b> <br>
 
<b>Project Field(s):</b>	Natural Resource Management, Community Development,
Cultural Education <br>
<b>Products/Services:</b>	Design/Technical Assistance 
<b>EDC Project Director:</b>	Micael Olsson <br>
<b>Funder:</b>	Biodiversity Conservation Network 
<b>Duration: </b>	1995 
<b>Location: </b>	Thailand <br>
 <br>
EDC has designed and developed a cultural learning program for the Laiwo Karen
living in the Thung Yai Wildlife Sanctuary of Western Thailand that would help
build Karen resolve to maintain cultural practices of sustainable forest
management.  The program would make use of interactive discussion groups led by
traditional elders and provide for a range of cultural reinforcement activities
for young people that would heighten cultural knowledge even as it was being
captured and transcribed.  It would make use of multi-channel language
instruction with Karen concepts of forest biology and resource management to
elevate traditional conservation values.  At the same time, the program would
provide multiple opportunities to strengthen the public's image of the Laiwo
Karen as responsible custodians of the Thung Yai forest. <br>
 <br>
 <br>
<b><u>INDONESIA EDUCATION POLICY AND PLANNING</u></b> <br>
 
<b>Project Field(s):</b>	Education Administration 
<b>Products/Services: </b>	Technical Assistance, Evaluation 
<b>EDC Project Director: </b> Hal Freeman		 <br>
<b>Funder:</b>	USAID <br>
<b>Duration:</b>	1992 
<b>Location:</b>	Indonesia <br>
 <br>
EDC assisted the Government of Indonesia's Department of Education and Culture
and USAID/Jakarta with a final external evaluation of the Education Policy and
Planning Project.  The EPP was designed to improve the quality of education in
Indonesia through the formulation, implementation and monitoring of better
educational policies and long range plans based on more complete and accurate
information and better analysis of that information. <br>
 <br>
<b><u>PAPUA NEW GUINEA:  RADIO SCIENCE PROJECT</u></b> <br>
 
<b>Project Field(s):</b>	Science Education <br>
<b>Products/Services:</b>	Interactive Radio Instruction 
<b>EDC Project Director:</b>	Frank Watson <br>
<b>Funder:</b>	USAID  <br>
<b>Duration:</b>	1986 - 1990 <br>
<b>Location:</b>	Papua New Guinea <br>
 <br>
In 1986, Radio Science Project and the National Department of Education began a
joint operation to develop and test a radio-based science course for grades 4 -
6 based on the PNG official national science curriculum.  The purpose of the
project was to improve science teaching in community (rural) schools, to
increase the children's knowledge of science and to make sure that information
was more interesting and relevant to the children of PNG.  The special
challenge of Radio Science Project was to adapt the interactive radio
methodology to a discipline that requires an inquiry approach.  Radio Science
Project was the first RI project to target student in the upper primary grades.
Since the completion of the Radio Science Project, EDC has maintained ties with
the PNG National Department of Education to assist in broadcasting the
lessons. <br>
 <br>
 <br>
<b><u>THAILAND: RADIO MATHEMATICS LESSONS</u></b> <br>
 
<b>Project Field(s):</b>	Math Education <br>
<b>Products/Services:</b>	Technical Assistance, Interactive Radio
Instruction 
<b>EDC Project Director:</b>	Klaus Galda  
<b>Funder:</b>	World Bank <br>
<b>Duration:  </b>	1980 - 1984 <br>
<b>Location:  </b>	Thailand <br>
 <br>
The goal of the Thai Radio Project was to design programs that would be as
effective in remote rural areas as in the more developed regions.  Broadcasting
began in 1980 when Nicaraguan radio math lessons were translated and adapted to
the Thai curricula and culture.  The Ministry of Education continues to use
interactive radio math at the national level. <br>
 <br>
 <br>
 <br>
<b><u>PAPUA NEW GUINEA COLLEGE OF ALLIED HEALTH SCIENCES</u></b> <br>
 
<b>Project Field(s):</b>	Nutrition, Health Education, Higher Education <br>
<b>Products/Services:</b>	Project Design, Curriculum Development <br>
<b>EDC Project Director:</b> <br>
<b></b>Funder:	USAID <br>
<b>Duration:</b>	1981 
<b>Location:</b>	Papua New Guinea <br>
 <br>
EDC staff helped the Papua New Guinea College of Allied Health Sciences develop
plans for a year-long diploma course in nutrition.  The course combined
classroom and field training and was designed to provide serving nurses,
extension officers, and other with the background needed to provide effective
interventions to improve the quality of nutrition in rural areas. <br>
