 <br>
 <br>
<b><i>Domestic</i></b> <br>
 <br>
<b><u>EXPLORING CHILDHOOD</u></b> <br>
 
<b>Project Field(s):  </b>Early childhood development, Families/Parental
Involvement <br>
<b>Products/Services: </b> Materials Development, Teacher Training 
<b>EDC Project Director:</b>  Marilyn Felt 
<b>Funder:</b>	National Institute for Maternal Health/Office for Child
Development, Busch Foundation 
<b>Duration:</b>	1970 - 1980 <br>
<b>Location: </b>	U.S. <br>
 <br>
This parenting/child development program teaches students about child
development and about themselves while they work closely and regularly with
young children.  Program goals include helping students become competent with
children, understanding how a child sees the world, gaining a sense of the
biological and social forces that influence child development, and exploring
their own identity.  Course materials, which include booklets, films, and
specific learning activities, are adaptable to the needs of learners of varied
cultural backgrounds.  Originally, developed for secondary school students, the
program was tested in over 500 classrooms around the country and has since been
used in over 7,000 school and non-school sites.  Materials developed for the
program such as films <i>Sarah Has Down's Syndrome</i>, filmstrip <i>Children
with Special Needs Go to School</i>, and booklet <i>No Two Alike:  Helping
Children with Special Needs</i> are currently used by Head Start programs,
social service agencies, church groups, parenting centers, hospitals, voluntary
agencies, mental health centers, adult education programs, and other community
groups across the country. <br>
 <br>
<b><u>PROJECT POTENTIAL</u></b> <br>
 
<b>Project Field(s):</b>	Early childhood development, Drug Abuse  
<b>EDC Directors:</b>	Joanne P. Brady, Michael J. Rosati <br>
<b>Funders:</b>	U.S. Department of Health and Human Services, U.S. Department
of Education <br>
<b>Duration:</b>	1991 -  <br>
<b>Location:</b>	U.S. <br>
 <br>
The goal of Project Potential is to provide preschool and elementary teachers
with the resources they need to work effectively with children who have been
exposed to drugs <i>in utero</i> or who continue to be exposed in their homes
and community settings.  EDC has completed development of manuals for
administrators, a monograph, and videotapes with accompanying guides for
teachers in Head Start and elementary schools.  These materials describe what
is known about drug exposure, offer strategies for educating vulnerable
children, and provide a framework for creating a supportive policy environment
for elementary schools and Head Start Programs.  The products were published
and distributed by the sponsoring government agencies in 1994.   <br>
 <br>
 <br>
<b><u>INTERACTIVE VIDEO FOR YOUNG CHILDREN</u></b> <br>
 
<b>Project Field(s):</b>	Early childhood development, Literacy <br>
<b>Products/Services: </b>	Interactive Video 
<b>EDC Project Director:</b>	Cynthia Char <br>
<b>Funder:</b>	American Interactive Media <br>
<b>Duration:</b>	1989 - 1991 <br>
<b>Location:</b>	U.S. <br>
 <br>
Interactive technology offers exciting possibilities for expanding and
enriching young children's emerging literacy experiences in the preschool and
early primary years.  Multimedia systems can offer an environment rich with
moving and still images, sounds (speech, music, and sound effects), and written
text, in which children can play and experiment - constructing their own
meaning and maintaining control over what happens and what is created.  In
conjunction with American Interactive Media (a Philips/Polygram corporation),
EDC has designed a set of interactive video materials for early reading.  Aimed
at four-to-six-year-olds, the discs will run on a new interactive video system,
CDI (Compact Disc Interactive), developed by Philips, Sony and Matsushita for
the consumer market. <br>
 <br>
 <br>
<b><u>JOHNSON &amp; JOHNSON/HEAD START HEALTH EDUCATION PROJECT</u></b> <br>
 
<b>Project Field(s):</b>	Early childhood development, Health Education <br>
<b>Products/Services:</b>	Materials Development, Video 
<b>EDC Project Director:</b>	Margaret Enright <br>
<b>Funder: </b>	Johnson &amp; Johnson <br>
<b>Duration:</b>	1992 -  <br>
<b>Location: </b>	U.S. <br>
 <br>
EDC is working with the Johnson &amp; Johnson/Head Start Health Education
Project to enhance health education and health promotion in Head Start
programs.  The goal of the project is to strengthen comprehensive health
education as a vital part of the preschool experience for Head Start Children,
parents, and staff.  Project staff are completing development of an annotated
resource guide of health education materials for children and adults, a health
education planning and implementation handbook for Head Start management teams,
and a video and promotional package for use by local programs. <br>
 <br>
 <br>
<b><u>CHILD TO CHILD:  MAXIMIZING OPPORTUNITIES FOR SOCIAL
INTEGRATION</u></b> <br>
 
<b>Project Field(s):</b>	Early childhood development, Children with
Disabilities <br>
<b>Products/Services:</b>	Training 
<b>EDC Director:</b>	Joanne Brady <br>
<b>Funder:</b>	U.S. Department of Health and Human Services, Administration for
Children and Families <br>
<b>Duration:</b>	1990 - 1993 <br>
<b>Location:</b>	U.S. <br>
 <br>
A growing number of children with disabilities are served in integrated
settings such as Head Start and child care programs.  These children must learn
the social skills needed to play and interact with their normally developing
peers.  EDC has formed a consortium with 10 other institutions to develop,
pilot-test, and implement a training package for Head Start staff and families.
The curriculum, Child to Child, provides guidance for teachers, administrators,
and parents and offers practical strategies to promote the social integration
of children with disabilities.  The training package has been field-tested
nationally and evaluation data have guided revisions to the materials.  The
Child to Child training program was disseminated nationally by the U.S.
Department of Health and Human Services during 1994. <br>
 <br>
 <br>
<b><u>NEW ENGLAND RESOURCE CENTER FOR TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE AND
SUPPORT</u></b> <br>
 
<b>Project Field(s):</b>	Early childhood development, Education, Health,
Families/Parental Involvement <br>
<b>Products/Services:</b>	Training, Technical Assistance <br>
<b>EDC Project Director:</b>	Sheila Skiffington <br>
<b>Funder:</b>	U.S. Department of Health and Human Services, Administration for
Children and Families <br>
<b>Duration:</b>	1987 -  <br>
<b>Location:</b>	U.S. - New England <br>
 <br>
Head Start's successes are widely known.  The program has changed the lives of
millions of children and families living in poverty and is acclaimed as one of
the most beneficial and cost-effective programs in the country.  The Resource
Center, serving New England's 95 Head Start programs, is part of a national
Head Start training and technical assistance system.  The system provides
intensive on-site technical assistance to management teams and other staff on
education, health, family services, and management issues; offers training
conferences; and assists program staff in planning for organizational change
and program expansion. <br>
 <br>
 <br>
<b><u>RESOURCE ACCESS PROJECT</u></b> <br>
 
<b>Project Field(s):</b>	Early childhood development, Children with
Disabilities 
<b>Products/Services: </b>	Training, Technical Assistance <br>
<b>EDC Project Directors:</b>	Philip H. Printz <br>
<b>Funder:</b>	U.S. Department of Health and Human Services, Administration for
Children and Families <br>
<b>Duration:</b>	1976 -  <br>
<b>Location:</b>	U.S. - New England <br>
 <br>
The New England Resource Access Project (RAP) assists Head Start Programs in a
six-state region, providing them with a range of services to meet the needs of
children with disabilities and their families.  RAP makes materials available
to Head Start staff through its resource library and suggests strategies to
promote collaboration with other local agencies.  Training and on-site
technical assistance are offered to help staff secure needed special services
and create an environment that encourages successful social interaction of
children with disabilities and their families.  Annual conferences, attracting
more than 2,000 Head Start staff, are held in each of the six states served by
RAP. <br>
 <br>
<b>Project GAINS (Gaining Access/Integrating Needed Services)</b> <br>
 <br>
<b>Project Field(s):</b>	Early Childhood Education, Children with
Disabilities <br>
<b>Products/Services:</b>	Training, Technical Assistance, Organizational
Development <br>
<b>Director:</b>	Joanne P. Brady <br>
<b>Funder:</b> 	U.S. Department of Education, Office of Special Education
Programs <br>
<b>Duration:</b> 	1990 - 1993 <br>
<b>Location:</b>	Manchester, New Hampshire <br>
 <br>
EDC, working with the Easter Seal Society of New Hampshire, has designed,
implemented, and evaluated a program in Manchester, N.H., that provides child
care services to children with serious disabilities in regular child care
settings.  This collaborative has created a program model that increases the
number of mainstreamed child care programs within the city of Manchester,
enhances the ability of other communities to serve children with disabilities,
and ensures that child care programs are well-coordinated with special
education services.  The project has provided training to more than 40 child
care staff and 20 foster grandparent volunteers and has developed
implementation materials for national dissemination. <br>
 <br>
<b>National Head Start Disabilities Services Training Center</b> <br>
 <br>
<b>Project Field(s):</b>	Early Childhood Education, Children with
Disabilities <br>
<b>Products/Services:</b>	Training, Materials Development <br>
<b>Director:</b> 	Joanne P. Brady <br>
<b>Funder: </b>	U.S. Department of Health and Human Services, Administration
for Children and Families <br>
<b>Duration:</b> 	1993 - ongoing <br>
 <br>
EDC has launched a national project to develop training materials to support
Head Start&#146;s efforts to serve young children with disabilities and their
families.  Working in a consortium with five other institutions, EDC will take
lead responsibility for designing and publicizing ten training guides over a
four-year period.  During the first phase of the project, staff conducted a
national needs assessment involving key constituents in the Head Start
community.  In phase two, we are developing two guidebooks for Head Start staff
that will be distributed nationally.  In future phases, we will develop and
disseminate an additional eight products on disability services. <br>
 <br>
 <br>
<b>Early Violence Prevention: Tools for Teachers of Young Children</b> <br>
 <br>
<b>Project Field(s):</b>	Early Childhood Education; Violence Prevention <br>
<b>Products/Services:</b>	Handbook; Teacher Training <br>
<b>Director:</b> 	Ron Slaby <br>
<b>Funder: </b>	Florence V. Burden Foundation, A.L. Mailman Family Foundation <br>
<b>Duration:</b> 	1991 - 1995? <br>
 <br>
Preschool, Head Start, and kindergarten teachers can help young children reduce
their aggressive behavior and develop alternative patterns of behavior that
will prevent involvement with violence in later life.  Young people who learn
non-violent ways of solving their social problems will be less likely to
experience harm from violence.  EDC prepared a book for teachers and caregivers
who work with children ages 3 to 7.  The book presents research findings on
effective classroom practices to reduce children&#146;s aggression, prevent
violence, and build skills in resolving conflict constructively.  It provides
teachers with numerous practical strategies for reducing aggressive behavior
and teaching children ways to prevent violence by examining how teachers select
materials, provide role models, respond to children&#146;s behavior, and teach
children the skills they need to solve problems effectively and non-violently.
The book is scheduled for publication in 1994 by the National Association for
the Education of Young Children. <br>
 <br>
<b>Building Effective Partnerships: Training Massachusetts Parent Advisory
Councils</b> <br>
 <br>
<b>Project Field(s):</b>	Early Childhood Education, Children with Disabilities,
Parental Involvement <br>
<b>Products/Services:</b>	Training, Technical Assistance, Videotape <br>
<b>Director:</b>	Peggy Enright <br>
<b>Funder:</b>	Mass. Department of Education <br>
<b>Duration:</b> 	1988 -  1990 <br>
<b>Location:</b>	Massachusetts <br>
 <br>
This project enhanced the capacity of special education Parent Advisory Concils
(PACs) to work cooperatively with school administrators to plan, implement, and
evaluate special education services in their communities.  EDC conducted a
needs assessment and multiple training events for PAC members and school
administrators, provided technical assistance and consultation, identified
groups requiring greater assistance in future years, promoted networking, and
developed a 17-minute videotape, <i>Making the Magic Happen</i>, to illustrate
the advantages of Parent Advisory Councils to school districts. <br>
 <br>
 <br>
<b>National Study of State-

Funded
Preschool Programs</b> <br>
 <br>
<b>Project Field(s):</b>	Early Childhood Education <br>
<b>Products/Services:</b>	National Policy Study <br>
<b>Director:</b>	Joanne Brady <br>
<b>Funder:</b>	U.S. Department of Health and Human Services, Office of Human
Development Services <br>
<b>Duration:</b>	1987 - 1988 <br>
<b>Location:</b>	U.S. Nationwide <br>
 <br>
As part of the New England Resource Center, EDC completed a national policy
study of Head Start's relationship to state-

funded
preschool efforts across the country.  This study was commissioned by ACYF to
examine Head Start's role in the burgeoning state-

funded
preschool movement and to explore existing and possible models of collaboration
between Head Start and providers of these state-

funded
programs.  The project findings have been published in <i>The Challenge of
Coordination</i>, a widely acclaimed report that has been disseminated broadly
to state and federal policymakers. <br>
 <br>
 <br>
<b>Head Start Family Service Center Evaluation</b> <br>
 <br>
<b>Project Field(s):</b>	Early Childhood Education <br>
<b>Products/Services:</b>	Evaluation <br>
<b>Director:</b>	Charles Deutsch <br>
<b>Funder:</b>	U.S. Department of Health and Human Services, Administration for
Children and Family (through a sub-contract) <br>
<b>Duration:</b> 	1991 - ?? <br>
<b>Location:</b>	Massachusetts <br>
 <br>
Head Start has long recognized that helping children means helping their
parents.  In 1990, 13 programs across the country were seleced as demonstration
sites to test a comprehensive Family Service Center approach to serving
children and familieis.  These demonstration sites address substance abuse,
illiteracy, and under-employment and are designed to provide eligible families
with a central location where they can find help for the wide range of problems
they face.  EDC conducted an evaluation of case management methods and
community referral systems for one of these programs in Somerville, Mass. <br>
 <br>
<b>Early Childhood/Generalist Assessment Development Laboratory</b> <br>
 <br>
<b>Project Field(s):</b>	Early Childhood Education <br>
<b>Products/Services:</b>	Development of national standards <br>
<b>Director:</b> 	Joanne Brady; Ingrid Chalufour <br>
<b>Funder:</b> 	National Board for Professional Teaching Standards <br>
<b>Duration:</b> 	1994 -  ongoing <br>
<b>Location:</b>	Nationwide (17 states) <br>
 <br>
EDC has been working with the National Board for Professional Teaching
Standards to develop nationally recognized credential and certification
programs for Early Childhood/Generalist.  Teachers from seventeen states
throughout the United States are now participating in field tests of the
proposed standards and assessment programs.<br><p>
<hr>
