<html>
<head></head>
<title>Third Symposium on Programs of Integrated Child Development in Contexts
of Poverty </title>
<body>
<b>Organisation of American States - Costa Rica, September 25-29, 1995</b><p>
 
	The <i>Third Symposium on Programs of Integrated Child Development in Contexts
of Poverty </i>was held in San Jose Costa Rica from September 25th to 29th.
The meeting was organized by the Ministry of Education of Costa Rica and the
Organization of American States, with assistance from UNICEF, UNESCO and PAHO.
Approximately 670 people from 25 countries participated.  Highlights of the
meeting included:<p>
<p>
	- 	An opening session that included a meaty presentation by the Vice President
of Coast Rica, Rebecca Gryspan, who explored <i>The Concept of Poverty in Latin
America and Strategies for Overcoming It</i>, and an excellent speech by the
Minister of Education, Eduardo Doryan.<p>
	-	A panel dealing with <i>Criteria for the Formulation of Policies and
Programs Favoring Children,</i> with presentations by respected government
officials from Peru, El Salvador and Costa Rica.<p>
	-	A presentation by Ruben Katzman from the Economic Council of Latin America
who, within a description of economic and social trends in the Latin American
region, emphasized inequities in the distribution of services for children and
attention to young children and noted an important relationship between family
structure and poor performance in school.<p>
	-	Sessions dealing with the quality of ECCD programs, children&#146;s rights,
children in especially difficult circumstances, the psycho-social needs of
children and families, lessons learned from successful early childhood
programs, and the relationship between research and policy. Robert Myers
presented a paper on this topic.<p>
	-	A teleconference by way of the WORLDNET television system that permitted
interaction between selected participants in the symposium and Patricio Alwyn,
Chilean President, Cesar Gaviria, Secretary General of the OAS, and Helen
Taylor, from the office of Head Start in the USA.<p>
	-	A cameo appearance and message from the President of Costa Rica.<p>
-	Full-day visits to selected early childhood programs in different parts of
Coast Rica.<p>
<p>
	Included in the conclusions of the meeting was a proposal that the Minister of
Education and the President of Costa Rica agreed to present to the up-coming
meeting of the Latin American Presidents in Bariloche which is to focus on
educational policy in the region.  The proposal is that leaders subscribe to a
goal of reducing by 50% over the next 10 years, the percentage of children who
enter the first grade of primary school with delays or distortions in their
psycho-social development.  Also included in the conclusions was a<i>
decalogue</i> of basic actions to be taken by parents in order to favor the
integral development of children during the early years.<p>
<TABLE><TD> 
<A HREF="cgroup.html"><IMG SRC=logo.gif ALT ="[ logo]"></A></TD><TD><BR>Presented by: <BR>The Consultative Group on<BR>
 Early Childhood Care and Development.<BR></TD><TR></TABLE>
</body>
