Source:
T&aacute;j&eacute;koztat&oacute; a csal&aacute;d-,gyermek-, &eacute;s
ifj&uacute;s&aacute;gv&eacute;delemr&otilde;l (Report on Family Care, Child-,
and Youth Care). N&eacute;pj&oacute;l&eacute;ti Miniszt&eacute;rium 1989, 1990,
1991, 1993.<p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b>Day care for children in Hungary is guaranteed by law in Hungary.  The
Social Act (1993) regulates its institutions, namely day care centers for under
threes, kindergartens and school-based day care.<b></b><p>
<b>Day care (for children under three)</b><p>
<b></b>Day care for under threes is almost entirely provided in center-based
institutions.  Quite recently, two of these were privatized and a few are
maintained by the church or foundations.  The regulation for all are the same.
The Social Act (1993) made it possible for local governments to contract
private or non-profit organizations to provide services.<p>
	Day care provision is regarded as a substantial complementary element to the
family benefit system.  Centers provide a choice for families, parents can
decide whether they want to use day care or take advantage of the financial
support available for those families who decide to bring up their young
children at home.<p>
	The preventive child protection role of day care centers is significant.  The
number of children served by the provision who are at risk and/or from socially
or financially deprived families has been growing steadily over the years.
Family support centers, health visitors and the public guardianship authority
refer more and more children to day care centers which at times seem to provide
an alternative to state care for some of these children.  In 1993, about 17% of
the families using day care applied for and paid either only a reduced fee or
no fee at all.<p>
	Children between the ages of 20 weeks to 3 years of age can be admitted to day
care centers.  Those whose development is judged to be lagging behind can stay
until they are four years old.  The others go to kindergarten at the age of
three.  During the past few years, day care centers have begun to admit special
needs children up to the age of six, too.  Relevant legislation was passed in
1994.<p>
	The Social Act (1993) defines the range of eligibility for day care for
children under the age of three.  It states that local governments have to
provide day care in their area for children:  <p>
-  whose parents work or are ill, and thus cannot take care of them during the
day<p>
-  whose physical and mental development requires day care<p>
-  brought up by lone parents <p>
-  who have got two or more sisters or brothers<p>
-  whose family is not able to care for them during the day because of their
difficult    <p>
   social/financial situation.<p>
Most of the times it is the day care center (i.e. the director of the center of
the day care adviser of the district or town) who decide about admission.  At
some places it is the elected body of the local authority who makes the final
decision.  Usually, if they have to set up priorities, it is the living
condition of the family and the status of the child which are taken into
account.<p>
	Considering the childcare leave available until 1 July, 1995, almost all
families who needed day care and were eligible, could find a place for their
children.  However, it is true only  on a national level since many of the
small towns and practically none of the villages have got day care centers.<p>
<p>
<b>Number of day care centers and places</b><p>
<b></b>

<pre>
