BOMI,
1994<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b>	Geographically, the day care centers in small towns and villages were
hit the hardest.  Between January, 1990 and December, 1992 the day care
facilities in 121 villages were closed (2 947 places) so, there are counties in
Hungary where there are not day care centers at all, or where they can be found
only in very small numbers (BOMI, 1992).  In these small settlements the only
way of providing day care for children under three is to admit them to
kindergartens into so called "mini groups".  In these groups the number of
children is less (15-20) than in a regular kindergarten group (25-30) but the
care provided for them is not suitable.  Not suitable because the educationally
oriented program of kindergartens was developed for older children,
kindergarten teachers are trained to work with older children and kindergartens
do not have the kind of facilities needed for diapering and caring for younger
children.<p>
	Parallel with the slow down of closing day care centers, their utilization has
been growing.  Utilization is calculated based on the number of days children
actually spent at the center.<p>
<p>
<b>Number of places and utilization of day care centers</b><p>
<b>1990-1993</b><p>
<b></b>

<pre>
           Year                  Number of places       Utilization in percentage   
           1990                       49 853                       87.2             
           1991                       40 867                      93.65             
           1992                       36 539                      94.73             
           1993                       34 318                       99.9             

</pre>
Central
Statistical Office, 1991, 1992, 1993, 1994<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b>The 99.9% utilization in 1993 meant that the centers were crowded.  They
were filled 20% above capacity (e.g. meaning that 120 children were admitted to
100 places).  Most of the children are between 2 and 3 years of age, but the
number of infants and children between 1 and 2 years of age has been
increasing.  The number of children above 3 is relatively high. They are in the
centers because they reach their third birthday sometimes during the academic
year and kindergartens usually admit new children at the beginning of September
each year only.<p>
<p>
<b>Age distribution of children in day care centers</b><p>
<b></b>

<pre>
