Central
Statistical Office, 1993, 1994, 1995<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
	Day care centers usually offer full time care, three meals a day, as well as
clothes and diapers for the children.  There are a few that provide weekly
care, mainly for those families whose social and economical status justify it
and/or for those children whose health and development is endangered at home
for some reason.  Besides full day care, centers have already started to offer
part-time care, overnight care, and organize playgroups, mother-toddler groups
and discussion groups for parents.<p>
<p>
<b>Kindergarten education</b><u></u><p>
<u></u>	In Hungary kindergartens operate as educational institutions under the
administration of the Ministry of Public Education and Culture. Kindergartens
are regarded as institutions which promote the childs personality and abilities
together with the families, and thereby lay the foundation of school education.
Kindergartens are also viewed as institutions which can successfully make up
for educational disadvantages.<p>
Kindergartens take children from the age of three to the age of seven, at the
oldest. Participation in kindergarten education is a right of every child, and
parents have the right to select the kindergarten they find most appropriate
for their children. Admission to kindergartens takes place on the basis of the
parents  request, by means of application, and through the decision of the head
of the kindergarten after considering local kindergarten opportunities.
However, attendance to kindergartens has never been compulsory for the whole
age group of children between the ages of three and seven. Attending
kindergartens has been made compulsory by the Public Education Law No I of
1995. for those children whose education provided by the family is seen as not
sufficient in promoting the child s development. The Public Education Law of
1993. ordered compulsory attendance of kindergartens for children who passed
the age of five. This obligation can be met by the parents taking the child to
the local kindergarten or to a kindergarten somewhere else. If the parents fail
to meet their obligation the notary of the local government authority is
duty-bound to proceed along appropriate lines.<p>
<u>The maintenance of kindergartens</u><p>
<u></u>	The Law No 1. of 1985 on Education, in line with previous legislation
allocated the right for operating kindergartens to local government
authorities. However, for-profit organizations, organizations funded from the
central budget, as well as nonprofit organizations can also establish and
operate kindergartens.<p>
	The Law No. XXIII of 1993-. which modified the Law No. 1. of 1985 passed at
the time of the political-economical transformation,- in conjunction with the
Law IV. of 199 on Freedom of Conscience and Religion created the opportunities
for organizations outside the public sector, to provide services to do with the
education of children. By now kindergartens can be established and operated by
not only the local government authorities, but other legal entities, as well as
individuals, provided their services meet specific requirements. Licenses are
required for every kindergarten with the exception of kindergartens run by the
local authorities.<p>
	The duties of the local government authorities concerning kindergartens are
stated in the law defining the duties of local authorities in relation to
educational institutions:<p>
Local government authorities of villages, towns, municipal towns and the
districts of the capital are obliged to make provisions for kindergarten
education. Local authorities can meet this duty by setting up and operating
kindergartens themselves, or in partnership, as well as by means of contracting
out these services .<p>
	The majority of kindergartens are operated by the local authorities
themselves, and their share in providing services, has remained unchanged in
the last four years.<p>


<pre>
    199/91          1991/1992         1992/93          1993/94      
     95.2%            95.6%            96.2%            96.4%       

</pre>
<p>
	Every kindergarten must possess a Deed of Foundation document, which is issued
by a government or local authority organization operating the service, or by
other legal entities.<p>
	The number of children attending kindergartens have increased by more than six
thousand -from 391,129 to 397,153-since the academic year 199/1991. According
to the forecasting of the Central Statistical Office the increased birthrate
witnessed from the 9s, which has been due to the larger cohorts of the 197s, is
to peak in 1999. However, while the number of children attending the
kindergarten has increased, the total capacity of kindergartens have diminished
by nine thousand -from 385,2 to 376,57, and the number of groups in the
kindergartens has shrunk by more than a hundred -from 16,55 to 15,952, and that
of kindergarten teachers by more than six hundred -from 33,635 to 32,957-, in
the same period.<p>
The services therefore cannot meet the full demand, and the number of children
whose application has been turned down due to shortage of places has increased
every year. In 1993/94 5,289 children were turned down, 912 more than in the
previous year, and 2,517 more than in 199/91.<u></u><p>
<u>The types of kindergartens and their organizations</u><p>
<u></u>Kindergartens operate from Monday to Friday, most of them 12 hours a
day. From the total of 4712 kindergartens as few as 355 keep open for eight
hours only. The opening hours of the kindergartens are set by the operating
authorities, on the basis of the parents working hours. Parents are free to
decide how many hours their children spend in the kindergartens per day, within
the kindergartens opening hours. <p>
	The size and organizational structure of kindergartens vary by centres. Some
of them work in one building, with one or more groups, while others operate in
different precincts but under the same administration. Whether  a kindergarten
is separate, or is a member of a bigger organization is dependent on how many
groups the kindergarten runs, on its geographic location, and on its loading.<p>
<p>
<b>Current system of child- and youth protection and its operation</b><p>
<b></b>Similarly to other branches of social services, child and youth
protection is divided into basic and special services.  Basic services aim at
prevention, that is at either preventing the establishment of the condition of
risk, or overcoming the state of being at risk. For this purpose a signalling
system is necessary, which can signal risks towards organizations able to give
support and authorized to take measures. Today this preventive system consists
of general practitioners, health visitors, the caregivers and teachers at day
care centres, teachers at school with duties of child care, and those police
staff which are commissioned with youth care, as well as the professionals and
family support centres. This system however is suffering from a lack of
communication among these agents, with the result that their work is not
coordinated, often overlap, and there are also cases which are not signalled by
any of the parties involved. The efficiency of the system would greatly benefit
from  basic and  further training courses given to these people, the curricula
of which would involve the detection and handling of risk situations for
children, and also from in this field.<p>
	The key institution in the present child care system is the Social Services
Department for Children Under Age, at the local authorities. The Family Law and
the adjoined legislation define the measures Social Services Departments for
Children Under Age can take, in case ,- for any reasons- the physical, mental
or moral development of the child is not secured. These measures are the
following depending on the degree of risk the child is exposed to:<p>
a/ protective-caring measures, which include reprimanding the child under age
for his or her behaviour  admonition of the parent  obliging the parent to
ensure that his or her child attend the educational institution etc.<p>
b/ provision of educational allowance<p>
c/ appointing a children's officer for the child at risk<p>
d/ placing the child in residential care on the request, or with the agreement
of the parent ("placed in residential care")<p>
e/ the temporary placement of the child under age in case of emergencies<p>
f/ taking the child into residential care in case of severe risk ("brought up
in residential care")<p>
g/ taking the child under age without a parent practicing parental supervision,
in state care ("brought up by the state")<p>
<p>
<b>The number of protective-caring measures</b><p>
<b></b>

<pre>
Protective-     1989         1990         1991         1992         1993      
  caring                                                                      
